<FIRST>r i PM-BRF--Peru-Rebels     07-19 0140</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Peru-Rebels,0143</SECOND>
<HEAD>Maoist Guerrillas Destroy Trout Farm</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HUANCAYO, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 100 Shining Path guerrillas attacked
a private fish hatchery in the Andes, blowing up laboratories and
incubation tanks and killing 50 tons of trout, police said.
   Guerrillas in three trucks and a microbus arrived at the hatchery
Monday, tied up seven employees and set dynamite charges around the
facility, which is 25 miles northeast of Huancayo and 165 miles from
Lima.
   Authorities said the rebels made off with some arms, radio
equipment and a pickup truck. Security forces left Huancayo Tuesday
to pursue the rebels.
   The Shining Path is a fanatical, Mao-inspired guerrilla group
that has waged an armed insurgency against Peru's elected government
since 1980.
   The government says more than 15,000 people have died in the
guerrilla war, including police, soldiers, government officials,
rebels and civilians.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
