<FIRST>r a PM-TaxusShrub     07-19 0297</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Taxus Shrub,0304</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawmaker Proposes Taxus Yew as State Shrub for Massachusetts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lawmaker says the state known to some detractors
as ``Taxachusetts'' needs an official shrub befitting its budget
woes: the taxus yew.
   Republican Rep. Peter Forman filed a bill Tuesday to add the
ornamental shrub common to the state to the list of official state
symbols.
   ``The name of this humble fir echoes the calls from the governor
(Democrat Michael S. Dukakis) and many elected Democrats _ taxes on
you, taxes for you, more taxes at every turn,'' said the House
minority whip.
   The Legislature's Democratic majority recently supported a $700
million temporary income tax increase. And if it agrees to Forman's
bill, the taxus yew could join such other symbols as the the
official state fish, cod; the official state beverage, cranberry
juice; and the official state dog, Boston Terrier.
   Forman, a Plymouth representative who has a taxus yew on his
Statehouse office desk, suggested the shrub might be planted at
major intersections across the state.
   ``In that way, people would be reminded of the recent fiscal
actions of the governor and the Democrats in the House and Senate
every time they drove by or every time they checked their pay
stubs,'' he said.
   A Dukakis aide responded by referring to Forman's attempts to
weaken the universal health care law.
   ``We expect Representative Forman to propose next week
legislation making the chain saw the official tool of the
commonwealth after what he did to health care coverage for the
working poor of this state,'' Dukakis spokesman Steve Crawford said.
   Crawford also said Forman should propose making ``pass-the-hat
the official sport of the commonwealth, considering the number of
times he has come to the administration looking for money for his
district.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
