<FIRST>r a PM-Nielsens     07-19 0370</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nielsens,0382</SECOND>
<HEAD>NBC's All-Star Game Gets Top Rating, But Fox Moves Up</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Major-league baseball's all-star game on NBC
scored with the most viewers and Fox used a couple of heavy hitters
to gain its first Sunday night victory over a major network in the
Nielsen ratings.
   For the week ended July 16, Fox Broadcasting edged ABC for third
place Sunday.
   The fledgling network's ``Married ... With Children'' moved up to
23rd place and ``America's Most Wanted'' was 29th. Both shows had a
21 percent share of the audience, the highest share level in Fox
history.
   The game was the lowest-rated all-star game ever in prime time.
It reflected the generally low ratings this year for all baseball
coverage.
   NBC's coverage of the game was closely followed by ABC's
``Roseanne'' in second place. Both were on Tuesday night, but
because of the game's early start they were in direct competition
only in the East.
   NBC was first on the A.C. Nielsen Co. chart with an average of
12. CBS followed with 8.9 and ABC with 8.6.
   The ratings are a percentage of the estimated 90.4 million homes
in the United States with television. The share is the percentage of
sets in use.
   ``Totally Hidden Video,'' Fox's highest-rated premiere show last
week in 21st place, dropped to 34th although the rating was off less
than a point.
   Fox had replaced several segments of the hidden-camera show after
it learned actors had been used and fired the producer. Allen Funt
of ``Candid Camera'' filed suit on grounds that some of the stunts
were taken from his show.
   The week's Top 10: NBC's All-Star Baseball Game, ABC's
``Roseanne,'' NBC's ``Cheers,'' NBC's ``A Different World,'' NBC's
``The Cosby Show,'' NBC's ``The Golden Girls'' and ABC's ``Wonder
Years,'' tied, NBC's ``Empty Nest,'' CBS' ``60 Minutes'' and CBS'
``Murder, She Wrote.''
   ABC was first among evening news show with a rating of 8.8. CBS
scored 8.6 and NBC 7.9.
   The lowest-rated show was NBC's ``Jim Henson Hour.''
   The bottom five among only the three major networks were: CBS'
``48 Hours,'' ABC's ``Incredible Sunday,'' CBS' ``Beauty and the
Beast,'' ABC's ``Have Faith'' and NBC's ``Jim Henson Hour.''
</TEXT>
