<FIRST>r a PM-FilmPreservation Bjt   07-19 0425</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Film Preservation, Bjt,0435</SECOND>
<HEAD>Film Enthusiasts to Name 25 Titles for Film Preservation</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Should stand; meeting begins at 4 p.m. EDT</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hollywood has produced hundreds of great
movies, yet which ones are the very best?
   Congress has created a blue-ribbon panel to answer the question,
and representatives of 13 film groups are meeting today at the
University of California, Los Angeles, to try to choose what they
deem the best 25 movies.
   The movies they select will be the first to come under the
protection of the National Film Preservation Act of 1988.
   Leading candidates are ``The Grapes of Wrath,'' ``Casablanca,''
``It's a Wonderful Life,'' ``The Best Years of Our Lives,''
``Citizen Kane'' and ``On the Waterfront.''
   The preservation act, signed into law last year, was drafted in
response to outcries about the practice of coloring old
black-and-white films.
   It stipulates that a panel of film experts select 25 titles
annually, which will be added to a national film register labeling
movies according to their cultural, historical and aesthetic
interest.
   ``This will not stop the tampering, but it will make public
knowledge that a film has been tampered with,'' said George Kirgo,
president of the Writers Guild of America and a preservation board
member.
   Congress did not forbid a movie copyright holder from editing
movies, or from using computers to add color to films.
   But the film preservation act requires that such movies must be
labeled as colored or altered ``without the participation of the
principal director, screenwriter, and other creators of the original
film.''
   ``All it will do is identify the films when they're tampered
with. The 25 films that we'll pick must be so identified in the
future,'' Kirgo said.
   In preliminary polling, 57 movies were nominated by at least two
of 13 members of the preservation board.
   The leader was ``The Grapes of Wrath'' with eight votes.
``Casablanca'' and ``It's a Wonderful Life'' drew seven votes each;
``The Best Years of Our Lives,'` ``Citizen Kane'' and ``On the
Waterfront'' received six votes each.
   Aside from the writers guild, members of the panel were named
from the Screen Actors Guild; the Directors Guild of America; the
National Society of Film Critics; the Motion Picture Association of
America; the UCLA film department; the Academy of Motion Picture
Arts and Sciences; the Alliance of Motion Picture and Television
Producers; the American Film Institute; the National Association of
Broadcasters; the department of cinema studies at New York
University; The Society of Cinema Studies and The University Film
and Video Association.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
