<FIRST>u a AM-StudioShooting     07-19 0374</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Studio Shooting,0387</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Crashes Truck Into Lorimar Studios, Kills Himself</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BERNIE WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CULVER CITY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man drove his truck through a
Lorimar-Telepictures studios gate, torched the vehicle, fired
shotgun blasts at a wall and killed himself, police said.
   The man's identity and the motive for the rampage at the motion
picture and television production complex were not immediately
known, said police Capt. Tom Mahoney.
   There were no other injuries, said police Lt. Jerry Dalven.
   The incident began shortly after 5 p.m., when the driver, who was
alone, handed a security guard two canisters and told him, ``You
have five minutes to live.''
   The canisters later were found to contain toxic methyl bromide
gas, Officer Ed Henneberque said.
   The driver had asked for someone, said witness Kelly Hustis.
Police could not immediately confirm the report.
   ``The guy just busted through the gates,'' said Bill McCullum, a
Lorimar security guard on duty at the gate after the incident. ``All
I know is I could have been the one lying on the ground.''
   The man then parked his vehicle against the wall of a studio
building, and apparently set it afire with a can of pressurized
lubricant, Henneberque said.
   A Los Angeles County Sheriff's Department bomb squad was called
to the scene after studio firefighters discovered what appeared to
be a hand grenade lying on a seat in the truck, the officer said.
   The man walked onto the lot brandishing a shotgun, said Dave
Stapf, a spokesman for the studio 10 miles west of downtown Los
Angeles. After firing about six shots at random, he killed himself,
officials said.
   Stapf said the man apparently was not a former employee.
   Last December, a man was charged with fatally shooting two
unarmed security guards in a similar rampage at Universal Studios.
   Nathan Trupp, 44, of Albuquerque, N.M., had been turned away from
a Universal Studios gate minutes earlier by the guards after he
demanded to see actor Michael Landon. He allegedly returned to open
fire on the guards without warning.
   Trupp pleaded innocent July 5 to murder and attempted murder
charges filed in the case after a judge reversed an earlier finding
that Trupp was mentally incompetent to stand trial.
</TEXT>
