<FIRST>u a AM-HostageShootings 1stLd-Writethru a0788 07-19 0425</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hostage Shootings, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0788,0436</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man With History of Taking Hostages Shoots Daughter, Self</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 6, 11 to give daughter's name; SUBS 13th graf, `No
one ...,' to CORRECT that police officer from Carlstadt, sted Suffolk County.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT MILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MASTIC, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who held various family members hostage
over the past 20 years kept police at bay for six hours Tuesday,
then shot and killed his daughter before turning the gun on himself,
authorities said.
   Suffolk County Police found the bodies of James Hyames, 59, and
his daughter, Lisa, 18, inside the family's Long Island home, said
Suffolk County Police Officer Salvatore Yovino.
   Hyames had been arguing with his daughter because she moved in
with her boyfriend and had recently sold her car, police said.
   Hyames also took family members hostage 20 years ago in Colorado
and in 1974 in Carlstadt, N.J., but did not kill any of them,
officials said.
   Hyames' wife walked out of their house during the argument
Tuesday, heard a shot, returned and saw Lisa Hyames lying on the
floor, said police Lt. William Kiley. She went to a neighbor's home
and called police.
   Carol Ianelli, another daughter of Hyames, said her father told
her on the telephone, ``I shot Lisa and she's lying in a pool of
blood.''
   When officers first approached the house, Hyames fired at them
with a handgun and drove them off. They waited two hours before
approaching again, but Hyames fired, grazing an officer's head,
Yovino said.
   Police surrounded the home and tried by telephone to persuade
Hyames to let them take Lisa out.
   Authorities connected Hyames' phone with that of his grown son,
Mark, in Harrisburg, Pa., in an effort to talk him into giving
himself up.
   At the end of the conversation, Hyames said ``goodbye,'' hung up
and a shot rang out, police said.
   With officers were several of Hyames' relatives, including
Ianelli, who said she hadn't spoken to her father in 15 years.
   Carlstadt Deputy Police Chief John Occhiuzzo, who along with a
priest talked Hyames into surrendering in 1974, was brought to the
scene Tuesday to try and help bring him out again, said Officer
Randy Jared.
   No one was hurt in the Carlstadt incident, in which Hyames held
his wife and two children hostage for 19 hours, but he served time
in jail, according to Carlstadt police Lt. Herb Scheidewig.
   Suffolk police had no information on the Colorado incident.
   The officer grazed with a bullet Tuesday was not seriously hurt.
</TEXT>
