<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-89 0245EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-CannibalismDig 1stLd-Writethru a0709 07-19 0528</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cannibalism Dig, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0709,0537</SECOND>
<HEAD>Scientists Locate Rows of Stones; Human Bone</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS spelling of Ayres to Ayres in grafs 2,9, 10. Alferd
is cq.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto staffing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELLEN MILLER HADDOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAKE CITY, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Archaeologists using shovels and other
garden tools found a human skull bone Tuesday underneath a marker
honoring the five men believed to be victims of 19th-century
cannibal Alferd Packer.
   ``It's definitely human,'' said archaeologist Jim Ayres as the
bone was unearthed in the apparent grave at noon.
   Walter Birkby, a physical anthropologist at Arizona State Museum
in Tucson, said it was a left temporal bone found in the human
skull. It will be shipped to the University of Arizona for analysis.
   The archaeologists are participating in a dig organized by George
Washington University law professor James Starrs, who wants to learn
the truth about the 1874 cannibalism case. He hopes to determine how
the five men were murdered and whether Packer consumed their remains.
   Packer formed a party of Utah men to search for gold in the San
Juan Mountains, but the group became snowbound on the 9,000-foot
mountain ridge in 1874.
   Packer claimed that one of the men, Shannon Bell, killed the
other four while Packer was away from camp. Packer said he then
killed Bell in self-defense and consumed the remains of the five men
to survive.
   Despite his claim, Packer was convicted of murdering one of the
prospectors in 1883. After that verdict was overturned by the state
Supreme Court, Packer was retried and convicted of manslaughter. He
was sentenced to serve 40 years in prison, but was paroled in 1901
and died six years later.
   The reputed gravesite of the five victims has been set off by a
marker, which honors the five men ``who were murdered on this spot
early in the year 1874 while pioneering for mineral resources of the
San Juan country.'' But researchers are uncertain whether the sign
marks the actual spot where Packer victims are buried.
   Working in short-sleeved shirts, hiking shorts and hats, Ayres,
Birkby and some of their graduate students dug about 6 inches under
the marker Tuesday before locating parallel rows of rock that they
speculated marked the graves of the five men. The human bone was
found a short time later.
   Ayres said the group had a photograph of the rocks in formation
that was taken in 1909, but he and Birkby were cautious about what
may lie below the rocks.
   ``We'll clean it up, shoot it, plot it on the map and then dig
some more,'' Birkby said. ``We don't know how deep it is.''
   To this day, the Packer case has triggered broad human interest,
from embellished legend to jokes, and the wry amusement is shared by
scientists on the dig as well as the onlookers.
   Starrs has nicknamed the dig area ``the bone zone,'' and is
selling T-shirts bearing a skeleton and the words, ``Gimme Five, the
Alferd Packer Expedition July 1989'' to help offset the costs of the
trip.
   Other T-shirts for sale in the area proclaim, ``Have a Friend for
Dinner,'' and ``Alferd Packer, Serving His Fellow Man.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890719-0018 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-89 0256EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Korea     07-19 0511</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Korea,0531</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition Criticizes Roh's Cabinet Changes As Cosmetic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By M.H. AHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Roh Tae-woo replaced six
Cabinet ministers today and fired the head of the politically
powerful national intelligence agency.
   Opposition leaders immediately denounced the changes as cosmetic
and claimed Roh ignored the public's desire for a complete change to
rid the government of officials who served under former President
Chun Doo-hwan.
   Most ministers in the 23-member Cabinet worked in some capacity
under the discredited and authoritarian Chun government.
   The changes today involved the home, construction,
communications, political affairs, labor, and health and social
affairs ministries.
   They were not expected to alter government policies and were
widely seen as a political housekeeping move aimed at reassuring
citizens that the governing party is concerned about social unrest,
rising crime and welfare problems.
   Prime Minister Kang Young-hoon and the other 16 ministers were
retained. The last Cabinet shake-up was in December 1988, when Kang
and 19 ministers were appointed.
   In the most noticable change, former Attorney General Suh
Dong-kwon, 56, replaced Park Seh-jik as head of the powerful Agency
for National Security Planning, fomerly the Korean Central
Intelligence Agency.
   Park was better known to foreigners as chief organizer of the
successful 1988 Summer Olympic Games held in Seoul in September.
   The intelligence agency has been widely criticized for apparently
not knowing beforehand of secret visits to communist North Korea by
dissident clergyman Rev. Moon Ik-hwan, opposition lawmaker Suh
Kyong-won and a radical student leader still in the north.
   Under South Korean law, unauthorized visits to the north are
illegal.
   The largest opposition group, the Party for Peace and Democracy,
said Suh Dong-kwon was ``in the vanguard of the government's
suppression of political opposition and dissent'' as attorney
general under Chun.
   Lee Sang-soo, a party spokesman, said the Cabinet change
``ignored the people's ardent desires for further democratization
and liquidation of human rights abuses and corruption'' under Chun,
who left office in February 1988.
   Lee In-che, spokesman for the opposition Reunification Democratic
Party, said the changes were ``not adequate to satisfy the people's
anticipation of renovation in government.''
   He said the public demanded better law enforcement and handling
of the nation's economic problems.
   Roh was elected president in December 1987, winning 36.6 percent
of the vote as two other candidates split the opposition vote.
   In other changes today, National Assemblyman Kim Tae-ho of the
governing party was made home minister, succeeding Lee Han-dong.
Sources said Lee was dismissed to hold him responsible for a surge
in violent crime in recent months. Police are under the home
minister's control.
   Kwon Yong-gack, president of the state-run Korea Housing Corp.
and a retired army general, became construction minister.
   Former governing party lawmaker Kim Chong-in was made health and
social affairs minister, Communications Minister Choi Young-choul
was reassigned as labor minister and former President Lee Woo-chae
of the state-run Korea Telecommunications Authority, took over
Choi's old post.
   Park Chul-un became the first minister of state for political
affairs. Park previously was a special presidential assistant on
policy matters.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
