<FIRST>r w PM-ContraAid     07-19 0365</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Contra Aid,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>GOP Lawmakers File Suit Against Bush Over Contra Aid Compromise</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX8</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A White House agreement giving top
congressional leaders the power to stop Contra aid later this year
is unconstitutional, four conservative GOP lawmakers charge in a
lawsuit against President Bush and Secretary of State James A. Baker
III.
   Meanwhile, some lawmakers Tuesday hailed Bush administration
plans to cut separate aid to the Contras' political operations as a
gesture of bipartisan cooperation and a move toward getting the
rebels to return home.
   Congressional leaders and Contra spokesmen confirmed that funding
for the Miami office will be sharply reduced. In Miami, Jorge
Rosales, a Contra spokesman, said it could mean the closing of the
office.
   The Democratic-controlled Congress passed a $50 million package
of non-military aid for the Nicaraguan rebels in April, but only
after the administration agreed to cut off aid by Nov. 30 if eight
Senate and House leaders do not approve its continuation through
February.
   In a lawsuit filed Tuesday in U.S. District Court, the pro-Contra
lawmakers said the bipartisan agreement sets a dangerous precedent
and violates the Constitution by circumventing the congressional
process.
   ``To allow one congressman or senator out of 535 to deny
implementing a law passed by Congress and supported by the president
is clearly unconstitutional,'' said Rep. Robert C. Smith, R-N.H. He
said the ``side agreement'' gives the six Democratic and two
Republican congressional leaders ``super veto power.''
   Also joining the suit were Rep. Phil Crane, R-Ill., and Rep.
Chuck Douglas, R-N.H.
   The funding for the Miami Contra office does not come out of the
Contra aid package approved by Congress in April.
   Contra spokesman Bosco Matamoros said the Miami office will be
moved to an undisclosed location in Central America and added: ``We
are increasing our activities.'' The decision does not affect the
Contras' office in Washington.
   Jason Isaacson, spokesman for Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn.,
described the cuts as ``good news,'' and said it showed the Bush
administration was following up on its agreement with Congress last
spring to seek ways for the rebels to return to Nicaragua.
   Rep. Robert Dornan, R-Calif., however, described the proposal as
``an absolute tragedy.''
</TEXT>
