<FIRST>r w PM-Gingrich     07-19 0437</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gingrich,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Georgia Republican Prepares Defense as Committee Prepares Vote</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Republican Whip Newt Gingrich is
enlisting a former colleague as he prepares to defend a
controversial book deal even before an ethics committee vote to
formally investigate him, according to GOP sources.
   The sources, speaking only on condition they not be named, said
Tuesday that Gingrich has asked former Rep. Ed Bethune, R-Ark. for
assistance as he awaits for a likely ethics panel vote Thursday to
launch a preliminary inquiry.
   Bethune, now a Washington attorney, would not discuss any
conversations he had with Gingrich.
   Gingrich, who triggered the investigation that brought down
former House Speaker Jim Wright, was accused in a complaint by Rep.
Bill Alexander, D-Ark., of possibly violating federal campaign
finance laws and House rules on gifts and outside income.
   The allegations focused on a partnership Gingrich formed, in
which 21 investors gave $5,000 each to promote ``Window of
Opportunity,'' a book written by the Georgia Republican, his wife
and a third author.
   Gingrich saw his House fortunes rise over the past year as those
of Wright, D-Texas, fell, because it was Gingrich who filed the
original ethics complaint against the Texas Democrat.
   The Gingrich investigation seemed a near-certainty after Chicago
lawyer Richard J. Phelan, who conducted the committee's probe of
Wright, acknowledged he's been contacted by the panel about handling
an investigation of Gingrich.
   House Republican Leader Bob Michel, of Illinois, said Gingrich
may also be ``thinking of contacting'' other former members for help.
   If the committee votes to start a preliminary inquiry, Gingrich
would need a legal team quickly, because he would have the right to
give the panel a statement defending himself against the allegations.
   Michel also said the investigation can become ``a pretty
expensive thing'' for the Georgia Republican.
   Gingrich wouldn't discuss the probe Tuesday, but when he was
asked if expected it to cost him a of money, said ``yes.'' He said
he would have more to say Thursday.
   Wright primarily financed his legal defense out of campaign
funds, but also established a separate legal defense fund which was
not subject to limits that apply to campaign donors.
   The ex-speaker had almost $500,000 in legal bills, supporters
said in mid-May this year, and that figure would have climbed
considerably if Wright had continued to defend himself in a trial
phase of the ethics investigation.
   The panel had accused Wright of 69 rules violations, including
some of the same charges that Alexander leveled against Gingrich:
violating outside income limits and keeping gifts from persons with
a direct interest in legislation.
</TEXT>
