<FIRST>r w PM-RedDye     07-19 0464</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Red Dye,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congress Leaves Dye in FDA's Hands</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twenty-nine years after calling for a study of
whether Red Dye No. 3 causes cancer, the House says the government
still needs to find out more about the substance.
   But a congressman said the Food and Drug Administration can ban
the substance without further delay if it wants to.
   The vote by the House Tuesday approving the $42.1 billion
agriculture appropriations bill included a provision calling for
more study of the dye, but left unresolved whether the dye that
gives maraschino cherries their distinctive red glow would be pulled
from the market.
   In 1960, when Congress called for a ban on foods that cause
cancer in laboratory animals, Red Dye No. 3 was put on a provisional
list that allowed it to stay on the market for additional study.
   ``It was supposed to last for 2{ years, during which time the
industries were supposed to test the dyes for safety,'' said Rep.
Ted Weiss, D-N.Y., calling for immediate removal of the chemical.
   ``The industry has had 29 years to test these dyes,'' he said.
   FDA Commissioner Frank Young has maintained the substance does
not pose a health threat to humans, and the Wall Street Journal
reported Tuesday that his office worked with canners and growers on
the language to postpone action.
   Large doses of the additive have caused tumors in rats, leading
consumer groups to demand that it be banned.
   Weiss complained about the language in the Appropriations
Committee's report on the bill that said the FDA should perform a
``long-term study'' on the dye. Although such language is not a
formal part of the law, it is used by agencies for guidance on
congressional intentions.
   The report said the study should be reviewed by the FDA ``prior
to making any decision relating to changes in the provisionally or
permanently approved uses of this color.''
   But Rep. Jamie Whitten, D-Miss., chairman of the House
Appropriations Committee, said it's up to the FDA commissioner to
decide whether Red Dye No. 3 will stay on the shelves.
   Weiss said the agency shouldn't wait any longer.
   ``Under the law, the FDA has no option but to follow through with
its stated intentions to terminate the provisional listing of Red
Dye No. 3,'' said Weiss. ``It is high time that it do so.''
   Weiss, chairman of the House Government Operations subcommittee
on human resources and intergovernmental relations, asked the FDA
Tuesday to provide all of its documents relating to the regulatory
status of Red Dye No. 3 over the past year.
   The appropriations bill covers spending for all agriculture
programs, as well as rural development programs like the Farmers
Home Administration, Rural Development Insurance Fund and Rural
Electrification Administration.
</TEXT>
