<FIRST>r w PM-Bush-EmptyPockets     07-19 0701</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Empty Pockets,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Hard-Pressed to Accommodate Foreign Money Demands</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush went to Eastern and Western
Europe with an open checkbook, but not with carte blanche to
accommodate the many countries and causes tugging at his sleeve.
   In fact, he left disappointed people everywhere _ in Warsaw, at
the headquarters of the Solidarity trade union in Gdansk, at the
seven-nation economic summit in Paris, and even in the Dutch capital
of The Hague.
   ``Everybody wants the United States to pick up the check for
everything,'' Bush grumbled as he returned home Tuesday from the
9,000-mile journey.
   He said a group of Dutch legislators he met with wanted U.S.
funding for international environmental cleanup programs. They all
assume ``we are rolling in money,'' and at the same time foreign
leaders are asking the United States to balance its budget, he said.
   ``They understand we are not rolling in money because of our
deficit,'' he said, returning home only hours after his
administration issued its semi-annual economic prediction
forecasting slower growth and higher interest rates than earlier
projections.
   However, it said the federal budget deficit will be lower this
year than was expected _ $148.3 billion, down sharply from the $164
billion predicted in February.
   From the start, the administration sought to play down hopes of
U.S. munificence in Europe.
   ``This is really not a trip to bestow economic largess,''
Secretary of State James A. Baker III said on Bush's first day in
Poland.
   In fact, the aid package Bush unveiled in the Polish parliament
was a drop in the bucket of Poland's urgent needs.
   Bush promised to ask Congress for $100 million to help private
entrepreneurs and $15 million to fight pollution in the city of
Krakow.
   He also pledged to ask U.S. allies to increase their aid to
Poland _ which he did later that week in Paris _ and to encourage
the World Bank to provide $325 million in loans for Polish
agriculture and industry.
   But the Polish government wrote to the seven-nation Paris summit,
asking for $4.3 billion in loans and debt relief.
   In the Baltic Sea port of Gdansk, Solidarity chief Lech Walesa
invited the Bushes to his home for lunch _ and asked for $10 billion
to help Poland. The next day, the Solidarity daily newspaper said
Bush's gift ``disappointed many people'' although it praised the
warm intentions it reflected.
   In Hungary, Bush promised $25 million to encourage private
enterprise and 60 American Peace Corps volunteers to teach English.
   On to Paris, where Bush encountered an embarrassing situation:
leaders of some two dozen developing nations were invited by
left-leaning French President Francois Mitterrand to participate in
the bicentennial parties of the French Revolution and to mingle with
their richer counterparts.
   The Third World group called for an urgent dialogue between
developed and developing nations to discuss economic and
environmental programs. But the United States and England rebuffed
the suggestion, and Mitterrand promised to support it _ at a later
date.
   The solution to the problems of the Third World countries,
advised Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady, was on a case-by-case
basis.
   Based on that approach, the United States sought to encourage a
conclusion to negotiations between Mexico and its commercial bankers
for a plan to ease the $100 billion Mexican debt. Those talks are
going on in New York.
   In fact, Bush and the other leaders _ of Britain, France, West
Germany, Japan, Italy and Canada _ issued a communique at the end of
their annual gathering sternly admonishing private banks to be more
realistic in their expectations from Third World debtors and to cut
their debts.
   On the environment too, the United States and its partners were
big on words but light on cash. They called for concerted efforts to
clean up the seas and oceans and preserve the eroding ozone layer
that protects the earth from harmful sun radiation, but did not
commit any money.
   Only one group of nations got relief. Bush promised, just prior
to leaving for Europe, that the United States will forgive $1
billion in debts owed by the earth's poorest lands _ those in
sub-Saharan Africa.
</TEXT>
