<SECOND>PM-Afghan-POWs,280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Advocate Says Rebels Suggest Deal for American POWs</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-US-Afghanistan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Afghan rebels who hold Soviet prisoners may
also hold the key to releasing Americans held in Southeast Asia,
says a POW advocate.
   ``They have indicated a clear desire to help ... and they are in
a position to help,'' said William M. Hendon, from Asheville, N.C.,
back from his second meeting in Peshawar, Pakistan, with leaders of
the Mujahedeen.
   Hendon quoted one of the rebels as saying, ``The Soviets can get
your men out like that,'' adding a snap of the fingers. ``The world
knows they got your prisoners. We will help you get them out.''
   Hendon a former Republican member of the House and former
Pentagon consultant, heads the McLean, Va.,-based POW Publicity
Fund, created to publicize a $2.5 million reward offered by 21
congressmen for the return of a American prisoners of war they claim
have been held captive since the Vietnam War.
   Relatives of POWs accompanied Hendon for the second trip, from
which they returned Saturday. They have been lobbying members of
Congress and others for the plan and for continued military aid to
rebels fighting the communist-backed government in Kabul.
   ``They've lived what we've lived for many, many years because of
their own losses,'' said one of the relatives, Beth Bischoff of
Wilson, N.C.
   The State Department says it has received no reports from the
Mujahedeen about the possibility of a three-way prisoner deal.
   The United States says it is unable to prove the existence of
POWs in Vietnam although it won't rule out the possibility. There
are 2,348 Americans unaccounted for in Southeast Asia.
   The Soviets claim 300 of their number are held by the rebels.
