<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-89 0326EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Budget     07-19 0492</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Budget,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pentagon Payday Shift Triggering Savings Gimmicks in Congress</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX10</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congressional budget writers complain that the
Pentagon's decision to move its Oct. 1 payday up by two days is
triggering a rash of deficit-cutting gimmicks by House and Senate
committees.
   The Defense Department payday shift would move $2.9 billion in
salaries to the end of the 1989 fiscal year _ and allow the agency
to claim an equal amount in savings from its fiscal 1990 budget.
   Objections to the idea crescendoed on Tuesday, even as the Bush
administration conceded that the economy is not performing as
robustly as it expected several months ago.
   In May, Defense Secretary Dick Cheney ordered the military's
monthly payday of Oct. 1 _ a Sunday _ moved up to Friday, Sept. 29,
saying the shift would avoid inconveniencing troops.
   But since fiscal 1990 begins Oct. 1, the rescheduling had the
effect of shifting $2.9 billion into the previous fiscal year,
freeing up $2.9 billion in 1990 for other purposes for the Pentagon.
   ``I think it has a budget consequence that was not intended by
the statute,'' House Speaker Thomas S. Foley told reporters Tuesday.
   Lawmakers grumbled that the payday shift enabled Cheney to claim
a solution to a dispute between the administration and Congress over
the Pentagon's budget, in which congressional budget officials were
claiming that the military will spend too much money next year.
   Now, congressional committees are mapping plans to achieve
similar budget savings by shifting paydays for civilian agencies
that they oversee.
   The House Appropriations Committee approved a spending bill
Monday that claims $358 million in savings by bumping ahead the Oct.
1 paydays for the Department of Veterans Affairs, the Environmental
Protection Agency and NASA.
   House Budget Committee Chairman Leon Panetta, D-Calif., told a
reporter Monday that committees controlling the Department of
Transportation and the Postal Service are planning similar shifts.
He and other congressional leaders are mapping plans to prevent the
idea from spreading.
   ``It'll set a powerful precedent,'' Rep. Bill Frenzel of
Minnesota, ranking Republican on the House Budget Committee, said
regarding the Pentagon payday shift. ``We'd be hard-pressed to say
the others can't do it if the one could do it.''
   Also Tuesday, the administration officially geared down the
economic projections it released in February.
   Administration officials estimated that short-term interest rates
would average 8 percent this year and drop to 6.7 percent next year,
that the economy would grow by 2.7 percent this year and 2.6 percent
next year, and that inflation would rise by 4.9 percent in 1989 and
4.1 percent in 1990.
   Each figure was more pessimistic than the administration forecast
in February _ estimates that at the time were called overly rosy by
congressional and outside economists.
   The administration projected that the fiscal 1990 deficit would
be $99.2 billion, well within the $110 billion shortfall target for
the year of the Gramm-Rudman deficit-reduction law.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890719-0028 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-89 0327EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-US-Afghanistan     07-19 0434</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Afghanistan,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Department Plays Down Afghan Rebel Massacre</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American officials are stunned by the slaying
of 30 Afghan rebels, and they say the massacre may prompt an
evaluation of where U.S. military aid goes but is unlikely to result
in less assistance.
   ``It's kind of a mess ... I'm greatly concerned,'' said Rep.
David Dreier, R-Calif., a strong supporter of the mujahedeen, as the
anti-government rebels call themselves.
   Dreier said if reports that supporters of Gulbaddin Hekmatyar of
the Hezb-e-Islami group ambushed and killed their rivals are true,
``We have to be very careful not to have him as a ... recipient of
our arms.''
   He said the United States has ``always had problems with
Hekmatyar,'' who Dreier said holds anti-Western views.
   In Pakistan, Qaribur Rehman Saeed, a spokesman for Hekmatyar's
hard-line Islamic group, acknowledged the group killed some
competing fighters from the Jamiat-e-Islami guerrilla organization.
Saeed said his group is still investigating what happened July 9 in
the Takhar Valley.
   State Department spokesman Richard Boucher said ``there may be''
some change in the distribution of aid, ``but at this point we don't
have any new details.''
   But, he said, ``The basic goal of supporting the mujahedeen,
urging them to unite, supporting their efforts of self-determination
_ that remains something we intend to continue pursuing.''
   There are seven major factions among the anti-government rebels,
with alliances sometimes shifting and some groups deeply opposed to
others.
   Boucher and others tried to play down the significance of the
internecine struggle.
   Asked why the United States would continue to aid a faction it
determined may have killed other rebels, Boucher responded: ``I
think what you're doing is taking one incident and blowing it out of
proportion.''
   He said, however, the United States deplored the incident, which
he labeled ``tragic'' and ``grave.''
   Another State Department official, speaking on condition of
anonymity, doubted U.S. assistance to the Mujahedeen would be
affected by the incident. That could change if such activities
become ``an endemic or pervasive problem,'' he said.
   Meantime, published reports quoted U.S. officials as saying they
have decided to increase military aid to the rebels in response to a
massive increase in Soviet military supply shipments to the Kabul
government.
   Although the Soviets withdrew their 115,000 troops from
Afghanistan in February as part an accord with the United States,
Moscow has been sending arms to the Kabul government at the rate of
$200 million to $300 million a month since March, a U.S. official
said.
   The Geneva accords called for an end to outside involvement in
Afghanistan.
</TEXT>
