<FIRST>r w PM-Senate-Ambassadors     07-19 0490</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Senate-Ambassadors,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Democrats Trying to Limit Political Ambassadorships</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite an initial defeat, Democratic critics
are pressing attempts to curb President Bush's nominations of large
numbers of political supporters and Republican contributors to
diplomatic posts.
   Sen. Albert Gore, D-Tenn., and other Democrats said the quality
of the nation's representation abroad suffers when ambassadors and
senior State Department officials are chosen for their contributions
to the Republican Party, not for professional qualifications to
handle their jobs.
   Up to two-thirds of Bush's diplomatic nominations have been based
on political connections, a far higher percentage than in any recent
administration, Democrats contend.
   But Gore's bid to restrict political nominees to no more than 15
percent of the diplomatic corps was defeated Tuesday, 79-20.
   He readied a fall-back position, limiting such nominations to no
more than 30 percent, a total in keeping with administrations dating
back to that of President John F. Kennedy in the early 1960s.
   Gore said he also will seek to rally opposition against nominees
whose non-political qualifications to represent the United States
abroad are thin.
   The Bush administration has submitted 42 diplomatic nominations,
of which 28 can be classified as political, Democrats said.
   They said many of them have few identifiable qualifications for
the jobs.
   But Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., and other senators contended the
proposed restriction would represent an unconstitutional intrusion
on the president's ability to conduct foreign policy.
   Gore said the political appointments destroy morale within the
U.S. Foreign Service and represent ``an abuse for which there is no
justification.''
   ``Other nations do not undermine their national interests
overseas to grant political favors or ensure loyalty to the
political line of the governing party,'' Gore said.
   In other action on pending State Department authorization bill,
the Democratic-controlled Senate approved an amendment forbidding a
president from soliciting foreign or private funds to carry out
foreign policy activities prohibited by Congress.
   The amendment, sponsored by Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y.,
reflects lingering political fallout from the Iran-Contra affair.
   It was adopted, 57-42, after Moynihan contended it was an
essential step to make sure a president and his staff do not move to
circumvent the law.
   But Helms, voting on the losing side, protested the amendment
``is a clear, bald effort to usurp the foreign policy prerogatives
of the president of the United States in a manner not allowed by the
Constitution.''
   He predicted President Bush will veto the entire State Department
authorization bill because of it.
   The provision would make violators subject to fines and jail
terms of up to five years.
   Testimony before the congressional Iran-Contra committees showed
the Reagan administration solicited millions of dollars from
American citizens, and from such nations as Saudi Arabia and Brunei,
for the Nicaraguan Contra rebels when U.S. aid them was banned by
Congress.
   ``This amendment can be summed up in three words: `Obey the
law,''' said Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell, D-Maine.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
