<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-89 0329EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-TaxBill     07-19 0639</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tax Bill,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rostenkowski Offers Changes in Catastrophic Health Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House tax-writers are weighing a plan to shift
more of the burden of the catastrophic health insurance program onto
older Americans with incomes of less than $25,000 a year.
   Rep. Dan Rostenkowski, D-Ill., chairman of the House Ways and
Means Committee, who would prefer to leave the Medicare catastrophic
program as is, offered a package Tuesday that would cut the cost of
the new insurance coverage for those with higher incomes.
   But Rostenkowski said the cool reception to his plan and pressure
from high-income earners among the elderly increased the likelihood
that catastrophic coverage will be repealed.
   Under current law, a typical couple with income between $15,000
and $20,000 would pay $59 for coverage in 1990. Rostenkowski
proposes to raise that to $101. A couple earning about $70,000, now
scheduled to pay $909, would pay $527 instead.
   ``It was not very well-received,'' Rostenkowski told reporters
after a closed committee session.
   Rostenkowski suggested the financing changes as part of a new
package he wants the committee to add to a bill, already approved,
designed to raise $5.3 billion in revenues for deficit reduction in
the next budget year.
   His proposals include:
   _A new tax that would cost the chemical industry _ and,
eventually, buyers of refrigerators and air conditioners _ about
$8.5 billion over five years. The tax would be imposed on
chlorofluorocarbons and other chemicals that are widely used in
cooling and insulation but which harm the Earth's ozone layer.
   _Reversing an earlier decision and allow individuals to deduct 10
percent of their credit cards, education loans and other consumer
interest in 1990.
   _Permanent extension of the 3 percent tax on telephone service.
   _A new tax of about $2 billion on mutual life insurance companies.
   _A significant expansion of federal tax assistance for
lower-income working families, part of an effort to improve aid for
child care. It would expand the earned-income credit, which gives a
working family with children and income under about $18,000 a tax
reduction _ or cash payment if no taxes are owed _ of up to $910.
The credit would rise to a maximum $1,217 for one child, $1,504 for
two children and $1,790 for three or more.
   An additional credit of up to $430 would be allowed if any child
is under age 6.
   _Extension of several tax benefits that have expired are due to
expire. These include a tax exclusion for tuition assistance
provided by an employer; a credit for employers who hire
disadvantaged workers; a benefit for those who invest in low-income
rental housing, and a 20 percent credit for increased investment in
research and experimentation.
   The toughest decision facing the committee is what to do about
the new law that insures older Americans against some costs of a
catastrophic illness. Many retirees object that it is financed
principally by a surtax on the elderly.
   Most of the money is raised from the 40 percent of people 65 and
older whose total income taxes exceed $150 a year. They pay a surtax
of 15 percent of taxes, with a 1989 maximum surtax of $800. Fewer
than 6 percent will pay the maximum.
   The remainder of the cost is financed through a $4 increase in
the $27.90 monthly premium paid for Medicare Part B, which covers
physicians' fees.
   Rostenkowski's new plan would cut the surtax by about two-thirds,
to a rate of 5 percent this year, with a maximum of $800, and the
rate would rise gradually to 10 percent (instead of 28 percent under
current law) in 1993.
   However, it would increase the Part B premium, which is paid by
all but the poorest beneficiaries. That premium, totaling $31.90 for
1989, would, when current-law increases are included, rise to $51 in
1993.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
