<FIRST>r a PM-ChainedSmoker Bjt   07-19 0606</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chained Smoker, Bjt,0624</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Chains Self to Sofa in Bid to Kick Cigarette Habit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY NACHTIGAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thomas Warren tried several methods,
including acupuncture and Smokers Anonymous, to break a 20-year
nicotine addiction.
   Nothing worked.
   Now, the 42-year-old Springfield man has had himself chained to a
280-pound sofa in his living room and rid his home of tobacco. He
intends to remain on the leash for three weeks in a drastic attempt
to kick the habit for good.
   ``I had my friends come over here and take a crescent wrench and
tie me up so there was no way of getting off,'' Warren said Tuesday,
his eighth day of being connected to the thin, 30-foot steel cable.
``I admitted that I was powerless over cigarettes and that they had
made my life unmanageable.
   ``I had to take control of the situation.''
   Warren describes himself as an artist, dog trainer and drug
counselor who beat a cocaine addiction 11 years ago. A pack-a-day
cigarette habit sticks with him, however.
   ``It's a crazy habit that's ruining my life,'' he said. ``It's
self-destructive, it's unhealthy. I used to run marathons, but I've
got respiratory problems now and can't run anymore. I can't do a lot
of the exercises that I'm used to doing.''
   Warren, who lives alone, roams about his small, secluded home
with the thin cable fastened at his neck by a bolt, like a dog
collar. His golden retriever, Rachel, can roam the yard, but
Warren's leash limits him from stepping much past the front porch.
   Warren, a Vietnam veteran, began smoking when he was in the Army.
He said it's especially important to quit smoking because of his
involvement with drug education.
   ``I'm going on the drug-lecturing circuit in September. I can't
smoke cigarettes and sit there and tell people how to get off
drugs,'' he said.
   He said he sought help to quit smoking from the Veterans
Administration, but was told VA hospitals didn't offer such a
program. Acupuncture, Smokers Anonymous, meditation, cutting back to
a quarter-pack and trying to quit cold turkey also failed.
   ``I felt the only way I could whip this once and for all and take
control of my life was to chain myself up,'' he said.
   Warren decided to chain himself for three weeks to guarantee a
modification of behavior, even though his body probably was free of
nicotine after three days.
   He said the urge to smoke in the first few days of confinement
was intense, adding, ``If you offered me a cigarette right now, I'd
say no way.''
   He had to chase away friends who smoked when they stopped by
because the temptation to ask them for a cigarette was too great.
   One man who saw a news report about Warren offered to sell him
herbal cigarettes, which he claimed contained no nicotine.
   ``I didn't want anything to do with those,'' Warren said with a
laugh. ``I'd already tried them before. They taste awful.''
   Jennifer Moore, a spokeswoman for the American Cancer Society in
Springfield, conceded that Warren's attempt to quit is
unconventional.
   ``There certainly are other methods I'd have suggested he explore
before resorting to that,'' she said. ``But I think what he's doing
shows how really bad he wants to quit and how powerful a drug like
nicotine is. It is just as powerful as cocaine or heroin.''
   Warren, who spends his days painting, keeping a journal and
watching movies, feels optimistic he will never smoke again once his
chain comes off later this month.
   ``I love to smoke, but I love to live more,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890719-0033 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-89 0332EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-S&amp;Ls     07-19 0533</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-S&amp;Ls,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Take Debate Over Thrifts Behind Closed Doors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House and Senate negotiators are bargaining
over a savings and loan bailout measure behind closed doors after
narrowing the major disputes between them to how to pay for the
rescue and who will regulate the most troublesome element of the
industry.
   Representatives of the two chambers agreed Tuesday to meet
informally in private the rest of this week with the aim of settling
what were described as minor differences on other issues.
   ``We ought to, over the next couple of days, get the legislative
language worked out so that we have the basis of a single package,''
said the Sen. Donald Riegle, D-Mich., the chief Senate negotiator.
   The biggest stumbling block is a fight, largely along party
lines, on how to raise the $50 billion needed immediately to cover
the losses of federally insured deposits in some 500 failed S&amp;Ls,
mainly in Texas and California.
   President Bush and other Republicans want to raise the money
through 30-year private bonds in order to avoid swelling the federal
deficit.
   Democrats want to make the administration borrow the money
directly through the Treasury _ saying it would reduce the bailout's
total cost by $4.5 billion over 30 years _ but exempt the new debt
from annual deficit-reduction targets.
   Each side has enough votes in the Senate _ 41 _ on the issue to
stymie the other. Despite the little room for bargaining, several
House-Senate conferees said Tuesday they were looking to the White
House and the legislative leaders for a compromise.
   Meanwhile, Riegle said he hopes the other major hurdle _ whether
the Treasury Department or the more independent Federal Deposit
Insurance Corp. should be put in charge of some 1,200
state-chartered thrifts _ will be ``resolved somewhere along the
way.''
   Loose regulation, particularly by Florida, California and Texas,
over state-chartered but federally insured thrifts is blamed for
losses totaling more than $50 billion to risky and often fraudulent
loans.
   Bush and the Senate want to regulate those institutions, as well
as more than 1,700 federally chartered thrifts, through a new Office
of Thrift Supervision in the Treasury Department.
   House conferees insisted Tuesday on giving FDIC Chairman L.
William Seidman rather than the Treasury the chief federal
regulator's role over state-chartered thrifts.
   However, one House source, speaking on condition of anonymity,
described the regulatory turf battle as a ``throw-away chip'' to be
used to ``get something'' in the form of a Senate concession on
another issue.
   Riegle and chief House negotiator Rep. Henry B. Gonzalez,
D-Texas, expressed optimism that agreement on a single package _
excluding the financing issue _ could be reached by Friday.
   ``We've got the train moving; we ought to keep the ball
rolling,'' Gonzalez said.
   The path was cleared for the informal talks after the House
conferees agreed tentatively Tuesday to retreat from their demand to
outlaw junk bond ownership by S&amp;Ls, a provision the Senate would
allow to continue.
   As a compromise, Gonzalez proposed and the Senate conferees
tentatively accepted a measure giving the FDIC and other regulators
discretion to say how many junk bonds S&amp;Ls can hold in their
portfolios.
</TEXT>
