<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-89 0344EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Taiwan     07-19 0645</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Taiwan,0665</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nationalist Party to Hold First Primary Elections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNIE HUANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ruling Nationalist Party holds its
first primary election Sunday in a sign that further democratic
change is coming to Taiwan, once the exclusive political domain of
party elders.
   The primary will select candidates for general legislative
elections in December, when the Nationalists will for the first time
face a challenge from a legal opposition party.
   Opposition parties were forbidden under martial law, which until
two years ago had been in effect since 1949, when the Nationalist
government fled to Taiwan after losing a civil war on the Chinese
mainland.
   Martial law was lifted as part of a political liberalization
program begun by former President Chiang Ching-kuo, son of former
Nationalist leader Chiang Kai-shek.
   The primary is in response to complaints from many of the ruling
party's 2 million members about the long-standing practice of
allowing party bosses to choose candidates for national elections.
They claimed only loyalists who toed the official party line were
selected.
   President Lee Teng-hui, who also heads the party, has promised
the primary would establish ``a fair and open system'' for choosing
qualified candidates. Any incumbent legislator or a person receiving
endorsement from 0.2 percent of party members within a district can
run.
   ``Party members no longer blindly accept orders from the top,''
said political science Professor Hu Fu of the National Taiwan
University. ``We are still a long way from true democracy but the
primary could push the Nationalists to move toward that direction.''
   The primary will choose about 100 candidates from a field of 250.
The process so far has had its rough spots.
   Premier Lee Huan's son, Lee Ching-hua, was forced to withdraw
after opponents claimed his candidacy was designed to perpetuate his
family's influence.
   The younger Lee, the popular secretary-general of Taiwan's
Olympic committee, said he dropped out because his father was
``nearly suffocated'' by criticism of the candidacy.
   Several candidates claimed local Nationalist offices with close
links to the military told party members to vote for certain
candidates, leading to accusations of military intervening in
politics.
   Candidate Wang Lin-lin showed the media a letter she claimed was
sent by the military to party members in her district asking that
they vote for a retired serviceman.
   ``Some party officials have not adjusted their old mentality,''
she said. ``They still want to call the shots. The old tactics
employed against the opposition are now used to hurt the party's own
candidates.''
   Party officials denied the allegations. But political observers
believe the Nationalist officials might be backing candidates loyal
to them to prevent losing control of the new legislature.
   ``If many candidates win the elections on their own, they may not
support the party's policies,'' said Chu Yun-han, a political
science professor at National Taiwan University.
   The primary also has been marred by rumors of some candidates
giving away expensive watches, foreign cigarettes or money to buy
votes. Officials said they were investigating the reports.
   The Democratic Progressive Party, the main opposition party, also
will hold a primary Sunday for its 20,000 members to elect 48
candidates from a field of 52.
   The party's populist platform attracts many native Taiwanese, who
constitute 85 percent of the island's 20 million people. The
remaining 15 percent are largely mainland Chinese whose families
came to the island during the Nationalist retreat.
   At stake in the December elections are 101 seats in the
Legislative Yuan, the highest lawmaking body.
   Not facing re-election are the 182 Yuan members, mostly
Nationalists, who were elected on the mainland before 1949 and
frozen in office because of the Nationalist claim to still be the
legitimate government of all China.
   As the aging lawmakers die or resign, Taiwan-elected members will
play an increasingly important role and can transform the Yuan from
a rubber-stamp organization, professor Hu said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890719-0036 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-89 0337EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-FloatingCocaine Bjt   07-19 0673</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Floating Cocaine, Bjt,0695</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cocaine Floating Ashore Keeps Beaches Abuzz</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL GRACZYK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CRYSTAL BEACH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   High tide has a new meaning these
days along Texas' Gulf Coast.
   Dozens of bundles of cocaine with an estimated street value of $5
million have washed up along more than 200 miles of coast during the
past three weeks, attracting a new breed of beachcomber to the
area's tiny fishing and resort towns.
   ``Everybody's talking about it and I think everybody's looking
for it,'' said Herb Knowles, who works at the Dirty Pelican Pier in
Crystal Beach, about 30 miles east of Galveston. ``Guys on the
weekend are out here at night on three-wheeled vehicles with big
spotlights on the beach.
   ``You tell me what they're looking for.''
   The first discovery occurred June 28 when five packages weighing
a total of about 14.5 pounds were found in the sand on Matagorda
Island, about 100 miles southwest of Houston.
   A week and a half later, five bundles totaling about 78 pounds
washed ashore on the Bolivar Peninsula across from Galveston, and 19
bundles weighing about 81 pounds were discovered by the Matagorda
County sheriff's department.
   The latest find occurred Thursday when six men fishing about 10
miles off Galveston found 25 bundles with 83 pounds of cocaine
floating in the Gulf of Mexico.
   Altogether, 61 packages containing 261 pounds of 98 percent pure,
uncut cocaine have been discovered by authorities or turned in to
them.
   ``It all has the same markings, which leads us to believe it's
from the same load,'' said James E. Caldwell, supervisory special
agent for the U.S. Customs Service in Galveston.
   Marine biologists have estimated the cocaine was in the water
from three weeks to a couple of months. It was bundled in watertight
packages of five bricks, each wrapped in fiberglass resin and duct
tape and then tied together with yellow plastic rope.
   Each brick was marked with the word ``CENTAVO'' and the
designation ``T5.'' On some of the bricks also is written ``USA 2.''
   The drugs probably came from Colombia, Caldwell said. How they
wound up in the gulf is anyone's guess.
   ``It could have been from a ship that went down. It could have
been an air drop. They could have tied it off with floats,'' he said.
   Officials have speculated that a drug boat may have been wrecked
during Tropical Storm Allison last month, dumping the contraband in
the gulf.
   Galveston County Sheriff Joe Max Taylor said these are the first
instances of cocaine washing ashore in Texas, although bales of
marijuana have washed up in the past.
   Texas isn't the only state awash in cocaine. More than 150 pounds
of cocaine has been found on and off South Carolina beaches during
the past two weeks, perhaps the result of an unsuccessful air drop
by smugglers, federal officials have said.
   In Texas, the Coast Guard and some sheriff's departments made
special cocaine patrols last week along miles of desolate beach, but
most of the search now is confined to routine patrols.
   ``We're not doing anything special,'' said Petty Officer Bowde
West of the Coast Guard Station at Port O'Connor. ``But this
definitely is the talk of the town, that's for sure.''
   ``People like to keep it quiet, but they were wanting to comb the
beaches to look,'' added Susie Segura, who can see miles of open
beach from her perch on Meacom's Pier off High Island, northeast of
Galveston.
   Knowles said he's seen everything from parts of houses to
bathtubs come ashore, but no cocaine yet. If he does, he said he'd
leave the package on the beach and call police.
   ``Nine times out of 10, they might think it was mine to begin
with,'' he said.
   The cocaine that's been discovered will be flown to Dallas where
federal authorities will destroy it, Caldwell said.
   ``It's pretty potent,'' he said. ``I imagine there have been some
people sick who see this on television. But some of it might still
be in the gulf.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890719-0037 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-89 0402EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     07-19 0500</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0527</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUGUSTA, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Move over, watch dogs. Step aside, security
guards. Attack snake does the job.
   Gale Gunter-Schultz said she had thought about posting a sign in
her yard warning prowlers that guarding her premises in this
northeast Georgia city was an ``attack snake'' _ her 10{-foot
Burmese python named Balthazar.
   She didn't, though, catching a burglar unawares.
   Mrs. Gunter-Schultz said her husband arrived home from a weekend
trip to find the window pried open to the bathroom _ where the
hungry python sleeps.
   ``Balthazar was probably pretty testy,'' Mrs. Gunter-Schultz
said. ``He had just shed, and that makes him hungry. Plus, it was
time for his regular feeding.''
   The python's last meal of two live rats was two weeks ago.
   Mrs. Gunter-Schultz said Balthazar probably hissed and struck at
the burglar.
   Police reported that the thief left the house undisturbed. A tire
iron, used to pry open the window, was found near the house.
   ``I never, never thought that he would stop a burglar,'' Mrs.
Gunter-Schultz said. ``He's usually pretty mellow.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SAXTONS RIVER, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two innkeepers are offering customers
$1 per mosquito bite to combat the notion that Vermont has been
taken over by bloodthirsty bugs.
   Robert Lynch and Thomas Nunan are giving a ``bounty for bites''
after publicity on state funding for the town of Brandon's insect
control program led to cancellations of inn reservations across the
state.
   Brandon, about 60 miles northwest of Saxtons River, has been hit
especially hard by the blood-sucking bugs this year. But most other
parts of the state don't have mosquito problems.
   Lynch, owner of the Saxtons River Inn, claimed his business was
off by 20 percent because of widespread mosquito fear, with 100
cancellations in June alone.
   Nunan, who owns the Black River Inn in Ludlow, said two bicycle
tours were cancelled at his inn this mnth because of the news
reports.
   He said other innkeepers have received calls from people who said
they would only visit with a guarantee of no bites.
   In response to the mosquito publicity, the state will spend
$40,000 to promote tourism, but the ads have no mention of the bugs.
   Lynch likes his bounty idea better.
   ``You've got the hit the problem directly, not smooth it over,''
he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials at the Kansas City Zoo thought
both their chestnut-headed ground thrushes were male _ until one
began laying eggs.
   Zoo officials thought the two Malaysian birds sounded and behaved
like males when they were brought to the zoo last year. Humans can't
tell the sex of the small, brown birds without a surgical
examination.
   Two baby birds hatched last week.
   ``They sort of surprised me,'' said Dave Wetzel, the zoo's
curator of birds.
   Zoo officials don't intend to forget which adult is the male and
which is the female _ they have given them different bands.
   Now there's the problem of figuring out the sex of the chicks.
</TEXT>
