<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     07-19 0229</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0236</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stocks Soar, Dollar Dips</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The key index on the Tokyo Stock Exchange rose
sharply Wednesday, while the dollar edged down against the Japanese
yen.
   The dollar ended at 141.80 yen, down 0.55 yen from Tuesday's
close of 142.35 yen. It started at 141.75 yen and moved between
141.75 yen and 142.40 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues gained 213.44
points, or 0.64 percent, to finish at 33,557.17, ending five
consecutive trading days of decline. It had lost more than 400
points from last Wednesday to Tuesday.
   ``But there was no strong buying incentive in the market because
Sunday's election was making investors nervous,'' said a dealer with
Nikko Securities, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Analysts have predicted the governing Liberal Democratic Party,
which has been suffering from a series of setbacks including an
influence-peddling scandal and an unpopular consumer tax, will lose
badly in the upcoming election for the upper house of the parliament.
   Dealers said Japanese investors have stayed away from buying
before the election because of fears a Liberal Democrat election
loss would lead to a plunge in the Nikkei.
   In currency dealings, the dollar's slip followed a
wider-than-expected U.S. trade deficit for May.
   Traders said the dollar is not further weakening despite the U.S.
trade deficit because of pessimism over the Liberal Democarts'
performance in Sunday's election.
</TEXT>
