<HEAD>FBI Brass Changed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Floyd I. Clarke has been named deputy director
of the FBI, an appointment that is the latest step in a quick rise
through the FBI ranks.
   Clarke, 47, was promoted Tuesday from his current position as
executive assistant FBI director. That appointment in February had
made him equal in FBI rank to Oliver B. Revell, once mentioned as a
possible director of the bureau, and John E. Otto.
   FBI Director William S. Session also announced Tuesday that Otto
would become associate deputy director for administration and Revell
associate deputy director for discrimination.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Clarke, Otto and Revell will continue to be part of the
director's advisory board on strategy, policy and planning, Sessions
said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Solons Say Rising Prices May Imperil Health Care</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some senators say rising prices for
prescription drugs may hurt health care for the elderly in the near
future.
   Steadily rising prescription prices have driven up the costs of
Medicaid programs and are a concern as well for the Medicare program.
   ``From 1981 through 1988, the prescription drug inflation rate of
88 percent dwarfed the general inflation rate of 28 percent,'' Sen.
David Pryor, chairman of the Senate Special Committee on Aging, said
Tuesday.
   Sen. Richard Shelby, D-Ala., agreed, saying ``soon many elderly
will be priced out of the market.''
   A report by the panel's Democratic staff said most of the drugs
pharmaceutical companies put on the market are duplicates of drugs
already being sold. It said 84 percent of the 348 drugs brought to
market by the 25 biggest companies between 1981 and 1988 were judged
by the Food and Drug Administration as providing ``little or no''
therapeutic potential to improve on existing drugs.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Deaver Trying to Cut Fine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former presidential aide Michael K. Deaver is
seeking to cut from $100,000 to $25,000 the federal court fine he
was assessed for lying under oath about his lobbying business.
   Deaver's request was made to U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield
Jackson, who imposed the sentence on Deaver, the former deputy chief
of staff for President Reagan.
   The request by Deaver says he wants the fine reduced because he
has legal bills of more than $1 million.
   But Whitney North Seymour, the independent counsel who prosecuted
Deaver's case, said the fine could be paid by selling Deaver's
house. Seymour's answer to Deaver's appeal said Deaver paid $990,000
for the house in 1985, but claimed it is now worth $1.45 million.
