<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-Markets     07-19 0291</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Falls, Stocks Rebound</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange's key index halted a losing
streak and sharply rebounded today, while the dollar lost ground
against the Japanese yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues gained 213.44
points, or 0.64 percent, to finish at 33,557.17 and end five
straight trading days of losses.
   ``But it was not an active trading that could build up energy in
the market,'' said Masahiro Umemori, an analyst with Nomura
Securities. Umemori said volume was small.
   First-section volume was estimated at 330 million shares,
slightly up from Tuesday's 300 million. Among the winners were
housing-related issues.
   In currency dealings, the dollar ended at 141.80 yen, down 0.55
yen from Tuesday's close of 142.35 yen. It started at 141.75 yen and
moved between 141.75 yen and 142.40 yen.
   The fluctuation in the dollar-yen rate today was mainly due to
position adjustment and profit-taking, said a trader with the Bank
of Tokyo, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   The Bank of Japan also reportedly intervened in the market by
selling some dollars. The central bank does not publicly comment on
its monetary activities.
   The dollar hit the day's high in midday trading, as institutional
investors bought the dollar after its lower opening following a
wider-than-expected U.S. trade deficit for May, he said.
   The U.S. Commerce Department reported Tuesday the nation's trade
deficit rose sharply to a seasonally adjusted $10.24 billion in May
from $8.29 billion in April.
   Despite the growing U.S. trade deficit, the dollar did not weaken
because of more pessimism over the yen, mainly due to the ruling
Liberal Democratic Party's expected poor performance in upper house
elections this weekend.
   ``Market sentiment is basically moving toward the weaker yen,''
he said.
</TEXT>
