<FIRST>r i PM-Greece     07-19 0434</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Greece,0449</SECOND>
<HEAD>Parliament To Investigate Former Socialist Premier and His Ministers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHILIP DOPOULOS</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Associated Press Writer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new parliament voted overwhelmingly
early today to investigate former Socialist Premier Andreas
Papandreou and four of his senior Cabinet ministers to see if they
should be charged with corruption.
   The decision to set up a 12-member parliamentary committee to
investigate the former officials' alleged involvement in a $200
million scandal involving the Bank of Crete came at the close of two
days of stormy debate.
   Along with Papandreou, former Cabinet ministers Agamemnon
Koutsogiorgas, Panayiotis Roumeliotis, George Petsos and Dimitris
Tsovolas, have been accused of ordering state-run companies to
deposit the equivalent of $12 million in the troubled Bank of Crete
in order to skim off the interest.
   Koutsogiorgas had served as deputy premier and justice minister;
Roumeliotis held the national economy portfolio; Petsos was
transport minister and later public order minister; and Tsovolas was
finance minister.
   Former Bank of Crete chairman Giorgos Koskotas, who has accused
Papandreou of authorizing the alleged scheme, is in a Salem, Mass.
jail fighting extradition. A decision is expected later this month.
   The Bank of Crete case was one of a series of scandals that
contributed to defeat of the Panhellenic Socialist Movement (PASOK)
in June 18 parliamentary elections.
   Voters failed to give any one party an absolute parliamentry
majority, prompting the conservatives and a communist alliance to
form a coalition government.
   The 300-member unicameral parliament decided on each of the five
former Socialist officials by secret ballot and overwhelmingly
favored investigating all of them.
   The parliamentary proceedings were carried live by state-run
Hellenic Radio and Television. Most Greeks were glued to their
television sets or radios till the early morning hours.
   The investigative committee has three weeks to complete its
findings and decide whether there are grounds for prosecution by a
special civil court comprised of Supreme Court judges.
   The 70-year-old Papandreou, on his honeymoon after marrying
35-year-old former airline hostess Dimitra Liani last week, has
denied any wrongdoing. He had told his deputies they were free to
vote according to their conscience.
   The coalition government was formed with a three-month mandate to
investigate the scandals that wracked the former Socialist
administration. At the end of the 90 days, the governing coalition,
led by conservative Premier Tzannis Tzannnetakis, said it will call
new elections.
   In last month's elections, the conservative New Democracy party
won 145 seats in parliament, the Communist-controlled Coalition of
the Left and Progress won 28 and PASOK received 125.
   The two remaining seats went to a small conservative group and an
independent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
