<FIRST>r a PM-Wedtech-Wallach     07-19 0447</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wedtech-Wallach,0463</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Puts Off Testimony From Natan Sharansky's Wife</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The wife of former Soviet dissident Natan
Sharansky flew from Israel to testify in behalf of E. Robert Wallach
at the Wedtech racketeering trial, but a judge temporarily blocked
her testimony.
   U.S. District Judge Richard Owen, saying he had yet to decide
whether she qualified as a character witness, planned to announce
his decision today.
   The New York Daily News reported, however, that Sharansky and his
wife, Avital, returned home Tuesday night.
   Wallach's attorney, Gary Naftalis, pleaded with Owen to allow
Mrs. Sharansky to take the stand Tuesday.
   He said the couple could stay for only one day because Mrs.
Sharansky's mother was dying.
   ``I'm upset,'' Mrs. Sharansky told the Daily News. ``My mother is
dying and I have two little children. I have never left them before.
I am sorry that my testimony will not be heard.''
   For his part, Owen said he wanted to review the law before making
a decision. ``I'm not going to be rushed into this,'' he said.
   Wallach, a San Francisco attorney and longtime friend of former
U.S. Attorney General Edwin Meese, is charged with two others in a
21-count racketeering indictment with illegally extracting almost $2
million from the now-defunct Wedtech Corp. The charges include some
$525,000 in bribes to Wallach to influence Meese and other
government officials.
   Once a small machine shop, Wedtech grew into a $100 million
government contractor through a special program that set aside
contracts without competitive bidding for minority-controlled
companies.
   Owen questioned Mrs. Sharansky outside the presence of the jury
to determine how well she knew Wallach.
   She said Wallach, whom she met in 1982, had been instrumental in
alerting Reagan administration officials about the plight of her
husband, who spent nine years in a Soviet prison camp.
   Sharansky, in court with his wife Tuesday, was released in March
1986.
   Wallach was available to her ``night and day'' to discuss
problems and strategy in her efforts to free her husband, said Mrs.
Sharansky.
   ``Always if he promised something to me, he did it,'' she said.
He never asked for compensation, she said.
   Wallach sought help for Sharansky from Meese, former national
security adviser Robert McFarlane and numerous members of Congress,
she said. He also introduced her to former Secretary of State Henry
Kissinger.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Baruch Weiss opposed calling Mrs.
Sharansky as a character witness. He said her testimony was
``designed to appeal to the sympathy of the jury in a way that a
character witness is not allowed.''
   Mrs. Sharansky was to be the 10th character witness called by
Wallach's defense team.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
