<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0291</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Lower, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell against most major currencies in
early European trading today, weakened by dollar-selling after
Tuesday's worse-than-expected U.S. trade deficit. Gold prices fell
in Europe.
   Dealers said the dollar showed signs of recovering in late
morning trading ahead of today's release of the U.S. consumer price
index for June.
   U.S. economists predicted in a survey that the index would rise
0.3 percent, compared with a 0.6 percent rise in May.
   Earlier, the Bank of Japan continued a bout of dollar-selling
sparked by the U.S. government's report of a $10.2 billion
merchandise trade deficit for May.
   In London, the British pound fell to $1.6215 from $1.6255 late
Tuesday.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe compared with late Tuesday:
   _1.8980 West German marks, down from 1.9138
   _1.6430 Swiss francs, up from 1.6395
   _6.4395 French francs, up from 6.4175
   _2.1374 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1505
   _1,374.75 Italian lire, down from 1,379.50
   _1.1890 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1907
   Earlier, the dollar fell in Tokyo to a closing 141.80 Japanese
yen from 142.35 yen at Tuesday's close. Later, in London, the dollar
slipped further to 141.67 yen.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $372.15 a troy ounce, up
from $371.95 bid late Tuesday. At midmorning, the city's five major
bullion dealers fixed a lower recommended price of $371.50.
   In Zurich, the noon bid price was $371.30, down from $371.50 bid
late Tuesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose 84 cents to a closing bid of
$372.86.
   Silver bullion fell in London to a bid price of $5.23 a troy
ounce, down from $5.27 bid late Tuesday.
