<FIRST>r a PM-OilSpill     07-19 0327</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Oil Spill,0339</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officials Emptying Tank After Underground Tunnel Leak</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DWIGHT OESTRICHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LINDEN, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials were emptying a 12.6 million-gallon
oil storage tank today before investigating why an unsealed tunnel
leaked nearly 300 gallons of fuel oil into a New York City area
waterway.
   Coast Guard spokesman Matthew Duesing said about 2 million
gallons of oil had escaped from the tank by Tuesday evening. Most of
it was contained in surrounding dikes, or pumped into barges or a
pipeline leading to a storage system in the adjacent New York City
borough of Staten Island.
   The oil that leaked into the Arthur Kill, a narrow waterway that
separates Linden and Staten Island, was confined to a 20-by-80-foot
area, said Gary Allen, a spokesman for the state Department of
Environmental Protection. Workers were vacuuming the oil from the
water and using absorbent booms.
   ``It is free flowing oil, so it should not take more then a day
to clean up,'' Allen said.
   Officials said they expected to empty the tank by around midday
today.
   ``We won't know what caused it until the tank is totally out of
service,'' said John Reiff, general manager at the Northville
Industries plant.
   The oil that fouled the Arthur Kill came from an unsealed,
underground tunnel used to carry fuel from storage tanks to barges
and ships, Coast Guard Capt. Robert C. North said. Workers put a
makeshift clay seal at the mouth of the tunnel to cut the seepage.
   ``It wasn't sealed and why it wasn't sealed is something we are
looking into,'' North said.
   ``There's no threat to people,'' said North. ``We're concerned
about the environment if the tank should rupture.''
   The leak of No. 6 fuel oil was reported at late Tuesday morning
at the Northville plant, where four tanks sit near the edge of the
Arthur Kill.
   Reiff said the damaged tank is 18 years old and was last
inspected 7{ years ago.
</TEXT>
