<FIRST>u i PM-SriLanka 1stLd-Writethru   07-19 0616</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sri Lanka, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0479,0637</SECOND>
<HEAD>Precede MADRAS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Thirteen Die in Attack on Religious Procession</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: This report was submitted to a government censor,
who deleted significant portions.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 12 grafs to UPDATE with police comment, new casualty
figures, details of attack. Pickup 14th graf pvs, `Tamil guerrillas...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Extremists hurled grenades at a
procession of Sinhalese and Tamil worshipers in a southern town,
killing at least 13 people and wounding about 85, police said today.
   The attack occurred Tuesday night at the end of a weeklong
religious festival in Kataragama, 105 miles southeast of Colombo,
said a police official speaking on condition of anonymity.
   No one immediately claimed responsibility for the attack.
   About 5,000 people had gathered for the procession, which
attracts both Sinhalese Buddhists and Tamil Hindus and is considered
a demonstration that the two communities can come together in
harmony despite the country's ethnic strife. Tamil Hindus from India
also were present.
   ``It is a tragedy beyond comparison,'' said Ranjith Madumma
Bandara, a government lawmaker who participated in the procession.
``There is nothing sacred in this country any more.''
   Bandara said two women walking beside him were killed in the
explosions but that he escaped injury.
   The Sri Lankan government imposed press censorship July 6 amid
escalating ethnic violence and a political dispute with India over
the withdrawal of Indian peacekeeping forces from the small island
nation southeast of Madras.
   In Madras, India, a Sri Lankan Tamil party blamed the attack on
Sinhalese militants from the left-wing People's Liberation Front.
   Ponnudurai Ravinesan, spokesman for the Eelam People's
Revolutionary Liberation Front, said he had information from Sri
Lanka that the grenades were thrown by radicals from the Sinhalese
group.
   The front has usually attacked only fellow Sinhalese since
launching an uprising against the government in 1987. It has accused
the Sinhalese-dominated government of selling out its own people to
make peace with Tamil rebels.
   Bandara said Dharamadasa Banda, minister of state for
rehabilitation, and other Parliament members were walking with the
procession from a Hindu temple to a Buddhist dagoba when three
grenades were hurled. Banda, a Sinhalese Buddhist who is the
religious chief for the two shrines, was among those injured,
Bandara said.
   The two shrines, which are about a half-mile apart, are located
in the predominantly Sinhalese district of Monaragala. The largely
Tamil district of Amparai borders Monaragala to its north.
   Tamil guerrillas embarked on a separatist war in 1983, targeting
the predominantly Sinhalese Sri Lankan security forces and Sinhalese
civilians.
   In 1987, India attempted to mediate peace on the island of 16
million people by signing an accord with the Sri Lankan government
that was designed to give Tamils in northern and eastern Sri Lanka
some autonomy.
   Indian troops were dispatched to the island to supervise a
surrender of arms by Tamil guerrillas, but the most militant Tamils
reneged on the pact and began battling the Indians.
   The Sri Lankan government this summer opened negotiations with
Tamil militants, and President Ranasinghe Premadasa subsequently
demanded that India withdraw its estimated 40,000 soldiers by the
end of July.
   Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi of India has said a premature pullout
would lead to even more bloodshed.
   Since 1983, about 14,000 people have died in the ethnic strife.
The government blames the Sinhalese extremists for about 3,500 of
the killings. The others, including nearly 1,000 Indian soldiers,
died in the Tamil insurrection.
   Sinhalese comprise about 75 percent of Sri Lanka's people. Tamils
make up 18 percent and say they are discriminated against by
Sinhalese in education, jobs and use of the Sinhala language.
   There also are small Moslem and Christian communities.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890719-0053 </DOCNO>
