<FIRST>r w PM-Jackson-Barry     07-19 0242</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Jackson-Barry,240</SECOND>
<HEAD>D.C. Mayor, Possible Rival Huddle</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   District of Columbia Mayor Marion Barry Jr. and
Jesse L. Jackson met into the early morning today at Jackson's
hotel, as speculation continued about the former Democratic
presidential candidate's possible run for Barry's job.
   Barry, accompanied by Walter F. Fauntroy, the district's delegate
to Congress, told The Washington Post after the 90-minute meeting
that the session had been about ``faith.''
   Jackson said Tuesday that he would establish his legal residence
in the nation's capital when he moves here later this year.
   However, he sidestepped questions about whether he would run for
mayor.
   When asked whether he would end all speculation by saying
unequivocally that he would not join the 1990 race for mayor,
Jackson said: ``I will not bear the burden of your frustration.''
   Jackson would have to become a legal D.C. resident by Nov. 6, one
year before the 1990 election, to be a qualified candidate.
   He has owned a house in D.C. since 1984, but has resided in
Chicago where the Rainbow Coalition, the political organization he
founded, has its headquarters.
   The coalition is relocating to Washington, and Jackson said he
will be living her by Sept. 1.
   The Jackson-Barry meeting, which ended at 12:45 a.m. today, was
the first between the two men since Barry said through aides last
week he would seek a fourth term as mayor.
   Jackson has repeatedly stated he would not run against Barry.
</TEXT>
