<FIRST>r a PM-GangRape     07-19 0455</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gang Rape,0468</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman Tells of Gang Rape, Beating</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL C. BUELOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JANESVILLE, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman told jurors she was gang raped by
teen-agers who kicked her husband in the face and shouted ``die,
die, die,'' while people in the neighborhood who saw the attack
refused her pleas for help.
   ``I saw a lot of people in their doors and windows, but no one
would help us. I thought I was going to be the only one to save my
husband,'' she said.
   Defense lawyer Walter Isaacson told jurors in his opening
comments Tuesday that the woman was a willing participant in sex
acts and the violence started after her husband decided ``that was
enough'' and the couple tried to leave.
   The 46-year-old woman was the first witness to testify in the
Rock County Circuit Court trial of Anthony Merriweather, 18, and
Craig Clifton, 19.
   They were among five people charged with first-degree sexual
assault and aggravated battery in the Nov. 10 attack on the couple
outside a tavern and in a surrounding working-class neighborhood in
Beloit, a small industrial city in southern Wisconsin.
   Deirick Conner, 18; Stanley Peacock, 19; and Tyree McAtee, 18,
pleaded guilty last week and face sentencing Aug. 22. The pleas came
in exchange for a prosecution promise not to seek maximum penalties.
   The woman testified she was sexually assaulted about a dozen
times by the five young men after they threatened to kill her and
her husband.
   The assaults started at the bar entrance, which was locked for
construction, she said. Her husband was pushed and punched when he
tried to pull her toward their car, she said.
   The assaults continued at a nearby house where she said she heard
one person tell her husband, ``You must not care very much about her
if you brought her here,'' and, ``She's ours now.''
   After struggling free, going outside and screaming for someone to
call the police, she said, ``I saw these guys running up and kicking
him (her husband) in the face.
   ``He was lying on his side and they'd come up and kick him. They
were saying `die, die, die,''' she said in a cracked, tearful voice.
She broke down later when shown a picture of her injured husband.
   Charlotte Golden, 17, said she was in her living room, heard
yelling and screaming outside and looked to see a group of
teen-agers ``hitting and beating on something in the middle of the
street.''
   Miss Golden said the woman ran into her front yard and screamed,
``Help me. They are trying to kill me.''
   But she said, ``I told her to get out of my yard ... because I
thought she was a prostitute.''
</TEXT>
