<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-89 0836EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Namibia-UN     07-19 0418</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Namibia-UN,0433</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Chief Tries to Untie Namibian Knots</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WDH1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.N. Secretary General Javier Perez de
Cuellar today began three days of talks aimed at resolving what he
called ``critical problems'' in a yearlong independence plan for
Namibia.
   The United Nations chief met with senior U.N. officials in the
territory. He was scheduled to hold talks with all major political
parties and Namibia's South African administrator, Louis Pienaar.
   ``I want to ensure that conditions are created that will enable
the holding of free and fair elections'' in November, Perez de
Cuellar said upon his arrival in Namibia late Tuesday night.
   South Africa, which has ruled Namibia since World War I, agreed
in December to carry out the U.N. independence plan under terms of a
regional peace accord. Under the U.S.-brokered pact, South Africa
also pledged to halt aid to guerrillas battling the Angolan
government.
   In exchange, the agreement stipulated that the estimated 50,000
Cuban troops supporting the Angolan government would be withdrawn.
   More than 5,000 U.N. personnel are in Namibia to monitor the
independence process in the territory.
   Perez de Cuellar indicated the independence plan is on track but
said ``critical problems remain.''
   He did not elaborate, but the remark was interpreted as a
reference to mutual suspicion between Namibia's South African
administration and the South-West Africa People's Organization, or
SWAPO, the group favored in the elections. SWAPO fought a 23-year
guerrilla war in an effort to drive out the South Africans.
   On Tuesday, SWAPO accused Pienaar of creating a ``war hysteria''
by claiming 1,900 SWAPO fighters were massed near the Angola-Namibia
border.
   SWAPO and U.N. officials said they found nothing to support the
claims during a visit to northern Namibia over the weekend.
   More than 1,000 armed guerrillas crossed into Namibia on April 1,
the day the independence plan took effect. The ensuing three weeks
of fighting left more than 300 guerrillas and 27 security force
members dead, and it jeopardized the independence plan.
   Perez de Cuellar is also expected to look into charges of
intimidation by the police force.
   An estimated 3,000 paramilitary police have been incorporated
into the regular police force, and SWAPO says they are harassing its
supporters.
   Perez de Cuellar was to visit several northern towns Thursday to
examine the security situation and observe repatriation of Namibian
refugees. A total of 41,000 refugees are to come home.
   The U.N. chief heads Friday to South Africa for talks with
government leaders there.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
