<FIRST>r i PM-Britain-China     07-19 0505</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-China,0520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officials Say Chinese Journalist Returned to Beijing on His Own</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Chinese journalist who fled to Britain following
the crackdown on pro-democracy protesters in his homeland returned
to Beijing because he wanted to, British and Chinese officials said
today.
   A Home Office spokesman said Xu Haining contacted the Chinese
Embassy on Monday and asked to return to China. He left the country
Tuesday after assuring an immigration officer at Heathrow Airport
that he wanted to leave, the official said.
   The spokesman, speaking anonymously in keeping with British
custom, would not comment on a report in The Daily Telegraph that Xu
turned himself over to the Chinese Embassy after veiled threats
against his mother appeared in a Chinese newspaper.
   Xu, 26, a prominent activist in the Chinese Democracy Movement
based in Hong Kong, had been granted permission June 30 to remain in
Britain for one year.
   A spokesman for the Chinese Embassy said Xu left ``of his own
free will.''
   The spokesman, also requesting anonymity, said Xu went to the
embassy July 9 seeking help to return home to be reunited with his
parents.
   ``We give our assurance that he will not be persecuted on his
return,'' the spokesman said. ``Everything will be all right for
him. He contacted the embassy himself. We did not know he was in
London until he came here.''
   Asked what reason Xu gave for wishing to leave Britain, the Home
Office spokesman said: ``I can't go into the individual conversation
that was held, but suffice it to say that he made a statement that
it was of his own volition.''
   The Daily Telegraph said Xu was escorted by officials from the
Chinese Embassy. The Chinese Embassy said a consular official
traveled with Xu to Frankfurt, where he caught a connecting flight
alone to Beijing.
   The newspaper quoted unidentified sources in Hong Kong, where Xu
had worked as a researcher for China's official Xinhua News Agency,
as saying he surrendered after seeing a newspaper advertisement that
suggested his mother might be harmed.
   The Evening Standard said the ad appeared July 10 and July 11 in
Singtao, a Chinese language newspaper published in London, and that
it said in part: ``Your mother is very grieved and worried, cannot
eat, sleep and (is) crying incessantly. In poor health. Please
speedily report your safety, otherwise consequences cannot be
foreseen. Everything will be as you wish.''
   The ad was signed ``your family,'' the newspaper said.
   The Home Office spokesman said he could not comment on where Xu
had been staying.
   ``Xu Haining was here legally, and somebody who is here legally
and holding a valid passport cannot be stopped from leaving the
country,'' he added.
   The Daily Telegraph said Xu escaped to London with the help of
the underground network that also assisted student leader Wu'er
Kaixi and university professor Yan Jiaqi, both of whom now are in
Paris.
   Xu fled China after speaking out against the Chinese leadership
following the military crackdown June 3-4 on demonstrators in
Beijing.
</TEXT>
