<FIRST>r w PM-Elderly-Suicide     07-19 0279</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Elderly-Suicide,270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Suicide Increasing Among Elderly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The suicide rate among elderly Americans has
increased in recent years, federal statistics show.
   The suicides rate among people aged 75 to 84 jumped 21 percent,
from 20.8 per 100,000 people in 1979 to 25.2 per 100,000 in 1986,
according to data compiled by the National Center for Health
Statistics.
   During that same period the suicide rate for all Americans edged
up 5 percent, from 12.1 per 100,000 to 12.8 per 100,000.
   The figures, included in a detailed national mortality report for
1986, did not include an explanation for the increase.
   The 21 percent suicide jump among the 75-84 group was followed by
a 16 percent increase for people aged 85 and over. Their rate rose
from 17.9 per 100,000 to 20.8 between 1979 and 1986.
   For the 65-74 age group the suicide increase was nearly 11
percent, from 17.8 to 19.7 per 100,000; there was a 2 percent rise
from 16.6 to 17.0 among people aged 55 to 64.
   The figures showed a sharp 50 percent increase in the rate for
youngsters aged 5 to 14, but that rate was still so low that only a
small change results in a big percentage difference. The rate rose
from 0.4 per 100,000 in 1979 to 0.8 in 1986.
   For the 15-24 age group, suicides were up 5 percent from 12.4 per
100,000 to 13.1 in 1986.
   Other rates were 15.7 per 100,000 in 1986 for people aged 25 to
34, down from 16.3 in 1979; 15.2 per 100,000 population for those 35
to 44, down from 15.4; and 16.4 per 100,000 for people 45 to 54,
down from 16.5.
</TEXT>
