<HEAD>News Reports Say Britain, Vietnam Will Force Return of Refugees</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 1 graf after 3rd, `The British...' to UPDATE with Hong
Kong officials refusing comment. ADDS 4 grafs after last pvs, `The press...'
with background on repatriation program, comment from U.N. official. No
pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain and Vietnam have agreed secretly to force
thousands of Vietnamese refugees in Hong Kong to return to Vietnam,
British news reports said today.
   The Guardian newspaper said the agreement was confirmed by
government officials in London and in Hong Kong. It did not identify
the officials.
   The British Broadcasting Corp. said without attribution in a
radio bulletin that details of the reported agreement had been
disclosed in Hong Kong.
   The Foreign Office would not confirm the report, and Hong Kong
officials refused comment.
   The Guardian said the refugees to be repatriated have been
classified as economic migrants from Vietnam rather than genuine
refugees. It said more than half the 50,000 boat people in Hong Kong
are likely to be sent back to Vietnam.
   The BBC said the reported agreement has been kept secret to avoid
provoking possible unrest among refugees in the British colony.
   The number of people fleeing Vietnam has increased in recent
years, many due to the poor state of Vietnam's economy rather than
political oppression. Many nations that have been accepting the
refugees have called for limits.
   The Guardian report quoted one source as saying the repatriations
could begin within a week. It said a meeting between British Foreign
Secretary Sir Geoffrey Howe and his Vietnamese counterpart, Nguyen
Co Thach, on June 28 had paved the way for the agreement.
   The paper also said Britain has agreed to end its embargo on
economic aid to Vietnam and will provide various forms of assistance.
   A Foreign Office press officer, who spoke on condition of
anonymity in keeping with British custom, said talks between British
and Vietnamese officials were still going on and that the granting
of British development aid to Vietnam was dependent on the
withdrawal of Vietnamese troops from Cambodia.
   The press officer added: ``We have nothing to announce on the
outcome of those talks yet.''
   Robert van Leeuwen, head of the U.N. High Commissioner for
Refugees in the colony, said he has not been informed of an
agreement between Britain and Vietnam.
   Van Leeuwen also said a group of Vietnamese officials would
arrive in Hong Kong on Wednesday night to interview 300 boat people
who have volunteered to return to their homeland instead of
remaining in detention centers in the British colony.
   So far, 143 boat people have returned to their country under a
program of voluntary repatriation. Another group is expected to fly
back in about one month, the U.N. official said.
   He added that there were indications the number of boat people
volunteering to return home is increasing.
</TEXT>
