<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-89 0948EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-CannibalismDig     07-19 0438</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cannibalism Dig,0448</SECOND>
<HEAD>Scientists Find Human Bones</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Alferd is cq.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELLEN MILLER HADDOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAKE CITY, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Experts seeking victims of 19th century
cannibal Alferd Packer dug up eleven bones, probably all from the
same man, but couldn't immediately tell how the person died or if he
was eaten.
   ``We haven't found anything to date to indicate sharp implement
marks,'' said Walter Birkby, a physical anthropologist from the
Arizona State Museum in Tucson.
   The first bone, the left temporal bone from the side of a human
skull, was found Tuesday by an expedition organized by Washington
University law professor James Starrs. Others came from a foot, leg
and hands.
   Birkby said the condition of the first bones found made him
optimistic he might be able to recognize knife marks, gunshot
wounds, or post-mortem breakage of the bones that could indicate
cannibalism.
   The diggers hope to sift the truth from the legends that have
grown up around the deaths of five Utah men who went with Packer on
a gold-prospecting trip in the San Juan Mountains in 1874.
   Packer, who admitted eating his companions' remains, was the sole
survivor. The way he told it, the group got snowbound on the
9,000-foot mountain ridge in 1874.
   He said Shannon Bell, one of the party, killed the other four
while Packer was away from camp. Packer said he killed Bell in
self-defense and ate the remains of the five men to survive.
   Packer was convicted of murdering one of the prospectors, Israel
Swan, on April 13, 1883, but the state Supreme Court overturned the
sentence and when he was retried, Packer was convicted of
manslaughter.
   Packer was sentenced to serve 40 years in prison, but was paroled
in 1901. He died April 24, 1907.
   The gravesite of the five victims has been set off by a marker,
which honors the five men ``who were murdered on this spot early in
the year 1874 while pioneering for mineral resources of the San Juan
country.''
   Working in short-sleeved shirts, hiking shorts and hats, and
using common garden tooks, archaeologist Jim Ayres, Birkby and some
of their graduate students dug about 6 inches under the marker
Tuesday before locating parallel rows of rock that they speculated
marked the graves of the five men. The first bone was found a short
time later.
   Lab work will determine age, cause of death and other details the
bones may be able to provide, Ayres said. The searchers' next task
was to find if there are five separate graves or if all the victims
bones were interred in one large pit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
