<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-SalesTax     07-19 0556</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Sales Tax,0576</SECOND>
<HEAD>Uno Hints at Reform of Sales Tax</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ERIC TALMADGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Sousuke Uno said in a campaign speech
today he will reconsider parts of a new sales tax that polls
indicate will cost his scandal-plagued party dearly in Sunday's
parliamentary elections.
   In her own electoral foray, Uno's wife, Chiyo, publicly
apologized for a sex scandal resulting from charges that her husband
kept a paid mistress.
   On his first campaign tour outside Tokyo since campaigns for the
upper house elections began July 5, Uno said people may feel some
``perplexity'' about the 3 percent tax that took effect April 1.
   ``If there are areas that need review, I hope to take
responsibility and correct them,'' Uno told reporters in Osaka
during a televised news conference. He did not elaborate.
   His governing Liberal Democratic Party bulldozed a tax reform
package, including the new sales tax, through Parliament late last
year. Opposition parties boycotted the proceedings, mainly in
protest over the role of the Liberal Democrats in an
influence-buying scandal.
   The scandal forced Uno's predecessor, Noboru Takeshita, to resign
June 2. Recruit Co., a publishing conglomerate accused of trying to
gain influence with the government, sold stock at cut-rate prices to
politicians and bureaucrats. Stockholders made big profits after the
stock went public.
   The opposition has claimed the sales tax, which has now become a
major election issue, would create an unfair burden on low-income
households.
   In other comments on his campaign swing, Uno said he does not
foresee a major loss Sunday.
   But at a separate news conference today, Ryutaro Hashimoto, the
party's No. 2 executive, hinted at a possible alliance with the
conservative opposition Democratic Socialists if the Liberal
Democrats lose many seats, the Japan Broadcasting Corp. reported.
   The Liberal Democrats are mainstream conservatives.
   Uno's own popularity has suffered after claims he paid a geisha
to be his mistress, and he generally has kept a low profile in the
campaign so far.
   In her apology today, the prime minister's wife spoke to a rally
of more than 5,000 women supporters of the Liberal Democratic Party.
``I deeply apologize for the criticism regarding my husband,'' she
told the audience.
   Uno himself has said only that he did nothing immoral. But
women's groups have denounced him, turning the sex scandal into
another major campaign issue.
   Polls indicate the Liberal Democrats, who have governed Japan for
34 years, will be an underdog in Sunday's elections for half the 252
seats in the upper house.
   The Liberal Democrats now hold 142 seats in the chamber,
including 73 not affected by this election. While it needs to win 54
on Sunday to maintain a majority, the latest poll indicated it will
capture only 33. The poll had a margin of error of five.
   The poll by the national newspaper Mainichi Shimbun also
predicted major gains for the leading opposition group, the Japan
Socialist Party, from its current 21 seats to a total of up to 70
seats.
   The predictions were based on interviews July 14-16 with 34,237
eligible voters picked at random across the country.
   In the survey, the Liberal Democrats' support rating was 27
percent, 18 points lower than in a similar poll before the last
election in 1986. Support for the Socialists climbed to 30 percent
from 13 percent.
</TEXT>
