<FIRST>r i PM-Hungary-SpecialDay     07-19 0308</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hungary-Special Day,0317</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hungary May Honor Day of 1956 Uprising</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Budapest's Communist Party has proposed
that Oct. 23, the day the 1956 anti-Stalinist uprising broke out, be
celebrated as a symbol of popular will for democratic reform.
   The proposal was indicative of the dramatic changes in the
party's assessment of the revolt.
   Only last year there was an official ban on any public gathering
Oct. 23, causing opposition groups to cancel a planned march while
thousands of police prevented groups from forming around sites
associated with the revolt.
   The ruling Communist Party this year reversed its decades-long
official assesment of the revolt as a counter-revolution, saying it
began as a popular uprising.
   Andras Fabriczky, a secretary of the Budapest Communist Party
committee, told the official news agency MTI Tuesday that
participants in the protests that broke out Oct. 23, 1956 with calls
for greater democracy, espoused reform ideas now also embraced by
the current Communist Party leadership.
   Oct. 23, should be a day of ``national reconciliation,'' marked
jointly by opposition groups and the party, MTI quoted Fabriczky as
saying.
   The Budapest committee said it also supported proposals by
opposition groups and reform communists that a square be named after
Imre Nagy, the premier during the revolt who was executed in 1958 on
charges of high treason.
   Earlier this month, the Hungarian Supreme Court canceled all
charges against Nagy in a move amounting to his legal rehabilitation.
   Last month his remains were reburied in an elaborate funeral
ceremony attended by hundreds of thousands, and the party and
government have embraced him as a forerunner of communist reforms.
   MTI quoted Fabriczky as saying the formal naming of a square
should take place Oct. 23, as well as the laying of a cornerstone
for a monument to the memory of the ``heroes and victims'' of 1956.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
