<DOCNO> AP890719-0067 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-89 1003EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-OzoneOrdinance     07-19 0457</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ozone Ordinance,0471</SECOND>
<HEAD>Irvine Adopts Stringent Measures To Curtail Ozone-Destroying Materials</HEAD>
<DATELINE>IRVINE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   City officials have approved a ban next
year on plastic food containers, coolants, solvents and other
products containing chlorofluorocarbons that deplete the Earth's
ozone.
   According to a city ordinance adopted Tuesday, local businesses
will be banned from buying, selling or using products containing
chloroflurocarbons, or CFCs, as of July 1, 1990.
   Scientists say CFCs are destroying the Earth's ozone layer, which
screens the sun's ultraviolet rays. Exposure to large doses of
ultraviolet rays can lead to skin cancer and other diseases.
   The measure, approved by a 4-1 vote, is believed to be one of the
most comprehensive ever adopted, city officials said.
   ``We think it is the most far-reaching ordinance in the United
States,'' said Mayor Larry Agran, who proposed the measure. ``We
think it will set the standard nationally and globally.''
   Under terms of the ordinance, violators would be fined $50 for a
first offense, $100 for a second offense and $250 for each
subsequent offense. Each day of noncompliance with the ordinance
would be considered a violation.
   The ordinance also creates the job of environmental program
coordinator, a person who would work with businesses to find
alternative compounds to those containing CFCs and who would have
authority to grant exemptions to the ordinance.
   CFCs are found in such products as coolants, cleaning solvents
and plastic food containers, including plastic coffee cups. They
have already been banned in aerosol products made in the United
States.
   Companies in this city 40 miles southeast of Los Angeles that are
expected to be most affected by the ban include insulation
installers, food packagers, fire extinguisher manufacturers, air
conditioning and refrigeration repair operations, and electronics
manufacturers.
   The ordinance will not ban the use of CFCs in automobile air
conditioners and refrigerators, but it will require service stations
and repair shops to capture and recycle the compounds.
   Several representatives of businesses that would be affected
spoke out against the ordinance during a 2{-hour hearing attended by
about 100 people.
   Scott Byington, an air conditioning serviceman, said the
ordinance would increase the price of home air conditioner repairs
from an average of $60 to $200.
   ``You're going to have a flood of exemption applications,'' said
Keith Lehm, Western regional manager for General Chemicals in
Wilmington, Del., a national manufacturer of CFCs. He called the
measure overzealous and disruptive.
   Alex Sapre, corporate projects manager for Hughes Aircraft Co.
said the issue would be better left to national or international
environmental experts.
   ``CFCs are a global concern and therefore need a global
solution,'' Sapre said.
   ``If we wait until all these people take action, we might as well
kiss off the future of the globe,'' the mayor said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890719-0068 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-89 1015EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-ArsenicPoisoning 1stLd-Writethru a0538 07-19 0475</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Arsenic Poisoning, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0538,0482</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman Charged in Death of Ex-Boyfriend, Ex-Husband</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with court appearance today; ADDS
background on victims; ADDS byline. Pick up 8th graf pvs: `At a news...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBIN TEATER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GRAHAM, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman charged with murder in the arsenic
poisonings of her former husband and former boyfriend and assault in
the non-fatal poisoning of her present husband made her first court
appearance today.
   Blanche Taylor Moore, 56, who was arrested Tuesday in Burlington,
waived her right to a court-appointed attorney during the brief
hearing in Alamance County Superior Court and was scheduled for a
probable cause hearing Aug. 1. She is being held without bond on the
murder charges.
   The investigation began after her present husband, the Rev.
Dwight Moore, was hospitalized May 7 because of nausea and vomiting
and his illness was traced to arsenic poisoning. Two bodies already
have been exhumed and authorities have suggested the probe could
widen to include other deaths.
   The charges against her:
   _First-degree murder in the 1973 death of her first husband,
James Taylor, filed by the Burlington Police Department. The body of
Taylor, a 45-year-old furniture refinisher, was exhumed two weeks
ago and found to have traces of arsenic poisoning.
   _First-degree murder in the 1986 death of Raymond C. Reid Sr., a
former boyfriend, in a warrant issued by the Forsyth County
Sheriff's Department. Reid, a grocer in Kernersville, signed a will
a month before he died leaving equal shares of his $68,000 estate to
Mrs. Moore and his two sons. Authorities exhumed his body and
determined that he had been poisoned.
   _Assault with a deadly weapon with intent to kill in the arsenic
poisoning of her current husband, who is being treated at North
Carolina Memorial Hospital in Chapel Hill, filed by the Alamance
County Sheriff's Department.
   At a news conference announcing the charges, authorities refused
to provide details of their two-month probe, or to give a possible a
motive.
   Alamance County Sheriff Richard Frye said his department has a
``short list'' of deaths that he will investigate in connection with
Mrs. Moore. But he declined to give names.
   ``We still have some follow-up to do,'' Frye said.
   Officials refused to say who owned the residence where Mrs. Moore
was arrested, how long she had stayed there, or whether she was
alone when arrested.
   ``We're just going where the investigation leads us,'' said Lt.
Steve Lynch of the Burlington Police Department.
   The charges were announced hours after an Alamance Superior Court
judge's order was filed Tuesday to exhume the body of the woman's
father, Parker D. Kiser Sr., who died in 1966.
   State medical examiner Dr. John Butts has said that Mrs. Moore's
former boyfriend and former husband died of heart failure caused by
arsenic poisoning.
</TEXT>
