<FIRST>u w PM-US-Cuba-Drugs 1stLd-Writethru a0439 07-19 0772</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Cuba-Drugs, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0439,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cuban Diplomat Meets With State Department on Drug Issue</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: To UPDATE with comments today from Cuban and Coast Guard spokesmen,
SUBS 2nd graf with 1 graf, SUBS 10th graf pvs bgng, `People who,' with
3 grafs, and SUBS 14th graf pvs bgng, `A spokesman,' with 2 grafs; inserts
phrase `the issue of' in parentheses in 3rd graf, `However, another'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal official says the United States wants
decisive action by Cuba against drug-smuggling, as that country
makes overtures for a joint anti-drug campaign, including a reported
meeting with a State Department official.
   Word of the meeting between a top Cuban diplomat and Michael
Kozak, deputy assistant secretary of state for inter-American
affairs, came Tuesday from Rep. Charles Rangel, D-N.Y., and was
confirmed today by a Cuban official.
   However, another State Department official, who spoke on
condition of anonymity, said, ``We have raised (the issue of)
narcotics with the Cubans on many, many occasions over the years.''
   ``We certainly think there's ample room for the Cubans to take
action,'' he said. ``We're looking for deeds rather than just
words.''
   He declined to accept Cuba's execution last week of four military
officials _ including a hero of the revolution _ for drug
trafficking as sufficient evidence of that country's commitment to
the war against drugs.
   The United States is waiting for such actions as ``interdicting
drugs, stopping the flow over their territory,'' the official said.
   Rangel said he was told of the meeting between Kozak and Jose
Antonio Arbesu Fraga, the new chief of the Cuban Interests Section,
by Arbesu and his assistant chief, Manuel Davis. The Cuban Interests
Section is that country's substitute for an embassy, attached
formally to the Czechoslovakian Embassy.
   The Cubans said Tuesday they ``have talked with the State
Department and told them that Cuba is waiting to see how Havana can
better establish a dialogue, because no matter what the political
differences are, no one can allow the drug traffickers to take
advantage,'' Rangel said.
   They also said they told Kozak they are ``willing to cooperate in
any international anti-drug venture,'' said Rangel, who chairs the
House Select Committee on Narcotics Abuse and Control.
   Clinton Adlum, a spokesman for the Cuban Interests Section, said
today that Arbesu, who arrived in the United States in June, ``has
visited with several officials at the State Department, including
Mr. Kozak. In these conversations ... the drug problem has come up.''
   However, Adlum said, there still is no ongoing dialogue between
the countries on cooperation in anti-drug efforts.
   ``Cuba is definitely interested in this,'' Adlum said. ``We have
always been interested in cooperation with anybody, including the
United States.''
   The State Department official said Kozak had ``met with Cuban
representatives many times over the years,'' but he declined to say
whether the specific meeting in question had taken place, or what
might have been discussed.
   One indication of possible change in the U.S. stance was the
cancellation of a closed-door Coast Guard briefing of Rangel's
committee on U.S.-Cuban drug cooperation.
   The meeting was scheduled for early Tuesday morning, but Coast
Guard Commandant Adm. Paul Yost called Rangel late Monday to cancel
it, saying ``changing developments'' were responsible, according to
Rangel.
   A Coast Guard spokesman, Lt. Cmdr Marc W. Wolfson said today,
``The admiral had to cancel the briefing because the administration
thought it would be premature to give a briefing while they're
reviewing the situation and taking a look at the circumstances in
the Caribbean right now.''
   While Wolfson declined to speculate on a possible change in U.S.
attitudes toward cooperation with Cuba, he said he believed the
State Department had advised Yost to hold off on the briefing.
   Cuban leader Fidel Castro called last week for cooperation
between the two countries to combat drugs.
   ``We need some way to communicate in this common battle,'' Castro
said in a four-hour speech to the Cuban Council of State. ``We need
to talk to the Americans about how to manage this situation.''
   He contended the United States failed to warn him of Cuban
military involvement in cocaine trafficking, saying the United
States had ``at least two names'' of military officers involved in a
cocaine-trafficking conspiracy long before contacts in Colombia
alerted Cuban officials.
   Last Thursday, one of Castro's trusted advisors, Army Maj. Gen.
Arnaldo Ochoa Sanchez, and three other military officers were
executed for smuggling tons of drugs into the United States.
   The drug scandal stunned and embarrassed Castro and his communist
government, which for years denied U.S. accusations that Cuba was
being used to smuggle cocaine and marijuana.
</TEXT>
