<FIRST>r a PM-HostageShootings 1stLd-Writethru a0512 07-19 0613</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hostage Shootings, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0512,0628</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man With History of Taking Hostages Kills Daughter, Self</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Rewrites throughout to RECAST lead, add daughter's last name,
CORRECT that survivor was stepmother, sted mother, of victim. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT MILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MASTIC, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man with a long history of family violence
fatally shot his 18-year-old daughter, wounded an officer trying to
rescue the woman and then killed himself, ignoring pleas from a
policeman who had persuaded him to surrender in a previous hostage
incident.
   Suffolk County police found the bodies of James Hyames, 59, and
his daughter, Lisa Fotiathis, at 7:30 p.m. Tuesday in their Mastic
home.
   Hyames had argued with Ms. Fotiathis just before noon, prompting
the young woman's stepmother, Marcine Hyames, to leave the house,
said Lt. William Kiley.
   Soon after, Mrs. Hyames heard a shot, ran back to the house and
saw Ms. Fotiathis lying on the floor and her husband holding a
handgun, Kiley said.
   She ran to a neighbor's and called police, Kiley said.
   Hyames fired at the first two officers on the scene, prompting
police to surround the house and evacuate nearby homes.
   About 2:15 p.m., a team of officers stormed the house to try to
rescue Ms. Fotiathis, who they thought was still alive. Hyames fired
again, grazing the head of Officer John Keene, 32, and police
retreated, said Suffolk County police spokesman Salvatore Yovino.
Keene's wound was superficial.
   Hyames was married several times and had a history of violence
against relatives.
   In Colorado 20 years ago, he shot his pregnant wife. She survived
but lost the baby and he went to prison, Kiley said.
   In 1974, in Carlstadt, N.J., Hyames held his wife and two
children hostage for 19 hours, keeping police at bay with gunfire. A
Roman Catholic priest and Carlstadt Deputy Police Chief John
Occhiuzzo talked Hyames into surrendering, and he served time in
jail, said Lt. Herb Scheidewig of the Carlstadt police.
   He kept in touch with Occhiuzzo over the years and during
Tuesday's standoff with Suffolk police, Hyames telephoned Occhiuzzo,
told him he'd shot his daughter and that police were after him.
   Occhiuzzo then drove to Mastic at the Suffolk police's request
and tried, with relatives and others, to get Hyames to surrender or
permit police to take Ms. Fotiathis to the hospital.
   Among the relatives who spoke to Hyames by telephone at the scene
was his daughter, Carol Ianelli, who hadn't spoken to her father in
15 years.
   ``That's what he does,'' she said after her sister's body was
found. ``This is him. I'm not surprised.''
   She said he told her on the telephone that he ``shot Lisa and
she's lying in a pool of blood'' and that he was ``not going back to
jail. Life is over for me.''
   Mrs. Ianello told reporters Hyames had recently caught Ms.
Fotiathis in bed with a man.
   Hyames was also angry because Ms. Fotiathis recently sold a car
against his wishes and had moved in with a boyfriend, said Kiley and
Sgt. William Pepper.
   Pepper said throughout the ordeal Hyames was ``very adamant that
he was not coming out, no matter what.''
   About 5:30 p.m., police connected Hyames on the phone with a
grown son, Mark, in Harrisburg, Pa. A few minutes later, Hyames said
goodbye to him, hung up and a shot rang out, police said.
   Police sprayed the house with tear gas, went in and found the
bodies.
   Neighbors and relatives said Hyames had worked at various jobs,
including as a security guard and a mechanic.
   It was not immediately clear whether the Colorado, New Jersey and
Long Island incidents involved different wives.
</TEXT>
