<FIRST>r a PM-RadioactiveLemonade     07-19 0287</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Radioactive Lemonade,0297</SECOND>
<HEAD>Worker Claims Someone Laced His Lemonade With Radioactive Material</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SCRIBA, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A nuclear plant worker who told authorities
he purposely drank lemonade he'd laced with radioactive material now
says someone else spiked his drink.
   ``The individual who said he spiked his lemonade has changed his
story and says he did not do it,'' said Cliff Spieler, spokesman for
the New York Power Authority, which runs the James A. FitzPatrick
plant on Lake Ontario.
   The investigation of the non-sickening dose of cobalt-60 and
other materials now becomes a criminal probe, Spieler said Tuesday.
   ``I won't vouch for his new story,'' Spieler said. ``But we've
got to go on the assumption that what he is saying now would be
correct.''
   The power authority disclosed Monday that the worker, a temporary
supervisor at the plant, told his investigators of drinking the
radioactive lemonade Friday after he set off a radiation scanner on
his way home from work.
   Authorities refused to reveal the man's name.
   He was monitored to determine precisely how much radioactive
material he ingested, but he wasn't hospitalized.
   The worker gave no indication why he changed his story, Spieler
said, adding that the power authority has asked for help from the
Oswego County Sheriff's Department.
   No other plant employees have been found who saw the worker drink
lemonade, the spokesman said. The man was supervising work on the
refuel floor, an area where nuclear fuel is loaded and unloaded from
the reactor.
   Officials estimated the worker's dose of radiation at 50 to 75
millirems, comparable to the amount of radiation in five chest
X-rays.
   In addition to cobalt-60, which emits penetrating gamma rays, the
man also swallowed cesium-137 and manganese-54, Schmidt said.
</TEXT>
