<FIRST>r i PM-Mozambique-SAfrica     07-19 0363</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mozambique-SAfrica,0373</SECOND>
<HEAD>South African Party Leader Talks With Mozambican President</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MAPUTO, Mozambique (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   F.W. de Klerk, the politician expected
to be South Africa's next president, met President Joaquim Chissano
for talks today in the National Party leader's first official visit
to a black African state.
   In Lusaka, Zambia today, President Kenneth Kaunda told reporters
he has invited de Klerk to meet with him for talks. Kuanda, one of
Africa's staunchest South Africa opponents, said he offered to meet
de Klerk in Livingstone in southern Zambia ``on any day that is
acceptable'' to him.
   Chissano said Monday that de Klerk had asked for the meeting in
Mozambique, but the South African Broadcasting Corp. said Chissano
requested the talks.
   When a reporter asked Chissano what he hoped to achieve, the
president smiled and pointed at de Klerk saying, ``Later ... he will
tell you what he wants to achieve,'' the national news agency AIM
said.
   In Johannesburg, the state-run South African Broadcasting Corp.
said the talks would include proposals to end Mozambique's 12-year
guerrilla insurgency.
   South Africa at one time supported the Mozambique National
Resistance guerrillas, who have been accused of atrocities against
civilians in their war against the Marxist government.
   Chissano told a news conference Monday that his government no
longer believes the South African government or military support the
guerrillas, although he said ``elements'' in South Africa still
provide aid.
   The South African delegation indicated it wanted to discuss
development aid to Mozambique and improvements to Maputo harbor, the
broadcast report said.
   De Klerk's delegation, which included Foreign Affairs Minister
Pik Botha, was met at the airport by Mozambican Minister of
Cooperation Jacinto Veloso. It then toured a waterfront residential
compound intended for families of South African trade mission
employees.
   The two countries have no formal diplomatic contacts, but
relations have improved dramatically since President P.W. Botha met
Chissano in September.
   De Klerk is expected to become president of South Africa after
P.W. Botha retires following Sept. 6 parliamentary elections.
   In Lusaka, Kaunda, one of Africa's staunchest South Africa
opponents, told reporters he offered to meet de Klerk in Livingstone
in southern Zambia ``on any day that is acceptable'' to him.
</TEXT>
