<FIRST>r i PM-Cambodia     07-19 0307</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cambodia,0315</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vietnamese Leader Supports Cease-Fire Call</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnam's foreign minister, Nguyen Co
Thach, said today the Vietnamese-installed government in Cambodia
should agree to a cease-fire with guerrilla forces opposing it,
official media reported.
   Also today, Prime Minister Hun Sen of Cambodia left for Paris to
attend an international conference on Cambodia starting July 30.
   Also expected at the Paris conference are the Cambodian guerrilla
factions; Vietnam and its ally, Laos; the six-member Association of
Southeast Asian Nations, and in their first collective attempt at
Cambodian peace talks, the five permanent members of the U.N.
Security Council _ Britain, France, the United States, China and the
Soviet Union.
   Vietnam's Radio Hanoi said Thach was asked during an interview on
Vietnamese television about a truce proposal made by Thai Prime
Minister Chatichai Choonhavan a few months ago.
   ``The Cambodian issue cannot be solved peacefully without a
cease-fire,'' Thach replied. ``Therefore, Vietnam fully supports the
Thai prime minister's proposal that the Cambodian parties sign a
cease-fire agreement in Bangkok and considers this as part of a
political solution to the Cambodian issue.''
   Hun Sen and Prince Norodom Sihanouk, leader of the three-party
guerrilla coalition, said in May they agreed in principle with the
proposal. But the Khmer Rouge, the largest and most hard-line
guerrilla force, rejected it.
   Thach also said that in recent talks in Indonesia, ``We have
formed a basis for a political solution to the Cambodian issue,''
but he did not elaborate.
   Vietnam invaded Cambodia in December 1978 and ousted the
communist Khmer Rouge, which killed hundreds of thousands of
Cambodians and attacked Vietnamese border villages during its nearly
four-year reign.
   Vietnam says it will withdraw its 60,000 to 70,000 troops from
Cambodia by Sept. 30, whether or not there is a political settlement
in the war.
</TEXT>
