<HEAD>Officials: Body Parts Found at Illegal Dump Internal Organs, Not
Limbs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal prosecutors said the human body parts
found at an illegal waste site in Brooklyn with alleged mob ties
were internal organs and not external limbs as a published report
said.
   Law enforcement sources cited by the Daily News on Tuesday said
arms, legs and part of a torso were found at the dump in September
after a mob informant tipped investigators that trash hauling
companies were being used to dispose of mob execution victims.
   A spokesman for the city's Department of Investigation, Ron
Davis, blamed poor internal communications in the office for the
discrepancy, the Daily News said today.
   Prosecutors contradicted statements by the city's Department of
Investigation about the grisly discovery at National-Stage Carting
Co. in Bay Ridge, the newspaper said.
   Federal prosecutor Aaron Marcu declined to comment on allegations
connecting the waste disposal companies with mob hits, the newspaper
said.
   ``As we charged in the indictment, an enormous quantity of
illegally stored infectious waste was discovered in an unlicensed
tractor-trailer outside of National Carting,'' Marcu said.
   Federal and city investigators got a search warrant and found the
body parts with four tons of medical waste in a refrigerated trailer
parked on a side street near the company.
   Ben Brafman, a lawyer for the company's owner, Angelo Paccione,
said, ``These were hospital materials. Whether it was disposed of
properly will be resolved at trial.''
   The Daily News said investigators describe Paccione as a major
figure in a carting cartel controlled by the Gambino crime family.
