<FIRST>r a PM-StudioShooting     07-19 0369</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Studio Shooting,0380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Who Went On Studio Rampage May Have Had Dispute With Production
Firm</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Henneberque is cq in 6th graf; Stapf is cq in 9th graf.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BERNIE WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CULVER CITY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who crashed his truck through a
gate at the Lorimar television studio, burned the vehicle and then
killed himself may have had a business dispute with a production
company there, police said.
   ``There may be a possible business dispute involving one of the
on-lot production companies. We just don't know which one,'' police
Capt. Thomas Mahoney said after the rampage Tuesday on the lot where
the TV shows ``Dallas'' and ``Knots Landing'' are made.
   The former Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer studio lot, now owned by
Lorimar-Telepictures Corp., has studios that are rented out to other
production companies.
   Police withheld the name of the dead man until relatives could be
notified. The man randomly fired six shotgun rounds, but no one was
there at the time and no else was wounded, police Lt. Jerry Dalven
said. The man turned the gun on himself when officers arrived and
ordered him to drop the weapon.
   The man drove up to a west gate at the lot shortly after 5 p.m.
Tuesday, police said. He handed a security guard two canisters of
methyl bromide gas and told the guard, ``You have five minutes to
live.''
   Officer Ed Henneberque said the gas is toxic.
   ``The guy just busted through the gates,'' said Bill McCullum, a
Lorimar security guard. ``All I know is I could have been the one
lying on the ground.''
   The driver parked the vehicle against the wall of a studio
building and apparently set it afire with a can of pressurized
lubricant, Henneberque said.
   Dave Stapf, a spokesman for the studio, said the man wasn't
believed to have been a former employee.
   ``At first, we thought it was special effects,'' said Kelly
Hustis, a truck driver at the lot. ``Then we saw the dust fly.''
   ``He didn't seem to want to hurt anybody. He stood there for a
long time telling a security guard to get back, get back,'' Hustis
said.
   The lot was not evacuated during the incident, Stapf said.
</TEXT>
