<FIRST>r i PM-Gulf-Vincennes     07-19 0412</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gulf-Vincennes,0424</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iran Air Families' Lawyer Calls U.S. Offer ``Inadequate''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ABU DHABI, United Arab Emirates (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lawyer representing
families of people who died when a U.S. warship shot down an Iranian
jetliner said today the United States' compensation offer is
``woefully inadequate.''
   The State Department announced Monday it will pay up to $250,000
for each full-time wage earner and up to $100,000 for each of the
others killed in the incident. It said the money would be paid to
selected intermediaries, either government or private, to make sure
it reaches the families.
   Attorney Nagib Y.A. Ghafoor said the money should be paid
directly to the families of the 290 victims rather than going
through intermediaries.
   He also noted that Iraq paid $750,000 to each of the families of
37 U.S. sailors killed when an Iraqi jet mistakenly attacked the USS
Stark in the Persian Gulf in May 1987.
   On July 3, 1988, the USS Vincennes fired missiles at what it
thought was an Iranian jet fighter flying over the Persian Gulf in
preparation for an attack. All 290 people on board the Iran Air
jetliner were killed when the plane crashed into the gulf.
   The State Department said the United States was not obligated
under international law to pay any compensation, and it blamed Iran
in part for the incident because it allowed a commerical jet to fly
over an area where a battle had been going on.
   But it recalled that former President Reagan announced eight days
after the Iran Air incident that the United States would pay
compensation in keeping with American ``humanitarian traditions.''
The proposed amounts were not announced until this week.
   Under the U.S. plan, which officials said was personally approved
by President Bush, the families to receive the money would have to
waive any further claims against the United States.
   The Stark settlement totaled about $27 million. U.S. officials
estimated the Iran Air victims' package could total $30 million.
   Ghafoor said the only difference between the two incidents was
that the Stark victims were military and the Iranian jetliner
carried civilians.
   He said the U.S. offer of ``up to'' certain amounts indicated the
United States intended to negotiate ``to minimize the amount'' of
payments.
   Iran has demanded compensation for the loss of the jet and is
suing the United States in the World Court.
   Relatives of some victims have filed a separate lawsuit against
General Electric Co., makers of the Vincennes' computerized radar
system.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
