<HEAD>Two Palestinians Killed by Israeli Army</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 1 graf and subs 7th pvs, `Soldiers who...' to CORRECT
that one of two Palestinians killed late Tuesday. Pickup 8th pvs, `An army...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli soldiers shot and killed two
Palestinians in battles with protesters in the occupied territories,
the army said today. A third Arab was reported killed as a suspected
collaborator.
   Also today, a 19-year-old Israeli woman died of injuries suffered
earlier this month in a bus crash caused by a Palestinian who
grabbed the steering wheel and forced the bus into a 200-foot ravine.
   The death of the Israel woman, a soldier, raised the death toll
in the July 6 crash to 16. On Tuesday, a 39-year-old woman hurt in
the crash became the first American to die in the Palestinian
uprising.
   In the West Bank, 20-year-old Samir al-Akhras, died after being
shot in a clash with soldiers conducting an early-morning,
search-and-arrest raid in the village of Beit Lid, an army spokesman
said.
   ``One of the forces encountered violent opposition, and in the
confrontation one youth was shot,'' said the spokesman, adding that
an army doctor tried unsuccessfully to revive him.
   In the Gaza Strip, soldiers imposed a curfew on the Khan Yunis
refugee camp following nightlong clashes between troops and
stone-throwers.
   Soldiers who opened fire to quell the violence fatally shot
16-year-old Bassam Farouk Ahmed al-Jabri through the heart late
Tuesday, Arab reports said.
   An army spokesman, speaking on condition of anonymity in line
with regulations, said al-Jabri was shot by soldiers while he was
among youths who were hurling rocks at troops.
   Another Palestinian, 65-year-old Rizik Abdel Razak Berat, was
reported shot to death, apparently by an Arab assailant, in the West
Bank. Arab reports said his body was found in a well in the village
of Taibe and that he was slain because he was suspected of helping
Israeli authorities.
   The army said it had reports of the man's death and police were
investigating.
   More than 80 Palestinians have been killed by fellow Arabs as
suspected collaborators since the rebellion began on Dec. 8, 1987.
   In the uprising 569 Palestinians and 37 Israelis have been
killed. The protesters are trying to drive Israeli occupiers from
the territories, which Israel seized from Arab neighbors in the 1967
Middle East War.
   In the occupied Gaza Strip, four Palestinian boys ages 8 to 14
suffered injuries from rubber bullets fired by troops during
stone-throwing protests today, Arab reports said.
   Another Arab man was shot and wounded by troops in the West Bank
city of Nablus, the reports said.
   The latest victim of the bus crash was identified by hospital and
army officials as Tova Maimon from the Tel Aviv suburb of Or Yehuda.
She died in intensive care.
   On Tuesday, Rita Levine, a lawyer from Philadelphia, died after
suffering serious injuries to her spinal cord and lungs, a
spokeswoman at Hadassah Hospital in Jerusalem said.
</TEXT>
