<FIRST>r a PM-TruantParent     07-19 0289</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Truant Parent,0297</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Sentences Parent to Jail for Allowing Child to Skip School</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mother of a junior high school student has
been sentenced to 10 days in jail for allowing her daughter to miss
101 days of school last year.
   After sentencing Debra Shaw to the maximum jail time, District
Court Judge David W. Young then instructed a jailer to give the
woman's two children a tour of the courthouse holding cells.
   ``Your mother is going to the dirty, funky, stinky Baltimore City
Jail because the two of you have played hooky,'' Young said Tuesday.
   Young blamed the children's truancy on their mother's laziness,
noting that she had failed to show up for several meetings with
school officials before charges were filed.
   ``I don't think she's done anything to get the children to school
except to open the door and show them the way out,'' Young said.
``Ms. Shaw, as far as I'm concerned all you do is take that welfare
check, you don't do anything to help your kids.''
   Ms. Shaw was convicted on one charge of failing to send
14-year-old Shantres Shaw to school.
   Ms. Shaw said her daughter had the flu and a sore throat for the
entire month of February, when Shantres did not attend school at all.
   Young said he had information that Shantres' 13-year-old brother,
James, missed a similar number of days.
   She probably will spend about three to five days in jail before
being released, Young said. Ms. Shaw had told the judge a family
friend would watch the children if she was sent to jail.
   ``I'm going to ... follow up with the school in the fall,'' the
judge said. ``To me, it's a sin.''
</TEXT>
