<FIRST>r i PM-Typhoon     07-19 0246</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Typhoon,0254</SECOND>
<HEAD>Typhoon Gordon Weakens to Tropical Storm; Death Toll at 35</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Typhoon Gordon weakened to a tropical storm today
after roaring through the Philippines, Hong Kong and southern China.
Reports said the death toll from the storm rose to 35 people.
   Chinese television today reported five people were killed, three
wounded and at least 10 missing after Gordon hit southern Guangdong
province Tuesday afternoon. The storm left 29 dead in the
Philippines and one in Hong Kong.
   The State Meteorological Bureau said Gordon was downgraded this
morning to a tropical storm, meaning its winds were less than 73 mph.
   The official Xinhua News Agency said more than 11,000 people in
Zhuhai, on the coast of Guangdong province, were stranded and
transport was cut off between Zhuhai and Doumen, 20 miles to the
west.
   It said 80 percent of the farmland in Doumen county was flooded.
   The television news showed waves crashing over sea walls, flooded
streets and buildings with only their rooftops visible.
   The typhoon, which hit the Philippines early Sunday with 116 mph
winds, left almost 186,000 people homeless on the islands and caused
at least $30 million in damage, according to the Phillipine Office
of Civil Defense. Damage estimates from Hong Kong and southern China
were not yet available.
   The Hong Kong Observatory today said the storm was located over
Zhangjiang, on the southwestern tip of Guangdong province, at
midmorning and was headed northwest at 12 miles an hour.
</TEXT>
