<FIRST>u w PM-ThirdWorldDebt 1stLd-Writethru a0468 07-19 0682</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Third World Debt, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0468,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brady Expects Agreement Between Private Banks, Mexico</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Top 9 grafs new to update with Brady testimony; picks up 7th
graf pvs, Rep. John.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady said today he
expects an agreement ``reasonably soon'' between private banks and
Mexico in the first test of his plan for reducing the $1.3 trillion
debt of poor Third World countries.
   Back from the Paris economic summit, Brady told the Joint
Economic Committee of Congress the endorsement of his plan by the
heads of state of the seven industrial powers puts pressure on
private banks to be more forthcoming in negotiating debt-reduction
agreements.
   Several members of Congress have expressed skepticism about the
workability of the plan and its reliance on government-backed
guarantees to cover interest payments to the private banks on the
remaining balances.
   The administration had sought to put some of those fears to rest,
hoping to announce at the summit an agreement in which Mexico's 15
creditor banks agreed to a 30 percent to 40 percent reduction in the
$54 billion they are owed by its government. No announcement was
made.
   ``I wish it were going faster, but these negotiations are very
complicated and take a long time,'' Brady said today. ``I think
we're going to get resolution reasonably soon.''
   ``And when we do get it,'' he said, ``I think everybody will feel
relieved that the first transaction has taken place and other ones
will follow much more quickly because we know how to do it.''
   Sen. Paul Sarbanes, D-Md., questioned whether private banks in
other countries were resisting the debt-reduction efforts in the
belief that their governments were not as supportive of Brady's plan
as the United States was.
   Last April, a month after the plan was revealed, it received a
qualified endorsement from the finance ministers of the six other
industrial powers _ France, Italy, West Germany, Britain, Japan and
Canada.
   Brady said the significance of the summit was that the issue has
now been ``kicked upstairs to the head-of-state level.''
   Rep. John LaFalce, D-N.Y., said Tuesday the summit may have
produced a recognition by both the private banks and the Bush
administration that Brady's plan cannot work without more direct
government intervention.
   ``The banks have changed their tune,'' said LaFalce, who wants to
establish a new international agency to take the lead on deciding
how to divide losses on Third World loans which have soured.
   ``They realize that the bank advisory committees can't facilitate
it,'' LaFalce said, referring to multinational groups of commercial
bank creditors who have been negotiating debt-reduction agreements
with Third World governments such as Mexico's.
   To pressure the private banks, LaFalce and other lawmakers have
introduced legislation that would effectively cut their profits if
they continue resisting substantial voluntary reductions in what
Third World countries owe.
   At the conclusion of the summit, Bush quipped to reporters that
he was willing to put replace Brady's name with his own on the
debt-reduction plan, but not until there is more evidence it will
work.
   While the Bush administration anticipated a breakthrough during
the summit in negotiations between 15 private banks _ headed by
Citicorp of New York _ on reducing Mexico's $54 billion debt and its
annual interest payments, an accord never materialized.
   Brady's plan was based on the premise that private banks would
forgive large portions of the debt owed them by developing countries
for guarantees from government-financed multinational lenders such
as the World Bank to protect them from further losses.
   Mexico originally sought a 55 percent forgiveness of their debt
to the private banks after Brady announce his plans in March.
   The banks reportedly have offered a 35 percent reduction, but
only on the condition the multinational World Bank and the
International Monetary Fund guarantee the interest payments on the
remaining balance.
   However, the agreement between Bush and the leaders of the six
other industrial powers provides only ``limited interest support''
by their taxpayers through the IMF and World Bank ``for transactions
involving significant debt and debt service reduction.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
