<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-89 1157EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-FishWars     07-19 0487</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fish Wars,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Agents Seize Alleged Kingpin Of Fish Smuggling Ring</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LES BLUMENTAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal agents arrested the alleged kingpin of
a fish-smuggling ring and detained the captains of two Taiwanese
fishing vessels in the North Pacific as part of a sting operation
involving the sale of $1.3 million worth of salmon.
   Brian Gorman, a spokesman for the National Oceanic and
Atmospheric Administration, said today that a U.S. Coast Guard
cutter was continuing to shadow at least two Taiwanese driftnet
vessels about 1,000 miles north of Midway Island that were involved
in the attempted illegal sale of 500 metric tons of salmon.
   Patrick Lee of Taipei, Taiwan, was arrested late Tuesday as he
walked out of the vault of a Seattle bank carrying suitcases filed
with more than $1 million in cash, Gorman said. Two associates of
Lee also were arrested in Seattle, he said.
   Gorman said that as Lee was arrested in Seattle, the fishing
vessel Red Fin chartered by NOAA was rendezvousing with several
Taiwanese vessels in the North Pacific to complete the actual
transfer of the fish.
   When the two captains boarded the Red Fin to arrange details of
the transfer they were detained, but their two vessels fled when the
Coast Guard cutter Morgenthau appeared on the scene, the spokesman
said.
   Congressional sources, who asked not to be identified, said the
State Department had asked the government of Taiwan for permission
to board and inspect the two vessels.
   Gorman said that Lee was being charged today in Seattle with
violations of the Lacey Act, which prohibits commerce in illegally
caught salmon or wildlife. The maximum penalty would be a five-year
prison sentence and $20,000 fine.
   In addition, Gorman said the U.S. attorney in Seattle may file
additional charges and a grand jury was expected to convene there
today.
   ``We think he is the kingpin,'' Gorman said of Lee, adding that
the sting operation had taken six-months to pull off.
   ``We've arrested people in the past in salmon-laundering
operations, but we have never had an undercover operation of this
size,'' said Gorman. ``Certainly this is the first time we have been
involved in a high-seas operation.''
   He said that in addition to alleged violations of U.S. law,
Taiwan prohibits the export of salmon.
   Sen. Frank Murkowski, R-Alaska, said the sting operation began
early this year when Lee contacted a member of the U.S. fishing
industry with an offer to sell salmon. The American company that Lee
approached than contacted agents of the National Marine Fisheries
Service.
   Over the next six months, an agent poised as a buyer and
communicated with Lee over ``monitored'' telephone and fax machines
to arrange the sale that climaxed in Tuesday's arrests, the senator
said.
   ``This should put the lid on one of the biggest salmon-pirate
operations, and if the others have any brains, they'll sit up and
take notice too,'' said Murkowski.
</TEXT>
