<HEAD>Afghan Rebels Claim 880 Government Soldiers Captured</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Afghan guerrillas said today they
captured 880 communist troops, including a handful of officers, when
they overran several government posts in the eastern province of
Paktia.
   The offensive was launched Sunday, but the Afghan News Agency,
which is controlled by the guerrillas and based in Pakistan, said
details of the fighting didn't reach Pakistan until Wednesday. A
second Afghan source, independent of the rebel groups in Islamabad,
confirmed the report.
   The fighting centered on posts 10 miles west of the
heavily-fortified town of Khost, 15 miles from the Pakistan border.
Many of the weapons sent through Pakistan to guerrilla positions in
Afghanistan pass through Paktia province.
   The Afghan News Agency described the fighting as ``one of the
biggest ever offensives against the communist regime troops in
Paktia.''
   The report said U.S.-backed insurgents also captured weapons and
military vehicles, including seven tanks, five of which were in
working order.
   In another report, the agency said up to 400 government troops
were killed or wounded in an attack last week on the border town of
Spinboldak in southern Afghanistan. The attack could not be
independently confirmed.
