<FIRST>r k BC-EditorialRdp 1stAdd   07-19 0552</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Editorial Rdp, 1st Add,0581</SECOND>
<HEAD>UNDATED: the results.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   July 12
   Charleston (W.Va.) Daily Mail on speaking fees for members of
Congress:
   President Bush has called for an outright ban on speaking fees
for congressmen and senators beginning in 1991. A new study by
Common Cause shows why this is a good idea.
   In all, 64 companies or lobbying groups spent $20,000 or more for
honoraria to congressmen and senators in 1987.
   The Tobacco Institute led the league with $123,400, followed by
the National Association of Broadcasters at $113,500. ...
   Most of the money goes to the leaders of the House and Senate,
the folks who set the congressional agenda. ...
   This money isn't passed out in the civic-minded spirit of
providing lawmakers with a forum for discussing the issues of the
day. Lobbyists get plenty in return; look at laws covering the
tobacco, television, banking, trucking and defense industries.
   Honoraria represent the legalized bribery of members of Congress
and should be banned. Congress belongs on the public payroll, not
the payrolls of special interests.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   July 14
   The Phoenix Gazette on the Helmsleys:
   ``The rich are different from you and I,'' author F. Scott
Fitzgerald once said to Ernest Hemingway. To which Hemingway
supposedly replied, ``Yes, they have more money.''
   There may be other differences.
   Leona Helmsley, the self-proclaimed ``Queen'' of the hotel empire
sheand her wealthy husband own, is on trial in New York for tax
evasion in using $4 million in company money to renovate her estate
in Greenwich, Conn., and claiming it as business expenses on her tax
return.
   In testimony the other day, her housekeeper testified that she
once told Helmsley, ``You must pay a lot of taxes.'' She said
Helmsley replied, ``We don't pay taxes. Only the little people pay
taxes.''
   Obviously there was a little semantic problem here. Helmsley was
describing her behavior, not stating the law. The jury will be happy
to correct the Queen's English.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   July 17
   The Keene (N.H.) Sentinel on the Seabrook nuclear power plant:
   There's really only one word that characterizes the history of
the Seabrook nuclear power project: incompetence.
   The advocates of nuclear power and the defenders of Seabrook have
tended all along to brand critics of the plant as irrational
anti-nukers. It's a false characterization.
   Those who worry about Seabrook are, for the most part,
level-headed people who have every reason to believe _ judging by
the plant officials' own behavior _ that something terrible may well
go wrong.
   Given the history of this turkey, there's nothing irrational
about that.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   July 16
   The Daily Union, Junction City, Kan., on the moon landing
anniversary:
   The tax dollars spent on the U.S. space program have been subject
to debate from time to time as to its worthiness and place in the
national budget.
   We believe a space exploration budget deserves to be part of our
nation's expenditures.
   The technological gains made through the development of the space
program are too numerous to mention. The advantages space affords
man to see his fragile planet from another perspective is worth the
price alone.
   But perhaps the space program fulfills one of man's greatest
needs. That is to explore the unknown, to learn about our
surroundings and to turn that knowledge into something for the
common good of all.
</TEXT>
