<FIRST>r a PM-ChappaquiddickTourism     07-19 0159</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chappaquiddick Tourism,0163</SECOND>
<HEAD>20 Years After Kennedy Accident, a Steady Stream of Visitors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHAPPAQUIDDICK ISLAND, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 20th anniversary of Sen.
Edward M. Kennedy's traffic accident was marked here today by the
usual curiosity among tourists to the island.
   ``It's the same all the time,'' said Alison Siok, a summer worker
on the four-car ferry between this bucolic island and Martha's
Vineyard. ``People are always curious. I'd say six out of 10 people
ask about it.''
   Ferry officials say that amounts to about 50 tourists a day in
the peak summer months.
   Edgartown Police Officer Paul Condlin said today that despite the
publicity surrounding the anniversary of the accident, he hasn't
seen an increase in the number of tourists asking directions to the
now-closed wooden bridge.
   ``Every year we have the same thing,'' Condlin said.
   A passenger in Kennedy's car, 28-year-old Mary Jo Kopechne, died
July 19, 1969, after the car plunged off the narrow bridge.
</TEXT>
