<HEAD>First Private Taxi Service Commissioned in Ho Chi Minh City</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first private taxi service since
economic reforms began has gone into service in Vietnam's Ho Chi
Minh City, according to Radio Hanoi.
   The Saigon Taxi Co., whose cars are equippped with air
conditioning and radio-cassette players, was commissioned July 10,
Radio Hanoi said Tuesday.
   ``This is the first private passenger car service ever set up in
Ho Chi Minh City following the application of the multisectorial
economic policy by the state,'' it said.
   It said the company was talking with authorities at Tan Son Nhat
Airport about servicing foreign customers.
   Ho Chi Minh City was called Saigon when it was the capital of the
U.S.-backed South Vietnam government, which fell to communist forces
in April 1975. In December 1986, the Communist Party endorsed for
nationwide application Western-style reforms including limited
private ownership and free enterprise.
