<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-89 1238EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Zimbabwe     07-19 0336</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Zimbabwe,0349</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Disperse Students Who Gathered to Hear Opposition Legislator</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Riot police fired tear gas to disperse
students who had gathered to hear an address by a maverick
legislator opposed to President Robert Mugabe's ruling party.
   About 5,000 students attended the meeting Tuesday night in the
main public hall on the campus of Zimbabwe University organized by
Edgar Tekere's Zimbabwe Unity Movement, student leaders said.
   Rioting broke out when police asked Tekere to end the meeting and
students were filing out of the hall chanting slogans at police
surrounding the hall, they said.
   Some students hurled stones at advancing lines of riot police,
said a student leader who requested anonymity.
   There were no immediate reports of injuries or arrests but
ambulance crews aided students affected by tear gas.
   Students said police chased rioters and fired tear gas canisters
into campus dormitories.
   Tekere and his aides left the campus before the disturbances
started.
   A police spokesman said police began withdrawing from campus soon
after dawn Wednesday. Most students reported for classes by noon
Wednesday, school authorities said.
   The meeting was the first public gathering addressed by Tekere
since he formed his opposition party on April 30.
   In May, police cited public order regulations as the reason for
banning a public rally planned by the new party in Harare. Tekere
canceled a second meeting when his supporters found themselves
locked out of a stadium where it was to take place.
   Tekere, 52, who helped found the ruling party in 1963 and became
one of Mugabe's staunchest allies, was fired from the politburo and
central committee last October.
   He was dismissed after he denounced widespread top-level
corruption.
   Forming his opposition party in April, Tekere promised to root
out corruption and vowed to prevent Mugabe from establishing a
one-party state in one of Africa's few Western-style democracies.
   Tekere claims the broad support of students, labor leaders and
peasants in the countryside who are disenchanted with corruption,
record unemployment, shortages of basic commodities and inflation.
</TEXT>
