<FIRST>u w PM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0457 07-19 0537</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0457,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Briefs Lawmakers on Trip</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: New throughout with meeting over, leaders' comments; edits to
tighten</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush today gave congressional leaders
a review of his trip to Europe, and House Speaker Thomas Foley
predicted Bush will win approval for his promised $125 million in
new aid to promote free enterprise in Poland and Hungary.
   The president also voiced opposition to a proposal in the Senate
that would restrict official U.S. contacts with representatives of
the Palestine Liberation Organization.
   Foley, speaking to reporters outside the White House following
the 75-minute meeting, predicted that Bush's aid package for reforms
in the Eastern Europe nations ``generally will receive strong
support.''
   He said Bush and the lawmakers did not discuss the space
initiative the president may announce Thursday, the 20th anniversary
of the first moonwalk. But the speaker said the sentiments Bush has
expressed previously that any space initiative ``has to be fiscally
responsible.''
   Foley said, ``The consensus of all those present was that (Bush)
had a very successful trip'' in both Eastern Europe and at the
economic summit in Paris. ``He deserved congratulations, which he
received.''
   Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, chairman of the Senate Finance
Committee, said he was ``very delighted to see the president's
enthusiasm as to what's happening in Eastern Europe and his desire
to take whatever initiatives we can'' to help change the communist
economic and political systems there.
   ``That was most encouraging. There's a lot more enthusiasm than
we saw on that three or four months ago'' from the Bush
administration, said Bentsen, who added that he ``certainly will''
support the aid for Poland and Hungary.
   Both houses of Congress are now considering the administration's
overall $14.4 billion foreign aid package. A House appropriations
subcommittee late Monday earmarked $15 million for Bush's initiative
in Hungary.
   Sen. Bob Packwood, R-Ore., the ranking minority member of the
Finance Committee, said it was hard to get any foreign aid through
Congress.
   But he called the aid proposals for the two Warsaw Bloc countries
``a very modest package. I think it's well worth giving them the
encouragement. ... You're wise to start out modestly until you see
if the reforms really come to fruition.''
   On another topic, Packwood said the PLO amendment the Senate is
considering would, in Bush's view, ``simply shut down the
negotiations. He was quite strong on that issue.''
   The amendment, co-sponsored by Sens. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., and
John F. Kerry, D-Mass., would bar negotiations with any PLO
representative unless the president first certified to Congress that
the representative had not played any role in terrorist activity
that resulting in the death, injury or kidnapping of American
citizens.
   Bush returned home Tuesday to a military honor guard and the
cheers of his Cabinet and a large crowd gathered on the South Lawn
of the White House.
   Bush was clearly tired from the grueling 9,000-mile journey
across four nations, but ebullient.
   ``Everywhere, in Warsaw, Gdansk and Budapest, among the leaders
of the summit nations, in the Netherlands, I found an enormous
amount of excitement,'' he said. ``Everywhere people seem to sense
that we live at a moment when positive change is possible.''
</TEXT>
