<FIRST>u w PM-KALFlight 1stLd-Writethru a0442 07-19 0459</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-KAL Flight, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0442,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Airline Supervisor Agreed Mistake Made</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: New throughout with today's testimony; adds byline</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Korean Air Lines supervisor agreed in 1983
that a navigation mistake by the crew of ill-fated Flight 007 led to
the shootdown of the plane by the Soviet Union, an analyst who
studied the tragedy testified today.
   Frank Houston of Seattle told a U.S. District Court jury that
KAL's chief trainer of pilots, Yoon Bae Kim, ``agreed by shaking his
head in the affirmative'' about the idea that the plane had been
off-course almost from the minute it took off from Anchorage, Alaska.
   Houston and Kim were among a group of aviation experts who looked
into the shootdown over Soviet territory, which killed all 269
people aboard the plane.
   Houston said he and other members of a team ran tests in a
simulator at Boeing facilities in Seattle based on the available
flight data about the jumbo jet that was destroyed by a Soviet
fighter plane on Sept. 1, 1983.
   The team of analysts concluded that the KAL crew probably had
punched into the plane's computerized navigation system the wrong
number for the longtitude before taking off from Anchorage, Alaska,
for Seoul, South Korea.
   ``It's like a touch-tone telephone; what they did in my opinion
is misdial,'' Houston said in describing the device the crew used to
program the navigation system aboard the plane.
   The plane was estimated to be 300 miles off course when it was
shot down by Russian military aircraft. The simulator tests with the
longtitude number off by 10 degrees placed the craft in the location
it is believed to have gone down inside Russian waters.
   Houston's characterization of Kim's views is important to the
civil suit in which families of 138 of the dead passengers allege
willful misconduct by the airline.
   On Tuesday, an attorney defending KAL said Flight 007 was on
course until only a short time before it was blown out of the sky.
   George Tompkins disputed the international investigation of the
incident in which Houston participated. That probe found the plane
was significantly off course for hours before it was destroyed by
the Soviet Union.
   Tompkins refused to concede the KAL jumbo jet was off track so
early. The best evidence is that the crew was flying its correct
route until shortly before it was destroyed, he said.
   Tompkins said the crew sent radioed position reports periodically
to Anchorage and Tokyo pinpointing the plane's location as being on
course for the first four hours of its flight.
   U.S. air traffic controllers who tracked the earliest parts of
Flight 007 before it went out of radar range reported nothing
abnormal, Tompkins said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
