<FIRST>r i AM-China     07-19 0584</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China,0599</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chinese Retaliating Against Soldiers, Sources Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Citizens angry at the army for killing
pro-democracy protesters in Beijing are retaliating with attacks on
soldiers, Chinese and Western sources said Wednesday.
   In Hong Kong, a Chinese language newspaper reported Wednesday
that about 20 more people were executed for joining in the
protests.Chinese officials denied the report.
   Incidents of shooting at soldiers in retaliation for the military
crackdown ``are going on, they're going on a lot and they're all
over the country,'' a Western diplomat in Beijing said on condition
of anonymity.
   He said there was no clear sign of a nationwide organization
behind the attacks, but he did not give other details.
   A Chinese source reported several cases of Beijing residents
firing on patrolling soldiers since the army shot its way into the
city center June 3-4. China has said about 200 people died in the
June attack, but Chinese witnesses and Western intelligence sources
said the death toll may have been as high as 3,000.
   ``People who lost family members can be anguished enough to do
something rash, like shoot a soldier,'' the source said on condition
of anonymity. ``Too many weapons and ammunition were taken (from
army trucks) during the turmoil.'' It was not clear if any soldiers
have died in the attacks.
   Official media reported that some protesters are continuing
``counterrevolutionary activities'' underground, and government
spokesman Yuan Mu has acknowledged that guns taken by crowds from
army trucks could cause further unrest.
   However, there has been only one reported attack on soldiers, in
which a truck barrelled past a checkpoint in Beijing on June 17 and
fired at the soldiers, wounding one. Two men in the truck later were
arrested.
   The government said it suspected sabotage when dynamite blew up
on a Shanghai train June 26, killing 24 people, but the attack did
not appear to be connected to troops.
   In Hong Kong, the Chinese language newspaper Ming Pao said the
executions of about 20 people took place about 10 days ago. It said
most of the group were members of an outlawed independent workers'
union set up during the protests.
   The Beijing People's High Court and police refused to comment on
the report. Several dozen executions are known to have taken place
since the protests were crushed, but the authorities have linked
only 12 to the protests. Many Chinese believe the number is far
higher.
   Many Chinese also believe large numbers of arrests are continuing
in secret even though the number reported have trickled to a few a
week. More than 2,060 arrests have been reported in the official
media since June 4.
   The Western diplomat estimated arrests nationwide at no more than
5,000. Chinese sources have put the number in Beijing at more than
2,000.
   In other developments, the Japanese Embassy said Chinese police
have promised a thorough investigation of an anonymous threat to
kill two Japanese in China each month.
   The threat was made in a letter mailed to Japan Airline's Beijing
office and signed by a previously unknown group, the Blood-Bright
Dare to Die Squad. The group accused Japan of colluding with ``the
Communist Party dictatorial government and (plotting) to launch a
large-scale economic invasion of China.''
   Embassy spokesman Minoru Kubota said his government's warning to
Japanese citizens to be careful in visiting China, issued after the
army attacked the student protesters, still stands. He said no
further action would be taken until police complete their
investigation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
