<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-89 1328EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Nicaragua 2ndLd-Writethru   07-19 0666</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nicaragua, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0591,0684</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nicaraguans Mark Anniversary of Sandinista Victory</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with Ortega speech. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DORALISA PILARTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Daniel Ortega today urged
President Bush to halt Washington's ``policy of war'' and stop
supporting the rebels as Nicaragua celebrated the 10th anniversary
of the Sandinistas' rise to power.
   ``The United States still hasn't decided to be respectful of the
rights of the nations of the Third World,'' Ortega told a Managua
rally of 200,000 cheering supporters, many waving red-and-black
flags of the ruling Sandinista National Liberation Front.
   ``If the president of the United States is for peace... he should
stop immediately his policy of war against the people of Nicaragua
(and) ... dismantle the Contras,'' Ortega said.
   Army and private trucks, public buses and family cars carried
Nicaraguans to the Plaza of the Revolution along Lake Managua
throughout the morning.
   ``Go! Go! Go!,'' shouted a squad of about 50 young people running
down a flag-bedecked avenue to the plaza. Most held small flags of
the Sandinista National Liberation Front and wore T-shirts with the
anniversary logo: ``We've got 10 down, and we keep going forth.''
   Some people had said they would boycott the rally because they
had little to celebrate in a country that ranks among the world's
poorest.
   In his 50-minute speech, Ortega said the government is
controlling inflation, and he repeated earlier pledges there will be
clean national elections as scheduled Feb. 25.
   The U.S. Congress cut off all but non-lethal aid to the Contra
rebels in 1988, shortly before rebel leaders signed a temporary
truce with the Sandinistas.
   Before entirely dismantling the Contras, the United States has
been insisting the Sandinistas reform election laws to accomodate
objections from opposition groups and ensure press freedom, fair
campaigning and balloting.
   Banks, businesses and government offices were closed to
commemorate July 19, 1979, when the victorious Sandinista rebels
marched into Managua to take power two days after dictator Anastasio
Somoza fled.
   Managua Mayor Carlos Carrion opened the ceremony with a speech in
which he said Nicaragua has withstood 10 years of ``imperialist
aggression'' and survived.
   ``Never again foreign domination,'' Carrion said. ``For 10 years,
Nicaragua's sovereignty has been in the hands of the people.
Nicaragua's sovereignty is not up for discussion, it's to be
defended with weapons.''
   Barricada, the official newspaper of the Sandinista Front,
carried no news on its front page, only two pictures of joyous
Nicaraguans, and in big red letters splashed accross the page: ``10
Years of Changes and Victory ... And More To Come.''
   ``Exciting, agitated, tormenting, hard and sweet; moving in their
pain and joy, these 10 years of revolution to which we have come
today, against all predictions and designs, have a positive balance
for the interests of the Nicaraguan people,'' it said in an
editorial.
   But some Managua residents said most of those at the rally would
be Sandinista militants or public employees afraid of losing
government jobs if they failed to attend.
   ``Five years ago, people were still very enthusiastic about the
revolution,'' a technician who did not want his name used said
Tuesday. ``People would paint and fix their houses, and neighbors
would tell each other, `Let's go to the plaza.'
   ``But Managua has been deteriorating. People are now feeling the
weight of the revolution.''
   An economic report underwritten by Sweden, Nicaragua's main
non-communist supporter, said last year's per capita output was
$300, making Nicaragua poorer even than Haiti, long the poorest
country in the hemisphere.
   ``Before, with what I earned I could support my children, buy
food,'' said a cleaning woman who identified herself only as
Socorro. ``But now, we're eating once a day. There just isn't enough
to go around. And I have two jobs and my husband also works.''
   The Sandinista government has blamed U.S.-supported Contra rebels
and U.S.-instigated cutoff of credit for the economic collapse. The
opposition blames Sandinista incompetence and the lack of private
sector confidence in the government.
</TEXT>
