<FIRST>r a PM-BoyPilot 1stLd-Writethru a0528 07-19 0407</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Boy Pilot, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0528,0410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Round-the-World Plane Crashes; No Serious Injuries</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with federal authorites investigating that
plane was overloaded, official now saying plane might be salvaged, recasts
2nd graf to clarify that father was at controls; No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GOLOVIN, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The plane being used by a boy trying to
become the youngest pilot to fly around the world crashed and burned
while taking off from a remote village in northwest Alaska. There
were no serious injuries.
   The father of 11-year-old pilot Tony Aliengena was at the
controls when strong winds flipped the single-engine plane Tuesday
night, giving his son a break while the group took a side trip to go
fishing.
   ``We've come too far to turn back,'' the father said, adding he
hoped to find another plane for his son to fly home to Orange
County, Calif., and claim the record.
   Tony, meanwhile, was in tears at the Golovin Community Health
Clinic. ``This is the worst stop yet,'' he said.
   Of the eight people on board, four suffered facial cuts _ Tony,
his father, his Soviet pen pal and traveling companion, Roman
Tchermenykh, and Joseph Lee, 29, of Los Angeles, a member of a film
crew making a documentary on the flight.
   Federal authorities are investigating the fact that eight people
were on board a plane with seats for six, said Federal Aviation
Administration spokesman Paul Steucke in Anchorage.
   The boy wasn't at the controls of the single-engine Cessna
Centurion because the flight was part of a fishing detour from the
main route. A two-engine chase plane carries relatives, media and
others along for the record attempt, but the single-engine plane is
the one the boy pilots.
   The crash occurred about 9 p.m. as the travelers tried to take
off for Nome from a gravel airstrip. A Seward Peninsula community of
120 people situated on the Bering Sea 90 miles from Nome, Golovin is
inaccessible except by boat and air.
   Preliminary reports indicated the plane was destroyed by flames,
but Steucke said today it appears the plane can be patched up enough
to be flown to Nome for more work. The plane's right wing was
damaged by fire.
   ``I don't care about the Friendship Flight right now,'' said the
boy's mother, Susan, who is accompanying Tony on his journey along
with other family members, friends and members of the media. ``I'm
just glad that we're all alive.''
</TEXT>
