<FIRST>u w PM-SavageAccused 4thLd-Writethru a0608 07-19 0854</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Savage Accused, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0608,800</SECOND>
<HEAD>Illinois Congressman Accused of Sexual Assault</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 10 grafs new with further detail, confirmation; picks up
at pvs 5th graf, House Speaker</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Peace Corps volunteer claims Rep. Gus Savage,
D-Ill., sexually assaulted her during a dinner outing in the capital
of Zaire, and material relating to the incident has been forwarded
to the House ethics committee, State Department officials said today.
   They confirmed a Washington Post story that quoted the volunteer
as saying Savage repeatedly fondled her for more than two hours in
the back of a chauffeur-driven embassy car.
   The woman said Savage continued his advances even though she
``tried everything ... short of hitting him, or hurting him
physically to make him stop,'' the newspaper reported in today's
editions.
   One State Department official, who insisted on anonymity, said
the U.S. ambassador to Zaire, William Harrop, had a confrontation
with Savage over the incident. An unidentified witness told the Post
that Harrop ``spoke very strongly'' to Savage ``chewed him out as
much as an ambassador chews out a congressman.''
   Jill Gross of the State Department inspector general's office
said today that allegations of the incident had been sent to the
House ethics committee on Tuesday night.
   ``They were sufficiently serious that someone should look into
them,'' she said.
   Efforts to reach Savage today were unsuccessful. He did not
return repeated phone messages left at his office.
   A Peace Corps official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
the woman has not brought a formal complaint against Savage and the
agency would not pursue the case without her consent.
   ``The ball is in her court,'' the official said. ``It's something
we told her right from the beginning.''
   Neither the State Department officials nor the Post disclosed the
identity of the volunteer.
   House Speaker Thomas S. Foley, D-Wash., said the House ethics
committee has authority to review the allegations against Savage.
   ``That committee is capable of reviewing matters within its
purview,'' Foley told reporters, adding that he was making no
judgment on the facts in the case.
   ``Every member of Congress has a high responsibility for personal
conduct as an elected member of the House of Representatives. If it
is true in this country, it is even more true when traveling abroad
as a representative of the United States,'' he said.
   The Post said Savage declined to comment on the account.
   An aide to Savage, Donnavan Dunkley, declined to discuss the
incident with The Associated Press when reached at home Tuesday
night.
   Peace Corps spokesman Lee Raudonis told The Associated Press the
volunteer had given the agency the account described in the
newspaper, but the agency had not been able to confirm the
volunteer's account independently.
   ``The fact that she's being given a new assignment indicates that
we think she is capable of the assignment and that we have
confidence in her,'' he said.
   The woman told the Post she did not file a formal complaint
because she did not want to publicize the incident and risk damaging
the Peace Corps. The paper said she agreed to the interview
reluctantly.
   According to the account in the Post, the incident happened March
19 when Savage made an official visit to the African capital of
Kinshasa and asked for a briefing on Peace Corps activities, which
the volunteer was scheduled to give in a few days.
   Other members of the dinner party included members of Savage's
staff and the American Embassy staff, including embassy information
officer Daniel McGaffie. Savage wanted to sample the city's
nightlife and insisted the woman ride with him, she told the paper.
   As soon as the three cars of the party left the ambassador's
home, ``He grabbed me,'' the volunteer said in her interview.
   ``He tried to force me to have sex with him. ... He kept touching
me, after I told him to stop, many times, loudly,'' she was quoted
as saying.
   After a two-hour outing that included stops at three or four
bars, the volunteer fled a hotel disco with Savage in pursuit, the
account continued.
   McGaffie was reported to have interrupted a ``tense public
encounter'' between the Savage and the volunteer and took the woman
home, according to the newspaper account.
   An official familiar with the meeting said Savage ``did not feel
as if it had been as extreme as she suggested.''
   The volunteer was sent to Washington for six weeks of treatment
of the sort given to victims of sexual offenses and is now awaiting
a new assignment by the Peace Corps.
   Sherman Funk, inspector general of the State Department, told the
AP, ``If true, the story is pretty egregious.''
   He said he had ``referred the incident to somebody else for
review. I don't think it's appropriate for me to comment further.''
   Savage has an unlisted number. The newspaper quoted him as saying
``Why don't you ask me about economic development projects? ...
   ``I don't want to talk about that ... Ask me the same kind of
questions you ask white congressmen. You don't ask white congressmen
questions like that ...,'' Savage, who is black, told the Post.
</TEXT>
