<DOCNO> AP890719-0118 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-89 1337EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Bangladesh-Floods Bjt   07-19 0808</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bangladesh-Floods, Bjt,0830</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bangladesh Prepares For Annual Deluge</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOHADEPUR, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rivers are rising and the people of
Bangladesh prepare for the annual deluge, which can bring the
blessing of rich harvests or the curse of destruction and death.
   After devastating floods last year that killed at least 1,400
people and submerged three-fourths of the country, the government
began an ambitious program to cope with future disasters.
   A giant earthen dam is being built around Dhaka, the capital, as
part of a two-year, $100 million flood-alleviation program.
   Warehouses of emergency rice and wheat supplies have been raised
in many parts of the country. About 400 helipads have been built to
facilitate emergency relief and rescue operations.
   Perhaps the most practical steps are being taken by the people,
who are resigned to the annual floods that invariably disrupt their
lives but, in good years, nourish the crops without washing them
away.
   At Mohadepur, a village of 6,000 people 30 miles northwest of
Dhaka, families have raised the ground beneath their bamboo houses,
which now stand on specially constructed hillocks several feet above
surrounding fields of rice and jute.
   The 22 men, women and children of four families who live on one
of the hillocks labored nearly a month, hauling baskets of gray mud
from the Isamati River, about 50 paces away.
   Jehanara, 20, lives in one of the four homes that form the
perimeter of the hillock's central courtyard. She said the houses
stand about 2 feet higher than they did when the 1988 flood peaked
in August and September.
   Last year, she and her neighbors said, the water reached at least
that far into their houses, which have mud floors. The walls are
made of mats woven from split bamboo, tied to bamboo poles, and the
roofs are of thatching or corrugated aluminium.
   Men from nearby houses said everyone in Mohadepur with the time
or money had raised at least the level of the family kitchen, which
usually consists of an earthen oven carved into the clay-like ground.
   During last year's flood, they said, families sometimes could not
eat for days at a time because there was no dry place to cook rice,
the staple in Bangladesh, and whatever other food was available.
   On an adjacent but lower hillock, Mohammad Ali said last year's
flood waters were three feet above ground level, so he raised the
area by two feet.
   How far people raise hillocks is a calculated gamble. The logic
goes like this: Since the 1988 flood was said to one in a century,
this one shouldn't be as bad, but if it is, knee-deep in water is
better than waist-deep or worse.
   Ali, prosperous by local standards because he raises more than
enough rice to feed his family and sells the excess, said he hired
17 men to elevate his compound. He said it took about 15 days and
cost him the equivalent of about $76.
   He said there is nothing he can do to save his one and one-third
acres of rice and jute if the floods are bad. The current rice crop
is due for harvest in late August.
   ``It's really difficult,'' the 40-year-old farmer said. ``In 1987
I lost the rice seedlings to too much rain. In 1988 I lost
everything to the flood.
   ``I may lose it again, but I can't find any other job. What can I
do? It's all up to Allah.''
   Rivers have not reached the levels of this time last year and
there is hope that, when they crest in a month or so, the floods
will be less severe. Up to 10 feet of water covered vast stretches
of Bangladesh last year.
   The government said 21 million people, nearly one-fifth of the
nation's 110 million, lost their homes last year and another 24
million were affected by the floods, which generally meant they were
temporarily displaced or could not feed themselves.
   About 30 million people relied on government-supplied food for at
least a month after the water receded.
   Because of the government program, if flooding is as bad this
year ``the number of people affected would be about (the same), but
the rescue work would be easier and quicker,'' Serajul Hossain Khan,
minister of relief and rehabilitation, said in an interview.
   He said the helipads would enable the air force to move food more
rapidly, but some foreign observers question whether helicopters are
the answer.
   ``What will they deliver except reporters?'' a Western relief
official said privately. ``On a good day they can get a dozen in the
air. You can't even begin to feed 30 million people by helicopter.''
   He and other foreign aid officials said the government appears to
have enough reserves, at least 1 million tons of rice and wheat, for
an emergency.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
