<FIRST>r i AM-Japan     07-19 0562</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan,0577</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prime Minister Promises to Reconsider Unpopular Sales Tax</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ERIC TALMADGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Sousuke Uno said Wednesday he would
review an unpopular sales tax, which has combined with sex and
bribery scandals to put his Liberal Democrats in serious danger of
losing this weekend's elections.
   His wife, Chiyo, appeared at a rally of party women in Yokohama
and apologized for the sex scandal, which involves allegations that
Uno kept paid mistresses.
   Polls indicate the Liberal Democratic Party, which has governed
Japan since it was formed in 1955, is the underdog in Sunday's
elections for half the 252 seats in the upper house of Parliament.
   Uno used his first stumping tour outside Tokyo since the campaign
began July 5 to pledge a review of the new 3 percent consumption
tax. It has become a a central election issue, particularly among
housewives already offended by the sex scandal.
   ``If there are areas that need review, I hope to take
responsibility and correct them,'' he told reporters at a televised
news conference in Osaka. Uno did not propose specific changes,
however, and reiterated general support for the tax.
   His party pushed a tax reform package through Parliament last
year during a boycott by opposition legislators, who were demanding
facts about alleged involvement of Liberal Democratic leaders in the
Recruit Co. influence-buying scandal.
   The conservative Liberal Democrats have majorities in both
houses, but consensus is highly valued in Japan and they were
criticized for ignoring opposition arguments that the sales tax was
unfair to low-income households. The tax reform law took effect
April 1.
   Uno described himself Wednesday as a ``commander leading the
battle'' and said he does not foresee a major loss this weekend, but
the governing party's No. 2 executive appeared to have a different
view.
   At a separate news conference Wednesday, Ryutaro Hashimoto hinted
at an alliance with the conservative opposition Democratic
Socialists if his the Liberal Democrats suffer a serious defeat, the
Japan Broadcasting Corp. reported.
   Allegations about Uno's sex life arose soon after he replaced
Noboru Takeshita on June 2. Takeshita resigned to take
responsibility for the Recruit scandal, which tainted the highest
levels of government, bureaucracy and business but did touch Uno.
   At a university in Osaka where he delivered a speech Wednesday,
Uno was met by dozens of hecklers and protesters carrying placards
demanding his resignation.
   In Yokohama, his wife said: ``I deeply apologize for the
criticism regarding my husband.'' The party used 80 buses to bring
more than 5,000 women to the rally, where Mrs. Uno made only brief
remarks.
   Of the ruling party's 142 seats, in the upper house, 73 are not
being contested in this election. It must win 54 seats Sunday to
retain a majority, but the latest poll indicates it will get from 28
to 38.
   The poll by the national newspaper Mainichi also indicated major
gains for the leading opposition Japan Socialist Party, from its
current 21 seats to 64-70. Mainichi's poll was based on interviews
July 14-16 with 34,237 eligible voters chosen at random across Japan.
   Support for the Liberal Democrats was given as 27 percent, 18
percent lower than in a similar poll conducted before the last
election in 1986. The Socialists rose in popularity from 13 percent
in 1986 to 30 percent, and Mainichi sid 26 percent of respondents
were undecided.
</TEXT>
