<FIRST>r a AM-BalloonLaunch     07-19 0277</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Balloon Launch,0285</SECOND>
<HEAD>Environmentalist `Deflates' Defense Department Idea</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE A. VENEZIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRIGANTINE, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Department of Defense officials
envisioned thousands of red, white and blue balloons floating into
the air to celebrate National Constitution Week.
   But an environmentalist who has seen how deflated balloons kill
marine animals only saw red. His concerns prompted the Defense
Department to cancel proposed launches at military bases around the
country.
   Robert Schoelkopf, director of the Marine Mammal Stranding Center
in Brigantine, was alerted to a Pentagon memo with suggestions on
ways bases could celebrate National Constitution Week in September.
   One suggestion called for ringing tower bells for 202 seconds on
Sept. 17 while simultaneously releasing red, white and blue balloons.
   In recent years, Schoelkopf has recovered dead marine animals _
including whales, dolphins and turtles _ that have suffocated on
deflated balloons that fell to the sea.
   In addition, ``The Defense Department would be in direct
violation of the Clean Ocean Act, which prohibits the disposal of
non-biodegrable products into the ocean,'' Schoelkopf said.
   After unsuccessful attempts to reach Defense Department
officials, Schoelkopf turned to U.S. Rep. H. James Saxton, R-N.J.,
who appealed to Defense Secretary Dick Cheney earlier this month.
   ``We don't need to spend thousands of dollars in taxpayers' money
to launch balloons that will kill dolphins and other marine
animals,'' Saxton said Tuesday from his Washington office.
   A Defense Department spokesman said Tuesday that another memo was
in the works withdrawing the suggestion for a balloon launch and
explaining why.
   ``As soon as the problem was brought to our attention, everyone
was alerted,'' Maj. James L. Adams said. ``We're reversing that
suggestion.''
  
</TEXT>
