<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-89 1358EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-KALFlight     07-19 0515</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-KAL Flight,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Witness Says Trainer of Pilots Agrees Crew Probably Misprogrammed
System</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Korean Air Lines' chief trainer of pilots
agreed in 1983 that crew members of Flight 007 probably
misprogrammed a navigation system, leading to the shootdown of their
jumbo jet over Soviet airspace, a witness testified Wednesday in a
lawsuit against KAL.
   Frank Houston of Seattle told a civil court jury in U.S. District
Court that he and other analysts who studied the tragedy reached the
conclusion while conducting tests in a simulator at Boeing
facilities in November 1983.
   At Houston's home, KAL's chief of training, Yoon Bae Kim,
``agreed by shaking his head in the affirmative'' about the idea
that the crew had misprogrammed the system, said Houston, resulting
in the plane being off course almost from the minute it took off
from Anchorage, Alaska.
   The team of analysts felt that the KAL crew probably had punched
into the plane's computerized navigation system the wrong number for
the longitude at Anchorage before taking off for Seoul, South Korea.
   ``It's like a touch-tone telephone; what they did in my opinion
is misdial,'' Houston said in describing the device the crew used to
program the navigation system aboard the plane.
   Houston said he invited those involved in the investigation ``to
my home. ... We had a drink. It seemed to be the consensus this was
the most likely cause.''
   ``The most likely cause of what?'' asked U.S. District Court
Judge Aubrey Robinson.
   ``The most likely cause of this tragic accident,'' replied
Houston.
   Houston explained that the misprogramming had caused the plane to
fly 10 degrees off course, leading it to a point 300 miles away from
its assigned flight path when it was shot down by a Soviet fighter
plane.
   The International Civil Aviation Organization concluded that
Flight 007 was off course for nearly 5{ hours and intruded into
Soviet territory for several hours before it was shot down.
   Houston, a retired airline pilot, was among the aviation experts
who assisted in the ICAO probe. The Sept. 1, 1983, shootdown killed
all 269 people aboard.
   Houston's characterization of Kim's views undermines statements
made Tuesday by George Tompkins, the attorney defending KAL in the
civil trial. Families of 138 of the dead passengers have filed suit
alleging willful misconduct by the airline.
   Tompkins said there was no proof of any programming error by the
crew and that Flight 007 was on course until shortly before it was
blown out of the sky by a Soviet jet fighter.
   The best evidence is that the crew of the KAL jumbo jet was
flying its correct route until about an hour before it was
destroyed, Tompkins said.
   Tompkins said the crew sent radioed position reports periodically
to Anchorage and Tokyo pinpointing the plane's location as being on
course for the first four hours of its flight.
   The families of the dead passengers are trying to prove that the
airline's crew knew it was off course but proceeded toward Seoul
anyway without the use of a misprogrammed navigation system.
</TEXT>
