<SECOND>AM-BRF--Gang Violence,0182</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fight Broke Out When Police Escort One Gang Onto Another's Turf</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police mistakenly escorted gang members
leaving a wake into another gang's territory, triggering a fight,
the sheriff's department said.
   One shot was fired at an officer during the July 12 melee and
authorities arrested 16 people, sheriff's Detective Robert Rifkin
said Tuesday. After the fight, an 18-year-old was killed in a
drive-by shooting that stemmed from the street fight, Rifkin said.
   Rifkin, an anti-gang detective, said the two escorting police
officers did not realize they were traveling with members of one
gang through territory controlled by another. The officers were
escorting the gang members as they walked from a wake for a slain
comrade.
   Police Lt. Robert Kimball, the officers' supervisor, said they
had no way of knowing that rival gang members were in the
neighborhood.
   Rifkin said he was told the brawl started after one gang member
being escorted told deputies he saw members of a rival gang, then
jumped into a car and approached the rival gang members.
