<FIRST>r w AM-SovietArsenal     07-19 0581</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet Arsenal,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Authors Say Soviet Nuclear Arsenal Now Dropping</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet nuclear stockpile peaked last year
and dropped in recent months because of Soviet President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev's military strategies, the authors of a book released
Wednesday said.
   ``The idea that they are churning out nuclear weapons like
sausage is baloney,'' William M. Arkin, one of the authors of
``Soviet Nuclear Weapons,'' said at a news conference. ``Under
Gorbachev there has been a significant change in the composition and
complexion of Soviet forces.''
   The book was published under the auspices of the Natural
Resources Defense Council, a private organization that describes
itself as ``long concerned about the dangers and problems posed by
the unleashed atom.''
   The volume contains pictures and explanations of Soviet nuclear
weaponry ranging from Blackjack bombers to Sierra class submarines.
It includes a map of what it says have been some 600 underground
nuclear explosions.
   The authors said they relied heavily on U.S. government
documents, using the Freedom of Information Act to obtain reports.
   One author, Thomas B. Cochran, said to Soviet journalists at the
news conference, ``This book should be published in the Soviet
Union.'' He and the other authors released a copy of a letter they
sent to Gorbachev during a recent trip to Moscow urging publication.
   ``You have stressed the need for historians to fill in the `blank
pages' of your history,'' the letter said. ``We hope that in some
small way our effort may stimulate Soviet accounts of the
development of atomic and hydrogen bombs, missiles, aircraft, ships
and submarines.''
   Figures in the book indicate a Soviet arsenal of 33,000 nuclear
weapons, about 40 percent larger than the United States has. But
Cochran, saying there is a U.S. superiority in readiness, said the
numbers can be deceiving.
   ``We believe that the arsenal is declining, that it peaked some
time last year,'' Cochran said of the Soviets' holdings. ``They're
not ahead of us and we're not ahead of them. The fact is both can do
a lot of damage to the other.''
   The book says the Soviets built up their arsenal grew because of
``the perception of how to achieve national security, the
advancement of certain foreign policy goals, the desire for
recognition as a superpower, domestic political struggles,
bureaucratic inertia, and military service rivalry.''
   Gorbachev's doctrine of ``necessary defensive sufficiency,''
however, has meant a slowdown.
   ``Soviet nuclear forces are following the U.S. pattern of the
past 10 to 20 years: Certain military missions that once used
nuclear weapons began to be phased out,'' a statement about the book
said. ``The weapon was either not replaced, or replaced with a
conventional system.''
   The book said the modernization of Soviet strategic nuclear
forces seemed to have slowed in the past two years, with the new
Blackjack bomber and SS-24 ICBM being introduced in small numbers.
   Arkin added: ``They have a lot of old junk and they never throw
anything out.'' But he also said, ``One should not confuse technical
obsolescence with real decisions to remove weapons.''
   He said large portions of the arsenals of both the United States
and the Soviet Union are not included in any of the arms control
negotiations.
   ``And those are the nuclear weapons that are most likely to cause
nuclear war,'' he said.
   He said 14,000 of the 33,000 Soviet warheads are not included in
any of the arms talks. He cited bombs on jet fighters, artillery and
naval weapons.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
