<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--FreewayRescue     07-19 0183</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Freeway Rescue,0188</SECOND>
<HEAD>Boy Rescued from Crushed Car</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 9-year-old boy was trapped and unable to breathe
after a truck rolled over the top of his family's car, but
passers-by used a jack, crowbars and a pole to pry off the car's
roof and help rescue him.
   Rhonda Largo, 39, of Mesa, said she was driving with her son and
daughter Tuesday when the truck overturned, crushing their car's
roof and folding a seat over on Anthony.
   Ms. Largo and her daughter were not hurt, but Anthony was unable
to breathe. ``His face was purple and his eyes were swelling shut,
'' she said.
   Seconds after the passers-by raised the roof and Anthony was able
to breathe again, firefighters arrived and cut away the wreckage to
free him.
   ``He was asking me `Am I going to die?' He was real brave. He
didn't cry,'' Rhonda Largo said.
   Anthony as in serious condition but his recovery prospects looked
good, officials of St. Joseph's Hospital and Medical Center said.
   Authorities said the truck's brakes had malfunctioned. The driver
suffered minor injuries.
