<FIRST>u i AM-Mexico-Drugs     07-19 0497</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Drugs,0515</SECOND>
<HEAD>Drug Barons Lived in Gilded Cage, Officials Admit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRIS ANGELO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two jailed drug kingpins lived in luxury in a
crowded prison, taking up enough space for 250 inmates and filling
their opulent quarters with jewels, guns and dozens of their
friends, officials said.
   A pool table, a large aquarium, Turkish baths, video equipment, a
television, fruit trees, gardens, telephone and radio equipment and
even fighting roosters were found inside the quarters after the two
men were transferred, officials said.
   The two inmates, drug barons Rafael Caro Quintero and Ernesto
Fonseca Carrillo, are among those charged in the 1985 kidnapping and
slaying of U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration agent Enrique
Camarena Salazar.
   The two invited five other prisoners and up to 50 friends and
relatives to stay at their refurbished quarters, said Alfonso
Cabrera Morales, city prisons director.
   Cabrera Morales said Tuesday that authorities confiscated seven
guns from Caro Quintero, and $109,000 in cash and an undetermined
amount in jewels from Fonseca Carrillo when the two were transferred
to maximum-security quarters recently.
   Television film of their sumptuous residences in the Northern
Prison showed kitchens, elaborately decorated living rooms and
bedrooms and a closet filled with Caro Quintero's cowboy hats. One
of the rooms had a fireplace.
   Reporters who visited the quarters on Tuesday said the plush
dwellings were air-conditioned and had telephone and radio
communications equipment. Caro Quintero's wardrobe included 35 silk
shirts, the Excelsior news service said.
   A maroon silk bathrobe hung in his marble bathroom, Excelsior
said.
   Cabrera Morales, who became prisons director four months ago,
said the plush lifestyle was uncovered during an investigation of
prison corruption.
   ``It was an unjust situation,'' he said.
   Each of the men was occupying a dormitory designed for 125
inmates.
   ``It's important to establish, and it is true, that another group
of 20 people who were not inmates, among them women, children,
assistants and all kinds of visitors there could be, were living
with them,'' he said of Caro Quintero's group.
   Fonseca also had 15 to 20 friends and relatives with him, he
said. Five other prisoners were invited to live there, he said.
   The official said complaints were filed against the two Tuesday
with the Attorney General's Office, he said.
   He blamed corruption in the prison system for the privileges.
   Lawyers for Caro Quintero and Fonseca have protested their move
to maximum-security prisons.
   Caro Quintero's lawyers said Monday he had ordered them to file a
complaint to the Mexico City prison system for abuse of authority,
conspiracy and intimidation, the newspaper El Financiero reported.
   Caro Quintero is serving a 34-year sentence for weapons and drug
charges. Fonseca is serving an 11 year sentence on other drug and
weapons charges.
   Neither he nor Fonseca have been tried in the Camarena case.
   Camarena and his Mexican pilot were kidnapped Feb. 7, 1985, in
the western city of Guadalajara. Their bodies were found on a ranch
March 5 of that year.
</TEXT>
