<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-89 1436EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-ForestBoy     07-19 0503</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Forest Boy,0517</SECOND>
<HEAD>11-Year-Old Evades Police, Embarrasses Authorities</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATTI HUUHTANEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HELSINKI, Finland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An 11-year-old who escaped from a boys'
home and evaded police by living in a forest has embarrassed social
authorities and prompted a parliamentary investigation into the case.
   The youth, identified only as Pikkis, has been on the run in the
forest near his former home in Espoo, outside Helsinki, for more
than a week. Friends secretly gave him food and clothing.
   Pikkis fled from an institution for homeless boys in Turku, 125
miles from Espoo, where he was sent by social authorities 18 months
ago.
   ``I ran away because I could not live in that place. The people
there are pigs. They ordered me about and hit me,'' Pikkis said in a
television interview, in which only his voice was heard.
   ``Living in the forest is much better than being in that boys'
home. I wouldn't go back even if they paid me,'' Pikkis said.
   The case of Pikkis, dubbed the ``forest boy'' by the media, has
generated interest in a country that prides itself on the high level
of welfare for the unfortunate and the care available for all
citizens.
   Assistant parliamentary ombudsman Pirkko Koskinen said
``something was apparently rotten,'' and she had commissioned a full
report on the case.
   ``Obviously, an 11-year-old boy cannot play at being Robinson
Crusoe. The forest is no place for him to live. We must find a
solution to the problem before the hot summer weather ends,'' she
said. ``Of course, what I'm particularly interested in is to find
out what happened at that boys' home in Turku.''
   Pikkis was sent to Turku after his parents separated because,
according to press reports, his father was incapable of looking
after him and his mother didn't want to.
   Annikki Alho, senior psychologist at the Turku boys' home, denied
anyone was beaten at the home, but said she could not discuss
Pikkis' specific case.
   ``It is obvious that our methods do not include hitting. We never
use such means on anyone. Besides, it is forbidden by law,'' Alho
said.
   ``Yes, there are Dickensian overtones to the whole affair but
when we get to the bottom of it I'm sure it won't be as bad as made
out by the press,'' Alho said.
   Last weekend, Pikkis was given shelter in a friend's house after
four adults were allowed in on his secret.
   On Monday, only minutes before he was due to meet welfare
authorities, neighbors put the police on his track, and the boy
again went underground.
   ``It is really unfortunate that we did not make contact with the
lad because we have a foster family lined up for him. At the moment
it seems that the media know more about the case than we do,'' said
Laura Jussila, social welfare officer in Espoo.
   ``Our prime concern is with the well-being of the boy but we do
not want to break the law or step on anyone's toes,'' Jussila said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
