<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-89 1446EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-China-Deng     07-19 0708</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Deng,0730</SECOND>
<HEAD>Steelworkers Say Deng's Speech Cleared Their Minds</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Off-hours classes at the Capital Iron and Steel
Co. used to focus on new technologies. Now, however, study is
mandatory and the text is senior leader Deng Xiaoping's speech on
crushing pro-democracy protests.
   All 184,000 workers at the company's facility in western Beijing
are taking part in once-weekly classes in which the themes of Deng's
speech are repeated, examples are raised and personal experiences
are recounted and analyzed.
   ``After studying (Deng's speech) I improved my thinking and
understand more clearly the nature of the rebellion,'' Wang Songjie,
a worker in Capital Steel's sintering plant, told five co-workers,
two top plant officials, three lower-ranking officials and a foreign
journalist on Wednesday.
   The workers, some about to go on shifts and some coming off,
gathered for their class in a tiny factory sitting room, copies of
Deng's June 9 speech to army officers balanced on their knees.
   Noisy fans kept the hot, muggy air circulating as the six
students took turns summing up what they learned about the
seven-week student movement for a freer society that Deng condemned
as an effort to overthrow the government and socialist system.
   The army ended it June 3-4 with an attack on the protesters in
central Beijing in which hundreds and perhaps thousands of people
were killed. Thousands have been arrested since.
   Not one of the participants mentioned the deaths or arrests, but
Wang appeared to defend them.
   ``If bad elements savagely cause turmoil and don't allow us to
attack them, this would be so unfair,'' he said. ``Martial law is
supported by the people.''
   ``We must have unified thinking,'' said Li Zuowei, an engineer.
``What is this thinking? It is the policy expressed by Deng
Xiaoping. This cannot be shaken and will not be changed.''
   Phrases from Deng's speech and newspaper commentaries abounded:
``a handful of people with ulterior motives,'' ``stability and
unity,'' ``uphold production,'' ``grasp well ideological education.''
   ``There have been many rumors,'' said worker He Dakun. ``But
after studying Deng Xiaoping's speech we expelled all outside
disturbances from our minds and put all our efforts into our work.''
   Rumors are indeed legion, including shaky reports that workers at
other factories are staging slow-down protests against the
government. At one point during the protests students reported they
had heard that Capital Steel workers were on strike, but those at
Wednesday's class denied it.
   ``In fact, many workers came to work even though transportation
was stopped,'' He said. ``One worker, Mu Kehua, in order to fulfill
the (factory) quota spent 70 yuan (about $19) on a taxi to get to
work.''
   Cao Muming, director of the sintering plant, said only one of his
plant's 1,088 workers joined the protesters in Tiananmen Square.
   ``He is being investigated and is studying,'' Cao said.
   The workers' recitations were expressionless, and there was no
opportunity to ask them privately what they thought. Many Beijing
residents say privately they oppose the army crackdown, although not
all supported the students.
   All across the nation, work units are holding classes to study
Deng's speech with the aim of wiping out the silent opposition. But
Capital Steel is taking special pains.
   As Beijing's most prominent factory, its workers epitomize in the
public mind the urban proletarian who is supposed to lead socialism.
During the student movement, authorities reportedly threatened to
punish any Capital Steel worker who took part.
   Now, they are determined to maintain Capital Steel's image as a
socialist bastion. Every other week, the workers in each plant
gather by the hundreds for political lectures.
   But the real education comes in the small groups, where workers
must show they have internalized the message.
   For any Chinese over the age of 30, that may not be difficult.
Veterans of the 1966-76 far leftist Cultural Revolution and more
recent, less-violent political campaigns are experienced in
stringing together phrases from official documents.
   The only time the discussion became lively was when a reporter
asked about the date of the largest march of the student movement,
when more than 1 million people filled Beijing streets.
   ``That was May 17,'' the workers said. What happened on the
street, it seemed, they had no need to study.
</TEXT>
