<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Korea-Bulgaria     07-19 0140</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Korea-Bulgaria,0144</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bulgaria to Open Trade Office in Seoul</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bulgaria, which has no diplomatic
relations with South Korea, will open a trade office in Seoul this
week, government officials said Wednesday.
   Under a bilateral accord reached this year, South Korea opened
its trade office in Sofia in April, they said.
   Bulgaria will thus become the fifth East European nation to
exchange trade offices with anti-communist South Korea, following
the lead of Hungary, Yugoslavia, Poland and the Soviet Union.
   Trade between Bulgaria and South Korea, which totaled $3.4
million in 1987, almost tripled last year, according to officials at
the state-run Korea Trade Promotion Corp.
   Hungary became the first communist nation to establish full
diplomatic ties with South Korea in February. Yugoslavia and Poland
are expected to follow suit by the end of this year.
</TEXT>
