<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     07-19 0354</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0369</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOON, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 20th anniversary of Neil Armstrong's stroll
on the moon certainly isn't going unnoticed Thursday in Moon, Ky.
   The mountain hamlet of perhaps 75 people already has installed
new ``Moon'' signs at both ends of town on highway 172 and is geared
up for a party that includes a prize drawing with a theme.
   Grand prize: a case of Moon Pies, a picture taken with the
postmistress of Moon, dinner and a play at Jenny Wiley State Park,
and a ``giant step'' in wet cement outside the Moon Post Office. The
first 10 runners-up also get boxes of the marshmallow-filled pies.
   The festivities were organized by Langley Franklin, president of
the Kiwanis Club in nearby West Liberty, who was in junior high
school when Armstrong became the first man to set foot on the moon.
   Both NASA and Gov. Wallace Wilkinson were invited to the event.
   Wilkinson sent his regrets and noted, ``It sounds like an out of
this world experience.''
   NASA politely thanked Moon and the Kiwanians for their interest.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ZIONSVILLE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dancers from the Bolshoi Academy dropped
the pas de deux for a few do-si-dos during a visit to an American
dairy farm.
   About 90 dancers and staff from the Soviet troupe put on T-shirts
and red bandanas for the old-fashioned hoedown at the Bella Estancia
farm Monday night.
   They were guests of the Indiana Dance Ambassadors, a group of
5-to 18-year-olds who wanted to give the travelers a look at life in
rural America. The Soviet group watched the American youths perform
a few tap dance routines, dined on country chicken and toured the
farm.
   ``They're amazing. They're so kind and generous,'' Beth O'Brien,
13, said.
   Like the other youngsters, she received gifts from the Soviet
visitors _ three pins, a small wooden doll, a book and a spoon.
   Soviet ballerina Galina Stepanyenko, 23, shared her impressions
of an American farm: ``It is so nice for someone to have such a
farm. When someone has such a farm, there's no necessity for them to
live in the city.''
</TEXT>
