<FIRST>r a AM-KhashoggiProfile     07-19 0611</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Khashoggi Profile,0631</SECOND>
<HEAD>Khashoggi Has Known Heights Of Opulence, Inside Of a Jail Cell</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Khashoggi, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto ZUR5</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Adnan Khashoggi has known the good times,
maintaining luxury homes in 10 cities and continent-hopping in his
private DC-8.
   More recently, he's known the bad: involvement in the Iran-Contra
scandal, a bankruptcy filing for one of his companies, indictment in
the Marcos case, and arrest and jail as Prisoner 67391.
   The 53-year-old Saudi financier has seen it all in an
extraordinary entrepreneurial life dedicated to the accumulation of
spectacular wealth and the cultivation of contacts worldwide.
   He was extradited to the United States from Switzerland on
Wednesday to face arraignment in New York on federal charges
stemming from Ferdinand and Imelda Marcos' alleged
multimillion-dollar theft of the Philippines treasury.
   Prosecutors accuse Khashoggi of posing as the owner of some of
the assets that were actually acquired by the Marcoses.
   Khashoggi's indictment and subsequent arrest on April 18 _
authorities grabbed him in an elegant Swiss hotel _ continued a
recent series of woes which include financial troubles and constant
controversy.
   The son of a physician to the Saudi royal family, Khashoggi
showed his talent in the art of the deal at an early age. While he
was still a boarding school student in Egypt, he introduced the
fathers of two classmates: one who made towels and sheets, the other
who was in the market for them.
   Khashoggi pocketed 200 pounds and learned an important lesson:
``It's only (by) putting people together you make money.''
   Khashoggi came to the United States to study economics at
California State University at Chico.
   While in California, he arranged for the export of U.S. goods to
Saudi Arabia. When he returned to his native country, he used his
royal connections to continue as broker between the West and Saudi
Arabia.
   Guns became Khashoggi's bread-and-butter, and he served as a
major conduit for military goods bound for Saudi Arabia.
   His Triad Holding Corp. soon branched out into Kenyan real
estate, Asian hotels, Indonesian shipping, French fashions, Lebanese
furniture, cattle raising in Arizona and an import company in the
Philippines.
   At the height of his financial success, he went through $250,000
a day. His yacht, later sold to developer Donald Trump, was fitted
with gold fixtures.
   But in the mid-1970s, Khashoggi became embroiled in the scandal
surrounding bribes by U.S. companies to foreign governments _
although he was never charged.
   It was alleged that part of Khashoggi's commissions were funneled
to foreign officials. In 1977 he flew to Barbados to avoid a
Securities and Exchange Commission subpoena; two years later, he
voluntarily gave a deposition to the SEC.
   His name made headlines again in 1986 when it was revealed that
he had brokered the U.S.-Iran arms deal at the center of the
Iran-Contra scandal.
   Khashoggi acknowledged he had a role in the deal, and said he
lost $10 million on it. He added that he never expected to make a
profit. If the result was peace between Iran and Iraq, he said, he
would make money by helping rebuild both countries.
   Khashoggi's wealth, meanwhile, seemed to vanish. Triad America
Corp., his U.S. holding company, filed for protection under
bankruptcy statutes. Work stopped on a $400 million office-shopping
complex in Salt Lake City.
   A British company, Lonrho PLC of London, sued because Khashoggi
defaulted on two $4 million loans; authorities temporarily seized
two Khashoggi jets and his two-story duplex apartment on Manhattan's
Fifth Avenue.
   Finally, Khashoggi defaulted on a loan to the Sultan of Brunei,
who claimed the collateral _ his yacht, the Nabila. The Sultan then
sold the boat for $30 million to Trump.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
