<SECOND>AM-Congress' Trash, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0617,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Recycle More of What Congress Produces Much Of, Lawmaker Urges</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: Inserts 14th graf, That amounts xxx with number of people working
for Congress; picks up last graf: Because it xxx</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE FEINSILBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Capitol Hill, which produces 60 tons of trash a
day, took a look Wednesday at ways it could recycle more of its
words, or at least the paper they're printed on.
   Before the House subcommittee on procurement and printing was a
bill by Rep. Bill Green, R-N.Y., calling on the architect of the
Capitol, George White, to devise a plan to recycling more of
Congress' rubbish.
   Only 10 percent of the paper the House and the Senate throws away
now is sold for reuse. Green said by passing his bill Congress would
be ``setting an example for the rest of the country.''
   White laid before the subcommittee an elaborate plan. It called
for a year-long pilot program under which workers in two
congressional office buildin of the executive, legislative and
judicial branches of the federal government'' to comply with local
laws ``respecting control and abatement of solid waste or hazardous
waste disposal.''
   ``We expect you to do it,'' she said.
   Fifty-three percent of Washington's waste is paper, said Ms.
Winters.
   ``The very nature of our city is reflected in the waste generated
within the city,'' she said.
   The city, she said, produces 381,000 tons of waste paper a year,
much of it high-quality paper, valuable when recycled.
   ``It is a national resource which must be reused. To do any less
would be to encourage a national disgrace.''
   White reported that Capitol Hill _ including Congress' hill
neighbors, the Library of Congress and the Supreme Court _ generate
20,000 tons of trash a year, much of it paper and only 10 percent of
it recycled.
   That amounts to roughly eight pounds a day for each of the 15,000
people who work for Congress.
   Because it is all lumped together it commands only $1 a ton from
recyclers. High quality paper, separated out, might go for $15 a
ton, he said.
</TEXT>
