<FIRST>r a AM-TaxResisters     07-19 0375</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tax Resisters,0388</SECOND>
<HEAD>Protesters Besiege IRS Auction of Tax Protesters' Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREENFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Several hundred protesters lined the
street around the Internal Revenue Service office Wednesday as tax
agents tried to auction the home of a pair of tax resisters.
   The only bidders were the protesters, who offered to trade
$21,414 in food and donated services to the poor for the home of
Randall Kehler, a founder of the Nuclear Freeze campaign, and his
wife, Betsy Corner. The couple has refused to pay federal taxes for
12 years to protest government spending on the military.
   The protesters' bid was rejected and the government acquired the
home for the minimum bid of $5,100.
   ``Food is not legal tender,'' said Robert Ruttenberg, an IRS
spokesman.
   The donated canned goods filled a truck parked outside the IRS
office.
   ``We feel good that this community is making a statement about
where our resources ought to be going and that is to support our
communities and feed the poor, not to build weapons and destroy the
planet,'' Kehler said.
   According to Ruttenberg, the couple owes about $27,000 in back
taxes.
   Kehler said that instead of paying taxes, he and his wife have
filed returns and donated the money they owed to local charities and
peace groups. They have continued to pay state and local taxes, he
said.
   ``The first year we had a taxable income was in 1977,'' he said.
``We would haaxes before any eviction proceedings can be
started against them and their 9-year-old daughter. Kehler said he
and his family won't pay and won't go quietly.
   ``We will refuse to cooperate with any eviction and non-violently
occupy our own home,'' he said.
   Ruttenberg said the number of tax resisters protesting military
spending has dropped to about 5,000 from about 22,000 in the early
1980s.
   ``If they want to change the law, let them elect people that will
do that,'' he said. ``But they are breaking the law and doing it at
the expense of other people, who have to pay their freight for
Social Secuirty and food stamp programs.''
</TEXT>
