<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Army     07-19 0488</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Army,0505</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soldiers Detail Abuses in Elite Infantry Unit</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A soldier in an elite infantry battalion
committed suicide and another shot himself in the foot to escape
brutality from fellow troops, a newspaper reported Wednesday.
   The daily Hadashot said both incidents occurred in a single
platoon. The unit, it said, was dominated by ``former criminals''
who beat recruits and gave orders to officers who were too
intimidated to discipline them.
   The commander of the Givati battalion, which often is used to
suppress Palestinian riots in the occupied Gaza Strip, said reports
of abuse in the unit were exaggerated, Hadashot and the independent
Haaretz reported.
   A military spokesman would not confirm details of the reports.
But the spokesman said the platoon's commander, deputy commander and
three non-commissioned officers were dismissed several months ago
and the platoon disbanded.
   The spokesman, who cannot be identified under briefing rules,
also said the head of southern command, Maj. Gen. Matan Vilnai, met
with Givati commanders ``in connection with recent incidents'' but
would not elaborate.
   Platoons in the Israeli army generally have about 20 soldiers.
   The soldier who shot himself in the foot was tried before a
military court and given a three-month suspended sentence for
unauthorized use of his weapon, the newspapers reported.
   He was identified only as a resident of the Negev desert town of
Ofakim.
   Hadashot said that during the trial it was disclosed that another
soldier in the platoon committed suicide, but gave no details.
   ``The picture painted by the accused was described by one judge
as a Sodom and Gomorrah,'' Haaretz reported.
   ``The accused described to us a situation where his unit is ruled
by soldiers with criminal backgrounds, who act violently toward
anyone who does not submit to their will,'' Haaretz quoted the court
decision as saying.
   Haaretz said soldiers in the platoon beat recruits and abandoned
their guardposts, but the newspaper gave no other details of
brutality.
   ``We wonder how such a unit will stand up when it is called to
battle,'' it said.
   The commander of Givati, identified only as Col. Y., told the
newspapers the soldier's testimony was incorrect, but confirmed
there were problems in the unit.
   ``I personally dismissed the platoon commander and the unit
commander for their lack of control over the soldiers,'' he said.
   He accused the court of being unnecessarily harsh and added: ``We
are talking about an elite unit that is doing difficult work in the
(occupied) territories and in Lebanon and to come today and dirty
their names in not reasonable.''
   It was not the first time Givati troops were accused in court of
brutality.
   In May, a military court convicted four Givati soldiers of abuse
and sentenced them to nine months in jail for beating a Palestinian
refugee in Gaza with their rifle butts and a broomstick. The Arab
died of later beatings he received from other soldiers, the court
said.
</TEXT>
