<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-89 1530EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Namibia     07-19 0586</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Namibia,0614</SECOND>
<HEAD>Release of Prisoners Announced in Namibia</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WDH1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Africa's administrator in Namibia
on Wednesday announced the release of 24 political prisoners and a
reduced role for some police.
   The moves by Namibia's top official, Louis Pienaar, are likely to
reduce tensions in the territory as it heads toward independence
after 74 years of South African rule.
   Pienaar made the announcement after he met with U.N.
Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar conferred for two hours
Wednesday.
   ``We are now, broadly speaking, back on track for elections in
early November,'' said Perez de Cuellar.
   However, he also acknowledged potential obstacles: ``It is
perhaps inevitable that after so many years of conflict, fears and
distrust should persist, but they should not be allowed to
continue.''
   Pienaar said: ``I am completely satisfied in the manner in which
the meeting was conducted.''
   He said the 24 men to be freed Thursday are considered the last
political prisoners in Namibia. However, he said he decided against
releasing eight men convicted or accused of political violence.
   Pienaar previously linked the freeing of political prisoners to
the release of people he believes are being held by the South-West
Africa People's Organization.
   The group, known as SWAPO, waged a 23-year guerrilla war against
South African rule of Namibia. It is now the favorite in
pre-independence elections set for November.
   South Africa agreed in December to carry out the U.N.
independence plan under terms of a regional peace accord. Under the
U.S.-brokered pact, South Africa also pledged to halt aid to
guerrillas battling the Angolan government.
   In exchange, the agreement stipulated that the estimated 50,000
Cuban troops supporting the Angolan government would be withdrawn.
   Pienaar said he changed his mind about freeing prisoners when
Perez de Cuellar assured him the United Nations would seek the
return to Namibia of all SWAPO detainees.
   SWAPO has said it released all 201 of its detainees in April.
However, only 153 returned to Namibia two weeks ago, and on
Wednesday they released a list of 439 people they say still are held
in southern Angola.
   Pienaar also said he would deploy to less-tense regions policemen
who previously belonged to a counterinsurgency unit known as
Koevoet, the Afrikaans word for ``crowbar.''
   Many of Koevoet's estimated 3,000 members were integrated into
the regular police force after the unit was officially disbanded in
January.
   Koevoet has been accused of dozens of atrocities in northern
Namibia, where most of the bush war was fought. SWAPO says former
Koevoet members, who are mostly black Namibians, continue to harass
its supporters.
   Pienaar also said U.N. police monitors in northern Namibia will
be encouraged to accompany local police patrols.
   The United Nations has more than 5,000 soldiers and police in the
territory, but their role is largely supervisory.
   Perez de Cuellar also met with members of 10 political factions.
   He was quoted as saying the vigorous election campaign was
heartening evidence that political leaders are working for national
unity.
   ``Namibia will need all of its people, all their skills and
resources ... when it stands before the world as an independent
state,'' he said.
   Pienaar also said one unresolved issue concerns his charges that
1,900 SWAPO fighters are massed in Angola near the Namibian border.
SWAPO denies the charges.
   The U.N. chief is to visit several northern towns Thursday to
examine security and observe the ongoing repatriation of 41,000
Namibian refugees. On Friday, he heads to South Africa for talks
with government leaders.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
