<DOCNO> AP890719-0147 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-89 1549EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Korea     07-19 0484</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea,0503</SECOND>
<HEAD>South Korean President Shakes Up Cabinet</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Roh Tae-woo on Wednesday
dismissed or reassigned six Cabinet ministers and fired his
intelligence chief, but the opposition denounced the moves as merely
cosmetic.
   The changes were not expected to alter government policies. They
were widely seen as political housekeeping moves to try to reassure
citizens that the governing Democratic Justice Party is concerned
about social unrest, rising crime and welfare problems.
   Opposition leaders said Roh had ignored the public's desire for a
complete change to erase the legacies of disgraced former president
Chun Doo-hwan. He left office in 1988 and later went into rural
exile after apologizing for abuses during his regime.
   Most of Roh's 23-member Cabinet worked in some capacity under the
Chun government.
   Wednesday's shake-up involved home, construction, communications,
labor, and health-social affairs ministers as well as the first
minister of state for political affairs.
   Prime Minister Kang Young-hoon and the other 16 ministers were
retained. In the last Cabinet changes in December 1988, Kang and 19
ministers were appointed.
   The most noticeable action Wednesday was the dismissal of Park
Seh-jik as head of the main government intelligence organization,
the Agency for National Security Planning. Park was replaced by
former Attorney General Suh Dong-kwon.
   Park, a former army general who served as chief organizer of the
1988 Seoul Olympics, was held responsible for his agency's failure
to detect a series of secret visits to communist North Korea by
South Korean dissident leaders.
   Under South Korea's anti-communist law, unauthorized visits to
the communist North are a crime.
   The largest opposition group, the Party for Peace and Democracy,
said Roh had filled his cabinet with hard-liners associated with his
disgraced predecessor.
   The party focused on the choice of Suh as intelligence chief.
``He (Suh) was in the vanguard of the government's suppression of
political opposition and dissent'' while in his legal post, said
party spokesman Lee Sang-soo.
   Lee said the Cabinet change ``ignored the people's ardent desires
for further democratization and liquidation of human rights abuses
and corruption'' under Chun.
   Lee In-che, spokesman for the second largest opposition group,
Reunification Democratic Party, said the changes were ``not adequate
to satisfy the people's anticipation of renovation in government.''
He said the public had anticipated a shake-up that would include the
premiership.
   In other changes announced Wednesday, National Assemblyman Kim
Tae-ho of the governing was made home minister, succeeding Lee
Han-dong.
   Kwon Yong-gack, president of the state-run Korea Housing Corp.
and a retired army general, became construction minister.
   Former governing party lawmaker Kim Chong-in was made health and
social affairs minister, Communications Minister Choi Young-choul
was reassigned as labor minister, and former President Lee Woo-chae
of the state-run Korea Telecommunications Authority took over Choi's
old post.
   Park Chul-un, a special presidential assistant on political
matters, was named first minister of state for political affairs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890719-0148 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-89 1539EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-HousingStarts 1stLd-Writethru a0620 07-19 0561</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Housing Starts, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0620,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Apartment Construction Leads Housing Start Rebound</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Economy, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS Northwest to Northeast in next-to-last graf bgng ``But
the''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN D. McCLAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Housing starts, led by a steep rise in
apartment building, rebounded 7 percent in June as interest rates
fell, the government reported Wednesday, but analysts said
single-family construction would remain weak as the economy
continues to slow.
   New homes and apartments were built at a seasonally adjusted
annual rate of 1.4 million units last month, up from 1.31 million
units in May when construction fell 2.5 percent, the Commerce
Department reported.
   While June's increase was the highest since an 8.6 percent hike
to 1.51 million units in February 1988, it reflected a 28 percent
rise in apartment construction, the highest since a 43 percent
increase in April 1988.
   Single-family construction fell in June for the third straight
month, prompting David Seiders, chief economist for the National
Association of Home Builders, to say this sector of the housing
market is ``still in a bit of the doldrums'' because of both
interest rates and the economy.
   ``Builders are extremely cautious,'' said chief economist David
Berson of the Federal National Mortgage Association. ``They're
waiting to make sure the decline in interest rates leads to a
sustained increase in single-family sales.''
   The housing industry had been among the sectors of the economy
hardest hit as interest rates edged upward over the past year while
the Federal Reserve sought to restrain economic growth and contain
inflation.
   But as inflation seemed to slow, fixed rate mortgages had fallen
to 10.07 percent by the end of June from a peak of 11.22 percent in
March and analysts began looking for a pickup in housing activity.
   Seiders, however, said Wednesday's report was not a signal that
interest rates have revived the housing industry.
   ``The really interest-sensitive part is single-family
construction, where we saw a bit of a decline,'' he said, adding
that another reason for the decline ``is the slowing economy which
will leave housing rather weak for the rest of the year.''
   Economist John Tuccillo of the National Association of Realtors
called the weak single-family sector a reflection of the health of
the residential construction market.
   Construction of single-family homes fell 2 percent in June to an
annual rate of 975,000 units, the lowest level since August 1984
when 967,000 units were started. Single-family construction fell 5.1
percent in May and 4.7 percent in April.
   Apartment construction, on the other hand, rose last month to an
annual rate of 425,000 units. But this sector often is volatile:
construction of multifamily units had risen 2.6 percent in May after
falling 26.6 percent in April.
   Tuccillo saw two other disturbing factors: ``a disproportionate
volume of activity in the West'' and a decrease in applications for
building permits.
   The West posted a 21.4 percent increase in starts to 443,000
units on a seasonally adjusted annual rate. The South also
registered an increase, up 5.8 percent to 548,000 units.
   But the Northeast had a 5 percent decrease to 171,000 units while
Midwestern starts were down 3.3 percent to 238,000 units.
   Applications for building permits, a barometer of future
multifamily housing activity, were down 3.5 percent, following
increases of 1 percent in May and 8.5 percent in April. They had
fallen the three previous months, however.
</TEXT>
