<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--RoughLanding     07-19 0159</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Rough Landing,0162</SECOND>
<HEAD>Plane Carrying 80 Soldiers Misses Runway</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MUSKOGEE, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Air Force and Army investigators have been
sent to determine what caused Wednesday's rough landing of an Air
Force C-5A Galaxy airplane carrying 80 soldiers, a flight crew and
seven helicopters.
   The plane landed just short of the runway at Davis Field in
Muskogee about 3 a.m. Wednesday. No one was injured.
   Army spokesmen on the scene said the skin on the plane's right
side was damaged and the aircraft's wheel wells were damaged.
   A spokeswoman for the Army's Joint Readiness Training Center at
Fort Chaffee, Ark., said the soldiers, members of the Army's 6th
Infantry at Fort Wainwright, Alaska, were being flown to Davis Field
for training. The Joint Readiness Training Center stages operations
at Davis before taking the soldiers and their equipment to Fort
Chaffee.
   The aircraft was flown by members of the 60th Military Airlift
Wing from Travis Air Force Base, Calif.
