<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-89 1700EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-CoalStrike     07-19 0415</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Coal Strike,0429</SECOND>
<HEAD>UMW, Pittston Begin Negotiations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK PAXTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DUFFIELD, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Contract negotiations between the United
Mine Workers and The Pittston Co. got off to a rocky start Wednesday
and the union accused the nation's largest coal exporter of being
inflexible.
   UMW President Richard Trumka said Pittston refuses to negotiate
in good faith and will not rescind what it calls its final offer,
which the union rejected last month.
   ``They want us to be flexible but they don't want to be,'' union
spokesman Joe Corcoran said.
   Pittston Coal Group President Michael Odom said Wednesday on
``CBS This Morning'' that the company is standing by its previous
contract proposal.
   ``At this point the movement will have to come from the union,''
Odom said. ``We have our proposal on the table.
   ``We feel our proposal recognized the dynamics of the coal market
we operate in ... we feel our proposal would put people back to
work.''
   Trumka said Odom's appearance on the show put the union in a sour
mood.
   ``How can the mood be good when they get on TV and say how
inflexible they are?''
   About 1,900 UMW miners are on strike at Pittston operations in
Virginia, West Virginia and Kentucky. The Virginia and West Virginia
miners went on strike in early April and the Kentucky miners
followed in June.
   Up to 46,000 miners in 10 states had been off the job in sympathy
with the Pittston miners until Monday, when most returned to work at
Trumka's urging. Isolated pockets of striking wildcat miners remain,
most in West Virginia.
   Wednesday's negotiations were conducted from separate rooms with
federal mediators shuttling messages between them.
   Corcoran said one of the main sticking points is Pittston's
insistence on ending its contributions to the 1950 UMW retirement
fund, which covers 130,000 pensioners who retired between 1947 and
1976.
   Pittston, which has 560 retirees covered by the fund, said it
doesn't want to contribute to pensions received by retirees of other
companies.
   Corcoran said the 1950 fund was established so miners who went
from company to company when mines shut down could have pensions.
   ``You're talking about guys who worked for eight or 10 different
companies, and when they retired, they wouldn't have a pension
because they didn't work for one company long enough,'' Corcoran
said.
   If Pittston pulls out of the retirement fund, he said, other
companies will want to do the same, which would put the burden on
the federal government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
