<DOCNO> AP890719-0157 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-89 1715EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-JohnstonFuneral     07-19 0229</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Johnston Funeral,240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former NATO Commander Eulogized</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ARLINGTON, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four-star Adm. Means Johnston Jr., who
commanded all NATO forces in Southern Europe, was buried with full
military honors Wednesday at Arlington National Cemetery.
   Johnston, 73, a native of Greenwood, Miss., was eulogized at a
memorial service by retired Adm. Thomas Moorer, former chairman of
the Joint Chiefs of Staff.
   Moorer called Johnston's death ``an extreme loss not only for his
family and friends, but for the whole country.
   ``He was a professional naval officer in every sense of the
word,'' Moorer said, adding that ``his standards included everything
that has made this nation great.''
   Moorer, a long-time friend of Johnston's, also described him as
``a true Southern gentleman.''
   After the service, Johnston's flag-draped casket was brought into
the cemetery atop a caisson drawn by six white horses, accompanied
by a four-member color guard, 20-piece band and 22-member ceremonial
guard.
   After the flag was carefully folded, it was presented by Navy
chaplain Stanley DeLong to Johnston's widow, Hope Manning Larkin
Johnston.
   Johnston, who lived in McLean, Va., a Washington suburb, died
last Friday at Walter Reed Army Hospital after a lengthy illness. He
was the son of the late Mr. and Mrs Means Johnston of Greenwood.
   Johnston achieved the rank of four-star admiral in 1973. He
retired in 1975 after 40 years of service in the Navy.
