<FIRST>r p AM-Barry-Jackson     07-19 0361</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Barry-Jackson,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mayor to Sign Bill Limiting Outside Income for Top City Officials</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Marion Barry said Wednesday that he will
sign a bill limiting outside income for top elected city officials
but denied it is an attempt to discourage Jesse Jackson from
entering the 1990 mayoral campaign.
   ``I think it's a good bill,'' Barry said. ``It doesn't affect me
_ I make enough money in this job.''
   The bill, passed last week by the District of Columbia Council,
places a $10,000 annual limit on honoraria for the mayor and the 13
members of the council. Some council members opposed the bill,
pointing out that Jackson earns much of his estimated $200,000
annual income from speeches and appearances. Barry earns $82,500 per
year.
   The bill was sponsored by council member John Ray, a declared
mayoral candidate. Council Chairman David Clarke, who also is
seeking the mayor's office, added an amendment placing a $10,000
yearly cap on book royalties for the mayor and council chairman.
   Barry denied that the bill was intended to discourage Jackson
from running and described it as ethics legislation. The mayor could
have vetoed the bill or allowed it to become law without his
signature.
   The mayor, however, sidestepped questions about whether he
anticipates having to run against Jackson and also refused to
comment on whether he expects Jackson to support his bid for an
unprecedented fourth term.
   ``God gave me a great brain _ I'm a smart politician,'' Barry
said. ``My timetable will not be decided by others.''
   Barry also refused to talk about a meeting he had with Jackson on
Tuesday at a downtown hotel. Jackson, who has said he is not running
for mayor but has declined to rule out an eventual run, met with
Barry and Walter Fauntroy, the district's non-voting congressional
delegate, for about 90 minutes.
   Barry described the session as a ``prayer meeting.'' Fauntroy
declined to comment on the meeting. Jackson was unavailable
Wednesday.
   The meeting came just hours after Jackson said he intended to
move his legal residence to Washington, a step which would allow him
to enter the mayor's race.
</TEXT>
