<SECOND>AM-Journal-Constitution,0252</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wendell `Sonny' Rawls Resigns as Managing Editor for Local News</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wendell ``Sonny'' Rawls, a Pulitzer Prize winner
who came to The Atlanta Journal-Constitution with editor Bill
Kovach, has left the newspapers eight months after Kovach's stormy
resignation.
   Newspaper officials also confirmed Wednesday that sports
columnist Dave Kindred has resigned.
   Rawls' departure as assistant managing editor for local news was
disclosed Wednesday in an article about plans for a movie about
Kovach's 23 months as editor.
   Journal-Constitution Editor Ron Martin declined to discuss
replacing Rawls or Kindred.
   The newspapers have not noted Kindred's departure, but his
sports-front column in the morning Constitution has been filled by
other staff columnists.
   Rawls is the last to leave of three New York Times veterans who
assumed top posts at the Atlanta newspapers. Kovach, who became
editor of the Journal-Constitution in December 1986, resigned in
November after skirmishes with corporate management. Dudley
Clendenin, hired by Kovach as assistant managing editor for
features, and John Mashek, national political correspondent, also
left.
   Rawls will cooperate with Atlanta novelist Pat Conroy, a Kovach
supporter, on the screenplay for the movie about Kovach.
   Under Kovach, the Journal-Constitution won a Pulitzer Prize for
reporter Bill Dedman's series on discriminatory lending in Atlanta
and shared another Pulitzer for the cartoons of Doug Marlette, hired
by Kovach from The Charlotte (N.C.) Observer.
   Dedman since has left the Journal-Constitution for The Washington
Post. Marlette has left to work for New York's Newsday.
