<FIRST>r w AM-US-Cuba     07-19 0395</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Cuba,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Wants Drug Data from Cuba</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration has asked Cuban
authorities for the results of their investigation of drug smuggling
into the United States by Cuban military officers, the State
Department said Wednesday.
   Deputy spokesman Richard Boucher said the administration is
interested in taking ``appropriate action'' based on whatever
information Cuban officials provide.
   No response has been received from Cuban authorities, Boucher
said.
   He acknowledged that there have been contacts recently between
Cuban and American officials but said that there have been no
discussions on formal cooperation in combatting drug smuggling.
   His statement was confirmed by Clinton Adlum, a spokesman for
Cuba's diplomatic mission here.
   The State Department has been wary about joint cooperation with
Cuba. There is uncertainty among U.S. officials as to whether the
recent trials of military officers charged with drug-related
offenses is part of a broader campaign in Cuba to halt use of that
nation's air space and territorial waters to ship illicit drugs to
U.S. markets.
   Some officials are concerned that the crackdown may be limited to
a small group of traffickers and that other drug smuggling
activities may be continuing with official acquiescence.
   Boucher said the United States is looking for a ``serious
effort'' by Cuba to end use of Cuban territory for U.S.-bound drug
shipments originating in Colombia.
   The United States wants Cuba ``to prosecute people, to
investigate allegations of complicity in drug trafficking and to
interdict trafficking through their air space and waters,'' Boucher
said.
   Cuban President Fidel Castro called last week for cooperation
between the United States and Cuba to curb drug trafficking.
   ``We need some way to communicate in this common battle,'' Castro
said in a speech. ``We need to talk to the Americans about how to
manage this situation.''
   He contended the United States had failed to warn him of Cuban
military involvement in cocaine trafficking, saying the United
States had ``at least two names'' of military officers involved in a
cocaine-trafficking conspiracy long before contacts in Colombia
alerted Cuban officials.
   Last Thursday, one of Castro's trusted advisors, Army Maj. Gen.
Arnaldo Ochoa Sanchez, and three other military officers were
executed for smuggling tons of drugs into the United States.
   Previously, Cuba had denied U.S. allegations that Cuba was being
used to smuggle cocaine and marijuana to the United States.
</TEXT>
