<FIRST>u i PM-Poland 6thLd-Writethru   07-19 0698</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland, 6th Ld-Writethru,a0597,a0681,a0692,0720</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Jaruzelski Elected President of Poland</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WAR13</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS thruout to combine previous, delete outdated material.
No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist leader Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski
was elected Wednesday to the country's powerful new presidency by a
slim margin in the National Assembly.
   Jaruzelski, the only candidate, was helped by a boycott by some
opposition lawmakers. The vote was 270 for, 233 against and 34
abstaining. There were 537 valid votes, and 269 were required to
win. The communist coalition has a 300-259 majority in the assembly.
   Government ministers gave one another a thumbs-up sign as word
spread through the chamber while the paper ballots were counted and
recounted.
   ``I state that Citizen Wojciech Jaruzelski has received the
required number of votes and has been elected by the National
Assembly to be the president of the Polish Peoples Republic,''
parliament speaker Mikolaj Kozakiewicz said after the vote.
   The post gives Jaruzelski, the Communist Party leader, control of
the military and foreign relations and allows him to nominate the
next prime minister. The office has a six-year term.
   Politburo member Marian Orzechowski nominated Jaruzelski earlier
today, saying no politician in Poland would be met with ``universal
approval'' but praising Jaruzelski as an advocate of national
reconciliation.
   Solidarity's parliamentary floor leader, Bronislaw Geremek,
neither endorsed nor opposed the nomination but said opposition
lawmakers could not forget Jaruzelski's 1981 martial-law decree that
was directed against the union.
   One by one, lawmakers filed up to a wooden box at the front of
the parliament chamber and deposited printed paper ballots with the
options, ``For,'' ``Against'' and ``Abstain.''
   Many held up ballots showing they were voting against Jaruzelski.
   ``I was and I am for Lech Walesa,'' said Senator Gabriel Janowski
said as he deposited his ballot against Jaruzelski.
   The voting took nearly 1{ hours. Votes were counted in the
presence of the lawmakers.
   As lawmakers gathered for the vote, about 50 anti-Jaruzelski
demonstrators from the Confederation for an Independent Poland
rallied outside. ``Jaruzelski Must Go,'' read one of their banners.
   After a long and emotional debate Tuesday, it had been expected
that most Solidarity lawmakers would vote against Jaruzelski, who
imprisoned many of them as he tried to crush their free trade union
movement with martial law.
   But some, while not forgiving the general for past repression,
argued that defeating him could undermine reforms needed to reverse
the country's economic decline.
   In addition to the Solidarity opposition, Jaruzelski faced
opposition in his own communist coalition, where some members are
openly sympathetic to Solidarity.
   Opposition leaders said they did not offer a presidential
candidate of their own because they believed that winning the
presidency would be unrealistic and could court a backlash from
communist hard-liners.
   In its editions today, the opposition Gazeta Wyborcza said in an
editorial that the country's new president would be ``a guarantor of
a stable course'' as Poland enters a transition period leading to
full democracy.
   Communist-controlled newspapers announced in banner headlines the
news that Jaruzelski _ citing ``a sense of duty'' _ had reversed a
June 30 decision eschewing the presidency and would run after all.
   The communist leadership asked him to reconsider.
   An announcement by Solidarity leader Lech Walesa that he would
cooperate with Jaruzelski as president and words of praise from
President Bush during a visit last week also appeared to have helped
persuade the general.
   Jaruzelski must deal with worsening food shortages and inflation
now headed for annual rate of 160 percent.
   The pressing economic problems have caused widespread discontent
and were the impetus behind the ruling communists' concessions to
Solidarity.
   In April, the free trade union movement was reinstated after a
seven-year ban and allowed to field candidates in June elections
that were the country's freest since the communists seized power
four decades ago.
   In parliament, where Solidarity won all but one of the seats it
was allowed to contest, the communist coalition has 300 of the 560
seats.
   In an apparent sign of growing discontent with climbing prices
and worsening shortages, 11,000 bus and streetcar drivers went on
strike Tuesday in the populous southern province of Katowice to
demand higher wages.
</TEXT>
