<UNK>Autopsy Inconclusive on Boy Who Died After Roller Coaster Ride</UNK>
<DATELINE>AUSTELL, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An autopsy Wednesday failed to pinpoint what
killed a boy who collapsed while riding the Z-Force roller coaster
at the Six Flags Over Georgia amusement park.
   William D. ``Brett'' Pope, 11, of Talladega, Ala., was pronounced
dead Tuesday night about an hour after being taken off the ride,
which makes six sharp, corkscrew dives.
   The ride, which was shut down immediately, will remain closed
until park and state officials finish an investigation, said Six
Flags spokesman Bob Maxwell.
   ``The ride appears to be operating perfectly, but we won't take
any chances,'' Maxwell said.
   A preliminary autopsy by the Cobb County medical examiner's
office failed to find a cause of death, said medical examiner's
spokeswoman Sally Lummus.
   Doctors were still piecing together the child's medical history,
the spokeswoman said. Once that is completed, the body will be sent
to the state crime lab for further analysis, she said.
   Six Flags spokesman Bob Maxwell said the boy appeared fine when
he boarded the ride with his family at 9:40 p.m., but was
unconscious when the ride ended minutes later.
   Maxwell said park personnel used cardiopulmonary resuscitation
until an ambulance arrived to take the boy to HCA Parkway Medical
Center, where he was pronounced dead about an hour later.
   Hospital spokeswoman Mimi Salkin said the child showed no outward
signs of injury.
   The roller coaster carries a warning that pregnant women and
people with heart or back problems shouldn't ride.
   Maxwell said the operators of the ride and other passengers were
being interviewed to determine if anything unusual occurred, but no
other injuries were reported.
   He said the boy's shoulder harness and lap belt were in place
when the ride ended.
   Pope, the son of Ron and Sandra Pope of Talladega, had just
completed the fifth grade, relatives said. His parents declined to
talk about his death.
</TEXT>
