<FIRST>r w AM-BorderCrossings     07-19 0401</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Border Crossings,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study Says Reforms Have Slowed Rate of Illegal Immigration</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Employer sanctions against hiring undocumented
workers appear largely responsible for slowing the rate of illegal
immigration across the Mexican border, according to a study released
Wednesday.
   The study by researchers for the Urban Institute and Princeton
University said 71 percent of the decline in apprehensions along the
U.S.-Mexico border appears due to the ``deterrent effect'' of the
1986 Immigration Reform and Control Act.
   Frank Bean of the Urban Institute and one of the study's authors,
said the sanctions against employers who hire undocumented workers
are the only real deterrent in the law, so ``it is not unrealistic
to think that most (of the deterrent effect) is due to sanctions, if
not all.''
   Dan Stein, executive director of the Federation for American
Immigration Reform, said the study provides the first major
empirical evidence that sanctions are effective.
   ``It shows that many people who don't have unbridled motivation
to get around the law are discouraged from coming. ... It is a
ratification of what we have been saying all along,'' Stein said.
   Using a statistical model, the study said the control act is
associated with a cumulative net reduction in apprehensions of
nearly 700,000 people, or 35 percent, below what would have been
anticipated if circumstances had not changed in the 23-month period
following the law's enactment in November 1986.
   Apprensions are considered the best available indicator of the
flow of illegal immigration across the southern border.
   About 12 percent of the decline is due to changes in the
Immigration and Naturalization Service's efforts, another 17 percent
is due to the law's agricultural legalization program, and the
remaining 71 percent is due to the ``deterrent effect,'' the study
said.
   In addition to the sanctions, the law's major features include
legalization programs for which more than 3 million undocumented
immigrants applied, and stepped up enforcement at the southern
border.
   INS spokesman Verne Jervis said the study ``supports our
contention that IRCA is effective in reducing the flow of illegal
aliens across the southern border. We think sanctions are a major
factor in the sharp decline in apprehensions and illegal border
crossings.''
   But Rep. Albert Bustamante, a Texas Democrat whose district
includes a stretch of border from Laredo to Del Rio, said he does
not believe the flow of illegal immigration is down.
</TEXT>
