<DOCNO> AP890719-0165 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-89 1622EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-US-Korea     07-19 0583</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Korea,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>South Korean Defense Minister Promises US Jet Purchase</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Dick Cheney praised South
Korea's decision to purchase U.S. fighter jets on Wednesday, but
indicated the sensitive topic of co-production of the sophisticated
fighters hasn't been resolved.
   Cheney met with reporters after completing the annual series of
talks with his South Korean counterpart, Lee Sang Hoon.
   ``I would like to get the best deal that we can,'' Cheney said,
when asked about the issue.
   The subject of co-production, still eagerly sought by the South
Koreans, has raised concern among some lawmakers on Capitol Hill who
are worried about the transfer of sensitive technology with a nation
eager to build its own aviation industry.
   Lee told reporters South Korea intends to purchase U.S. fighters,
but had not yet decided which type.
   Asked about a possible co-production plan, Cheney said he had
advised his counterpart to purchase U.S. produced fighters.
   He added, however, that it is in the U.S. interest to see that
the Republic of Korea has necessary equipment to upgrade its air
defenses and that the two sides ``have been discussing the best
method'' by which that can be accomplished.
   Cheney said the two sides ``have been exploring other
possiblities and other options'' and that no final decision has been
made.
   ``What is likely to result will probably be some blend,'' Cheney
said, adding that he was pleased the Koreans had decided to purchase
U.S. planes over those of other nations.
   The U.S. secretary also reassured his South Korean counterpart
that the United States has no immediate plans to cut U.S. troop
strength on the Korean peninsula.
   Lee and the U.S. secretary said their talks had been fruitful,
and they issued a joint statement in which both sides pledged ``to
maintain the close and longstanding security relationship'' between
the two countries.
   The South Koreans have expressed interest in either the F-16,
made by General Dynamics Corp., or the F-18, made by McDonnell
Douglas Corp.
   The South Koreans reportedly seek to buy a dozen of the planes,
assemble three dozen more from U.S.-supplied kits and then build
about 72 on their own.
   Sens. John Heinz, R-Pa., and Alan Dixon, D-Ill., have called the
proposed deal a threat, contending it would transfer critical U.S.
technology to a nation that will use it to develop its own aviation
industry to compete with U.S. firms.
   Lawmakers made the same argument last month as they approved a
plan to co-produce the FSX fighter with Japan but placed
restrictions on negotiations for further stages in the project.
President Bush has threatened to veto the resolution.
   Cheney has come under pressure from some members of Congress to
slash U.S. troop strength in South Korea, given that nation's
prosperous economic condition.
   The secretary has refused to make any changes in the U.S.
position this budget year, but has not ruled out looking at such a
proposal in the future.
   The United States spends $2.6 billion a year on troops in South
Korea.
   Cheney assured his Korean counterpart ``that U.S. troops will
remain in Korea as long as they are needed to meet the threat and as
long as the government and the peoples of the Republic of Korea want
them there.''
   In response to the congressional demands, Pentagon officials have
begun to consider possible plans for a reduction in about 43,000
U.S. troops on the Korean peninsula, but the proposals are only in
preliminary stages, officials have said.
</TEXT>
