<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-89 1944EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Teachers-AIDS     07-19 0367</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Teachers-AIDS,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Union Launching AIDS Education Project</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American Federation of Teachers on
Wednesday named 11 cities in which the union will help teachers and
school districts develop policies on AIDS education and related
issues.
   Under the five-year, $1 million program, funded by a grant from
the Centers for Disease Control, the union will provide technical
assistance tailored to the needs of locals in the pilot cities.
   Among the most pressing needs, according to a survey of AFT union
leaders, is for information on where to get AIDS education materials
and which ones are appropriate for which age groups.
   The survey found that 72 percent of respondents said there is a
great need to focus on age-appropriate educational materials; 71
percent requested information on books, pamphlets and articles; and
62 percent sought information about model AIDS education efforts.
   Other concerns uncovered in the survey were what kinds of
attendance policies are appropriate for students who have AIDS;
where to obtain factual data on techniques to prevent infection; and
confidentiality questions such as who needs to know if a student or
school employee has AIDS.
   Lou Nayman, director of the union's AIDS project, said
controversies over attendance and AIDS education have torn
communities apart and resulted in negative publicity.
   ``We hope to avoid some of that by getting involved very early on
with key decisionmakers,'' he said. ``The purpose of this program is
to prevent fights, not to start any. ... We are not going into a
locality saying, `We at the top have decided this is what you need
to do.'''
   Nayman said teachers, administrators, board of education
officials, community groups and health authorities would be involved
in various local projects. He said they might include a critical
review of AIDS instructional materials, in-service teacher training,
school policy development and seminars on the legal issues
surrounding AIDS.
   The sites selected by AFT are New York; Baltimore; Washington;
New Orleans; Chicago; Cincinnati; Denver; San Francisco; Portland,
Ore.; Corpus Christi, Texas, and Oklahoma City.
   Another program will affect the Indiana State Employees
Association, an AFT affiliate.
   AFT is an international union representing some 700,000 teachers,
paraprofessionals, school employees, nurses, health care workers and
state employees.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
