<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-89 1945EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-SenateSpat     07-19 0584</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Senate Spat,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mitchell Accuses Helms of Stalling Action on State Department Bill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a tart exchange that tested the limits of
senatorial courtesy, Democratic leader George Mitchell accused
Republican Sen. Jesse Helms on Wednesday of trying to stall
consideration of a $4.6 billion State Department authorization bill.
   Mitchell was trying to get the Senate moving on more than a
hundred amendments to the bill when Helms, the floor manager of the
bill, stood up to ask for additional time for more to be submitted.
   Helms at first protested that Mitchell was trying to curb the
amount of time being given to debate on the bill. But when the Maine
Democrat said the North Carolina Republican had read him wrong,
Helms amended his complaint to say he was worried about Mitchell
seeking to limit amendments.
   Helms, the ranking Republican member of the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee, long has been known for exploiting the Senate
rules to promote his conservative foreign policy aims, including
delaying tactics and the adroit use of amendments.
   Mitchell said: ``I don't want to delay this bill any further.
This is already in the fourth day. ...''
   Helms: ``Well, Mr. Majority Leader, I say this as your friend and
one who wants to cooperate with you, but don't ignore the fact that
it was you who scheduled the first day of consideration of this bill
on a Friday ... and it was you who declared that there would be no
vote ... telling senators, `Go, go, bye, bye, stay home!' ''
   Mitchell: ``There's no reason why senators can't be present to
submit amendments if they're serious about doing so.''
   Helms: ``Does the majority leader give any assurance ... that no
attempt will be made to add the foreign aid bill to this
authorization bill for the State Department. Does the majority
leader contemplate linking them together and making them one bill?
   Mitchell: ``No, I do not.''
   Helms: ``I can be assured that that's not going to happen?''
   Mitchell: ``If I can get cooperation to get this bill passed, the
president's bill, then I will be pleased to discuss that with the
senator. But what the senator is asking is that he have unlimited
right to delay this legislation for as long as he wants ... and also
extract from me a commitment that I will not present another bill
that he doesn't want. In others, heads, the senator wins, tails, I
lose. That's what the senator is suggesting.''
   Helms: ``Sounds like a good proposition to me. ... I regret that
he has implied that I am delaying this bill. I don't think the
senator could document that. It's not so.''
   Mitchell: ``The senator is the (Republican) manager of the bill.
I announced last night that we were going to go to this bill at 9:15
this morning.''
   Helms: ``Right.''
   Mitchell: ``Managers of the bill have the responsibility in the
Senate to be present when the bill is to be presented. We had a
30-minute delay this morning ... because the senator didn't show up
on time.''
   Helms: ``You told me last night you were going to have a morning
(other business) period.''
   Mitchell: ``I specifically announced it. ...
   ``This is the president's bill. This is the administration's
bill. I'm doing my best to accommodate the president. And what I
find over and over and over again is that I am struggling to advance
the president's interests, when members of the president's party are
opposing the president's interests.''
</TEXT>
