<FIRST>r i AM-Mexico-Election     07-19 0359</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Election,0369</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leftist Party Launches Weeklong Protest Against Vote Fraud</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGIO CARRASCO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A leftist opposition party announced Wednesday
a weeklong campaign of demonstrations and rallies in several cities
to protest alleged fraud in Michoacan state legislative elections.
   In paid advertisements in Mexico City newspapers, the Democratic
Revolutionary Party said it ``demands respect for the will of the
people and that our victories be recognized ... the victories of the
people of Michoacan.''
   A state election board ruled Tuesday night that the governing
Institutional Revolutionary Party won 12 of the 24 seats in the new
Michoacan legislature and the Democratic Revolutionary Party six,
with the rest going to three other minority groups.
   Supporters of the Democratic Revolutionary Party, claiming it had
been cheated out of nine seats, blocked roads in Michoacan for a
week to protest the alleged fraud.
   Attorney General Enrique Alvarez del Castillo threatened to take
legal action after a man who suffered a heart attack was allegedly
held up at a Michoacan roablock for three hours and died.
   The roadblocks were lifted Wednesday before the attorney general
spoke, Democratic Revolutionary Party officials said, but groups of
opposition supporters remained outside the governor's mansion in
Morelia, the state capital about 150 miles west of Mexico City.
   The July 2 elections in Michoacan and four other states were
widely seen as a test of President Carlos Salinas de Gortari's
intentions to clean up Mexico's fraud-ridden balloting system, which
has kept the Institutional Revolutionary Party in power 60 years.
   Salinas' own election in July 1988 was marred by opposition
accusations of irregularities.
   The conservative National Action Party carried Baja California,
with its candidate Ernesto Ruffo becoming the first to defeat the
governing party in a governor's race.
   The Institutional Revolutionary Party won state elections in
Chihuahua and in its strongholds of Zacatecas and Campeche, but the
elections in Michoacan are still in dispute.
   Democratic Revolutionary leaders said in Wednesday's
advertisements that ``the PRI and the government machinery have
indulged in election fraud on a large scale'' and accused them of
altering voter registration rolls, stealing ballot boxes, and
closing polling stations.
</TEXT>
