<FIRST>r i AM-China-Floods     07-19 0233</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Floods,0239</SECOND>
<HEAD>Floods Kill 1,300; Official Warns of More Flooding</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least 1,360 people have died in flooding in
China since the beginning of June, but an official said the disaster
still could get worse.
   Yang Zhenhuai, deputy director of the State Flood Control
Headquarters and minister of Water Resources, said the worst of the
flooding could occur in the next three weeks.
   The official Xinhua News Agency on Tuesday quoted Yang as saying
about 2,700 people die in floods each year.
   Sichuan, China's most populous province, has suffered the most
this year. More than 800 people have been killed and 5,500 wounded
in flooding across 53 counties. Yang said 221 of the dead were
buried in eight feet of mud and rock when a cliff collapsed.
   He said flooding has been more serious than usual along the
Yangtze River, which flows through Sichuan province, the Huaihe
River and the upper reaches of the Yellow River.
   The news agency said 13 provinces have been hit by serious
flooding that inundated 3.7 million acres of arable land and
destroyed 370,000 homes. In Sichuan alone, 715,000 tons of grain was
lost.
   State TV has shown footage for the past several weeks of severe
flooding throughout south and southwestern China. Shots of people
stranded on rooftops and second-floor balconies, floodwaters nearly
touching the arches of bridges, and swirling river waters are
commonplace.
</TEXT>
