<FIRST>r a AM-Cuomo-Quayle     07-19 0243</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cuomo-Quayle,0249</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cuomo: Don't Worry About Quayle's Competence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic Gov. Mario Cuomo said Wednesday
that people should stop discussing whether Vice President Dan Quayle
is ``a dummy'' and worry about more important issues.
   ``They call Quayle a dummy, so what?'' said Cuomo when asked
about a new book that quotes former Quayle campaign advisers saying
unflattering things about the Republican vice president. ``If you've
got nothing else to do next Sunday at 4 o'clock, spend five minutes
reading about Quayle.''
   ``He's the vice president. What are you going to do about it,
impeach him for incompetence?'' said Cuomo during an interview with
Albany radio station WAMC. ``He's the vice president _ move on. He
won't be as bad as others we've had. Let's be candid _ what have we
had, all geniuses?''
   Cuomo was being questioned on WAMC's weekly ``Capitol
Connection'' show about the ongoing HUD housing scandal and calls
for an ethics investigation of New York Republican Sen. Alfonse
D'Amato.
   ``HUD, the accusation against D'Amato, people say Quayle's a
dummy. Let me respond to all of them this way: Who cares?'' said
Cuomo. ``Especially since there are so many more important things.''
   Cuomo said Americans should be more concerned about drugs, health
care and the homeless.
   The new book, ``Whose Broad Stripes and Bright Stars? The Trivial
Pursuit of the Presidency 1988,'' by political columnists Jules
Witcover and Jack Germond, is to be published in several weeks.
</TEXT>
