<FIRST>r i AM-Mozambique-SAfrica     07-19 0446</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mozambique-SAfrica,0461</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mozambique Says Nations Talk of Rapprochement with South Africa</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MAPUTO, Mozambique (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nations of southern Africa are
discussing ending the isolation of white-ruled South Africa if it
makes sufficient social and political reform, President Joaquim
Chissano said Wednesday.
   Chissano made the comments after a three-hour meeting with South
African's next president, F.W. de Klerk.
   The president of Mozambique expressed optimism about de Klerk's
commitment to end apartheid quickly after taking power.
   De Klerk says he plans to negotiate a constitution providing a
national vote for South Africa's black majority within five years.
   ``I was pleased to hear that the commitment is to work to achieve
this goal as quickly as possible,'' Chissano said. ``Especially,
there is a commitment that during the mandate of the future
president this problem of discrimination should be solved so that
there will be real democracy in South Africa.
   ``All the countries in southern Africa are discussing together,
and if there is a sound process of change in South Africa, I think
that South Africa will be part of that group of countries,'' he said.
   De Klerk's proposals have won approval from European leaders and
prompted the United States to invite a South African leader to visit
Washington for the first time in more than 30 years.
   However, Foreign Minister Pik Botha of South Africa said
Wednesday that de Klerk turned down the invitation to meet with
Secretary of State James Baker after American congressmen opposed
such a meeting.
   In another sign of change in South Africa this month, retiring
P.W. Botha of South Africa met for the first time with imprisoned
African National Congress leader Nelson Mandela.
   The African National Congress is the leading group fighting
apartheid. By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially
segregated society in which the 28 million blacks have no vote in
national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and
maintain separate districts, schools and health services.
   In Lusaka, Zambian President Kenneth Kaunda, one of South
Africa's staunchest foes, told a news conference he had invited de
Klerk to meet with him. No date has been set.
   Zimbabwe's President Robert Mugabe, who had ruled out meeting
South African leaders until they spoke to Mandela, said Monday he
would consider meeting de Klerk or Botha if the African National
Congress agreed.
   Chissano broke the ice by meeting in September with Botha.
   The two neighbors' relations have steadily improved since then.
South Africa has encouraged its businessmen to invest in Mozambique,
which is ravaged by a guerrilla insurgency that South Africa once
supported.
   De Klerk is expected to become president of South Africa after
Botha retires following Sept. 6 parliamentary elections.
</TEXT>
