<FIRST>r w AM-Senate-Ambassadors     07-19 0636</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Senate-Ambassadors,640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Refuses to Put Limit on Number of Political Ambassadors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate rejected a resolution Wednesday
seeking to limit the number of political appointees President Bush
could send as ambassadors to the nation's embassies.
   The vote rejecting the Senate resolution was 61 to 38. It would
have set the limit to 30 percent.
   The vote came after Democratic members of the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee voiced complaints that up to two thirds of the
ambassadorial appointments made in the first six months of the Bush
administration have been political supporters of the president, not
professional diplomats.
   That percentage, if continued, would reverse the typical average
in the last several presidential administrations, senators said..
   The amendment, offered by Sen. Al Gore, D-Tenn., to a pending
bill authorizing $4.6 billion in spending for the State Department
and allied agencies, represented a fallback position.
   The Senate on Tuesday soundly defeated, 79-20, his attempt to
impose a mandatory 15 percent ceiling on the number of political
nominations to diplomatic posts.
   Gore said many of his colleagues had found that too severe.
   But he said the situation needs to be addressed.
   ``All of us in both parties are really uneasy and embarrassed,''
Gore said.
   ``It is not just a question of the occasional candidate whose
credentials are grossly inadequate,'' he said. ``It is our
realization that the well being of our country really does depend
more on the astuteness of our diplomats than at any time since the
very earliest days of the Republic.
   Earlier, the Senate Foreign Relations Committee examined the
qualifications of a number of ambassadorial candidates, including
wealthy Republican contributor Joseph B. Gildenhorn and former child
actress and ambassador Shirley Temple Black.
   Gildenhorn, a Washington lawyer and real estate investor with
banking interests, has been nominated to be U.S. ambassador to
Switzerland. From 1984 to early this year, he and members of his
immediate family contributed nearly $230,000 to Republican campaigns
and causes.
   The nominee told the committee that he believed the American
Academy of Diplomacy, an organization composed of 100 distinguished
former diplomats, including all former secretaries of state, treated
him unfairly when it rated him as ``unqualified'' for the job.
   ``I consider myself qualified in all of my endeavors,''
Gildenhorn said, ticking off a series of accomplishments, including
his graduation with honors from the Yale University Law School.
   ``I'm proud of my accomplishments and I'm pleased that I have
achieved financial success over the years,'' Gildenhorn said. ``I'm
honored that the president thinks I'm qualified ... I feel confident
that I am ready to do an able and competent job as ambassador to
Switezerland.''
   Sen. Joesh R. Biden Jr, D-Del., told Gildenhorn that there is
rising concern about the number of major GOP fundraisers and
contributors being named ambassadors.
   Given Bush's background as a diplomat with service as U.S. envoy
to China and United Nations ambassador, ``it has come as somewhat of
a surprise,'' Biden said.
   Under questioning, Gildenhorn said he plans to study French, one
of the major languages of Switzerland, depending on ``what my time
schedule is.''
   But he said that while he does not now speak French, or German or
Italian, ``I would not be adversely effected because English is used
universally.''
   Mrs. Black previously served as U.S. ambassador to Ghana and has
held a large number of positions, including posts at the United
Nations.
   Sen. Paul Sarbanes, D-Md., told her that in contrast to some of
the Bush nominees, she has established a substantial and impressive
record and is qualified for the position to which she has been named.
   Even in 1974 when she was first nominated as an ambassador,
Sarbanes said, ``I thought you brought a record of consequence and
had demonstrated that you were a serious person.''
</TEXT>
