<FIRST>r i AM-Haiti     07-19 0515</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Haiti,0531</SECOND>
<HEAD>Relatives of Ex-Officer Detained in US Stage Sit-In at Consulate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL NORTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ Police dispersed relatives and
friends of an expelled army commander when the protesters staged a
sit-in Wednesday before the U.S. Consulate to protest the
ex-officer's detention in New York.
   The protest was in support of former Presidential Guard commander
Col. Philippe Biamby, one of three officers expelled in April after
attempting a coup.
   Dressed in white and clutching a Bible, Biamby's mother, Ketly
Biamby, 69, sat in a wicker chair on the sidewalk facing the
consulate when 25 armed police appeared and ordered her and four
other relatives and friends to leave.
   Police, who said the group had not obtained a permit for the
sit-in, chased away onlookers and journalists.
   U.S. Embassy Spokeswoman Susan Clyde said the embassy asked for
``police protection, not knowing what sort of demonstration the
sit-in could develop into.''
   Mrs. Biamby began a hunger strike Monday to protest the detention
by U.S. Immigration authorities of her son and two other former
Haitian officers, Lt. Col. Leonce Qualo and Col. Himmler Rebu.
   The three, hospitalized in a medical unit of the Metropolitan
Correctional Center in Manhattan, have been on a hunger strike since
June 26.
   ``I will go all the way, and die with them if necessary,'' Mrs.
Biamby said in front of the consulate in downtown Port-au-Prince.
``Will they (U.S. authorities) let us die?''
   Charles Troy, U.S. Immigration and Naturalization Spokesman in
New York, confirmed Tuesday the three are on a hunger strike. He
said they are free to take back their passports and leave if they
withdraw their request for political asylum.
   The three were expelled from Haiti to the neighboring Dominican
Republic on April 3 after troops loyal to Haitian ruler Lt. Gen.
Prosper Avril foiled their attempted coup the day before.
   They flew to Miami two days later and asked for political asylum.
They have remained jailed in the U.S. Immigration and Naturalization
Service detention facility in New York pending review of their
request.
   Their detention has stirred controversy in Haiti. Independent
Radio Metropole broadcasts a daily countdown of the number of days
the three have been jailed.
   ``They are victims of an INS policy of racial discrimination''
Jacques Biamby, Philippe Biamby's brother, said as police ordered
him away from the Consulate.
   Avril, U.S. and other Western diplomats said the coup attempt and
a rebellion the following week by two units, also crushed by
loyalist soldiers, were financed by supporters of former dictator
Jean-Claude ``Baby Doc'' Duvalier, who fled into exile in France in
1986.
   Philippe Biamby's father, Pierre Biamby, served as interior
minister and close adviser to Francois ``Papa Doc'' Duvalier, who
ruled from 1957 until his death in office in 1971.
   Pierre Biamby was linked to the 1964 massacre by Duvalierist
thugs of more than 20 mostly wealthy men, women and children in
Jeremie, on Haiti's southwestern tip.
   During the April coup attempt the three ringleaders briefly held
hostage several of Avril's relatives, including his children, wife,
80-year-old mother-in-law and an American houseguest.
</TEXT>
