<FIRST>u w AM-HUDProbe 1stLd-Writethru a0731 07-19 0617</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-HUD Probe, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0731,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pierce to Testify Again in HUD Investigation</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Adds 12 grafs of detail</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD L. VERNACI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Housing Secretary Samuel Pierce Jr. will
testify at least twice more to a congressional panel investigating
allegations of mismanagement and favoritism in the agency he headed
for eight years, the subcommittee's chairman said Wednesday.
   Pierce's earlier testimony _ that he was not involved in many of
the project-funding decisions at the Department of Housing and Urban
Development _ has been called into question by later witnesses.
   Subcommittee Chairman Tom Lantos, D-Calif., said staff members
for the panel met with Pierce Wednesday.
   ``There was no discussion with respect to the substance of his
statements,'' Lantos said. ``That would have been inappropriate.''
   Pierce will testify Aug. 3 before the House Government Operations
subcommittee on housing and employment and will come back at least
once and perhaps twice more after Labor Day, Lantos said.
   At the August hearing, Pierce will be asked about his possible
role in approving funding for a project in Durham, N.C., that
converted a defunct hosiery mill into housing for the elderly.
   HUD staff members recommended strongly that the project should
not receive $15 million in government money, saying the project was
too expensive, was located atop a toxic waste site and was too close
to railroad tracks.
   Last week, Shirley McVay Wiseman, former assistant secretary for
housing at HUD, testified under oath that Pierce himself ordered her
to approve money for the project.
   ``I want the project funded,'' Wiseman quoted Pierce as saying.
   That project was being pushed by a former law partner of Pierce.
   Pierce met Wednesday with Stuart Weisberg, staff counsel for the
subcommittee, who eluded reporters waiting outside his office in
anticipation of the meeting.
   Lantos, who called the meeting private, refused to say how many
other people met with Pierce or whether it was held outside the
Capitol complex.
   ``I will not tell you where it was held,'' Lantos said. ``It was
a relaxed, lengthy, cordial and productive meeting.''
   The subcommittee has been examining allegations of influence
peddling at HUD in which well-connected Republicans obtained scarce
funds to fix up housing projects either they or their clients were
developing. In one case, former Interior Secretary James Watt was
paid more than $300,000 to help a developer obtain funds to fix up a
300-apartment housing project.
   In addition, the subcommittee has investigated HUD's practice of
using private agents to finalize the sale of foreclosed property
owned by the department. In at least a dozen cases, these closing
agents failed to hand over money from the sales to HUD, resulting in
a loss estimated at $20 million.
   Lantos said he expects the hearings to continue through the fall
and will move into other areas of HUD but the panel will not try to
investigate everything about the department.
   ``We're sort of viewing this as a Whitman Sampler (a box of
chocolate candy),'' Lantos said. ``We won't go after each piece of
chocolate.''
   While the inquiry eventually will end, it will not reach a tidy
conclusion, he said.
   ``The HUD crisis is an ocean without a shore,'' Lantos said. ``We
will not reach the shore because there isn't one.''
   A Republican member of the committee said members ``were not
interested in trying to get someone to perjure themselves'' but
needed to hear from Pierce to resolve conflicts between his earlier
testimony and the accounts of subsequent witnessses.
   ``He was very adamant in saying never, that he was never
involved,'' said Rep. Christopher Shays, R-Conn. ``He have a
conflict that we need to resolve. We just really want the truth on
what he did.''
</TEXT>
