<HEAD>Bush Nominates Ambsassadors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said Wednesday he will nominate
former Peace Corps Director Loret M. Ruppe as the new ambassador to
Norway.
   Bush also announced he will nominate former Iowa Republican
chairman Sally J. Novetzke as ambassador to Malta.
   The president also is nominating Miklos Salgo, who has headed
State Department efforts to decide the fate of the bugged,
unoccupied new U.S. Embassy in Moscow, for the rank of ambassador in
his role as special negotiator for property issues.
   Salgo, 74, is a former business executive and U.S. ambassador to
his native Hungary. He recently recommended a plan to try saving
part of the Moscow embassy. Some lawmakers want it torn down and
built anew with American, not Soviet, labor.
   Mrs. Ruppe, 53, served a record eight years as Peace Corps
director until this past May 1, when she was succeeded by Paul D.
Coverdell. She was chairman of Bush's presidential primary campaign
in Michigan and then co-chairman of the state's Reagan-Bush
committee in 1980.
   Mrs. Novetzke, 57, of Cedar Rapids, Iowa, is a longtime GOP
activist who was state party chairman in 1985-87 and was co-chairman
of Iowa's Bush for President campaign last year.
   The White House also announced these other nominations:
   _John A. Knauss, 63, professor of oceanography at the University
of Rhode Island, to be undersecretary of commerce for oceans and
atmosphere.
   _Donald F. Rodgers as a member of the National Labor Relations
Board, succeeding John E. Higgins Jr. for a term expiring Nov. 16,
1992. Rodgers, 62, a former Teamsters union executive, is special
coordinator for senior worker and retiree programs for Labor
Secretary Elizabeth Dole.
   _Clifford R. Oviatt Jr. as a member of the NLRB, succeeding
Wilford W. Johansen for a term expiring Aug. 27, 1993. Oviatt, 63,
is a partner with the law firm of McGuire, Woods, Battle &amp; Boothe in
McLean, Va.
   _Joshua I. Smith to be chairman of the Commission on Minority
Business Development. Smith is founder, chairman and chief executive
officer of the MAXIMA Corp.
   _Sheldon J. Krys as assistant secretary of state for diplomatic
security. A career foreign service officer, he is a former
ambassador to Trinidad and Tobago and has been assistant secretary
of state for administration and information management since 1988.
