<FIRST>r i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0639 07-19 0718</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0639,0737</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Killed, 39 Injured in Clashes</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE number of injured, second Palestinian
killed in clash with soldiers, comment from Arens; no pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARJORIE OLSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers killed two Palestinians in clashes in
the occupied West Bank Wednesday, army and hospital officials said,
and a third was reported slain by Palestinians who accused him of
collaborating with Israel.
   A soldier who suffered injuries in a recent bus crash blamed on a
Palestinian and a 12-year-old boy who fought earlier with soldiers
also died on Wednesday, the army said.
   At least 39 Palestinians were wounded by plastic or lead bullets
in confrontations with Israeli troops, including 23 in the Rafah
refugee camp in the occupied Gaza Strip, Arab hospital reports said.
   Fifteen others from Rafah were treated for minor injuries from
rubber-coated steel pellets used by the army in riot control, they
said. They included a 4-year-old girl hit in the mouth.
   The deaths raised to at least 571 the number of Palestinians
killed since the uprising against Israeli rule in the West Bank and
Gaza Strip began Dec. 8, 1987. Thirty-seven Israelis also have died.
   Industry Minister Ariel Sharon, a hard-liner in Prime Minister
Yitzhak Shamir's Likud bloc, renewed his criticism of the
government's handling of the uprising.
   ``The time has come to deal with one subject, restoring security
to the daily lives of Jews and to stop talking nonsense,'' Sharon
said.
   Sharon also criticized Shamir and Likud's Foreign Minister Moshe
Arens for their meetings with local Palestinian leaders and
reiterated his opposition to any contact with the Palestine
Liberation Organization.
   ``The PLO is the main obstacle to peace in the Middle East and
therefore, there should be no talks with it. The PLO pretends to be
speaking in the name of all the Palestinians. We don't accept and
will not accept it,'' he told parliament.
   Samir Akhras, 20, was fatally shot during a predawn army raid on
the village of Beit Lid near Tulkarem, the army said.
   ``One of the forces encountered violent oppositon, and in the
confrontation one youth was shot,'' said an army spokesman,
insisting on anonymity. ``An army doctor tried unsuccessfully to
revive him.''
   Also killed was Khader Jazri, 20, who was shot in a
stone-throwing clash with troops in Jenin, Arab reports said. The
army said it was checking the report.
   A 12-year-old boy from Rafah, Iyad Abdel Fatah Al Badli, died
Wednesday at the Tel Hashomer hospital near Tel Aviv, after being
shot in the head in a clash with troops on July 8, the army and Arab
reports said.
   Arab reports said the body of Rizik Abdel Razak Berat, 65, was
found in a well in the West Bank village of Taibe near Ramallah.
They said he had been shot, apparently by an Arab assailant,
allegedly for helping Israeli authorities. The army said it was also
checking this report.
   More than 80 Palestinians suspected of collaborating have been
killed by fellow Arabs since the Palestinian uprising began.
   The latest Israeli fatality of the uprising was 19-year-old Tova
Maimon, a soldier who died Wednesday of injuries suffered July 6 in
a bus crash blamed on a Palestinian.
   The Palestinian, who is in police custody, allegedly grabbed the
wheel of the bus on the Jerusalem-Tel Aviv highway and steered it
into a 200-foot ravine.
   On Tuesday, Riva Levine, 39, a lawyer from Philadelphia, died of
injuries from the crash, which killed 16 people and injured 25.
   Army radio on Wednesday played a tape of an interview made last
week with Ms. Levine, who said the bus attack had strengthened her
resolve to move to Israel.
   ``Yes, I would like to live here for a while,'' she said. ``If
anything, what happened shows me how important it is for Jewish
people to live in Israel.''
   In the Gaza Strip, soldiers clamped a curfew on the Khan Yunis
refugee camp after nightlong clashes between troops and stone
throwers.
   In the West Bank city of Nablus, a military court sentenced two
Palestinians to life in prison and four others to terms of 15 years
for killing a soldier on Feb. 24.
   The soldier, paratrooper Binyamin Meisner, 24, died after
Palestinians dropped a concrete block on him from a rooftop in
Nablus.
</TEXT>
