<FIRST>u w AM-Lucas 1stLd-Writethru a0697 07-19 0892</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lucas, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0697,850</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nominee Defends Commitment, Actions in Customs Incident</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New material, editing thruout</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William C. Lucas, nominated as the nation's
chief civil rights enforcer, on Wednesday defended both his
commitment to the drive against discrimination and his actions when
customs inspectors found $8,800 worth of undeclared goods in his
luggage.
   Sen. Howard Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, querying Lucas about the 1985
incident with the Customs Service, asked, ``How do you explain
concealing receipts and merchandise from the customs inspectors?''
   Lucas said the violation involved jewelry carried in a cosmetics
case by an unidentified member of his family.
   He said he had not been aware of all the purchases his wife and
daughters had made during their trip to Japan and South Korea. Their
declaration to customs inspectors in Seattle, he said, was for
merchandise worth $4,800.
   Lucas was told by the committee chairman, Sen. Joseph Biden,
D-Del., that his nomination to head the Justice Department's civil
rights division ``has been contentious and will be contested.''
   One Democratic senator said he wanted Lucas called back to answer
other questions but a Republican predicted Lucas would be swiftly
confirmed by the Senate.
   The black former sheriff and county executive fielded repeated
questions about his run-in with customs inspectors.
   Metzenbaum quoted a Customs Service report as saying that the
Lucas family had initially said they had no receipts but that a
search revealed there were receipts. The senator said customs
officials reported Lucas repeatedly told them that the luggage
contained ``sweatshirts.''
   Lucas also told the committee that his family were inexperienced
travelers and had been unclear about how to report the goods.
Metzenbaum said the Customs Service described Lucas as an
experienced traveler.
   Metzenbaum asked why Lucas had failed to disclose on a committee
questionnaire that he had once been investigated for violating
customs regulations for which he was fined. The senator did not say
how much Lucas had been fined for trying to conceal undeclared
merchandise.
   Lucas said there had been no investigation.
   ``You didn't think when they went through your pockets and the
pockets of your family that that wasn't an investigation?''
Metzenbaum asked.
   ``I wasn't searched, nor did I consider that an investigation,''
Lucas responded.
   He was also questioned about his commitment to enforcing civil
rights laws.
   ``If a case is brought to me involving a cross burning on the
lawn of a citizen, believe me, this is not just cold facts to me,''
the 61-year-old former Wayne County, Mich., official told the
committee.
   ``I have been there. I have smelled the smoke. I have smelled the
fear.''
   He did not elaborate.
   Several senators said they were not certain that Lucas was the
right man to champion the civil rights cause.
   Lucas was repeatedly asked his opinions of several Supreme Court
decisions this year that have inflamed the civil rights community.
Its leaders say the rulings will make it increasingly difficult for
minorities to make headway in the areas of job discrimination, sex
bias in the workplace and minority set-asides in public contracts.
   Lucas declined to criticize the court in a number of instances in
which senators gave him an opportunity to do so. Instead, he said he
would monitor the effect of the rulings and promised to push for
legislation if problems arise.
   ``Frankly what I think you are saying is, `We'll make a study of
it and, if it doesn't work out, propose legislation,''' said
Metzenbaum, adding, ``But time has a way of slipping by.''
   Lucas' reception split largely along party lines.
   ``He will be a moderator, a conciliator, a unifier,'' said Orrin
Hatch, R-Utah, while Sen. Charles Grassley, R-Iowa, described Lucas
as ``a monument to what can be achieved without regard to race or
color.''
   Hatch predicted that Lucas would be confirmed with little delay
and told the nominee:
   ``I happen to believe that you will make one of the greatest
attorneys general of the United States in charge of the civil rights
division or any other division if you were given the chance and the
opportunity.''
   But Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., told lawmakers there were
``a number of serious questions that need to be answered'' and Sen.
Paul Simon, D-Ill., after questioning Lucas, said he still had
doubts about the nominee's commitment.
   After Lucas finished more than three hours of testimony, one
senator said he still had enough questions about the nominee's past
that he wanted Lucas called back to the stand.
   Sen. Howell Heflin, D-Ala., told a reporter, ``There are a lot of
charges against him. We need to get to the bottom of them.''
   Heflin, asked if he wanted to question Lucas further about
misstatements he made on a 1981 application to join the New York
bar, replied:
   ``I ain't got to the bottom of it yet.''
   Lucas' critics hammered at his relative lack of experience within
the civil rights field, but his supporters scoffed at that.
   The Bush administration has acknowledged that Lucas has never
taken part in a trial or handled an appeal but has sought to stress
his talents as a manager. Nevertheless, giggling swept over the
hearing room when, during an exchange with Sen. Arlen Specter,
R-Pa., the nominee declined to argue a legal point, saying, ``I am
new to the law.''
   Lucas received his law degeee in 1962.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
