<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0615,0670</SECOND>
<HEAD>Warnings Given After Grenades Kill 13 in Sri Lanka</HEAD>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING to restore writethru designation</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with six grafs to CORRECT spelling of Sinhalese in 1st
graf and UPDATE with assassination attempt; picks up 5th pvs `The annual...'</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   This report was submitted to a government censor,
who deleted some material.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attackers threw grenades into a crowd
of Sinhalese and Tamil worshipers at a ceremony meant to promote
ethnic peace, killing 13 people and wounding 85, authorities said.
   A police official said three grenades were hurled at the
gathering Tuesday night in Kataragama, a town about 100 miles
southeast of Colombo.
   No one claimed responsibility for the attack.
   (United News of India said a Sri Lankan Tamil politician escaped
assassination Wednesday but 13 people were injured when a grenade
thrown at his car missed and struck another vehicle.)
   (Vardaraja Perumal, a moderate Tamil leader and chief minister of
Northeastern Province, was traveling in a motorcade in Jaffna when
the grenade was thrown, the agency said. The report could not be
confirmed in Sri Lanka.)
   About 5,000 people had assembled in Kataragama for a procession
ending a week-long religious festival that attracts both Sinhalese
Buddhists and Tamil Hindus, the police official said, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   The annual ceremony is viewed as a demonstration that Tamils and
majority Sinhalese can live together in peace and harmony. Tamils
are waging war for an independent homeland, prompting a backlash
among Sinhalese militants.
   ``It is a tragedy beyond comparison,'' said Ranjith Madumma
Bandara, a government lawmaker who participated in the procession
from a Hindu temple to a Buddhist shrine.
   ``There is nothing sacred in this country anymore,'' he added.
   Hours after the explosions, the government warned people to be
vigilant in crowded places such as bus and train stations.
   ``The subversives are prepared to place explosives and detonate
them by electrical or other means to cause death and destruction of
innocent civilians,'' it said without identifying the subversives.
   Bandara, a Sinhalese Buddhist, said two women walking beside him
were killed but he escaped injury. Another women and three children
were also killed.
   Among the injure was Dharamadasa Banda, minister of state for
rehabilitation and religious chief for the two shrines, said Bandara.
   (In Madras, India, a Sri Lankan Tamil party blamed the attack on
Sinhalese militants from the left-wing People's Liberation Front.
Ponnudurai Ravinesan, spokesman for the Eelam People's Revolutionary
Liberation Front, said he had information from Sri Lanka that the
grenades were thrown by radicals of the front.
   (The front has often attacked fellow Sinhalese since it launched
an uprising in 1987 to overthrow President Ranasinghe Premadasa's
government. It accuses the Sinhalese-dominated government of selling
out its own people in efforts to make peace with Tamil rebels.)
   About 14,000 people have been killed on this island nation off
southern India since the strife began. Tamil militants launched
their war for a independent homeland in 1983.
   Tamils form 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people and claim
they are discriminated against by the Sinhalese, who make up 75
percent of the population.
   The government imposed censorship July 6 amid escalating violence
and a political dispute with India over withdrawal its peacekeeping
forces.
   Premadasa has demanded India withdraw its estimated 40,000
soldiers by the end of July. Indian Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi
rejected the request, saying a premature pullout would lead to more
bloodshed.
   Indian troops were dispatched to Sri Lanka on July 30, 1987, to
supervise a peace pact designed to give Tamils some autonomy in the
north and the east. The most militant Tamil guerrilla group ignored
the accord and started attacking Indian soldiers, Sri Lankan
security forces and civilians.
   India became involved in its neighbor's problems because of
sympathies of its own 60 million Tamils for the rebel cause.
</TEXT>
