<FIRST>r w AM-Garcia-Disclosure     07-19 0261</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Garcia-Disclosure,260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Friends and Backers Contribute Money for Congressman's Defense</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Friends and supporters of Rep. Robert Garcia,
D-N.Y., contributed $14,600 last year to a defense fund for the
indicted congressman, who has estimated he'll owe lawyers up to
$200,000 for his Wedtech defense.
   A fund to help pay legal fees was established March 20, 1987,
according to Garcia's financial disclosure form, filed last month
after he received an extension from the clerk of the House. The
forms are due every May 15.
   ``The fund is maintained separately and independently from the
congressman,'' says an addendum to the disclosure form.
``Contributors and contribution amounts are not reported to
Congressman Robert Garcia.'' The total was listed as $14,600.
   Garcia was indicted last November along with his wife, Jane, on
charges that they took bribes from the Wedtech Corp.
   Prosecutors have charged that the former Bronx, N.Y., military
contractor funneled $86,100 through a lawyer in Puerto Rico to Mrs.
Garcia for ``consulting services'' that really amounted to influence
peddling by her husband. Wedtech's founder also allegedly gave Mrs.
Garcia a diamond-and-emerald necklace and a $77,500 check disguised
as an investment. Trial is scheduled for September.
   Garcia has already spent more than $110,000 from his campaign
treasury for legal fees and had only $4,430 left in the account at
the beginning of 1989.
   Garcia's spokesman, Ron Simoncini, said Wednesday he could not
immediately answer questions about the form. But earlier this year,
Garcia told The New York Times his legal fees could reach $200,000.
</TEXT>
