<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     07-19 0339</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0345</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms Over Eastern Third of Nation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms developed Wednesday over the Southeast and into the
Ohio Valley and Great Lakes, with locally heavy rain.
   Showers and thunderstorms extended from the coast of the
Carolinas across southern Georgia, Florida, the central Gulf of
Mexico coast and Louisiana, from northern Georgia across western
Pennsylvania, and from northeastern Alabama across the lower Ohio
Valley, Illinois and Wisconsin.
   Showers and thunderstorms were scattered over New England and
thunderstorms developed over New Mexico.
   Louisville, Ky., got 1.25 inches of rain during the six hours up
to 2 p.m. EDT and the National Weather Service reported some urban
flooding. Lexington, Ky., got 1.15 inches in the same period. Two
inches of rain fell in less than an hour at Earl Park, Ind., the
weather service said.
   Wind gusts from morning thunderstorms in Texas caused damage near
Arbala and Seymour, the weather service said.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 60
degrees at San Simeon, Calif., to 111 at Phoenix. Wednesday's low
for the Lower 48 states was 41 degrees at Craig and Gunnison, Colo.
   For Thursday, showers and thunderstorms were forecast from
central Maine and New York state across central Florida, from the
lower Great Lakes across the Ohio Valley, Illinois, the Tennessee
Valley and the central Gulf of Mexico states through southeastern
Louisiana.
   Highs in the 70s were predicted from New England across the Great
Lakes, the Ohio Valley, Illinois and Missouri, and scattered along
the northern and central Pacific Coast; in the 80s from southeastern
New York state across South Carolina and the Tennessee Valley, from
inland Georgia across the lower Mississippi Valley, the upper
Mississippi Valley, from southern South Dakota across northern Texas
and eastern Colorado, as well as scattered along the southern coast
of California and central Washington state; around 100 over Idaho,
much of Nevada, inland California and southern Arizona to near 115
through the desert Southwest; and generally in the 90s over the
remainder of the nation.
</TEXT>
