<FIRST>r i AM-Canada-Abortion 1stLd-Writethru a0671 07-19 0517</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Canada-Abortion, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0671,0529</SECOND>
<HEAD>Injunctions Against Abortion Putting Pressure on Government</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: To ADD more comment from Ms. Dodd, INSERT 4 grafs after 8th
graf pvs, `I think...' Pickup 9th graf pvs, `A woman...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Quebec woman seeking an abortion asked an
appellate court Wednesday to overturn an injunction obtained by her
former boyfriend in the third such case this month in Canada.
   The cases have increased pressure on the government to come up
with a new abortion law. Canada has been without legislation since
early 1988, when the Supreme Court threw out the existing law,
saying the cumbersome procedure required for an abortion infringed
on women's rights.
   The Toronto Star on Wednesday quoted Justice Minister Doug Lewis
as saying the government will tackle the abortion issue this fall
but will not necessarily come up with a new law.
   In Quebec, 21-year-old Chantal Daigle turned to a three-judge
appeals panel after Superior Court Judge Jacques Viens Monday
granted an injunction sought by her former boyfriend, Jean-Guy
Tremblay, 25.
   Ms. Daigle is 20 weeks pregnant. She could seek an abortion
outside of Quebec but could face a two-year prison sentence and a
fine if the injunction stands.
   Last week in Toronto, the Ontario Supreme Court threw out an
injunction that was preventing Barbara Dodd, 22, from having an
abortion.
   She went ahead with the operation immediately, but on Tuesday she
appeared publicly with Greg Murphy, 23, who had sought the
injunction, and she accused abortion rights groups of encouraging
her to have the operation.
   ``I think the fetus should have the right to life,'' said Ms.
Dodd.
   She said pro-choice activists, whom she did not name, ``used me
to promote their cause.''
   ``I was under control by those people,'' Ms. Dodd said as Murphy
sat beside her at the news conference. ``I was never given a moment
to myself to think about what I was doing.''
   Cherie MacDonald, spokeswoman for the Ontario Coalition for
Abortion Clinics, said her organization had not pressured Ms. Dodd
to go through with the procedure.
   ``It's absolutely false,'' she said. ``She is a very confused
young woman.''
   A woman in Winnipeg, Manitoba, went ahead with an abortion
earlier in July after her former boyfriend failed to obtain an
injunction.
   The House of Commons has been reluctant to act on the
controversial issue. The federal government placed six options on
abortion before the House of Commons in July 1988. None received a
majority.
   In a column Wednesday in the Globe and Mail newspaper, lawyer
Jacques J.M. Shore wrote that many Canadians are disappointed and
angered by the federal government's ``continued laissez-faire
attitude'' toward abortion.
   ``It is becoming more obvious each day that Canada cannot remain
unique in the Western world as a nation with no legal boundaries
concerning the willful termination of pregnancy,'' he wrote. ``At
least until a new law is passed, Canadians can expect that
additional names will be added to the growing list of women ... who
are required to battle in court before being allowed to undergo an
abortion.''
</TEXT>
