<FIRST>r a AM-SavagePast     07-19 0593</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Savage Past,0610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Allegations of Sexual Misconduct Latest to Plague Illinois Congressman</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Like a cat with nine political lives, Rep. Gus
Savage has survived gaffes that might have ended many political
careers.
   He has been slammed by political challengers for absenteeism in
Congress and globe-trotting appearances for questionable causes,
accused by government agencies of failing to disclose sources of
funds and investigated for personnel practices.
   But the latest crisis _ allegations of sexual misconduct raised
by a 28-year-old Peace Corps volunteer _ could be the most
explosive. In an article Wednesday in the Washington Post, the woman
accused the 63-year-old congressman of repeatedly fondling her in
the back of a chauffeur-driven embassy car while he was visiting
Zaire in March.
   Savage frequently counters criticism by labeling it racially
motivated, and none of his past problems have affected his
popularity in the 2nd District, a predominantly black area that
contains some of the nation's most impoverished neighborhoods.
   Last November, he was re-elected with 83 percent of the vote,
having earlier topped a five-way Democratic primary by getting more
votes than his four challengers combined.
   When asked about the alleged sexual misconduct, Savage told a
reporter from the Washington Post: ``I don't want to talk about
that. ... Ask me the same kind of questions you ask white
congressmen.''
   Savage gained prominence in Chicago political circles first as a
civil-rights organizer and later as publisher of a chain of
community newspapers.
   He made unsuccessful tries for the Democratic congressional
nomination in 1968 and 1970, losing to candidates backed by the
powerful Democratic machine controlled by then-Mayor Richard J.
Daley.
   When the white incumbent retired in 1980, voters in the 2nd
District on Chicago's South Side chose Savage over the machine's
hand-picked black candidate.
   The the Chicago Sun-Times found he finished his first year in
office having participated in only 51 percent of the recorded votes
_ the lowest percentage in the House.
   The following January, Savage showed up at a demonstration in
Lisbon, Portugal, leading 50,000 demonstrators against American
policy who were described as mainly Communist trade unionists.
   Savage dismissed his critics, saying at the time: ``I have
different priorities than most politicians. I didn't go to Congress
to get along, or to go along.''
   He defended his absenteeism at another juncture by saying, ``It
is plumb foolish to depend on legislation from a white Congress to
provide for black liberation.''
   The Federal Election Commission filed a civil suit against
Savage's 1982 campaign in 1984, accusing it of failing to report the
source of its money and asking the court to impose a $5,000 fine.
   More recently, Savage came under fire for inflaming racial
passions in Chicago's mayoral elections. During the February
primary, Savage called eventual winner Richard M. Daley, who is
white and a son of the late mayor, a ``born-and-bred racist.''
   When Democratic National Committee Chairman Ron Brown came to the
city to campaign on Daley's behalf, Savage called the black party
leader an ``Oreo'' for supporting Daley over black challenger
Timothy Evans.
   Savage; his son, Thomas John Savage; and Walter Fauntroy, the
District of Columbia's congressional delegate, also are subjects of
a preliminary investigation by the FBI into Fauntroy's employment of
the younger Savage.
   Investigators have said Thomas Savage reported he was living in
Chicago and running for the Illinois Legislature at the same time he
was on Fauntroy's payroll.
   The FBI also is looking into any connection between the younger
Savage's job and his father's employment of a former Fauntroy aide.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890719-0192 </DOCNO>
