<FIRST>r i AM-PapuaNewGuinea     07-19 0234</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Papua New Guinea,0242</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rebel Leader's Brother And Others Killed In Jungle Fighting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORT MORESBY, Papua New Guinea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Security forces shot and
killed the brother of rebel leader Francis Ona in jungle fighting on
the strife-torn island of Bougainville, officials said Wednesday.
   Also killed in gun battles Tuesday was another member of the
Bougainville Republican Army, which seeks to secede from Papua New
Guinea.
   The rebels also want the equivalent of $10 billion compensation
for environmental damage caused by the huge Bougainville copper mine.
   The open-cut mine, among the world's 10 largest, provides 45
percent of the country's export income and 17 percent of government
revenue.
   The mine had 3,000 employees until sabotage attacks forced it to
close in May and a state of emergency was declared. At least 23
people, including three soldiers, have been killed in the violence,
which broke out in November.
   Papua New Guinea, an Australian colony until 1975, has a mainly
Melanesian population of 3.5 million. It is the biggest recipient of
Australian foreign aid in the South Pacific.
   Police said Ona's brother, Ambrose, was killed during fighting in
rugged jungle to the east of the mine. Army commander Col. Lima
Dotaona said his troops also recovered explosives that had been
stolen from the mine by rebels.
   Dotaona repeated an appeal to the militants to lay down their
arms, saying further fighting will only cost lives.
</TEXT>
