<FIRST>u a AM-ArsenicPoisoning     07-19 0574</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Arsenic Poisoning,0591</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman Makes First Court Appearance On Arsenic Poisoning Charges</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BTN1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBIN P. TEATER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GRAHAM, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman was charged with using arsenic to
kill her first husband and a boyfriend, whose bodies were exhumed
after her current husband fell ill on their honeymoon. Other deaths
are being investigated, officials said.
   Blanche Taylor Moore made her first court appearance Wednesday,
the day after she was arrested, and her lawyer said she is innocent
of all charges.
   ``Mrs. Moore personally, while traumatized and upset over being
arrested and denied bond, is determined to rally and present her
side of all this. ... She maintains her innocence,'' said her
attorney, Mitchell McEntire.
   Mrs. Moore, 56, a small, graying woman wearing orange prison
overalls, appeared before Alamance County Superior Court Judge
Spencer Ennis. He set a probable cause hearing for Aug. 1 and deputy
sheriffs took her back to jail.
   She was arrested Tuesday night at the Alamance County home of her
daughter, Cindy Taylor.
   She was charged with assault with a deadly weapon with intent to
kill in the poisoning of her husband, the Rev. Dwight Moore, 54, who
has been hospitalized since May with what doctors say is arsenic
poisoning.
   Also Tuesday, Burlington police charged her in the 1973 arsenic
poisoning death of her first husband, James N. Taylor. And in
Forsyth County west of here, the sheriff's department issued a
warrant charging Mrs. Moore in the death of Raymond Reid, a
boyfriend who died in 1986.
   Bond was set at $100,000 on a charge of assault against Moore,
but no bond has yet been set on two first-degree murder charges. She
cannot be released until bond is set and posted for those charges.
   Taylor's and Reid's bodies were ordered exhumed after Moore fell
ill, and authorities concluded that their deaths had been caused by
arsenic. On Tuesday, a judge also ordered the exhumation of the body
of Mrs. Moore's father, Parker D. Kiser Sr., to determine whether
his 1966 death was caused by arsenic.
   Reid, the manager of a Kroger grocery store, signed a will a
month before his death bequeathing equal shares of his estate to
Mrs. Moore and his two sons, Steven and Raymond Jr. Mrs. Moore
reported she received more than $22,500 from the estate.
   Taylor, a 45-year-old furniture refinisher, also died of heart
failure caused by arsenic poisoning in October 1973, State Medical
Examiner John Butts said.
   Authorities declined to say how many deaths they are
investigating, but Alamance County Sheriff Richard Frye said his
department has ``a short list'' of other deaths he is investigating.
   Mrs. Moore has so far declined to talk with police, Frye said
Wednesday.
   Moore was taken May 7 to N.C. Memorial Hospital in Chapel Hill
complaining of nausea and vomiting shortly after his April honeymoon
in New Jersey. The arsenic was discovered within a few days after
his admission. Moore remains hospitalized in fair condition.
   Mrs. Moore, a 30-year Kroger employee, filed a $14 million sexual
harassment lawsuit against the grocery chain in January 1986,
alleging a superior, Robert Hutton, harassed her by threatening her
job security. The lawsuit was settled out of court in July 1987, but
the terms were not disclosed.
   In the suit Mrs. Moore said she felt ``completely alienated and
antagonistic toward men and has not been able to maintain any
meaningful social contacts with members of the opposite sex.''
</TEXT>
