<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-89 2110EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-YuccaMountain     07-19 0464</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yucca Mountain,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Watkins Urged to Declare Nevada Site Unsuitable for Nuclear Waste</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Richard Bryan, D-Nev., urged Energy
Secretary James D. Watkins on Wednesday to scrap plans to build a
high-level nuclear waste dump in Nevada, saying delays ``now made it
certain'' the site would not be ready in time.
   The Energy Department has set a 2003 target date for opening the
underground repository, but a series of technical and political
obstacles have put that target in doubt.
   The dump would hold waste from commercial nuclear plants that
will be dangerously radioactive for at least 10,000 years. It is
about 100 miles northwest of Las Vegas.
   Nuclear utilities are desperate for a permanent storage facility
because the cost of keeping waste in ``temporary'' storage at
reactor plants is escalating.
   Bryan said Watkins has legal authority to halt the department's
work at Nevada's Yucca Mountain, which so far has been limited to
preparing a means of ``characterizing'' the site, or determining its
geologic suitability as a dump.
   Bryan said in a letter to Watkins that the department should turn
away from the underground storage idea to consider ways of storing
the waste at reactor sites in ``dry casks'' or other methods.
   ``I believe you can restore scientific integrity and rational
public policy to a program that, if continued, is destined to fail
for scientific, economic and political reasons,'' Bryan said in his
letter.
   A Nuclear Regulatory Commission geologist, in a report made
public Tuesday, said preliminary Energy Department analyses of
volcanic potentials near Yucca Mountain had grossly understated the
chances of an eruption.
   The geologist, John Trapp, said the odds of an eruption during
the next 10,000 years may be about one in six, rather than the
one-in-30 chance cited by other scientists.
   Sen. Harry Reid, D-Nev., said on the Senate floor Wednesday that
Trapp was a ``hero.''
   ``He did what no one expected him to do: Tell it like it really
is and let the chips fall where they may,'' Reid said, adding that
the proposal for storing nuclear waste at Yucca Mountain was
seriously flawed and an economic disaster.
   ``A nuclear waste repository under Yucca Mountain would be as
smart as storing nitro-glycerin in a boiling tea pot,'' he said.
   Watkins has said he feels bound by the Nuclear Waste Policy Act
Amendments of 1987 to carry out a suitability study at Yucca
Mountain, even though the state government has gone on record
opposing the project.
   Christina Sankey, a department spokeswoman, said in response to
Bryan's letter that while she was not sure Watkins had seen it, the
plea would not change his mind that it is too early to give up on
Yucca Mountain.
   ``He opposes such a move,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890719-0195 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-89 1854EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>b a AM-DC-10Crash 7thLd-Writethru a0765 07-19 0606</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-DC-10 Crash, 7th Ld-Writethru, a0765,0624</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Airliner Crashes in Iowa with 298 People on Board, Some Survive</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto staffing, LaserGraphic NY57</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES with 80 survivors, other details.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SIOUX CITY, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A United Airlines DC-10 carrying 298
people crashed in an explosive ball of fire Wednesday while trying
to make an emergency landing. At least 80 people survived, an
official said.
   Flight 232 from Denver to Chicago carried 287 passengers and 11
crew members, said Deborah Jones, a United spokeswoman.
   The crash, a half-mile from a runway, could be one of the worst
in U.S. history.
   A witness, Mark Smith, said he saw survivors walking away from
the crash.
   ``We could see the plane tumbling down the runway'' after ``a
wing hit the ground,'' said Smith, who said he was working about
1,500 yards from the site.
   He said the plane broke into ``15,000 different pieces'' and the
only intact piece was the nose.
   The plane experienced ``complete hydraulic failure'' before the
crash just after 4 p.m., Federal Aviation Administration spokesman
Fred Farrar said.
   The tail engine failed, and this may have caused a hydraulic
failure, said Bob Raynesford, another FAA spokesman.
   ``This plane went down on approach to the airport. They were
having problems before it went down. So they were prepared at the
scene,'' said police Lt. Gene Erickson.
   Raynesford told CNN that ``there appear now to be 80 survivors.''
   CBS-TV quoted Janet Flanagan of St. Luke's Regional Medical
Center as saying that 26 people walked in, and at least nine were
critically injured.
   Diane Kay, a spokeswoman for the Marion Health Center, said 24
survivors had been brought there.
   ``They're all being treated,'' she said. ``We're seeing burns and
multiple injuries. I don't have a condition report at this time.''
   ``We did hear a jolt. We saw all the smoke,'' said Jean Hopper,
manager of a Motel 6 near the airport. ``The smoke is still rolling
quite heavily from the airport.''
   Witnesses watched as the plane struggled to make it to the
airport.
   ``We watched it circle coming in to the southeast of our plant.
We were optimistic. We thought it was going to make it,'' said Glen
Olson, city editor of the Sioux City Journal. Olson and other
employees watched the airplane circle from the newspaper plant, six
miles away.
   The airport has two active runways, each 9,000 feet long, which
can accommodate a plane the size of a DC-10. The area immediately
around the airport, which is seven miles from downtown, is crop land
in corn, soybeans and pasture with some trees.
   No unusual weather was reported. Wind speeds were clocked up to
30 mph.
   The nation's worst air crash happened 10 years ago and involved a
DC-10.
   On May 25, 1979, American Airlines Flight 191 lost an engine on
takeoff from Chicago's O'Hare Airport, banked sideways out of
control, slammed into a field and exploded. All 258 passengers and
13 crew members died, as well as two people on the ground.
   The National Transportation Safety Board laid primary blame for
the crash on the airline, citing ``maintenance-induced damage'' _ a
10-inch crack in the engine mount _ that caused the left engine to
tear loose. The NTSB also criticized McDonnell Douglas' design as
vulnerable to maintenance damage.
   McDonnell Douglas suspended production of the DC-10 airliner in
1983. DC-10 orders collapsed in 1979 because of the recession and
the May 1979 crash of an American Airlines DC-10 in Chicago that
killed 273 people. Bad passenger reaction to the crash apparently
discouraged airlines from placing orders. In all, 369 DC-10s were
produced, the last one in February 1983.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
