<FIRST>u w AM-Senate-China     07-19 0453</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Senate-China,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ambassador Says ``Very Few'' Chinese Students Arrested</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Bob Dole said China's ambassador to the
United States told him Wednesday that ``very few'' Chinese students
were arrested in the crackdown on pro-democracy demonstrations and
only 10 people have been executed.
   Dole, the Senate GOP leader, said Ambassador Han Xu made the
remarks to him after being handed a protest letter signed by 42
Republican senators.
   The letter predicted ``tremendous'' damage to U.S.-Chinese
relations ``should your government continue on the course of
state-sponsored violence and intimidation on which you are
embarked.''
   ``In his view very few students were arrested and most of those
who are sought were criminals,'' Dole said, reporting on his meeting
with the ambassador.
   ``He said there had been only 10 executions,'' added the senator
from Kansas.
   Sen. Pete Wilson, R-Calif., who attended the meeting, said that
the ambassador was told that television and newspaper reporting from
China indicates that hundrds of people have been arrested and many
executed.
   He said the ambassador did not accept that characterization of
the situation.
   Dole said the ambassador also protested arrangements being made
to enable Chinese students and scholars in the United States to
extend their stay in order to avoid persecution in China.
   ``It was his view that most Chinese students would like to stay
in the United States permanently,'' Dole said. ``He said they aren't
in any danger at home and that they are needed at home.''
   The letter noted that Han Xu is concluding his service in the
United States and returning to China.
   ``We want to be certain you take with you no illusion about our
reaction to recent events in China, and our concern about their
impact on U.S.-Chinese relations,'' the letter said.
   ``The American people, and those of us who have been elected to
represent them, are outraged that your government has so brutally
repressed peaceful demonstrations of hundreds of thousands of
Chinese citizens,'' the letter said.
   ``We regard the continued harassment, arrest and even execution
of those deemed responsible for organizing the demonstrations as
gross violations of the rights of your citizenry.''
   Earlier, the Senate adopted a resolution naming the small park
across the street from the Chinese Embassy here Tiananmen Square
Park.
   The sponsor, Sen. Malcolm Wallop, R-Wyo., said the park would
``remind Beijing that America will never and can never forget the
ruthless and callousness of the Chinese government in crushing their
citizen demonstrators and their aspirations.''
   The resolution also expressed the sense of the Senate that a
statue should be erected in the park in plain view of the embassy to
further honor the students who were killed in the square.
  
</TEXT>
