<FIRST>u a AM-CollegeDeseg     07-19 0554</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-College Deseg,0570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judges Order Louisiana To Dismantle Higher Education System</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA ASHTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Louisiana's illegally segregated system of
higher education must be dismantled to achieve a better racial mix
at 17 public colleges and universities, three federal judges ruled
Wednesday.
   Among the changes ordered by the panel are the creation of a
single board to govern higher education instead of the four existing
now, restriction of admissions at some universities, and
establishment of a community college system.
   ``The present scheme for governing education in Louisiana _ three
operating boards and one coordinating board _ has perpetuated
illegal segregation in Louisiana's higher education even though the
system's creation postdates the filing of this case,'' the judges
said.
   ``The system of multiple boards is therefore a defect in the
state's system of higher education that violates the federal
constitution.''
   The lawsuit was filed 15 years ago by the U.S. Justice
Department. It became clear in December 1988 that the issue could
not be settled, so the three judges appointed Paul Verkuil,
president of William and Mary College in Virginia, to conduct
hearings and write a desegregation plan. He submitted it in May.
   The plan was recommended by Gov. Buddy Roemer when he took office
in 1988.
   ``The state has won. The people have won. I believe we have Buddy
Roemer and three judges to thank,'' said the governor's attorney,
John Kennedy, at a news conference. Roemer was on vacation.
   The court gave the state 30 days to disband the four governing
boards and appoint a new 17-member board. The court declined to set
a ratio of white-to-black members.
   The order calls for Louisiana State University in Baton Rouge to
be designated the flagship university with the greatest number of
graduate and research programs.
   It also calls for creation of an intermediate level of
institutions offering significant doctoral and other graduate
programs, and for gradually merging the LSU law school and the
Southern University law school, both in Baton Rouge.
   The court refused to set the amount of money that must be spent
to adopt the order.
   ``Taking into consideration funds freed by the elimination of
duplicative programs, the board, the president and his staff, shall
develop budgets for the reclassified institutions, including
spending for improving the quality of predominantly black
institutions whenever fiscally possible,'' the court said.
   The jurists who wrote the order were 5th U.S. Circuit Court Judge
John M. Wisdom, U.S. District Judge Charles Schwartz and District
Judge Veronica Wicker.
   Other reaction from around the state was varied.
   Former Gov. John McKeithen, who left the LSU Board last year and
was the first governor to push desegregation, was skeptical.
   ``For the life of me, I don't know any way to make a white go to
Grambling or a black go to Louisiana Tech,'' McKeithen said. ``And
the one board is still going to have its politics. You're going to
have a segment on the board that favors LSU, a segment that favors
USL and one that favors Southern.''
   Larry Crain, president of the Board of Trustees for State
Colleges and Universities, said the court order is a welcome change.
   ``I think all of the boards have been anticipating this for some
time. What we're going to have to do is make it work,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
