<FIRST>r w AM-DrugEvictions     07-19 0310</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drug Evictions,220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Restores Power To Evict Drug Criminals from Public Housing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate unanimously adopted an amendment
Wednesday to restore to public housing authorities the power to
evict drug criminals from federally funded public housing.
   The measure, sponsored by Sens. Daniel P. Moynihan, D-N.Y., and
Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y., was added to the Foreign Relations
Authorization Act of 1990.
   ``Today, we have restored the original intent of my provision to
last year's drug bill,'' Moynihan said afterward. ``Don't let it be
said that we didn't get tough. We drew the line. Now we can work
toward our original goal of demanding accountability.''
   During final consideration of the 1989 supplemental
appropriations bill in June, language was added to limit Moynihan's
original eviction provision in the Anti-Drug Abuse Act of 1988. Both
Moynihan and D'Amato voted for the supplemental, not realizing they
were voting to undo the eviction measure, D'Amato said at a news
conference Monday in New York.
   The new provision restores the ability of federal officials to
waive administrative hearings for drug criminals when the hearings
would duplicate eviction proceedings in state courts.
   ``By passing this amendment, we are saying that we will no longer
subsidize violence and criminal activity in public housing,''
Moynihan said Wednesday.
   In considering the same foreign relations authorization bill, the
Senate unanimously passed a Moynihan amendment offering political
and financial assistance to Burmese students.
   The amendment provides $250,000 in refugee assistance for Burmese
protesters living in Thailand, India and border camps; 15
scholarships to Burmese students who have sought asylum outside
their country, which is engaged in civil war; and requests a report
from the attorney general and secretary of state on U.S. immigration
policy toward Burmese protesters.
   The amendment also calls on the administration to continue its
condemnation of human rights violations by the current military
regime in Burma.
</TEXT>
