<FIRST>u i AM-JaruzelskiProfile     07-19 0582</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Jaruzelski Profile,0598</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski, Martial Law and Reform</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DRUSILLA MENAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski speaks now of
reconciliation and reform, but his martial law declaration of 1981
echoes so loudly in Polish ears that the stern man behind the dark
glasses nearly lost the presidency.
   Earlier this year, his Communist Party shifted course
dramatically and decided to make Solidarity legal again after trying
for more than seven years to obliterate the independent union.
   Jaruzelski's government, aware that the Communists needed help in
controlling Poland's social unrest and economic crisis, offered
talks with the opposition that produced political reforms leading to
Wednesday's presidential election in Parliament.
   ``It would be the greatest drama for me if history one day said
those decisions were wrong,'' he said in a recent interview with The
Associated Press. ``That's why I wish so much that the agreement,
that this pluralism, passes the test in real life.''
   Straight and serious, often seeming remote behind the glasses and
a lifetime's worth of military medals, Jaruzelski is a far cry from
presidential counterparts in the West.
   Little is said of his domestic life and he rarely engages
citizens or reporters in conversation during public appearances.
   He was born July 6, 1923, to an upper-class family in eastern
Poland and was attending a Roman Catholic boarding school in Warsaw
when Poland was invaded at the beginning of World War II.
   His official biography says he ``stayed'' in the northeastern
Soviet Union during the war, working as a laborer. Poles who knew
the family, however, said the Jaruzelskis were caught by Soviet
occupiers and deported a Siberian labor camp, where Wojciech's
father died.
   The young man entered a Soviet officer training school in 1943
and later served with the communist-led Polish First Army, which was
formed in the Soviet Union and fought with the Red Army against the
Nazis.
   Jaruzelski joined the Polish Communist Party in 1947 and rose
through the political and military ranks, becoming defense minister
in 1968.
   In October 1981, at the height of Solidarity's defiance,
Jaruzelski became Communist Party chief, the only career military
officer to hold supreme power in a Soviet bloc country.
   Two months later, he announced martial law. Solidarity was
suppressed, then outlawed and its leaders arrested. Western aid and
investment was cut off and Poland slid into economic crisis.
   ``It was such a difficult and dramatic decision, and for me
personally very painful,'' Jaruzelski said in the AP interview.
   The general has not apologized for martial law or repudiated it,
and he leaves open the question of whether loyalty to the Kremlin or
a patriotic wish to prevent Soviet intervention prompted his action.
   Whatever his motive, the memory of those times has created
profound skepticism about his recent movement toward reform and
democratic change.
   When he told the Communist Party leadership June 30 he would not
run for the new, more powerful presidency, Jaruzelski acknowledged
he was linked too closely to martial law and too little to reform.
   ``I will not crawl to this post,'' Jaruzelski said in the AP
interview two days before the announcement.
   Then came a pledge of cooperation from Lech Walesa, the shipyard
electrician who founded Solidarity and won the 1983 Nobel Peace
Prize, and appearances with President Bush and other Western leaders.
   He changed his mind _ from a ``sense of duty'' was the military
way he explained it _ and ran for the presidency after all.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
