<FIRST>r i AM-France-Fashion     07-19 0728</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-France-Fashion,0749</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Faces on Couture Scene</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUZY PATTERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Fashion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   On the eve of the winter couture collections,
opening Sunday, the talk is more about new faces on the French
fashion scene than about hemlines.
   So many Italians are showing that one wonders if it won't be a
spaghetti revolution.
   In May, Gianfranco Ferre took over the chief creative post at
Dior from Marc Bohan, Dior's couturier for 30 years.
   Angelo Tarlazzi was designated as head of Guy Laroche's couture,
following Laroche's death last February. He has long been on the
Paris scene and plans to keep the French-based ready-to-wear firm he
has headed with his own label for 12 years.
   Two other famous Italians, Valentino and Gianni Versace, will
show during couture week _ but separately, rather than as part of
the official French Chambre Syndicale couture group of 23 houses.
   It will be Versace's first-ever showing in Paris. Valentino has
already shown couture once, but has shown his luxury ready-to-wear
for several years. Both are throwing festive parties after their
shows in museums, but Versace's offering might look stilted, since
he's draping his outfits on steel mannequins.
   What do the French think of all these Italians invading the
sacred halls of haute couture? Jacques Mouclier, president of the
Chambre Syndicale de la Couture Parisienne, is sanguine.
   ``It's a demonstration of Paris supremacy in fashion that they
all want to come. We don't worry about it. If we subtracted the
foreign designers, we wouldn't have many left. Ungaro is of Italian
origin, and so is Cardin, whose name was Cardini. And think of Karl
Lagerfeld.''
   Born in Germany, Lagerfeld is Chanel's designer and also creates
his own ready-to-wear line in France.
   ``For the last ten years we've been encouraging foreigners _ many
Japanese, Italians and the American Patrick Kelly _ to work and show
their ready-to-wear here.''
   But now Mouclier thinks that the foreign newcomers should do as
Lagerfeld and Tarlazzi did, ``become nationalized or unofficially
French. We'd like to see them give up their commitments abroad and
work only in France.''
   Ferre, 44, will be giving up designing couture under his own name
in Milan, to design for Dior _ arguably the most prestigious couture
label in the world. But he has kept his own ready-to-wear operation
in Milan.
   Ferre's show for Dior will be held in a private mansion, the
Salomon de Rothschild Foundation, followed by a gala dinner for
select clients.
   Fashion-watchers reckon that this is a move to help pacify any of
the rich and fairly conservative women who might find the change
from Bohan to Ferre upsetting.
   Backed by the Agache financial group headed by Bernard Arnault,
which also finances Christian Lacroix, Dior reportedly wanted new
angles and excitement, which Ferre may or may not deliver. Trained
as an architect, he is known for his sharply constructed outfits and
his love of rich fabrics.
   A preview model in a French newspaper showed a wasp-waisted coat
with raised collar worn with spike heels that hinted strongly of the
old ``New Look,'' created by Christian Dior himself in 1947.
   Angelo Tarlazzi said, ``I won't do anything shocking, or
overdressed for the house of Laroche.''
   But he does promise big, long and comfortable coats over skinny
``cigarette'' pantsuits, as well as a version of the sexy backless
sheath created by Guy Laroche for film star Mireille Darc.
   More changes this season: Lanvin, which has been bought by the
Midland Bank, will not be showing couture at all, as designer Maryll
Lanvin left when the new management came in. ``We haven't found a
designer yet,'' said a Lanvin spokesman.
   And Madame Gres _ at 86 the ``doyenne'' of French couture _ will
be showing a collection featuring cocktail clothes and evening
gowns, in the new Gres shop on the Rue du Faubourg St. Honore,
having not shown for two seasons.
   ``The main lines are hers,'' said an assistant. ``But since she
is quite fatigued, she has had a lot of help in details.''
   All over town, couturiers are revving up to lay on their
surprises for next winter, but they are giving out a few previews as
well. So far, it seems that as with ready-to-wear, almost anything
goes: lots of short skirts, a few long and swirly ones, big and warm
coats, and trousers back with a vengeance.
</TEXT>
