<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-89 1937EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-TaxBill     07-19 0567</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tax Bill,500</SECOND>
<BYLINE>House Committee Approves Child Care Tax Credits ^By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House Ways and Means Committee on Wednesday
approved $16 billion worth of tax credits and child-care benefits to
lower-income families over the next five years.
   The initiative, which is somewhat more generous than President
Bush recommended for child care but less than the Senate voted, was
approved on a 26-10 vote.
   The action came as members of the tax-writing panel continued to
look for a way to solve a heated controversy over reducing the
income tax surtax that older Americans pay for catastrophic-illness
insurance. Aides indicated there was no progress on that issue
Wednesday.
   The child-care amendments were added to a bill designed mainly to
raise $5.3 billion in revenues for deficit reduction in 1990. The
committee has not decided how to pay for child care, although it is
weighing proposals by Rep. Dan Rosteniowski, D-Ill., the chairman,
that would impose new taxes on mutual life insurance and chemical
companies and make permanent the temporary 3 percent tax on local
and long distance telephone service.
   There is continuing talk among committee members about cutting
the tax on capital gains, which would be expected to raise revenues
for a year or so. Bush has called for a cut but many Democrats are
opposed because most of the direct benefit would go to those with
incomes over $100,000.
   The panel's child-care initiative, which would become effective
in 1991, is ``a giant step forward,'' Rostenkowski told reporters.
   ``I hope the Bush administration will committee itself to its
campaign promise and do something for children,'' he said.
   The proposals would benefit not only families in which both
spouses work outside the home but also those families in which one
spouse stays at home to care for the children.
   The heart of the committee's child-care plan would expand the
existing earned-income credit, which is worth up to $910 a year in
tax cuts _ or in cash if there is no tax liability _ for working
families with children and incomes up to about $18,000.
   The committee voted to raise the maximum credit to $1,217 for a
family with one child; $1,540 if there are two children, and $1,790
if a family has two or more. Under current law, the credit is the
same regardless of the number of children.
   The plan would create a new credit for families with one or more
children under the age of 6. This credit, which would be in addition
to the earned-income credit, would be for 6 percent of the first
$6,500 of earned income, with a top credit of $430 in 1991.
   A third part of the committee's package would authorize $1.55
billion worth of federal grants for social services, with 80 percent
of the money earmarked for improving child-care services.
   By a 20-14 vote the committee rejected an attempt by Rep. Hank
Brown, R-Colo., to eliminate the increase in social-service grants
and use the money to finance an even larger credit for families with
children under 6.
   Unlike the child-care plan passed by the Senate, the Ways and
Means Committee bill does nothing to change the tax credit now
allowed working parents to help offset expenses of caring for a
child. The Senate voted to make that credit available even to
families whose incomes are so low that they owe no tax.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
