<FIRST>u w AM-Savage-Sex 1stLd-Writethru a0688 07-19 0912</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Savage-Sex, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0688,840</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressman Savage Accused of Assaulting Peace Corps Worker</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: To give Savage comment, INSERTS grafs 3-4 bgng: ``Savage denied,''
and SUBS graf 7 pvs bgng: ``Savage failed,'' with four grafs, now garafs
9-12 bgng: ``Savage angrily;'' also SUBS 10th graf pvs, now graf 15: ``She
eventually,'' to specify treatment.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House ethics committee was asked Wednesday
to investigate charges that Rep. Gus Savage, D-Ill., sexually
assaulted a Peace Corps volunteer while on an official trip to Zaire
last March.
   Three of Savage's Democratic colleagues _ Reps. Patricia
Schroeder of Colorado, Matthew McHugh of New York and Barney Frank
of Massachusetts _ formally requested the ethics investigation,
which means the congressional panel must inquire into the
allegations.
   Savage denied the charges.
   ``They tried to destroy Dr. Martin Luther King with a lie. ...
I'm in very good company,'' he told reporters from Chicago
television stations on the Capitol steps.
   At the same time, officials at the Peace Corps said they were
willing to seek disciplinary action against the Chicago Democrat,
but won't do so without the woman's consent.
   ``The ball is in her court,'' said one agency official, who spoke
only on the condition of anonymity. ``It's something we told her
right from the beginning. ... We would go great guns.''
   The Peace Corps worker claims Savage fondled her for more than
two hours in the back of a chauffeur-driven embassy car in Kinshasa,
the capital of Zaire, on March 19, according to several government
officials who confirmed an account originally published in The
Washington Post.
   ``He tried to force me to have sex with him. ... He kept touching
me, after I told him to stop, many times, loudly... He kept saying,
`That's the way the world works,''' she was quoted as saying.
   Savage angrily brushed past a reporter on the House floor
Wednesday and used expletives when she asked for comment. But
outside on the Capitol steps, he offered a different account of the
night in question.
   ``We were in a caravan of four or five cars,'' Savage said in
remarks monitored in Chicago. ``We made four or five brief stops and
got out of the car and got back in. If there were any kind of abuse,
then why would she keep getting back into the same car?''
   He added: ``It doesn't surprise you that the person who remains
independent of plantation politics in Chicago, that that man who
refuses to be bought or to be bossed, that grates hard on some of
you white journalists. ... But that will not stop Gus Savage at
all.''
   Savage is black.
   Neither the government agencies involved nor the Washington Post
has disclosed the woman's name.
   The newspaper account quoted her as saying Savage's advances
continued even though she ``tried everything ... short of hitting
him, or hurting him physically to make him stop.''
   She eventually left her post in Zaire to get counseling and
medical treatment at a Washington hospital and is awaiting another
Peace Corps assignment, the agency official said.
   Jill Gross of the State Department inspector general's office
said the allegations were forwarded in a letter to Rep. Julian C.
Dixon, D-Calif., chairman of the House ethics committee. The
committee had no formal comment.
   The State Department has no jurisdiction in the case, Gross said,
but the allegations ``were brought to our attention'' from
department employees in Zaire and ``they were sufficiently serious
that someone should look into them.''
   She declined to release the letter sent to the ethics committee,
citing confidentiality.
   The three Democrats wrote in a letter to Dixon:
   ``We write to ask the ethics committee to inquire into the
assertion that our colleague from Illinois, Mr. Savage, behaved
improperly towards a federal employee while on a congressional
tour.''
   The two-paragraph letter noted that the lawmakers had no
independent knowledge of the incident, but added: ``We believe that
the accusation is sufficiently serious to justify your looking into
it.''
   The incident allegedly occurred while Savage was on an official
visit to Zaire in mid-March and had dinner one night at the
residence of U.S. Ambassador William Harrop. The dinner attendees
included the Peace Corps volunteer, who was scheduled to brief the
congressman a few days later on agency activities there, an official
said.
   After dinner, Savage insisted the woman ride alone with him in an
embassy limousine while the congressmen, members of his staff and
others visited area bars, the official said.
   As soon as the three cars left the ambassador's home, Savage
``grabbed me,'' the woman told the Post.
   The volunteer tried to flee from Savage at a hotel disco and was
eventually escorted home by an embassy officer, a Peace Corps
official said.
   She reported the incident the next day to Bruce Cohen, Peace
Corps director in Zaire, and Harrop later confronted Savage, this
official added.
   The ambassador ``spoke very strongly'' to Savage and ``chewed him
out as much as an ambassador chews out a congressman,'' an
unidentified witness told the Post.
   The woman did not make a formal complaint against Savage because
she thought it would hurt the Peace Corps, said an official who
added she is still reluctant to initiate a case against the
congressman.
   ``We have a pretty impressive record going against people who
violate Peace Corps types,'' the official said.
   ``If this person is willing to testify, we'll go up to (Capitol)
Hill with it,'' he said.
</TEXT>
