<FIRST>r a AM-ExxonValdez     07-19 0320</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Exxon Valdez,0328</SECOND>
<HEAD>Valdez Towed Closer To San Clemente Island</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The damaged Exxon Valdez was towed toward an
island Wednesday for repairs to enable it to enter port, and no
leaks were observed from the tanker for the third day in a row,
officials said.
   A series of samples taken from the cargo tanks on the ship that
cause the nation's worst oil spill were being analyzed for toxicity
and hydrocarbon content. Results were expected in several days, said
Coast Guard Petty Officer Elizabeth Neely.
   The ship, which was 14 miles south of San Clemente Island on
Tuesday, was to moved to within 7 to 10 miles south of the island on
Wednesday, said Exxon Shipping Co. spokeswoman Jan Cool.
   San Clemente Island is 60 miles northwest of San Diego.
   Cool said Exxon officials were trying to determine whether divers
operating in ocean waters can safely cut off a half dozen steel
plates hanging from the ship's bottom.
   Cool said they would determine whether the work can be done in
the open ocean before taking the tanker into an anchorage just off
the island.
   The plates peeled away during the ship's 2,500-mile journey from
Alaska, where it underwent preliminary repairs after smashing onto a
reef March 24 in Prince William Sound and spilling nearly 11 million
gallons of crude.
   The plates, one of which hangs down about 70 feet, must be
removed so the Valdez can navigate a San Diego Harbor channel whose
depth averages about 40 feet.
   The Valdez is scheduled to undergo a nine-month, $25 million
repair at San Diego's National Steel and Shipbuilding Co., once it
has been declared free of navigational and environmental hazards.
   On July 10, Coast Guard officials suspended the Valdez's
scheduled harbor entry after an 18-mile slick was sighted near the
ship. Discharges of oil mixed with organic compounds such as
plankton continued for several days after that.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
