<FIRST>r a AM-MonkeyHerpes 1stLd-Writethru a0659 07-19 0514</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Monkey Herpes, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0659,0528</SECOND>
<HEAD>Company Tries to Slience Former Employees</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with judge silencing one employee,
saying he'll schedule hearing on Monday; picks up 5th graf, `Casey has
...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LISA PERLMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PAW PAW, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge on Wednesday granted a research
lab's request to silence a former technician who complained about
safety and health procedures more than a year before another worker
died of a rare virus.
   International Research and Development Corp. won a preliminary
injunction in Van Buren County Circuit Court against James Casey in
connection with a lawsuit the company filed against Casey and David
Bailey last September.
   IRDC alleges the men violated a confidentiality agreement with
the company by giving statements _ some of which the company says
are false _ to government investigators who were inspecting the
company.
   Judge Meyer Warshawsky ruled that IRDC could suffer irreparable
harm to its reputation if Casey continued making allegations against
the Mattawan company.
   Warshawsky warned Bailey not to discuss the case but did not
include him in the injunction. IRDC had sought to silence Bailey as
well.
   Casey allegedly told inspectors from the U.S. Food and Drug
Administration about health and safety problems at the lab,
resulting in several citations and a loss of business, IRDC
attorneys said.
   Warshawsky said that on Monday he would set a date for the trial
of IRDC's lawsuit.
   Casey has countersued the company, contending he was exposed to
dangers at the lab and was fired in retaliation for his complaints
about safety problems.
   The court action comes one month after the death of a technician
who contracted a rare virus from an infected research monkey.
Another former IRDC technician is hospitalized with the infection,
the deadly herpes B virus.
   The company alleges statements made by Casey and Bailey have
contributed to bad publicity and death threats from animal rights
groups.
   Attorneys for Bailey and Casey said their clients' right to free
speech outweighs any harm that might come to the company.
   The independent contract research laboratory tests drugs and
chemicals for medical, pharmaceutical, veterinary and agriculture
companies.
   After seven years as manager of the large-animal toxicology
department, Bailey went to company officials in 1987 to discuss
perceived safety violations, his attorney said.
   ``Nothing happened,'' attorney Craig Lubben said of the company's
response. ``Things became worse ... he feared about the quality of
the testing.''
   In January 1988, Bailey quit after 10 years with the company.
Casey was fired in November 1987 after 10 years with the company.
He, too, had complained to company officials.
   Both men were warned against discussing company operations with
anyone, their attorneys said.
   Company vice president Francis X. Wazeter III testified that his
business depends on confidentiality because the lab tests compounds
that are trade secrets or have patents pending.
   IRDC attorney John Allen said the company could be irreparably
harmed if Bailey and Casey discuss their experiences at the company.
   Casey's attorney, Joseph Cutro, said any bad publicity
surrounding IRDC is the result of last month's death.
</TEXT>
