<FIRST>r i AM-CyprusProtest 1stLd-Writethru a0706 07-19 0710</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cyprus Protest, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0706,0725</SECOND>
<HEAD>Greek Cypriot Women Cross `Green Line' in Anniversary Protest</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with number arrested, color. Pickup
5th pvs, `The women...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEX EFTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Turkish Cypriot police wrestled with Greek
Cypriot women who forced their way across the island's ethnic
dividing line Wednesday, past U.N. soldiers, to protest the 15th
anniversary of the Turkish invasion.
   The police arrested dozens of the 1,000 women who, accompanied by
a Greek Orthodox bishop and two priests, held a ``Women's Return''
march to protest the invasion that drove them from their homes in
northern Cyprus. The bishop, Chrysostomos of Kition, and a priest,
whose name was not known, also were arrested.
   The semi-official Anatolia news agency in Turkey said 109
demonstrators were arrested, including the bishop and the priest.
Four of the detainees were taken to a hospital for treatment of
``minor injuries.''
   Turkish Cypriot police dragged many detainees away by the hair or
clothes. Canadian soldiers of the multiniational U.N. peacekeeping
force on Cyprus formed a human barrier to protect others.
   Police dragged away Steve Weizman, a British reporter for Reuters
news agency, after punching and kicking him. Katherine McElroy, also
of Reuters, was arrested.
   Anatolia said those detained were being held in a gymnasium. The
agency quoted Brig. Gen. Ali Yalcin, the Turkish Cypriot police
commander, as saying they will receive ``legal treatment.''
   Greek Cypriot President George Vassiliou and senior police
commanders held an emergency meeting at the Nicosia police
headquarters. They requested U.N. intenvetion to secure the release
of all detainees, government sources said.
   The women penetrated the ethnic boundary, called the Green Line,
at dusk after scuffling with the Canadian soldiers who patrol it and
knocking down barbed wire barricades at the Ayios Kassianos
neighborhood.
   They occupied a war-damaged elementary school and the St. Georges
Church. Some climbed onto the church roof with a bell and began
ringing it, while others sang hymns in Greek.
   Canadian soldiers warned the women they would not be able to
protect them from Turkish Cypriot policemen gathering by the dozens
only 10 yards away, but were ignored. The buffer zone along the line
is about 50 yards deep at that point.
   Marina Demitriou, an organizer of the march, shouted at the
Canadians: ``You should tell the Turks to go away. This is our land
and we have the right to be here.'' A Canadian officer replied:
``We're trying to protect you. Now please go away.''
   A few minutes later, Turkish riot police supported by dozens of
rifle-carrying soldiers charged into the buffer zone, pushing the
women outside the church onto the ground and arresting some. The
policemen entered the church.
   The organizing committee issued a statement saying the
demonstration was intended ``to reiterate our right to return'' to
the northern third of the island the Turkish army seized in an
invasion that began July 20, 1974.
   Turkey invaded, with the stated intention of protecting ethnic
Turkish Cypriots, because of a short-lived coup against the late
President Makarios led by Greek officers. About 120,000 ethnic Turks
live on Cyprus, making up 17 percent of the population.
   In March, 40 Greek Cypriot women were arrested and held for
several hours after a similar attempt to cross the line.
   Turkish authorities had warned the protesters they would be
arrested and jailed for ``illegal entry'' if they crossed the line
on Wednesdday.
   ``As soon as the women enter our territory, they will come face
to face with soldiers of the Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus and
the necessary steps will be taken,'' said Rauf Denktash. He is
president of the northern state proclaimed in 1983, which only
Turkey recognizes.
   Maj. Gen. Clive Milner, Canadian commander of the 2,300-member
U.N. force, met protest leaders at his headquarters Tuesday and told
them his soldiers would seek to prevent any attempt to breach the
Green Line.
   The heavily fortified buffer zone stretches 112 miles across the
eastern Mediterranean island and ranges in width from four miles in
open country to as little as three yards in urban areas.
   The U.N. Force in Cyprus has been deployed along the line since
1964. It includes soldiers from Austria, Britain, Canada, Denmark,
Finland, Ireland and Sweden.
</TEXT>
