<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-89 2120EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-Salmonscam     07-19 0567</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salmonscam,0585</SECOND>
<HEAD>Agents Seize Alleged Fish-Smuggling `Kingpin,' Follow Two Ships</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM KLAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. officials said Wednesday they've netted a
Taiwanese businessman who allegedly masterminded the sale of 550
tons of U.S.-spawned salmon illegally caught on the high seas.
   The sale was made to undercover agents, who arrested Patrick Lee
of Taipei as he carried suitcases holding $1.3 million in cash out
of a Seattle bank vault.
   ``We think he is the kingpin,'' Brian Gorman, spokesman for the
National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration in Washington, D.C.,
said of Lee.
   Evidence collected in a six-month sting operation ``demonstrates
the blatant piracy of American salmon on the high seas,'' said
Rolland Schmitten, regional director of the National Marine
Fisheries Service.
   Two associates of Lee also were arrested in Seattle. Three
others, including the captains of the two fishing boats, were in
custody in the mid-Pacific late Tuesday after they had boarded a
fish-transport vessel used by undercover agents acting as buyers of
the salmon.
   Lee and John Chin Wang, formerly of Taiwan but a recently
naturalized U.S. citizen, and Wesley Ming Hsu of Los Angeles were
each charged Wednesday in U.S. District Court with one count of
violating the Lacey Act, which prohibits commerce in illegally
caught salmon or wildlife.
   Jen Chu, an interpreter, and ship captains Tsun Long Lin and Shu
Meng Ging will be charged with violating the Lacey Act when they
arrive in Seattle, said Wayne Lewis, an agent of the National Marine
Fisheries Service in Seattle.
   The maximum penalty for each Lacey Act violation is a fine of
$20,000 and a five-year prison sentence.
   The case probably will be presented to a federal grand jury in
Seattle and additional charges are likely, Lewis said.
   ``This should put the lid on one of the biggest salmon-pirate
operations, and if the others have any brains, they'll sit up and
take notice too,'' said Sen. Frank Murkowski, R-Alaska.
   Meanwhile, a 180-foot fish transport vessel and a Coast Guard
cutter tracked the two captain-less Taiwanese fishing vessels some
1,000 miles north of Midway Island.
   The vessels carry part of the 550 tons of salmon that were
supposed to have been delivered to Lee. The price was $1.25 per
pound for the fish.
   Coast Guard Cmdr. Brian Hunter said armed boarding parties of
federal agents were aboard bothvessels, and were awaiting permission
to board them. He said the United States has asked permission to
board from the government of Taiwan.
   There was no evidence the thousands of pounds of salmon were
being thrown overboard, as had happened in one recent attempt to
halt a Taiwanese fishing boat in the North Pacific, Hunter said.
   The sting operation began early this year when Lee contacted a
member of the U.S. fishing industry with an offer to sell salmon.
The American company that Lee approached contacted National Marine
Fisheries Service agents.
   Over the next six months, a NMFS agent posed as a buyer and
communicated with Lee over ``monitored'' telephone and fax machines
to arrange the sale, which climaxed in his arrests Tuesday.
   Schmitten said the illicit harvest of U.S.-spawned salmon on the
high seas threatens to destroy American fish runs. ``Unless we stop
it, we're not going to have any fish runs,'' he said.
   The 550 tons involved in the sting sale equals whole season-size
catches of certain species for Washington state fishermen, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890719-0211 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-89 2122EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Poland 3rdLd-Writethru a0808 07-19 0882</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0808,0908</SECOND>
<HEAD>Assembly Barely Elects Communist Leader President</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to CLARIFY that 15 lawmakers did not participate
but that it was not clear how many boycotted election; pickup 5th graf
pvs, `With 537...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WAR13</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski won the powerful
new presidency Wednesday without a vote to spare after some
opposition legislators boycotted the election and some members of
his own Communist Party opposed him.
   The Communist Party leader, who imposed martial law in 1981 but
later encouraged reforms that swept Solidarity into the legislature,
said he hoped to unite the nation.
   Jaruzelski, wearing civilian clothes and his customary dark
glasses, was met by applause from Communist lawmakers when he
arrived at the joint session of parliament barely an hour after the
vote and took the oath of office. Solidarity lawmakers were silent.
   ``I want to be a president of reconciliation, a representative of
all Poles,'' Jaruzelski, 66, said in a brief acceptance speech. ``I
will serve the nation. I will serve the fatherland, the one that has
not perished, the one that is and will be.''
   Of the National Assembly's 559 members, 270 voted for Jaruzelski
and 233 against. Thirty-four lawmakers abstained and 15, some of
whom boycotted the election, did not participate. Seven ballots were
counted invalid.
   With 537 valid votes, 270 _ or 50 percent plus one _ was ruled
the number required for election.
   The two-chamber National Assembly has 300 members from the
Communist Party or their allies and 259 members from Solidarity.
   The close vote indicated some dissatisfaction from Communist
hard-liners, who oppose Jaruzelski's compromises with Solidarity.
The Solidarity boycotters may have provided victory by reducing the
number of votes Jaruzelski required.
   Government ministers gave one another the thumbs-up sign as word
of Jaruzelski's victory spread through the chamber.
   Interior Minister Gen. Czeslaw Kiszczak, Jaruzelski's second
choice for president, was ebullient.
   ``I am very happy. ... He is the best for this office, which will
be so difficult in these times,'' Kiszczak said.
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa sent a letter of congratulations to
the general, who suppressed and crushed the independent union early
in the decade, but who later began to advocate reform.
   ``My wish for you is that the time you are given to perform this
office will be a stage in the history of our homeland effectively
leading to freedom and democracy and to regaining Poland's proper
position in Europe,'' Walesa said. Solidarity spokesman Janusz
Onyszkiewicz read the letter to reporters.
   In Washington, the Bush administration congratulated Jaruzelski
and said: ``The choice of leadership is an internal matter for the
Polish people. Our only concern is to see the political and economic
reform process go forward.''
   Since 1985, Jaruzelski has been head of the Council of State, the
collective leadership whose chairman sometimes was referred to as
president. Real power rested with party Politburo, which he also led.
   By electing Jaruzelski, the National Assembly assured him
continued control of the military and foreign relations. The
president also will choose a prime minister, who then will form a
government with parliamentary approval.
   One by one Wednesday, lawmakers filed up to a wooden box at the
front of the chamber and deposited printed paper ballots.
   Many held up ballots showing they were voting against Jaruzelski.
At least three said they weren't participating at all because there
was only one candidate.
   ``I was and I am for Lech Walesa,'' said Sen. Gabriel Janowski of
Siedlce said as he deposited his ballot against Jaruzelski.
   Solidarity's parliamentary floor leader, Bronislaw Geremek,
neither endorsed nor opposed the nomination, but said opposition
lawmakers could not forget Jaruzelski's 1981 martial-law decree,
under which many of them were imprisoned.
   ``We express the hope that the future president ... will act for
the realization of the promises of democratization for the
fulfillment of the promises of change in our country,'' Geremek said
from the podium.
   As lawmakers gathered for the vote, about 50 anti-Jaruzelski
demonstrators from the Confederation for an Independent Poland
rallied outside. ``Jaruzelski Must Go,'' one banner read.
   Some Solidarity members, while not forgiving the general for past
repression, argued that defeating him could undermine reforms needed
to reverse the country's economic decline.
   ``It is a great relief,'' said Sen. Karol Modzelewski of Wroclaw.
``We would have been in real trouble if he did not make it.''
   In its editions Wednesday, the opposition Gazeta Wyborcza said in
an editorial that the new president would be ``a guarantor of a
stable course'' as Poland enters a transition period leading to full
democracy.
   On Tuesday, Jaruzelski cited ``a sense of duty'' and reversed his
June 30 decision not to seek the presidency.
   An announcement by Walesa that he would cooperate with Jaruzelski
as president, and words of praise from President Bush during a visit
last week, may have helped change his mind.
   Jaruzelski must deal with worsening food shortages and inflation
now headed for annual rate of 160 percent. The pressing economic
problems have caused widespread discontent and impelled the
Communist Party's concessions to Solidarity.
   In April, the free trade union movement was made legal again and
allowed to enter candidates in June elections that were the freest
since the Communists gained power four decades ago.
</TEXT>
