<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-Strikes     07-19 0238</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Strikes,0247</SECOND>
<HEAD>Transit Strike Continues, Strike Breaks Out at Gdynia Shipyard</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A strike by 11,000 transit workers
stretched into a second day Wednesday in the nation's largest
province, and shipyard workers in the Baltic port of Gdynia laid
down tools and demanded higher pay.
   The strikes came amid signs of a deteriorating economy, including
a sharp jump in inflation, which is approaching an annual rate of
160 percent. There are shortages of meat and many other goods.
   The strike at the Paris Commune shipyard in Gdynia broke out
spontaneously Wednesday morning, according to the Solidarity
Information Service in Warsaw. It was not immediately clear how many
workers were participating.
   A strike committee was formed of union representatives and
independent workers and was to present management with a list of 13
demands, including higher pay and better work organization, the
inforamtion service said.
   In Katowice province, in southern Poland, talks broke off Tuesday
night in a bus and tramway strike that began in the morning,
paralyzing mass transit. It was not immediately clear what transit
workers were demanding.
   Solidarity representatives said they did not instigate the strike
but were participating in negotiations to bring it to an end.
   The union information service said local authorities were trying
to organize alternative transportation services using buses owned by
state-run cooperatives and private enterprises.
   Katowice province is an industrial area of nearly 4 million
people.
</TEXT>
