<FIRST>u a AM-Crash-Airports     07-19 0528</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Crash-Airports,0546</SECOND>
<HEAD>Relatives, Consolers Gather at 3 Airports</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Stands for Philadelphia story promised in advisory.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-DC-10 Crash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JULIA RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   News that a 9-year-old boy had survived the DC-10
crash at Sioux City, Iowa, broke the pall surrounding United
Airline's posh Red Carpet Room at Stapleton International Airport on
Wednesday evening.
   The doomed jet had taken off from Stapleton about 12:45 p.m.
bound for Chicago's O'Hare International Airport and Philadelphia
International Airport.
   ``Isn't it great. We're taking the first plane out (to Sioux
City). He's alive. He made it,'' an overjoyed Rabbi Avrohom
Brownstein told reporters as he and his wife burst out of the VIP
room where relatives of passengers on the plane had gathered.
   Brownstein, the director of Beth Jacob High School in Denver, and
his wife, Chava, had just received word their son, Yisroel,
nicknamed ``Sroli,'' had survived the crash and was in a Sioux City
hospital with a broken arm and minor burns.
   ``He's OK. He always wanted to have a broken arm anyway. We just
talked to him on the phone and he's OK,'' Brownstein said. He said
his son had been going to Philadelphia to visit friends.
   Mrs. Brownstein said she heard the first reports of the crash on
her car radio.
   ``... Things started filtering in. First the plane was from
Denver, then going to Chicago. I thought to myself, `Oh, no!' And I
had to pull over. I waited for someone to come and get me,'' said
the rabbi's wife.
   Earlier, United employees escorted 25 to 30 visibly shaken
relatives past ranks of reporters and television cameras. The media
was not allowed into the VIP area.
   In Philadelphia, meanwhile, four people with firsthand knowledge
of the pain of losing loved ones rushed to the airport as soon as
they heard about the crash.
   ``The purpose of our visit is to comfort the families, to support
those people who wonder if their family members are alive,'' said
Stan Maslowski of Haddonfield, N.J.
   Maslowski's 30-year-old daughter, Diane, died Dec. 21 when a
terrorist's bomb exploded aboard a Pan Am Boeing 747. The explosion
killed 259 aboard the plane and 11 on the ground in Lockerbie,
Scotland, where the wreckage fell.
   Maslowski said the relatives of the Pan Am victims have formed a
network of more than 400 people who are prepared to rush to airports
to console anyone waiting for a plane that had crashed.
   On Wednesday, their message reached no relatives. Maslowski said
United officials told him no one waiting for passengers had reported
to the airport.
   And at Chicago's O'Hare, a knot of nearly 100 people _ reporters
and curious passersby _ gathered at a lounge next to the gate where
the jet was to have arrived from Denver about 4 p.m.
   People entering the lounge appeared grim. A woman entered crying,
her fingertips at her mouth. Two men leaving refused to speak with a
reporter, one swearing as he brushed by.
   Outside the room, a phalanx of 20 Chicago police officers and
O'Hare security personnel guarded entrance to the lounge.
   At one point, a clergyman was ushered into the room.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
