<FIRST>r w AM-US-Angola 324   07-19 0301</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Angola, 324</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cuban Withdrawal from Angola Called on Schedule</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cuban troops are withdrawing from Angola on
schedule, the assistant secretary of state for Africa said Wednesday.
   ``Over 26 percent of their troops have left, everything is going
in apple pie order, and the Soviet contribution has been very
useful,'' Herman Cohen told the Cable News Network in an interview
on ``International Hour.''
   ``They helped bring about the agreement signed last September,
they're urging the MPLA to observe the ceasefire, they urged the
MPLA to go into this negotiation. So we're working very closely with
them to make sure it all stays on tracks.''
   MPLA is the Portuguese acronym for the Marxist party that rules
the former Portuguese colony in southwest Africa. Cohen said there
had been about 50,000 Cuban troops supporting it.
   Cohen said Jonas Savimbi, head of the rebel UNITA forces, will
not take part in a new government for a year or 18 months, but then
he would have to get a big job such as prime minister.
   ``I think he has to play a major role in any Angolan government
because he represents at least 40 percent of the Angolan people and
maybe more,'' Cohen said.
   ``So he's going to have a high post. The only way the government
and the country can stay together is if he bring his people along
into it. He has already conceded that the president of Angola with
be the current president, President (Jose Eduardo) dos Santos. So
he's not looking to take over that job.''
   Cohen said Angola will probably have a parliament and a one-party
government, with MPLA and UNITA merged into something new.
   The administrations of former President Ronald Reagan and
President Bush have supported Savimbi. Cohen said he had tremendous
support in Congress.
</TEXT>
