<FIRST>a i AM-Heath-Thatcher Adv24   07-19 0835</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Heath-Thatcher, Adv 24,0855</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv24</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday AMs, July 24, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Ted Heath at War With the Woman Who Took His Job</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE SHEPHERD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALISBURY, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Among the more riveting sideshows in
British politics is Edward Heath's war of words with the woman who
took his job.
   The former prime minister has been out of office for 15 years,
but his bitterness toward Margaret Thatcher seems undiminished.
   In Britain, former prime ministers tend to fade away into
lifetime sinecures in the House of Lords.
   Not Ted Heath. From his seat in the House of Commons, he erupts
periodically against the woman he believes has betrayed the
Conservative Party's principles and his dream of European unity.
   Europe is only the latest in a long run of contentious issues.
Heath has attacked Mrs. Thatcher's economics, her foreign policies,
her attitude to the poor. He has called his relationship with her
``a polite nihilism.'' She shrugs and says: ``We all know Ted.''
   They are a study in contrasts: Heath, the consensus man,
flagbearer of the benevolent ``one-nation conservatism'' of the
Victorian prime minister Benjamin Disraeli; Mrs. Thatcher, the
hard-line, free-market radical, a consensus-hater and proud of it.
   She is a round-the-clock political being with few outside
interests; he, in office, was a yachtsman and sometimes symphony
conductor, and still is. Now he has taken up cultivating orchids. An
accomplished pianist, he owns two Steinways and has written books on
music, sailing, travel and Christmas carols.
   At 73, he exudes a fleshy vigor, topped off by a grand mane of
white hair and the famous ear-to-ear smile. He is too partisan to be
regarded as an elder statesman, but on European issues his opinions
command attention.
   It was Heath who brought Britain into the European Economic
Community in 1973, after years of resistance both at home and in the
France of the late Charles de Gaulle. Now the EEC is striving for
greater unity through a single European currency and central bank,
and harmonized social policies, and Heath wholeheartedly supports
the idea.
   His latest broadside against Mrs. Thatcher was triggered by her
claim that the EEC was bent on rolling back her free-market
revolution by forcing socialism upon Britain and engulfing it in
bureaucracy.
   On television he accused Mrs. Thatcher of ``an attempt to mislead
the public.'' Then, in an interview with The Associated Press at his
home on the grounds of Salisbury Cathedral, he amplified:
   ``This is nonsense. ... It can't possibly be true. If the people
of this country elect another Labor government they may get
socialism. A large part of the EEC is not socialist and isn't going
to support socialism now.''
   He said he believed Mrs. Thatcher was confusing ``socialism''
with the ``social order,'' which the EEC wants to bring about by
harmonizing social welfare, and which he says the Conservative Party
has believed in since the mid-1800s.
   For Conservatives, proud of their tradition of party unity, the
squabbling is an embarrassment. But Heath is unrelenting. On radio
and television panels, on the international lecture circuit and in
the House of Commons, where his debating skills always draw a good
crowd, he warns that Britain is in danger of becoming a second-class
member of the European club.
   ``My view of Europe ... is to bring about an ever-increasing
unity inside the Community, a way of life in which you work
together, share each other's benefits and problems and enable people
to have a much higher standard of living than they would otherwise
have, and put the community in a position where it can influence
international affairs.'' Heath says.
   ``If Britain doesn't want to take part, they will be left
outside. The other 11 will go on without us and we shall then become
a second-rate, second tier in the Community.''
   Critics say Heath is still nursing wounds inflicted when he was
dumped as party leader in 1975 in favor of Mrs. Thatcher, the first
woman to lead a political party in Britain. A year earlier he had
lost the third of his four electoral battles against arch-rival
Harold Wilson of the Labor Party.
   ``I think Ted felt desperately and totally betrayed by the
party,'' says Lord Whitelaw, who also lost to Mrs. Thatcher in the
party leadership fight.
   ``This rather shy, rather withdrawn man felt deeply affronted,''
Whitelaw said in a television interview in April. ``Certainly he
would mind more than most people who had been beaten by a woman.
Most men wouldn't like it, but I think he minded more.''
   He added that Heath, a bachelor, had no wife to say, ``What's the
good of feeling so bitter about it?''
   The true extent of Heath's bitterness is likely to be revealed in
his forthcoming memoirs.
   ``I would have thought there would be massive interest in them,
wouldn't you?'' he asked with a tiny smile and the promise: ``I'm
not going to be discreet.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs July 24</NOTE>
