<FIRST>a a AM-ReligionToday Adv21   07-19 0855</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Religion Today, Adv 21,0880</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv21</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Friday AMs, July 21, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Methodists Take on Down-Home Songs in Newly Available Hymnal</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Laserphoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Contrary to church trends toward loftier music,
United Methodists are turning to some foot-tapping gospel songs that
the denomination previously shunned.
   Such hearty spirituals as ``Go Down Moses'' and ``Shall We Gather
at the River'' are additions to the church's new hymnal now being
distributed to congregations nationwide.
   ``It's a serious reformation in United Methodist hymnody,'' says
the Rev. Carlton R. Young of Nashville, Tenn., the hymnbook editor.
``We have made a profound turnaround to give people the songs they
like to sing.''
   Many of them, such as ``In the Garden'' and ``Softly and Tenderly
Jesus is Calling,'' had been excluded from previous denominational
hymnals as too sentimental.
   But they and other popular gospel songs, spurned by musicologists
and generally omitted from formal church repertoires, are in the new
book, along with the longtime classic numbers.
   ``We've still got the highbrow stuff, Bach, Mendelssohn and
Vaughan Williams, everything we had,'' Young said in a telephone
interview. ``But we've expanded it to include that which had not
been included.
   ``Before we've had an elistist hymbook and such musical taste
came at a high premium. Now we've put the premium on that which
people can enjoy and sing readily, alongside the good music.''
   Copies of the new hymnal are rolling out to congregations from
the church's publishing house in Nashville, Tenn., with 3 million
expected to be delivered by September and an additional million by
October, an unprecedented 4 million.
   That's almost one for every two members of the 9 million-member
denomination, the nation's second largest Protestant body.
   Most news stories about the book, which is replacing a 1966
version, have played up changes to make lyrics more sexually
inclusive of people, such as changing ``Good Christian Men,
Rejoice'' to ``Good Christian Friends, Rejoice.''
   Most such alterations are submerged in the texts, such as a
phrase in ``Hark the Herald Angels Sing,'' changed from ``pleased
with man with men to dwell'' to ``pleased with us in flesh to
dwell.''
   Masculine references are almost always retained for God and
Jesus, as in ``Come, thou Almighty King.'' Even the male generic
term for humanity is kept in ``Dear Lord and Father of Mankind.''
   Two hymns portray feminine attributes of God as like a mother
eagle, her broad wings described in one number as checking the fall
of her young as they struggle to fly.
   However, far more dramatic than the broadened gender metaphors is
the book's opening to songs historically excluded from hymnals of
major liturgical churches _ Presbyterian, Episcopal, Lutheran, Roman
Catholic and Methodist.
   Past exclusion of popular gospel songs and spirituals ``has been
our main inadequacy,'' Young said. ``The complaint for the last 50
years is that we didn't have the hymns people wanted to sing.''
   Musicologists spurned such songs, Young observed. ``Only the
people liked them.''But they now occupy a principal place, alongside
traditional hymns. ``I don't think any mainline denomination has had
the turnaround that we've had,'' Young said.
   The newly incorporated songs evolved in America from revivals of
the 19th century and out of the travail of blacks rather than from a
European heritage, which has long dominated most American hymnals.
   ``We were slow'' in accepting the home-grown creations, Young
said. Yet ``they are at the heart and recall of our constitutency.
They're familiar to our people. But they hadn't been in the book.''
   Among the black spirituals included for the first time are
``Swing Low, Sweet Chariot,'' ``It's Me, It's Me, O Lord,'' ``This
Little Light of Mine,'' ``Tis the Old Ship of Zion (Give Me That Old
Time Religion),'' ``I'm Goin' a Sing When the Spirit Says Sing'' and
``Kum Ba Ya, My Lord.''
   Gospel favorites newly added include ``Marching to Zion,''
``Nothing but the Blood,'' ``I Surrender All,'' ``Pass Me Not O
Gentle Savior,'' ``There's Within My Heart a Melody,'' ``Leaning on
the Everlasting Arms'' and ``Lord of the Dance.''
   Altogether, the book's 625 hymns include 84 gospel songs and 38
black spirituals, a total of 122. There also are 17 Spanish hymns,
offered in that language for the first time, 14 Asian and seven
American Indian hymns. Of 300 carry-overs from the old book, 60 are
by founder John Wesley or brother Charles.
   Two martial-style hymns, ``Onward Christian Soldier'' and ``The
Battle Hymn of the Republic,'' at one point were eliminated by the
revision committee, but were reinstated in response to 11,000
protest letters.
   The result of such input, Young said, is a populist instead of
elitist hymnbook compiled under membership influence. ``The
political climate will not sustain anything that does not belong
squarely within the earshot of the average Methodist.''
   Young, 63, professor of church music at Emory University's
Chandler School of Theology in Atlanta who took leave five years ago
to head the hymnal revision, said the book ``fully breathes the
American spirit.''
   He said it may make the church ``a more lively place.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri AMs July 21</NOTE>
</DOC>
