<FIRST>a a AM-ReligionRdp Adv21   07-19 0569</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Religion Rdp, Adv 21,0592</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv21</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Friday AMs, July 21, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Friday in Palmyra-dated item is July 21.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rev. Avery Post, retiring after 12
years as president of the United Church of Christ, says that
``obsessive devotion'' to the American flag is among national
``signs of pathos and vulnerability.''
   More worrisome, he says, are ``those who are exploiting this
insecurity and vulnerability for political ends.''
   In his parting keynote address to the denomination's recent
general synod, Post urged it not to get bogged down in conflict over
subsidiary issues, but also not ``to sit at ease in Zion.''
   ``Biblical faith introduced me to a justice lifestyle at the
beginning of my ministry, and I expect to stay on the case for God's
justice until the end of my days,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unofficial figures compiled by a United
Methodist publication, Newscope, indicate the denomination's
membership fell below 9 million in 1988, to about 8.89 million.
   Membership in the denomination, third largest in the nation, has
been declining for 22 years.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Because of China's harsh suppression of
pro-democracy students, the American Jewish Committee has canceled
plans for sending a delegation there this summer ``in the interest
of deepening relationships between the American Jewish community and
Chinese people.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PALMYRA, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 1989 rendition of the famed Hill Cumorah
pageant staged by the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints
(Mormons) opens Friday evening for a seven-day run.
   The huge pageant, portraying the spliritual struggles of
purported ancient peoples in the Americas, this year has a cast of
500. An additional 1,400 volunteers have behind-the-scenes tasks.
   More than 100,000 people attended last year's pageant and
officials expected at least that many this year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The annual conference of the Church of the
Brethren decided to develop a new denominational statement on
peace-making.
   This is something the 155,000-member church has emphasized ever
since its founding in 1708.
   One of three historic ``peace'' churches, along with the
Mennonites and Quakers, the Brethren agreed a new positive statement
is needed to help people leave as peace-makers in all aspects of
life.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In his first address to the American
Baptist Churches as new general secretary, the Rev. Daniel Weiss
called for a broad coalition of U.S. churches to fight drugs,
homelessness and AIDS.
   He said at the denomination's biennial meeting Christians ``can
make a difference'' acting together. He urged them to ``stop arguing
over the nature of the Bible and begin to hear it and obey it.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anti-war and anti-abortion activists are
working together in some cases.
   That was so in recent demonstrations at the Seneca Army Depot and
at a Highland Hospital abortion clinic, Religious News Service
reports.
   It said most of the activists at the Army Depot were
anti-abortion protest veterans and most of the protesters at the
abortion clinic were veteran anti-war protesters.
   The Rev. Daniel Berrigan, a Jesuit priest and leading figure in
the anti-war movement, helped coordinate both protests. A
10-foot-long banner proclaimed the linkage this way:``War is
abortion, abortion is war.''
   Organizations combining protests against war and abortion include
Plowshares, which organized the demonstrations in Rochester; an
evangelical group called JustLife; and Pro-Lifers for Survival.
</TEXT>
