<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The trade deficit widened sharply to $10.24
billion in May, reflecting a record monthly appetite for imports,
fewer goods sold abroad and lost ground in America's bid to shrink
the trade gap.
   The May imbalance reported Tuesday by the Commerce Department
weakened the stock and bond markets. It was the biggest deficit in
five months and represented a 23.6 percent increase over the $8.29
billion deficit registered in April.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration lowered its forecast
for the economy, predicting growth of 2.7 percent this year and 2.6
percent in 1990.
   The revisions disclosed Tuesday by White House officials were
more pessimistic than administration forecasts in February, which at
the time were described by many outside economists as unrealistic.
   The administration also revised downward its projection for the
1989 deficit to $148.3 billion from $164.1 billion predicted in
February, mainly due to revenues running $13.2 billion higher than
anticipated.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By The Associated Press</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   International Business Machines Corp. announced a 39 percent
quarterly profit increase swollen by a one-time gain, while Apple
Computer Inc. reported a smaller-than-expected 5.3 percent gain.
