<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-89 0147EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-SavingsBonds     07-19 0213</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Savings Bonds,0222</SECOND>
<HEAD>Treasury Announces Savings Bond Interest Schedule</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Treasury Department has announced a
schedule of maturity dates for U.S. Savings Bonds designed to reduce
confusion among bond holders who are unaware when their bonds stop
earning interest.
   ``Financial institutions and savings bond and note owners will
now only have to recall an easy to remember `40-30-20' formula to
determine how long bonds will earn interest,'' the department said
Tuesday in a statement.
   For instance, it said:
   _``Series E savings bonds issued before December 1965 will stop
earning interest exactly 40 years from their issue dates.
   _``Series E bonds, Series EE bonds and Savings Notes (Freedom
Shares) issued after November 1965 will stop earning interest
exactly 30 years from their issue dates. Outstanding Series H bonds,
issued between 1959 and 1979, also have a 30-year final maturity.
   _``Series HH bonds issued since 1980 will stop earning interest
20 years from their issue dates.''
   In addition to ending bond-holder confusion, the department said
the new formula would reduce its adminstrative costs by reducing
questions from bond owners asking when their bonds will stop earning
interest.
   It said within the next year, as new bonds are printed and
issued, the final maturity will appear on the face of the bonds.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
