<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-89 0153EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Media     07-19 0594</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Media,0614</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tribune Co., E.W. Scripps, McClatchy Report 2nd Qtr. Profit Gains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Higher second quarter profits were reported Tuesday by several
major media companies, with Tribune Co. posting an 18 percent profit
increase over the same period last year, E.W. Scripps Co. reporting
an 8.6 percent gain and McClatchy Newspapers Inc. posting a 31.7
percent rise.
   Chicago-based Tribune Co. reported a profit of $75.3 million, or
95 cents a share, compared with $63.6 million, or 84 cents a share,
in the second quarter of 1988. Revenue during the period rose to
$643.1 million from $613 million.
   E.W. Scripps reported a second-quarter profit of $25.2 million,
or 32 cents a share, on revenue of $320.9 million, compared with
$23.2 million, or 32 cents a share, on revenue of $305.4 million a
year earlier.
   The year-earlier period included a one-time $2.6 million gain
from the Cincinnati-based company's share of the sale of property by
American City Business Journals.
   McClatchy, publisher of the Sacramento Bee, reported net income
of $10 million, or 35 cents a share, in the three months ended June
30 compared with $7.6 million, or 27 cents a share, in second
quarter 1988. Revenue during the period rose to $97.3 million from
$90.2 million.
   Tribune Co., publisher of the Chicago Tribune, New York Daily
News, and several other daily newspapers, credited its results to
partly improved performance by its newspaper publishing and
broadcast divisions. Circulation revenue was unchanged, while retail
advertising revenue increased and newsprint expenses declined.
   The broadcast and entertainment division improved operating
profits by 7 percent, but gains were limited by a $10 million
write-down of broadcast rights, the company said.
   Operating profit dropped nearly 35 percent for newsprint
operations due to a decline in the average selling price of
newsprint and a stronger Canadian dollar.
   For first-half 1989, Tribune Co.'s profits rose to $112.1
million, or $1.44 a share, from $95.8 million, or $1.26 a share, a
year earlier.
   Tribune Co. also owns six independent television stations, five
radio stations and the Chicago Cubs baseball team.
   E.W. Scripps attributed its earnings gain to higher cable and
broadcast results, which helped offset weaker newspaper advertising
and declining comic character licensing revenue. Operating income
was up 12 percent to $18.1 million for broadcasting and more than
doubled to $5.8 million for cable, the company said.
   The company's 80.4 percent-owned Scripps Howard Broadcasting Co.
posted a profit of $7.3 million, or 71 cents a share, on revenue of
79.1 million. That compared with net income of $4.9 million, or 47
cents a share, on revenue of $70.1 million a year earlier.
   E.W. Scripps has 19 daily newspapers and cable systems serving
540,000 subscribers. Through Scripps Broadcasting it operates nine
television stations, five radio stations and cable systems serving
220,000 subscribers.
   For the six months, E.W. Scripps posted a profit of $40.2
million, or 51 cents a share, on revenue of $615.8 million. The
compared with a profit of $34.2 million, or 47 cents a share, on
revenue of $585.5 million in the year-earlier period.
   McClatchy said its performance was helped by improved advertising
linage and circulation at the Bee. Ad revenue rose 7.5 percent and
circulation revenue was up 9.7 percent.
   The company also publishes five other major daily newspapers,
seven community newspapers and a group of senior citizen tabloids,
all in California, Washington and Alaska.
   For the six months, profit rose to $14.8 million, or 52 cents a
share, from $12 million, or 43 cents a share, a year earlier.
Revenue rose to $184.2 million from $173 million.
</TEXT>
