<SECOND>PM-Holly Farms-Tyson,0316</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tyson Closes Tender Offer For Holly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tyson Foods Inc. says that it has been
tendered about 17.5 million shares of Holly Farms Corp. stock under
terms of its $70-a-share tender offer.
   Tyson said Tuesday it had agreed to buy all validly tendered
shares, and that those tendered together with what it already owns
would give it about 97 percent of Holly farms' outstanding shares.
   ``Within 30 days we should complete the merger entirely. From
that point, it's just get out and go to work,'' said Bob Justice, a
spokesman for Tyson of Springdale, Ark.
   The $1.4 billion buyout follows a takeover struggle for Holly
Farms that began last October and pitted Tyson against ConAgra Inc.
of Omaha, Neb.
   Tyson is the nation's largest poultry processor while Holly Farms
is a diversified company heavily involved in fresh fryer sales.
   After the merger, which will give Tyson control of 20 percent of
the domestic poultry market, Tyson plans to sell some $500 million
worth of Holly assets, Justice said.
   Tyson's tender offer expired at 2 p.m. EDT, and Justice said a
preliminary count showed that Tyson received tenders for 17.5
million Holly Farms shares.
   With the Holly stock already held by Tyson, the tendered shares
represented 97 percent of Holly Farms outstanding shares, he said.
   During Tyson's takeover advance, Holly Farms attempted twice to
merge with ConAgra. Holly stockholders voted down such a move in
April, and Tyson's $70-a-share offer ended the second attempt last
month.
   ConAgra's last offer involved a cash and stock swap with an
estimated value of $68 a share to Holly stockholders.
   ``We welcome all Holly Farms people to join with us to continue
production of the highest quality food products available in the
market today,'' Tyson president Don Tyson said in a statement.
</TEXT>
