<HEAD>Rhode Island Firm Offers to Buy Eljer Faucet Maker</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PLANO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eljer Industries Inc., the plumbing products
manufacturer spun off this year from Household International Inc.,
says it has received an unsolicited $211.4 million cash buyout offer
from the building products manufacturer Nortek Inc.
   Eljer Chairman Donald C. Clark said he would recommend against
accepting the bid.
   Eljer said Nortek, which already owns about 8 percent of Eljer's
outstanding stock, said it would pay $32.50 per share for the
company, based in the Dallas suburb of Plano. There are about 7.6
million shares of Eljer stock outstanding, including Nortek's
holding.
   ``It will be reviewed by the board in due course,'' Clark said,
adding, ``I believe that a sale of the company within a few months
after it has been spun off from Household International is clearly
premature.''
   Eljer's announcement of the offer Monday sent its stock up $5.50
a share to $34.12{ in trading on the New York Stock Exchange.
   On Tuesday, Eljer slipped 50 cents a share to $33.62{.
   Eljer, which employs about 4,900 workers, completed its spinoff
from Household Industries in mid-April.
   For the quarter ended April 2, the company reported pro forma
earnings of $1.49 million, or 21 cents per share, on sales of $100.9
million. The company said it expects to earn $1.95 per share for the
full year.
   Eljer is the nation's third-largest marketer of plumbing fixtures
and also manufactures other building products, including heating and
ventilation products for residential and commercial construction,
remodeling and repairs, and do-it-yourself markets.
   Nortek, based in Providence, R.I., is a diversified corporation
involved in manufacturing products for the building, aerospace,
industrial and electrical industries.
