is buying just 30,000 PCs from Olivetti this year for sale in the
United States, the Wall Street Journal reported Monday.
   The announcement was widely expected after AT&amp;T's announcement
last week of a personal computer development agreement with Intel,
which is better known for selling bare chips, not whole computers.
   On Saturday AT&amp;T said it planned to swap its 22.2 percent stake
in Olivetti for an 18.6 percent stake in Olivetti's holding company,
Cie. Industriale Riunite. AT&amp;T is barred from selling that stake for
five years without approval of the holding company.
