<FIRST>r f PM-SantaFeCuts     07-19 0234</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Santa Fe Cuts,0241</SECOND>
<HEAD>Santa Fe Eliminates 450 Jobs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Santa Fe Railway says it is eliminating an
estimated 450 non-union jobs in an effort to make the railroad more
competitive.
   Employees affected range from clerical workers to upper level
management in all 12 states where Santa Fe operates, said spokesman
Robert Gehrt.
   ``Nearly all of these reductions are being achieved through a
voluntary severance and early retirement program, although there
will be a limited number of involuntary separations,'' Michael R.
Haverty, company president, said Tuesday in a news release.
   Santa Fe Railway is a wholly owned subsidiary of Santa Fe Pacific
Corp. It operates approximately 11,500 miles of mainline freight
trackage linking Chicago with 11 other states, mostly in the
Southwest.
   The railroad's total employment stood at 19,633 at the beginning
of the year, and with Tuesday's announced cuts and other actions,
the company said it expects a reduction to less than 18,000 by the
year's end.
   More than half of those cuts have already been made, Gehrt said,
and spokeswoman Susan Metcalf added that some of the remaining jobs
to be eliminated involve normal attrition and retirement.
   ``In order to survive and prosper in today's transportation
environment, it is necessary that we provide high quality service at
competitive prices. We must reduce our ongoing expenses if we are to
accomplish that,'' Haverty said.
</TEXT>
