<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-89 0202EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-CanadianPork     07-19 0279</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Canadian Pork,0288</SECOND>
<HEAD>Commerce Determines Canada Subsidizes Some Pork Exports</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Commerce Department has ruled that imports
of unprocessed fresh, chilled and frozen pork from Canada are being
subsidized by about 3 cents per pound, a ruling that could mean new
duties of the same amount.
   The department's determination, announced Tuesday, now goes to
the International Trade Commission, which has 45 days to decide
whether the imports injure the U.S. pork industry.
   If the commission agrees with the Commerce finding, the
department will order the Bureau of Customs to collect
countervailing duties on the imports to offset the subsidies.
   Canadian pork imports that would be subject to such duties were
about $341 million last year.
   The department's investigation was triggered by a January
complaint from the National Pork Producers Council, the National
Pork Council Women, ConAgra Red Meats Inc., Dakota Pork Industries
Inc., Farmstead Foods, IBP Inc., Illinois Pork Corp., Thorn Apple
Valley and Wilson Foods Inc.
   The department said its investigation did not include processed
or preserved pork products such as canned hams, cured bacon,
sausage, ground pork or live swine. It noted it had found imports of
live swine to be subsidized in a 1985 investigation.
   The Canadian Embassy said it would use the dispute resolution
procedures of the new U.S.-Canadian free trade agreement to press
its view that the department is wrong.
   The Embassy said U.S. law is wrong under international trade
rules to count as a subsidy income-stabilization arrangements
designed to smooth out fluctuations in farmers' incomes. Also, U.S.
law should not automatically assume that any benefits from such
plans are fully passed through to the pork processor, the Embassy
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890719-0242 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-89 0207EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-SemiconductorIndustry Bjt   07-19 0660</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Semiconductor Industry, Bjt,0678</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lower Profits May Be Sign of Semiconductor Industry Downturn</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICH CARTIERE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Intel's Corp. 25 percent drop in its
second-quarter profit was another sign that the semiconductor
industry faces a significant downturn, according to some industry
analysts.
   ``The slowdown is now a reality,'' said Michael Boss, an analyst
with Dataquest Inc. of San Jose. ``We saw the seeds of it in the
first quarter, but it's taking a little longer to play out in terms
of revenue.''
   Boss said his company predicted the downturn last year and
doesn't expect an end until the second quarter of 1990. Many
semiconductor companies will experience negative growth through the
next two quarters, he said.
   Intel on Tuesday reported its second-quarter earnings fell to $99
million, or 53 cents a share, from $130 million, or 73 cents a
share, in the same period last year. Revenue rose 3 percent to $747
million. Intel's stock finished the day down $2.50 at $28.87{.
   The company's report followed an earnings and sales decline
reported by Advanced Micro Devices of Sunnyvale last week and
indications by a key industry economic gauge that orders may be
gradually slowing.
   Second-quarter earnings by AMD fell by more than half while sales
fell 11 percent. Jerry Sanders, AMD's chief executive, predicted
revenues will remain flat for the rest of the year.
   While the industry's ``book-to-bill'' ratio released last week
for the month of June reached an all-time high, the order rate
suggested the industry may slow down gradually later this year. The
ratio measures orders vs. shipments.
   June's 1.6 percent increase in orders was below the average 3.1
percent increase over the past 10 years, according to Thomas
Thornhill, an analyst for Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in San
Francisco.
   Some analysts think the apparent slowdown will be short-lived,
and is likely a strong seasonal drop.
   Analyst Mel Phelps with Hambrecht &amp; Quist in San Francisco said
Intel's earning were partially hurt by a $17 million charge due to a
planned factory shutdown, and without it, earnings per share would
have climbed another 7 cents, he said.
   The company took the charge to cover costs associated with the
1990 planned shutdown of a wafer fabrication plant in Livermore. The
company is attempting to transfer the plant's 400 workers to other
locations.
   Phelps anticipates strong Intel sales through the end of the
year, partially because of the introduction of new microproccessor
products, and total revenues of $3.1 billion, compared with $2.8
billion last year.
   Analyst Michael Stark of Robertson, Stephens &amp; Co. in San
Francisco said Intel's report was the sign of at least a summer
slowdown. He expects it to be short-lived, and for sales to continue
strong growth through the rest of the year, although not by as much
as he would like.
   ``It's raised a flag of caution in some people's minds; We really
don't think it's more .... but it's clearly the full brunt of a
seasonal weakening,'' he said.
   But analyst Rick Whittington of Kidder, Peabody &amp; Co. in New York
said the industry was heading into a ``quasi-recession or even an
absolute recession.''
   Whittington, who has been advising clients to sell Intel stock
for the last six weeks, said Intel's introduction of the new
microproccesors ``strategically makes sense, but they run the risk
in the short term of experiencing a classic downturn and as they
shift gears they could be blasted away with margins really sharply.''
   Intel said new orders received for advanced microprocessors were
strong, continuing a recovery from an inventory correction that
occurred in the fourth quarter of 1988. Second-quarter orders also
were higher than those in the first.
   Dataquest's Boss said that because of the relative strength of
the year's first two quarters, the worldwide and North American
semiconductor markets will end the year with about 15 percent
growth, compared with 34 percent in 1988. Next year should see flat
growth, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
