<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-89 0832EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-SoybeanCorner Bjt   07-19 0476</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soybean Corner, Bjt,0492</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Of Two BOT Deadlines for Soybean Liquidation Passes Quietly</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Chicago Board of Trade's emergency directive
to defuse what may have been a developing corner on the soybean
market apparently achieved its first goal uneventfully.
   Tuesday was the deadline for traders to reduce their holdings of
July contracts to 3 million bushels, and prices closed at the end of
the day showing no signs of shock.
   Prices settled 9\ cents lower to 18 cents higher. The July
contract, which settled at $6.96{ a bushel, and the August delivery
were the only two to close higher.
   A second deadline under the emergency order, believed aimed at a
large soybean position of the Italian agribusiness giant Ferruzzi
Spa, comes Thursday, when traders will have to reduce their July
holdings to no more than 1 million bushels.
   Meanwhile, the Soviet Union and China issued letters suggesting
the emergency order interferes with the free markets used by world
soybean suppliers.
   ``Such an action,'' the Soviet letter said, ``if not very well
economically and legally justified, undermines the basic principle
of commodity futures trading as a hedging mechanism for our sellers
of U.S. grain.''
   In Washington Tuesday, Wendy Gramm, chairman of the Commodity
Futures Trading Commission, said her agency has taken no stand on
the Board of Trade action, but will try to determine if it was
justified.
   Financial analysts, meanwhile, presented their theories about the
mixed price reaction in soybean trading Tuesday.
   ``Supply tightness aside, there are two reasons the closing
prices were interesting,'' said a trader who spoke on the condition
of anonymity.
   ``The first is that the volume in July beans was very thin
because nobody wants to get involved. That might explain the healthy
price climb there.
   ``As for August, Ferruzzi may simply have rolled their July
contracts into the next month,'' he said.
   Ferruzzi, which failed in court last week to block the BOT order,
has denied rumors that it attempted to illegally corner the market.
   Ferruzzi has said it accumulated contracts for delivery of as
much as 24 million bushels of soybeans _ when only about half that
many soybeans actually were available for sellers to honor
commitments _ to meet export business commitments and ensure a
steady flow of product for its processing plants.
   This line of reasoning was disputed by the American grain
merchant Cargill, which issued a statement Tuesday on the issue.
   ``While a major market participant has said that its long July
soybean futures position was to cover its processing and export
commitments,'' it said, ``those commitments could have been covered
easily and at lower cost in cash markets.''
   Cargill also denied rumors that it asked the Board of Trade to
limit the July soybean holdings, and said its own position in that
delivery was ``insignificant.''
</TEXT>
