<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-89 0835EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-SteelImports     07-19 0207</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Steel Imports,0215</SECOND>
<HEAD>Imports Edge Higher In May</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Although steel imports increased to 1.47
million tons in May, up 10 percent from April, they remained well
below the level of a year earlier, according to an industry
association.
   Imports for the first five months of the year were down
dramatically, the American Iron and Steel Institute of Washington,
D.C., said Tuesday.
   Import tonnage for the first five months totaled 7.15 million
tons, down 21 percent from January through May 1988, the institute
said.
   Foreign steel represented 17.1 percent of the market in the first
five months of this year, down from 20.7 percent in the 1988 period.
   The May tonnage represented 17.2 percent of the apparent supply
in the U.S. market, compared with 16.4 percent in April and 21.5
percent in May 1988.
   Excluding 873,000 tons of foreign steel ordered by U.S. producers
for processing on their own mills, the five-month tonnage totaled
less than 6.3 million tons, or 15 percent of apparent consumption,
according to the New York-based American Institute for Imported
Steel.
   The goal of the Voluntary Restraint Agreements in place through
September is to limit imports to 18.5 percent of the market, not
counting semi-finished steel bound for U.S. mills.
</TEXT>
