<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-89 0839EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-EEC-Rolls-Royce     07-19 0255</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EEC-Rolls-Royce,0267</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rolls-Royce to Raise Limit on Foreign Shareholders</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The EEC Commission Wednesday said that
Great Britain will raise its limit on foreign shareholders in
Rolls-Royce PLC to 29.5 percent from 15 percent.
   The move followed talks with the British government, challenged
by the commission over the 15 percent ceiling.
   The new limit will be valid until the end of 1992, a shorter
period than the five years requested by Britain, according to Claus
Ehlermann, a commission spokesman.
   Rolls-Royce, a British aero-engine group, was privatized in 1987.
   The commission challenged the British ceiling earlier this year,
saying that the measure breached European Economic Community rules
which outlaw restrictions on foreign investments except where
national security is at stake.
   The British government argued that it imposed the restrictions
because Rolls-Royce was involved in military production.
   The commission's inquiry into the Rolls-Royce share ceiling was
triggered by West German and Belgian investors who complained they
had been forced to sell Rolls-Royce shares at a loss.
   Separately, a commission official, who asked not to be named,
said that the EEC was still examining a similar 15 percent limit on
foreign share holdings in British Aerospace PLC, a British weapons
and aircraft manufacturer.
   The British government imposed the limit in 1985 when it sold its
remaining shares in British Aerospace. But the government retained a
golden share which makes the company effectively bid proof.
   The spokesman would not say whether a similar arrangement to that
concerning Rolls-Royce would be worked out for British Aerospace.
</TEXT>
