<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-89 1026EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-HousingStarts 1stLd-Writethru f0046 07-19 0446</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Housing Starts, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0046,0457</SECOND>
<HEAD>Housing Starts Rebound in June</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs pvs 10th graf, The overall, to CORRECT that decline was
in some regions sted overall</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN D. McCLAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Housing construction, reflecting lower interest
rates, rebounded 7.0 percent in June after falling for four straight
months and reaching the lowest level in May since 1982, the
government said today.
   Fixed mortgage rates, which peaked at 11.22 percent in March
before falling to 10.07 percent by the end of June, had been blamed
for the recent decline in housing activity.
   The Commerce Department reported that new homes and apartments in
June were built at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 1.40 million
units, up from 1.31 million units in May when construction fell 2.5
percent.
   June's increase was the highest since an 8.6 percent hike to 1.51
million units in February 1988. It reflected a 28.0 percent increase
in apartment construction, the highest since a 43 percent increase
in April 1988.
   May's overall drop had been the fourth consecutive one, adding up
to the longest string of declines since activity slowed for five
months in a row from February through June 1987. The May level was
the slowest pace since the 1.30 million rate in December 1982.
   The housing industry had been among the sectors of the economy
hardest hit as interest rates edged upward over the past year with
the Federal Reserve seeking to restrain economic growth to contain
inflation.
   Analysts said the decline in mortgage rates had come too late to
help the housing industry in May, but thought activity would pick up
as rates continued to fall.
   Construction of single-family homes fell 2.0 percent in June to
an annual rate of 975,000 units, the lowest level since August 1984
when 967,000 units were recorded. They fell 5.1 percent in May and
4.7 percent in April.
   But apartment construction rose last month to an annual rate of
425,000 units. Construction of multi-family units had risen 2.6
percent in May after falling 26.6 percent in April.
   By region, overall housing construction decreased last month by
5.0 percent in the Northeast, where starts fell to a seasonally
adjusted annual rate of 171,000 units.
   The Midwest also recorded a drop, down 3.3 percent to 238,000
units.
   The West, on the other hand, posted a huge 21.4 percent increase
to 443,000 units. Starts in the South were up 5.8 percent to 548,000
units.
   Applications for building permits, a barometer of future housing
activity, were down 3.5 percent, however, following a 1.0 percent
increase in May and an 8.5 percent hike in April. They had fallen
the three previous months.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
