<FIRST>u f PM-Eastern 1stLd-Writethru f0055 07-19 0619</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0055,0638</SECOND>
<HEAD>Company Seeks More Money, May Have Lesser Schedule</HEAD>
<HEAD>SUBS grafs 5 and 6 with 3 grafs to UPDATE with pilots union denying
negotiations stalled; picks up 7th graf pvs, ``But while ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Assoicated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines will have to wait another day
before a federal bankruptcy judge rules on its request to release
$100 million from the company's creditors to finance a planned
August expansion.
   U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Burton Lifland in New York adjourned until
Thursday to give the company more time to negotiate with its
creditors' committee, which asked the judge Tuesday to give Eastern
only $40 million to ease its cash crunch.
   Eastern, which filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy reorganization
five days after it was hit March 4 with a massive strike, has told
its creditors it needs the entire $100 million, and half of it
immediately.
   Meanwhile, Eastern Chairman Frank Lorenzo and President Phil
Bakes scheduled a news conference in Atlanta today. No details were
released late Tuesday.
   Pilots union spokesman Hank Weber said negotiations were
continuing with the company.
   ``They're still negotiating,'' Weber said, denying published
reports that the two sides were at an impasse. ``I don't know who's
throwing out this stuff.''
   Company spokesman Robin Matell said he couldn't comment on
negotiations.
   But while Eastern proposed to guarantee 2,300 pilot jobs, up from
an original guarantee of 1,700, the union sought guarantees for
2,400. The union also would not agree to work-rule and other
concessions in the amount sought by Eastern, the newspaper reported
today.
   Eastern claims it can rebuild without the unions into a smaller,
efficient carrier. It more than doubled its daily schedule to 220
flights this month, and had promised to fly 390 by Aug. 1.
   However, the request for release of funds by the creditors stated
Eastern plans to fly 330 flights daily in August. Company officials
said the figure used by their attorneys in New York was inaccurate,
but they also acknowledged some cancellations may be necessary.
   A company spokeswoman said Tuesday that Eastern will announce by
early next week which, if any, flights will be canceled.
   Documents obtained by the pilots union and information from
travel agents indicated Eastern's major problems are in Atlanta, the
focus of its rebuilding plan.
   Eastern is no longer selling tickets on nearly 50 flight legs in
and out of Atlanta, including to Cleveland, Ohio, and between
several smaller cities in Alabama and Florida and other southern
points.
   ``There are some flights proposed that they can't meet the
schedule,'' said Sal DePace, co-owner of Golden Jet Travel Inc. in
Atlanta. ``I don't know whether it's because of pilots, because of
airplanes or why.''
   DePace, chairman of the National Association of Retail Travel
Agents, said he talked to Eastern management officials on Tuesday
and was told there would be a temporary reduction in flights to some
smaller cities.
   ``It's not going to be a permanent situation as I understand
it,'' he said.
   Eastern spokeswoman Karen Ceremsak said no flights have been
canceled, but Eastern is trying ``to minimize passenger
inconvenience, so we are not taking new bookings.''
   ``You have to look at where you're going to impact the most
customers, and how your crew capability and planes match up,'' Ms.
Ceremsak said.
   ``In virtually all the markets involved there are other Eastern
flights,'' she said. Eastern will announce any cancellations within
a week, so that passengers will have plenty of time to adjust, she
said.
   Fewer than 300 of Eastern's 3,800 union pilots have come back to
work since the March 4 walkout by the Machinists, pilots and flight
attendants crippled the carrier that had been flying nearly 1,100
flights daily.
</TEXT>
