<FIRST>r f BC-Resort-Japanese     07-19 0485</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Resort-Japanese,0502</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japanese Firm Buys Dana Point Resort</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DANA POINT, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan's largest maker of kimonos has
purchased the 350-room Dana Point Resort hotel for more than $100
million, one of the largest real estate deals in Southern California
this year.
   Japanese garment giant Masuiwaya bought the hotel overlooking the
ocean from Edward and Thomas Slatkin of the Edward Thomas Companies.
   The Slatkins had bought the hotel and resort, which occupies 11.6
acres, for a reported $65 million from the Southmark Pacific Corp.
of Pasadena 17 months ago.
   Analysts said Masuiwaya, which also owns the Colonial Inn in La
Jolla and the Cliffs in Northern California, may be getting in on
the start of a booming resort area.
   Edward Thomas Companies said the sale to Masuiwaya's investment
arm, Tokyo Masuiwaya California Corp., was completed Tuesday. The
new owner retained the hotel's current management, the Slatkin
brothers told the Los Angeles Times.
   Edward Thomas Companies was represented by Goldman Sachs and Co.,
while Tokyo Masuiwaya California Corp. was represented by Yasuda
Trust and Banking Co.
   Despite the huge appreciation that the Dana Point Resort sale
represents, the price was not out of line for a coastal resort,
industry analysts said.
   ``If you look at recent hotel sales in Southern California, like
La Costa Resort in San Diego County that sold for $250 million and
Hotel Bel Air for $110 million, it is in keeping with what is
happening,'' said Jim Burba, a partner in the Costa Mesa office of
Pannell Kerr Forster, an accounting firm.
   ``Prime hotel property in Southern California is selling at very
high prices in comparison to other parts of the U.S. because this is
perceived to be a strong economy and a strong market,'' Burba said.
   Masuiwaya's purchase appeared tied to Orange County's promise as
a future resort center, said Richard N. Kipper, a partner at
Laventhal &amp; Horwath in Costa Mesa.
   ``The Japanese have to be aware of the plans for several major
high-end resorts on the Orange County coast and are interested in
coming in at the start of the creation of a prime resort
environment,'' Kipper said.
   Local authorities have approved plans to build nine hotels along
the coast between Corona del Mar and Laguna Beach, in Huntington
Beach and in Dana Point.
   Harry Hartnett, a consultant with Kenneth Leventhal &amp; Co. in
Newport Beach, said the deal is a continuation of the Japanese
pattern of acquiring so-called ``trophy'' hotel properties that have
a high visibility and prestige.
   ``They did it first in Hawaii, and now that they have bought most
of the major hotels there, they are turning to California,'' he said.
   In recent years, Japanese investors have acquired the Hotel Bel
Air in Beverly Hills, La Costa Resort Hotel and Spa in Carlsbad and
the Westin chain, which includes the Westin South Coast Plaza in
Costa Mesa and the Westin Bonaventure in Los Angeles.
</TEXT>
