<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 11am, CORRECTION,0272</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Fixes typo in June CPI 5th graf</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market rallied sharply today, inspired
by better-than-expected news on inflation.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials climbed 30.53 to 2,575.11
by 11 a.m. today on Wall Street.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by nearly 3 to 1 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 960 up, 327 down and
500 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 73.30 million shares at
midmorning.
   The Labor Deartment reported this morning that the consumer price
index rose 0.2 percent in June, down from 0.6 percent the month
before.
   The consensus estimate on Wall Street had called for a 0.3
percent June increase.
   Though the latest figure came as no dramatic surprise, analysts
said, it bolstered hopes that the Federal Reserve might soon relax
its credit policy further.
   The news helped push interest rates lower in the government
securities market today. Prices of long-term Treasury bonds, which
move in the opposite direction from interest rates, rose more than
$5 for each $1,000 in face value, putting their yields in the 8.14
percent-8.16 percent range.
   Gainers among the blue chips included General Electric, up 1~ at
56[; American Telephone &amp; Telegraph, up { at 37; Exxon, up ~ at 46[;
McDonald's, up ~ at 31, and International Business Machines, up { at
115\.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
1.90 to 186.81. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up 2.13 at 372.30.
