<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-89 1147EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s f BC-Disney-Eisner Adv23   07-19 0258</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Disney-Eisner, Adv 23,0266</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv23</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Sunday July 23 and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>CEO Uneasy in `Uncle Walt' Role on TV Show</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Disney</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BURBANK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Eisner, the executive who hosts
``The Magical World of Disney'' on Sunday night television, says
he's uneasy in his ``Uncle Walt'' role.
   Eisner, who began giving homey introductions to the family
anthology show after he was named chairman and chief executive
officer of The Walt Disney Co., said in an interview it was strictly
a business move.
   ``I'm not wild about the notoriety or the public acceptance or
all that stuff,'' Eisner said. ``But we decided early on that we had
to be a company with a rudder.''
   Eisner, 47, was referring to a management team, including
president and chief operating officer Frank Wells, that was credited
with revitalizing the company after a takeover battle in 1984.
   Part of the magic of the old Disney shows, they felt, was the
introduction by Walt Disney before his death Dec. 15, 1966.
   ``I figured that I had to do it irrespective of my own desires
for privacy _ and my wife's demanding of it _ because I thought it
was part of the job,'' Eisner said.
   Viewers seem to like the spots, but it's a different story with
Eisner's wife, Jane, and children, Michael, Eric and Anders.
   ``I think I'm pretty poor,'' Eisner said. ``I think it's worse
than it is _ though my children will confirm it's as bad as I think
it is.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv for Sunday July 23</NOTE>
