<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-89 1157EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   07-19 0398</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0412</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Rise On Rumored Soviet Demand</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices were higher in
early trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade amid talk that the
Soviet Union was in the market for corn and soybeans.
   The rally in the corn market reflected a rise in cash prices,
which began climbing late Tuesday afternoon on rumors the Soviets
were pricing U.S. corn, analysts said.
   ``The chances are pretty good that something has been done or at
least inquired on,'' said William Biedermann, a vice president and
director of research for Allendale Inc., a futures brokerage in
Crystal Lake, Ill.
   Talk of a Soviet deal for as much as 200,000 metric tons of South
American soybean meal gave the soybean market a boost.
   The price for July delivery of soybeans whipsawed in early
trading as players tried to squeeze a little more profit out of the
contract before it expires on Thursday. The July soybean contract
has been extremely volatile in the past week, following a Board of
Trade order requiring traders to reduce their positions in that
contract.
   ``It's a no-man's land,'' said one trader, who noted that with
few players in the July contract, its price is subject to sharp
swings.
   Wheat futures were a little higher on perceptions of dry-weather
damage to the spring wheat crop.
   In early trading, wheat was 1{ cents to 4\ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.91 a bushel; corn was 1 cent to
4} cents higher with July at $2.53 a bushel; oats were 3 cents to 5\
cents higher with July at $1.47 a bushel; soybeans were 6{ cents to
52{ cents higher with July at $7.48 a bushel and the more heavily
traded August contract at $6.96 a bushel.
   Cattle futures were mostly lower while pork futures were mostly
higher in early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .33 cent lower to .02 cent higher with August at
72.47 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .15 cent to .30 cent lower
with August at 83.40 cents a pound; live hogs were .02 cent to .52
cent higher with July at 47.90 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were .05 cent lower to .50 cent higher with July at 28.77 cents a
pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled lower on Tuesday.
</TEXT>
