<FIRST>r f PM-Nissan-Millionth     07-19 0405</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nissan-Millionth,0420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Company President Won't Predict Union Vote Outcome</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CONNIE CASS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SMYRNA, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nissan Motor Manufacturing USA rolled its
1-millionth vehicle off the assembly line this morning in a
celebration of company unity one week before a union vote to
organize the plant.
   Jerry Benefield, president and chief executive officer of
Nissan's only U.S. factory, declined to predict the outcome of next
week's United Auto Workers organizing vote.
   ``I think our employees will speak for themselves,'' said
Benefield, who wore work clothes in the tradition of managers at the
Japanese auto company. ``It's between the union and our employees.''
   Benefield wore a T-shirt that read, ``1 Team Makes a Million,''
and many in the crowd of employees, managers and Nissan dealers had
buttons that read, ``Keep 1 Team.''
   Benefield drove the milestone white pickup truck off the assembly
line to applause and cheers from the crowd of about 100. No
pro-union activity was visible in or around the plant.
   A white pickup named Job 1 was the first vehicle produced at the
plant when it opened June 16, 1983.
   Nissan has a total of 3,200 employees working two shifts, and an
annual payroll of more than $100 million.
   Initially the plant only built light pickup trucks but added
Sentra passenger cars in March 1985. As of June 30, Nissan had
produced 601,083 trucks and 396,729 Sentras in Smyrna, which lies
about 30 miles southeast of Nashville.
   The company is preparing to add a third vehicle line in 1992,
bringing its total production capacity to 440,000 vehicles per year
and making it the highest volume facility under one roof in the
United States, according to Nissan.
   The factory is one of three nonunion U.S. plants owned by
Japanese automakers.
   Long a target of the United Auto Workers, the 2,400 hourly
workers at Nissan will vote Wednesday and Thursday on union
representation. The UAW has concentrated on worker injuries and
assembly line speeds as major campaign issues.
   It was the non-union environment of Tennessee that contributed to
Nissan's decision to build its highly sought plant here, and Nissan
officials maintain the lack of a union continues to help production
and employment expand.
   ``As we begin the production of our second million vehicles, we
will continue to make it a priority for our company to contribute to
the quality of life in the Middle Tennessee area,'' Benefield said
before today's ceremony.
</TEXT>
