<TEXT>
   The stock market ran up a broad gain today,
inspired by better-than-expected news on inflation.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials climbed 25.98 to 2,570.56
by noontime today on Wall Street.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by more than 2 to 1 in nationwide
trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 928 up, 480
down and 525 unchanged.
   The Labor Department reported this morning that the consumer
price index rose 0.2 percent in June, down from 0.6 percent the
month before.
   The consensus estimate on Wall Street had called for a 0.3
percent June increase.
   Though the latest figure came as no dramatic surprise, analysts
said, it bolstered hopes that the Federal Reserve might soon relax
its credit policy further.
   The news helped push interest rates lower in the government
securities market today. Prices of long-term Treasury bonds, which
move in the opposite direction from interest rates, rose about $5
for each $1,000 in face value, putting their yields in the 8.15
percent-8.17 percent range.
   Gainers among the blue chips included General Electric, up 1| at
55~; American Telephone &amp; Telegraph, up \ at 36}; Exxon, up } at 46;
McDonald's, up } at 30~, and International Business Machines, up \
at 115.
   Tandem Computers gained 1[ to 19. The company reported per-share
earnings for its latest fiscal quarter of 31 cents, compared to 18
cents in the comparable period a year earlier.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
1.62 to 186.53. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up 1.77 at 371.94.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 104.63 million shares at
noontime, up from 76.39 million at the same point Tuesday.
