<FIRST>u f PM-AviationBills 2ndLd-Writethru f0082 07-19 0569</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Aviation Bills, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0082,0584</SECOND>
<HEAD>Smoking Opponents to Push for Ban on all Airline Flights</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 10th graf, A ban, to CORRECT that DeFazio from Oregon,
not California.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congressional smoking opponents, seeking a ban
on smoking aboard all U.S. airliners, will ask a House panel to
overrule a subcommittee vote keeping only the current ban for
flights under two hours.
   In a series of parliamentary moves aimed at heading off a total
ban, pro-smoking forces won their first victory in the House Public
Works and Transportation aviation subcommittee on Tuesday.
   ``They're probably all out there puffing happily right now,''
said Rep. James Oberstar, subcommittee chairman.
   The subcommittee voted 17-18 against a move to extend the
temporary ban on two-hour flights to cover permanently all flights
up to four hours. Oberstar's bill proposing a total ban was amended
to extend the ban on two-hour flights from April 23, 1990, to April
23, 1992.
   Oberstar, D-Minn., said heavy lobbying by tobacco interests
helped defeat the total ban in the subcommittee.
   The subcommittee also approved two other measures affecting
aviation: a limit on the liability of small plane manufacturers and
a delay in implementing a rule requiring collision avoidance systems
on large airliners.
   The liability and collision measures are to be taken up by the
full committee on Thursday, Oberstar said. The smoking bill also was
scheduled for Thursday but committee spokesman David Smallen said
today Oberstar decided to postpone it for a later meeting.
   The smoking vote was on the first of several measures pending in
Congress that would limit or ban smoking on airliners.
   Other bills and amendments in House committees would make the ban
on flights of under two hours permanent, phase in a ban affecting
flights of up to four hours, or extend the two-hour ban to all
flights with 15-minute-per-hour smoking intervals after the first
two hours.
   A ban on flights under four hours, proposed by Rep. Peter
DeFazio, D-Ore., would have applied to nearly all flights except
those that go nonstop coast-to-coast.
   DeFazio said this would accommodate smokers and give nonsmokers
the option of making one connecting flight on a cross-country trip
to stay on no-smoking flights. Under the present law, it would take
five flights to make a smoke-free flight from San Francisco to New
York, DeFazio said, with stopovers in Salt Lake City, Denver, Omaha
and Chicago.
   He said smokers could get prescriptions for nicotine-laced gum if
they felt a four-hour flight was too long to go without smoking.
   ``Then they could put nicotine into their systems without putting
it into everyone else's,'' DeFazio said.
   The bill changing the requirement for computerized devices that
alert pilots to nearby aircraft would let the Federal Aviation
Administration extend a Dec. 30, 1991, deadline for installation of
the $100,000 units.
   Airlines say they need more time to install the units and to test
the system to see how it works when several airliners are equipped
with them.
   The collision avoidance system includes a screen in the cockpit
which shows the pilot planes in his vicinity and, if necessary,
audibly instructs the pilot to climb or descend to avoid a collision.
   The liability act would decrease risks to manufacturers but would
not cap liability claims. Proponents said that despite increases in
general aviation safety, insurance to cover aircraft accidents has
skyrocketed, forcing manufacturers out of business.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
