<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-89 1350EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s f BC-Spain-BigBang Adv23   07-19 0938</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Spain-Big Bang, Adv 23,0967</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv23</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Sunday July 23 and thereafter</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Spanish Markets Gear Up for ``El Big Bang'' ^By FRANCISCO CONDE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Brokerage houses, banks and investors in
Spain are readying themselves for July 29 and ``El Big Bang'' _ the
most sweeping changes in the country's four stock exchanges since
the first was founded in 1831.
   ``Without a doubt, the reform represents a revolution,'' said
Frederik Artesani, 29-year-old head of research at Lombardia y
Lacaci, one of Spain's leading brokerages.
   ``It is the definitive step to bring Spanish financial markets
and practices completely in line with those in the international
financial system.''
   Luis Carlos Crossier, head of the new National Securities
Commission, says he is convinced Spain's Big Bang will be as
important as the one in London that deregulated British financial
markets in October 1986.
   ``Defending the rights of investors is one of the principal goals
of the June 1988 bourse reform law,'' said Crossier, whose agency
will police the markets, like the Securities and Exchange Commission
does in the United States. ``And if we don't achieve this it will
mean the total failure of the reform.''
   The economic boom that followed Spain's January 1986 entry into
the European Economic Community has spurred Socialist Prime Minister
Felipe Gonzalez to modernize its markets with sophisticated
computers and greatly increased competition.
   The key result of El Big Bang, as it has come to be known, will
be the end of the so-called Latin model exchange, in which
government-appointed brokers monopolize trading and supervise
themselves.
   ``On July 29, we go to the Anglo-Saxon model: the civil servant
brokers disappear and the four stock exchanges _ Madrid, Barcelona,
Bilbao and Valencia _ become interconnected private corporations
owned by member brokerages or dealer companies,'' said Madrid Stock
Exchange spokesman Jaime Sanz.
   The Madrid stock exchange accounts for nearly 70 percent of all
trading done in Spain.
   Stock exchanges in Paris, Milan, Athens and Lisbon are still run
along the lines of the Latin model, which dates to the Napoleonic
era in the early 19th century.
   On July 29, at least 20 percent of the more than 350 companies
now listed in Spain will be quoted on the new Computer Automated
Trading System (CATS) linking the four exchanges. The Toronto Stock
Exchange, a pioneer in the use of automated securities trading, was
the developer of CATS.
   The four Spanish exchanges, once a cacaphonous din of yelling
buyers and sellers, will gradually be phased into the new system,
where the market price of stocks will be determined by people
communicating via computer terminals.
   In anticipation of the big day, most Spanish brokers already have
established their own firms, either alone or in conjunction with big
Spanish banks or foreign banks and brokerage houses.
   The fixed 0.25 percent-per-share commissions earned by current
brokers will also give way to full commission competition among the
48 brokerage firms and the 50 broker-dealers who so far have
registered under the new law.
   The Big Bang reform and the stampede of brokerages and banks to
the market have incited a bidding war for the best people in the
business.
   Brokerage and banking firms are raiding each other, in some cases
shattering long-established trading and management teams.
   Industry sources say a few of the top Spanish professionals have
been lured away by yearly salaries of up to 40 million pesetas or
about $341,000. Three years ago the rate was 5 million pesetas.
   Monica Morales, managing director of Ibercorp, a private bank and
brokerage firm, says ``offers going around are ludicrous.
   ``One brokerage lost 11 people in one day. We've lost one
analyst, one person in corporate finance and two fund managers.''
   Concern has intensified in the industry that competition will
become even more brutal after July 29.
   ``There are too many participants, and I don't think there will
be enough market to go around,'' Morales said.
   ``The market reform is totally necessary and inevitable, but I'm
not terribly happy about it. The problem is that there are so many
things to do in such a short time and many things left hanging.''
   Croissier acknowledges the government has carried out the reform
at a breakneck pace to prepare Spain for further financial reforms
in Europe that will help shape the European Community's single
market restructuring in 1992.
   But he said the reforms will not be completed for another year.
Still to be established is a new code of conduct aimed at banning
insider trading for the first time and creating a new transaction
settlement system to speed up the current archaic one, which takes
weeks.
   The reform replaces a 1967 law and subsequent decrees by the
authoritarian government of Gen. Francisco Franco. His death in 1975
cleared the way for the restoration of a democratic government two
years later.
   ``The old bourse code is quite outdated, and it has been
overwhelmed by the boom in stock market investment and new practices
and methods,'' Croissier said.
   Between 1985 and 1988, the value of securities traded on the
Madrid Stock Exchange nearly tripled, rocketing from 6.3 trillion
pesetas or $52.8 billion to 18 trillion pesetas.
   Spain's booming economy, averaging a 4.5 percent growth rate over
the past three years, has drawn foreign money like a magnet. Direct
foreign investment in Spain went from $1 billion in 1983 to $4
billion last year.
   The Madrid Stock Exchange index ended 1986 with a whopping 53.4
percent increase. In 1987, despite the global stock market crash in
October, the index rose 9.1 percent. Last year it rose 20 percent.
   End adv for Sunday July 23
</TEXT>
</DOC>
