<DOCNO> AP890719-0269 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-89 1353EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Sweden-InsiderTrial     07-19 0365</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Sweden-Insider Trial,0378</SECOND>
<HEAD>Immigrant Tycoon Sentenced to Five Years for Fraud</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Refaat El-Sayed, an immigrant who became
a business tycoon and national hero, was convicted of fraud and
insider trading Wednesday and sentenced to five years in prison.
   El-Sayed, 43, was convicted on 14 counts of swindling investers,
perjury, insider trading and fraud in the biggest white-collar case
brought to a Swedish court.
   The Stockholm District Court also sentenced Gaston Portofaix, the
finance manager of El-Sayed's former company Fermenta AB, to one
year in jail. Portofaix said he would appeal the verdict.
   An immigrant who came from Egypt in 1964, El-Sayed parlayed his
1981 purchase of the failing biotechnical company Fermenta into a
financial empire based on pharmaceuticals.
   Charm and informality in the normally tight-laced Swedish
business world won him public attention. The popular press was
enamored with his tie-less style and his weekend soccer-playing in
the fifth league, as his personal fortune grew to become Sweden's
largest.
   In 1985, El-Sayed's wealth in Fermenta stock alone was estimated
at $1 billion kronor, or about $156 million.
   His business acumen also was admired by a nation emerging from
recession into prosperity. Swedish television voted him Man of the
Year in 1985.
   His success began to unravel the following year when it was
discovered that his claim to have a doctorate degree was phony. The
disclosure led to a closer look at the company's transactions, and
El-Sayed was found to have put misleading information in annual
reports to improve the company's profits.
   He also was charged with selling off Fermenta shares before the
release of a negative report.
   El-Sayed declared bankruptcy in 1987 when Fermenta's shares
became worthless and he was ousted from the company's management.
   The court ruled that El-Sayed had grossly misused his position
and the ``special trust'' as head of Fermenta to mislead the stock
market.
   It said there were no extenuating circumstances, and ruled that
El-Sayed was forbidden from heading a company in Sweden for a
five-year period.
   El-Sayed has been held in jail since May 25, when the court ruled
he might try to flee the country if freed. Swedish prison boards
routinely remit half the sentence.
</TEXT>
