<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-89 1422EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-ComputerExports 1stLd-Writethru   07-19 0464</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Computer Exports, 1st Ld-Writethru,f0030,0481</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cheney Opposes Easing Export Restrictions on Computers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 11 grafs new with Cheney comments; picks up 4th graf pvs,
Eliminating export ... Also moving on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Dick Cheney said today he
disagrees with a Bush administration proposal to lift restrictions
on exporting personal computers to Soviet bloc nations.
   ``I do not support that decision,'' Cheney told reporters.
   ``My concern is that it will give them a computer capability that
has military applications. That should be avoided,'' the secretary
said.
   ``It gives them significant capabilities they do not now
possess,'' he said.
   Cheney termed inaccurate a Washington Post report that he had
been persuaded to withdraw Pentagon objections to the proposal
during a meeting with Commerce Secretary Robert Mosbacher.
   The decision reportedly came after a fierce debate among the top
members of President Bush's Cabinet.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater, told of Cheney's remarks,
noted that Bush supports the decision on the computers.
   The Commerce Department announced Tuesday that it was removing
export controls on AT-compatible and similar desk-top personal
computers to non-communist nations.
   It said the administration will also propose to the 17-nation
Coordinating Committee on Multilateral Export Controls (COCOM) that
export restrictions be lifted against the Soviet bloc nations.
   Cheney said he would prefer that exports be permitted for ``a
lower level of technology.''
   Mosbacher, in a statement released Tuesday, said Bush's trip to
Poland and Hungary had ``paved the way for expanding trade in areas
that improve prospects for prosperity in Eastern Europe without
harming America's national security.''
   ``Eliminating export controls on AT-compatible personal computers
is one way to meet this objective,'' he said. ``Consistent with the
spirit of the president's initiatives, we are creating new
opportunities for U.S. manufacturers to sell more widely abroad.''
   The AT is an IBM model that was widely emulated.
   The department said regulations removing the controls on exports
to Western nations will appear in the Federal Register on July 18
and be effective immediately.
   The COCOM committee, based in Paris, consists of Australia,
Belgium, Britain, Canada, Denmark, France, West Germany, Greece,
Italy, Japan, Luxembourg, Netherlands, Norway, Portugal, Spain,
Turkey and the United States.
   ``The net result of this decontrol is to focus and maintain
export restrictions on those items that are truly strategic, and
that we can control effectively,'' Mosbacher said.
   ``In this case, these computers are available in 11 countries and
from 70 vendors outside COCOM countries,'' he added. Those countries
include Hungary and Czechoslovakia in the East Bloc.
   The department said there were about 6 million AT-compatible desk
top personal computers sold worldwide by U.S. companies in 1988. Of
those, 2.7 million worth more than $1 billion were sold outside the
United States.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
