<FIRST>r f BC-RalstonSale     07-19 0147</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Ralston Sale,0153</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ralston Selling Bremner Cookie Company</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ralston Purina Co. has agreed to sell its
Bremner Inc. subsidiary, which makes cookies and crackers, to
Beatrice Foods Inc. of Canada.
   Terms of the agreement announced last week were not disclosed,
and the parties still must negotiate a definitive agreement. Ralston
expects to close the deal before Sept. 30, the end of its fiscal
year, company spokesman Patrick T. Farrell said.
   Beatrice Foods of Canada is a cookie company based in Toronto and
is owned by the Canadian holding company, Onyx Corp.
   Bremner, based in Louisville, Ky., makes 19 varieties of cookies
and crackers. Many Bremner products sell under store labels or under
a Ralston label, Farrell said. Under the agreement, Bremner no
longer would be able to use the Ralston name.
   Bremner has 450 employees. Ralston bought the company in December
1977.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890719-0274 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-89 1454EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-EEC-Airlines     07-19 0284</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EEC-Airlines,0294</SECOND>
<HEAD>EEC Commission Proposes More Flexibility In Airline Fares</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The European Commission proposed
Wednesday to give European airlines more flexibility in setting
fares, but stopped well short of complete deregulation.
   European Commissioner for Competition Sir Leon Brittan said that
the proposals would ``remove obstacles to competition'' and should
thus lead to lower prices for consumers.
   EEC Transportation Commissioner Karel Van Miert said the package
was meant to strike a balance between price liberalization on the
one hand and maintaining high standards of safety and security on
the other.
   Brittan said the package also sought to avoid the U.S. experience
in deregulation, in which ``big airlines gobbled up smaller ones''
after price controls were lifted, through rules against predatory
pricing.
   Under the proposals, airlines flying between two EEC countries
could cut prices by up to 20 percent from the previous season if one
of the governments on the route approves. A price cut of more than
20 percent would trigger an anti-dumping procedure by the Commission.
   Moreover, price cuts of less than 20 percent could be challenged
by other airlines flying the route, or by the other government. The
cheaper fare would then be suspended for up to two months, while the
Commission investigates the charge, Van Miert said.
   The proposals will be sent to the EEC Council of Ministers for
consideration by national governments. Van Wiert and Brittan said
they hope the package can be adopted as EEC law and become effective
in July 1990.
   Under the current system, airlines must have the approval of both
governments on a route to cut prices, giving an effective veto on
fare reductions to governments seeking to protect a national airline.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
