<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-89 1553EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Media     07-19 0741</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Media,0767</SECOND>
<HEAD>Profit Up at McGraw-Hill, LIN, ATC; Down at Media General</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   McGraw-Hill Inc., the publishing and information services
concern, said Wednesday its second-quarter earnings rose 13.3
percent, while another communications concern, Media General Inc.
said its profit fell 62.3 percent.
   LIN Broadcasting Corp., meanwhile, posted a 23.2 percent profit
increase for the second quarter while cable television operator
American Television &amp; Communications Corp. said its profit rose 12
percent.
   New York-based McGraw-Hill said it earned $50.8 million, or $1.04
a share, in the three months ended June 30 compared with $44.8
million, or 92 cents a share, a year earlier. Second-quarter revenue
rose 8.6 percent to $482.2 million from $443.7 million.
   The company said its publishing, information services and
financial services operations each had higher revenue in the quarter.
   But income from operations fell to $77.0 million from $147.9
million a year ago, largely because last year's second-quarter
results included a $222 million gain on the sale of McGraw-Hill's
interest in a magazine operation in Japan.
   Operating profit rose 16.6 percent in the information services
company, dipped slightly in the publishing division that includes
books and Business Week magazine and fell 8.5 percent in financial
services, which includes the Standard &amp; Poor's credit rating service.
   For the first six months, McGraw-Hill earned $81.9 million, or
$1.68 a share, up from $71.8 million, or $1.48 a share, a year ago.
Six-month revenue rose to $898.3 million from $839.4 million a year
ago.
   Media General, based in Richmond, Va., said it earned $6.1
million, or 23 cents per share, in the April-June period compared
with $16.2 million, or 56 cents a share, a year earlier. Revenue
fell to $149.9 million from $196.6 milion a year ago.
   The company said the decline reflects heavy newsprint
discounting, a weak newspaper economy and last year's exchange of
its Pomona, Calif., newsprint mill and cash paid for Media General
Class A stock to settle a takeover attempt.
   It said revenue from its newspaper segment was flat while revenue
from broadcasting and newsprint operations fell sharply, largely
because of the absence of revenue from its broadcast services unit
sold last December and the from the Pomona mill.
   For the first half of the year, Media General said its earnings
fell 35.4 percent to $17.9 million, or 69 cents per share, from
$27.7 million, or 96 cents a share, a year earlier. Six-month
revenue fell to $299.2 million from $382.6 million.
   Media General owns four daily newspapers in Richmond,
Winston-Salem, N.C., and Tampa, Fla.; 31 weekly newspapers;
television stations in Charleston, S.C., Jacksonville, Fla., and
Tampa; and two cable TV franchises in Virginia.
   LIN Broadcasting, a New York-based company that is the target of
a multibillion-dollar takeover bid from McCaw Cellular
Communications Inc., said it earned $27.6 million, or 52 cents a
share, in the second quarter, up from $22.4 million, or 42 cents a
share, a year earlier.
   Revenue for the quarter rose to $66.2 million from $59.8 million.
   LIN said its latest results reflect pretax legal and financial
advisory costs of $3.4 million related to the McCaw offer. The
companies have said they are continuing talks although LIN
previously rejected a $120-a-share offer.
   For the first six months, LIN earned $47.8 million, or 90 cents
per share, up 34.3 percent from $35.6 million, or 66 cents per
share, a year earlier.
   Six-month revenue rose to $119 million from $108 million a year
earlier.
   LIN has interests in cellular telephone communications systems,
operates seven television stations and publishes city guides for use
in hotels.
   American Television, a Stamford, Conn.-based cable operator that
is 82 percent owned by Time Inc., said it earned $23.2 million, or
21 cents per share, in the three months ended June 30 compared with
$20.7 million, or 19 cents per share, a year earlier.
   Revenue rose to $240.1 million for the quarter from $201.0
million a year ago.
   American Television said the results reflected a strong operating
performance as well as consolidation of its now wholly-owned cable
system in Memphis.
   For the first six months, ATC earned $43 million, or 39 cents per
share, up 12.3 percent from $38.3 million, or 35 cents a share, a
year earlier.
   First-half revenue rose to $472.8 million from $394.6 million a
year earlier.
   ATC owns or manages cable TV systems serving 4.1 million basic
cable customers, second only to the Telecommunications Inc. of
Denver with nearly 10 million basic cable customers.
</TEXT>
