<HEAD>Dun &amp; Bradstreet Posts 29 Percent Profit Gain In Second Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dun &amp; Bradstreet Corp., the information services
giant that produces the Nielsen television audience ratings, Moody's
credit ratings and a host of other business reports, said Wednesday
its profit rose 29.2 percent in the second quarter despite a slight
dip in revenue.
   Dun &amp; Bradstreet said it earned $150.4 million, or 80 cents per
share, for the three months ended June 30 compared with $116.4
million, or 62 cents a share, a year earlier.
   Second-quarter revenue slipped 0.2 percent to $1.058 billion from
$1.059 billion in 1988.
   Results for 1988 included $14.3 million in costs associated with
the company's May 1988 acquisition of the market research concern
IMS International.
   Dun &amp; Bradstreet said the decline in revenue partly reflected the
absence of results from Official Airline Guides, sold late last year
to publisher Robert Maxwell.
   In addition to the Nielsen TV ratings and Moody's Investors
Service credit rating, Dun &amp; Bradstreet offers Donnelly yellow pages
and marketing operations and the McCormack &amp; Dodge business reports.
   The company said its results were not affected by its
previously-disclosed settlement, subject to court approval, of
lawsuits involving allegations of overcharges for credit reports.
The settlement called for creation of an $18 million fund for
possible reimbursements to customers. It said the company had
previously provided for these costs.
   For the first six months, Dun &amp; Bradstreet said its earnings rose
21.8 percent to a record $293.7 million, or $1.57 a share, from
$241.1 million, or $1.29 a share, a year earlier.
   First-half revenue rose 2.4 percent to $2.12 billion from $2.07
billion a year earlier.
