<FIRST>r f AM-Earns-Honeywell     07-19 0350</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Honeywell,0361</SECOND>
<HEAD>Honeywell's Profit More Than Doubles in Second Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Honeywell Inc. said Wednesday its profit more
than doubled in the second quarter from a year earlier.
   The defense contractor and building controls maker reported that
its second-quarter profit jumped to $74.8 million, or $1.73 a share,
from $31.6 million, or 75 cents a share, in the second quarter of
1988.
   Honeywell lost $435 million in 1988 and announced last month that
it would cut its workforce of 78,000 by 300, mostly through layoffs.
   ``The strong second-quarter results, following a good first
quarter, indicate we are making progress in improving our financial
performance,'' said James J. Renier, chairman and chief executive
officer. ``We look forward to the second half of the year with
confidence.''
   The 1988 second quarter included after-tax charges of $43
million, or $1.01 a share, related to unrecoverable contract costs
and the discontinuance of a product line, Honeywell said. Those 1988
charges were partially offset by a gain of $15 million, or 35 cents
a share, from the sale of real estate.
   Second-quarter revenue this year rose 1.8 percent, to $1.78
billion from $1.75 billion in 1988.
   Profit for the first half of this year increased 54.2 percent _
to $137.7 million, or $3.19 a share, from $89.3 million, or $2.11 a
share, a year earlier. The increase occurred despite a 1.2 percent
decline in first-half revenue to $3.45 billion from $3.49 billion.
   Renier said operating profit in Honeywell's industrial business
was up substantially, with notable strength in industrial automation
systems. Space and aviation systems also posted strong profit in the
second quarter, led by a substantial increase in commercial avionics
results and continued recovery in the military avionics group,
compared with a loss in the second quarter of 1988.
   Operating profit declined modestly in Honeywell's home and
building automation and control business, as expected, due to
continuing softness in construction markets. Profits from commercial
services, on the other hand, increased significantly.
   Profit declined in the company's defense and marine systems
business, compared with very strong results in the same period last
year.
</TEXT>
