<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     07-19 0320</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0334</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Sag, Pushed Down By Weakness In Gasoline Pits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gasoline futures prices tumbled Wednesday,
dragging down crude prices, after a report showed a steep rise in
gasoline inventories.
   Wholesale unleaded gasoline for August delivery fell 1.37 cents
to 54.69 cents a gallon on the New York Mercantile Exchange. Other
contract months generally declined, with September falling 1.13
cents to 53.37 cents a gallon.
   Among other refined products traded on the exchange, wholesale
heating oil for August delivery fell .13 cent to 50.37 cents a
gallon.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil for August delivery fell 53
cents to $19.81 per barrel, dropping below what analysts consider a
key psychological barrier at $20.
   Analysts said a sharper-than-expected rise in gasoline
inventories dragged prices lower.
   The American Petroleum Institute weekly report, released after
the close of trading Tuesday, showed total motor gasoline stocks
rose 5.2 million barrels to 222.855 million barrels in the week
ended July 14. Heating stocks also rose by 5.4 million barrels to
110.2 million during the week.
   ``People made the decision that the marketplace is over with for
gasoline and there was strong selling,'' said Madison Galbraith,
senior energy specialist for Merrill Lynch Energy Futures. ``They
decided we have enough gasoline around for the summer, there's no
problem anymore and they're saying they don't want to hold any
more.''
   Energy analysts said a rise in gasoline inventories was
anticipated but such an steep increase was not expected.
   The demand for gasoline has weakened in recent weeks due to
rising retail prices at the pump.
   Prices soared in March and April as refiners bought gas in
anticipation of possible shortages in the face of expected strong
consumption during the summer driving season. But the expected
demand never materialized due to the high prices, analysts said.
   Crude oil stocks were 1.4 million barrels lower at 331.3 million
for the week, API reported.
</TEXT>
