<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     07-19 0588</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0609</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up; Gold Down</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar gained ground against most major
foreign currencies Wednesday in an unusual reaction to inflation
news that ordinarily might have dampened enthusiasm for dollar
buying.
   Gold prices dropped, reflecting the good U.S. inflation reading
and the dollar's advance. Investors often choose gold as a hedge
against rising inflation.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery tumbled $4.30 to $368.30 a troy ounce. Republic National
Bank of New York quoted a bid of $368.20 for an ounce of bullion at
4 p.m. EDT, down $3.70 from Tuesday's late bid.
   Immediately after the Labor Department reported in the early
morning that the Consumer Price Index edged up 0.2 percent in June,
currency dealers sold dollars. Last month's CPI rate was
significantly smaller than May's 0.6 percent increase and the lowest
monthly rate since February 1988.
   The initial dollar selling was based on the thinking that
moderating inflation could increase the chances for the Federal
Reserve Board to loosen its credit policies further and drive down
U.S. interest rates.
   But the dollar sales soon abated.
   John McCarthy, chief currency dealer at the Amsterdam Rotterdam
Bank's New York office, said renewed demand for dollars emerged when
it became apparent that the sellers lacked enough conviction to push
the dollar below thresholds considered technically important.
   Plus, the dollar benefited from rallies in the stock and bond
markets Wednesday, which indicated that demand for
dollar-denominated investments remains robust despite the
possibility of lower U.S. interest rates.
   ``I think the fact that U.S. rates are declining is not a barrier
to interest in the dollar,'' said McCarthy.``People are buying U.S.
securities for capital appreciation. The attractiveness of the U.S.
bond and stock markets makes the dollar attractive.''
   The financial markets will be waiting Thursday for clues about
Fed policy when Alan Greenspan, the central bank chairman, testifies
at a congressional hearing.
   In Tokyo, the dollar closed at 141.80 Japanese yen, down from
142.35 yen. In London late Wednesday the dollar traded higher at
141.90 yen. Later, in New York, the dollar closed at 142.50 yen, up
from 141.50 on Tuesday.
   The British pound weakened against the dollar. Strikes by British
labor unions recently have discouraged investor interest in
sterling. One pound cost $1.6195 late in London, cheaper for buyers
than late Tuesday's level of $1.6255. Sterling fetched $1.6127 late
in New York's day vs. Tuesday's $1.6235.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Tuesday's
rates, included: 1.9125 West German marks, up from 1.8960; 1.6565
Swiss francs, up from 1.6430; 6.486 French francs, up from 6.4325;
1,380.50 Italian lire, up from 1,372.00; and 1.18885 Canadian
dollars, down from 1.19115.
   Selected late rates for the dollar in Europe compared with
Tuesday's late rates were: 1.9007 West German marks, up from 1.8920;
1.6465 Swiss francs, up from 1.6395; 6.4490 French francs, up from
6.4175; 2.1340 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1505; 1,374.50 Italian
lire, down from 1,379.50; and 1.1887 Canadian dollars, down from
1.1907.
   Gold bullion prices moved lower.
   Gold closed in London, the major market, at a bid of $371.75 a
troy ounce, down from $371.95. The closing Zurich price was $371
bid, down from $371.50.
   Earlier in Hong Kong gold closed at a bid of $372.05, up from
$369.75.
   Silver bullion traded late in London at $5.23 a troy ounce, down
from $5.27. On New York's Comex, silver bullion for current delivery
closed at $5.153 a troy ounce, down from Tuesday's settlement of
$5.242.
</TEXT>
