<FIRST>r f AM-USX-Verdict     07-19 0323</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-USX-Verdict,0337</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stock Gains Despite Jury Verdict</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARL BOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   USX Corp. stock traded higher Wednesday despite
a jury verdict that a former unit of the Pittsburgh oil, gas and
steel concern should pay at least $243.5 million in an antitrust
case.
   In consolidated New York Stock Exchange trading, USX stock closed
at $35.87{, up 62{ cents a share.
   The rise reflects investors' relief that the jury's verdict fell
short of recent projections, said analyst Andrew Gray of the
investment firm Donaldson, Lufkin &amp; Jenrette.
   There was also doubt about who would ultimately be responsible
for the damages and whether the award will withstand appeals.
   A plaintiff's attorney had said that with the doubling and
trebling of certain of the damages, the Bessemer &amp; Lake Erie
railroad could owe $638 million under the verdict returned Tuesday
in U.S. District Court in Philadelphia.
   Several analysts had projected the company's liability at $1
billion, Gray said.
   Plaintiffs including four major steel producers accused the B&amp;LE
of conspiring in 1983 and 1984 to block the development of
self-unloading ore boats in order to retain business hauling ore to
steel plants.
   USX sold the B&amp;LE last year to Transtar Inc., a holding of
Blackstone Capital Partners LP.
   ``When Blackstone and Transtar bought the B&amp;LE they didn't assume
any responsibility for the liability in this incident,'' USX
spokesman William Ryder said Wednesday. ``Whether USX will be
ultimately responsible remains to be litigated'' with Blackstone.
   The $638 million figure represents the ``speculation or
extrapolation on the part of the plaintiffs' attorney,'' he said.
   ``The fact of life is ... this is only the district court. It
could go higher'' and the award could be reduced on appeals, Gray
said.
   Gray said he expects USX earnings to remain strong with potential
for growth should natural gas prices rise as expected and petroleum
exploration intensify, boosting sales of the company's highly
profitable tubular goods.
</TEXT>
