<DOCNO> AP890719-0291 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-89 1804EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     07-19 0753</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0779</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gold Futures Slump To 4-Week Low As Inflation Cools</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Gold futures prices slumped to their lowest levels in a month
Wednesday as investors dumped precious metals and snapped up stocks
following a government report showing a slowdown in inflation.
   On other markets, stock-index futures soared; energy futures
plunged; grains and soybeans advanced; and livestock and meat
futures were mixed.
   Gold settled $4.30 to $4.90 lower on New York's Commodity
Exchange with the contract for delivery in August at $369.30 a troy
ounce and the spot July contract at $368.30. It was gold's lowest
close since June 16, when the August contract settled at $368.80.
   Silver futures fell 8.9 cents to 10.4 cents with July at $513.30
a troy ounce.
   The Labor Department's report of a lower-than-expected 0.2
percent rise in consumer prices in June prompted an immediate dip in
the gold market and primed it for a big drop when the dollar rallied
in afternoon trading.
   ``They were particularly unsettled by the Consumer Price Index
because even after you subtracted food and energy, you still got a
low number,'' said John O'Connell, a precious-metals market analyst
in New York with the futures brokerage Refco Inc.
   He said traders typically strip the food and energy components
from the government's inflation indicators to get a truer picture of
how Federal Reserve Board policies are affecting price movements.
Food and energy prices are less affected by monetary policies than
prices of other goods, O'Connell said.
   Gold prices began falling last week following another government
report that showed inflation at the wholesale level slowing. Gold is
often perceived as an inflation-resistant investment.
   Despite gold's weakness, analysts weren't quite ready to turn
bearish on a market that has shown a good deal of strength in the
past six weeks.
   ``I think we still have to go down a few dollars to technically
confirm the weakness,'' said Bernard Savaiko, senior metals analyst
with PaineWebber Inc.
   Stock-index futures approached an all-time high on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange as program trading and arbitrage boosted both
stock and futures prices.
   The contract for September delivery of stocks tracked by the
Standard &amp; Poor's 500 index settled 3.7 points higher at 338.25. The
September contract traded as high as 339, just 0.45 point below the
all-time high for a near-month contract.
   On the New York Stock Exchange, the Dow Jones average of 30
industrials jumped 39.83 points to 2,584.41.
   Gasoline futures prices tumbled on the New York Mercantile
Exchange, dragging down crude prices, after a report showed a steep
rise in gasoline inventories.
   The American Petroleum Institute weekly report, released after
the close of trading Tuesday, showed total motor gasoline stocks
rose 5.2 million barrels to 222.855 million barrels in the week
ended July 14. Heating oil stocks rose by 5.4 million barrels to
110.2 million during the week.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 9 cents to 49 cents
lower with August at $19.85 a barrel; heating oil was .13 cent lower
to .03 cent higher with August at 50.37 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was unchanged to 1.37 cents lower with August at 54.69
cents a gallon.
   Grain and soybean futures finished moderately higher on the
Chicago Board of Trade as rainy weather moved out of the Corn Belt
and talk turned to expectations of stronger foreign demand for grain.
   Soybeans for July delivery finished sharply higher but analysts
dismissed the rally, saying it represented limited buying in a thin
market ahead of the July contract's expiration on Thursday.
   Wheat settled 2 cents to 3} cents higher with July at $3.90 a
bushel; corn was { cent to 6 cents higher with July at $2.54\ a
bushel; oats were 4 cents to 4} cents higher with July at $1.46{ a
bushel; soybeans were 7\ cents to 32 cents higher with July up 32
cents at $7.27{ a bushel and the more actively traded August
contract up 13{ cents at $6.87{ a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures ended mixed on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange in position-squaring ahead of Friday's quarterly
Agriculture Department cattle-on-feed report.
   Live cattle settled .13 cent lower to .15 cent higher with August
at 72.67 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .25 cent lower to .10
cent higher with August at 83.65 cents a pound; live hogs were .25
cent to .85 cent higher with July at 48.02 cents a pound; frozen
pork bellies were .80 cent lower to .75 cent higher with July at
29.02 cents a pound.
</TEXT>
