<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-89 2215EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Conrail     07-19 0360</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Conrail,0374</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reports 15 Percent Drop In 2nd-Qtr Profit, Anti-Takeover Strategy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Conrail announced Wednesday that its profit
dropped 15 percent in the second quarter of the year, blaming the
coal strike, inflation and an accelerated maintenance schedule.
   In addition, the freight railroad announced adoption of a
strategy to discourage hostile takeover attempts.
   Earnings totaled $82 million, or $1.19 per share, for the second
quarter, compared with $97 million, or $1.41 per share, a year
earlier.
   Second-quarter revenue edged up to $881 million from $879 million
last year.
   Operating income fell, primarily because of lost traffic during
the coal strike in June, said James A. Hagen, chairman, chief
executive and president of the railroad.
   Inflation pushed costs up by $10 million and $8 million worth of
equipment and maintenance work was finished earlier this year than
last, affecting the bottom line in the second quarter, Hagen said.
   For the first six months of the year, Conrails' earnings were
down 2 percent to $142 million, or $2.07 per share, on revenue of
$1.75 billion. Conrail earned $145 million, or $2.10 per share, on
revenue of $1.71 billion for the first six months of 1988.
   Conrail's board adopted a so-called shareholder rights plan
intended to make taking control of the company more expensive for an
unwanted investor.
   ``The rights are designed to assure that all of Conrail's
stockholders receive fair and equal treatment in the event of any
proposed takeover of the company and to guard against the use of
abusive tactics to gain control of the company without paying all
shareholders a premium value,'' Hagen said.
   The plan is intended to encourage suitors to negotiate with the
board of directors, he said. The strategy is not in response to any
threat or proposed takeover, Hagen said.
   The plan issues one right per share to stockholders. If an
unwanted suitor's stake in the company increase to more than 10
percent, all shareholders except the raider can use their rights to
buy two shares of stock for the price of one.
   The company also Wednesday declared a 35 cent dividend, up from
the 30 cent dividend declared a year ago.
</TEXT>
