<FIRST>u f AM-Eastern     07-19 0696</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern,0719</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern Officials Say Smaller August Expansion Not Sign of Failure</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Northwest, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The top officials of Eastern Airlines on Wednesday
maintained that the overall program to rebuild the strikebound
carrier is proceeding well despite having to cut back on a planned
flight schedule expansion next month.
   Eastern Chairman Frank Lorenzo and President Phil Bakes also said
negotiations with striking pilots were not going well, denounced a
plan by Chicago businessman Joseph Ritchie and the unions to buy the
airline, and announced a plan to buy new aircraft.
   As about 20 strikers picketed outside a downtown Atlanta hotel,
Bakes told a news conference that too much attention is being paid
to the actual number of flights Eastern will have in its planned
August expansion.
   The airline originally promised to have 390 flights daily by Aug.
1 but said this week some reductions may be necessary. Before the
strike by Machinists, pilots and flight attendants that started
March 4, Miami-based Eastern had about 1,100 flights daily. It now
has 220.
   Bakes characterized the August expansion as merely part of a
nine-month plan to rebuild the airline without the unions.
   He said that so far Eastern has ``significantly exceeded those
plans.''
   Bakes refused to say exactly how many flights will be on the
schedule in August. He said the airline is refusing to take bookings
on flights for which crew training is incomplete.
   ``We have said we would fly approximately 390 flights, and when
we finish the month of August we will be somewhat less than that,''
Bakes said. ``But putting it in context, it is literally irrelevant
to the strategy the company is on.
   ``The overall plan is coming along very, very nicely,'' he said.
   Ron Cole, a spokesman for the Air Line Pilots Association,
accused Lorenzo and Bakes of ``putting a happy face on a ridiculous,
sorry situation.''
   Cole said the reduction in the projected August flights is a
clear sign that Eastern's rebuilding plan is not working.
   ``Lorenzo is setting up the travel agents and the traveling
public to take another bath,'' Cole said from Tampa, Fla., where
representatives of Eastern and the pilots union have been meeting
for several days.
   Bakes said the airline has made progress in financial results,
hours flown and numbers of passengers carried. He insisted that
Eastern has enough money from the sale of assets to persevere
through the rebuilding period, though he would not respond when
asked how much money the airline was losing each day.
   Eastern is awaiting a ruling from a federal bankruptcy judge on
its request to release $100 million being held in escrow by the
company's creditors, to finance the August expansion.
   The appearance by Lorenzo and Bakes in Atlanta followed
unconfirmed reports that negotiations between the company and the
pilots union had broken down. The two Eastern officials refused to
discuss specifics of the talks but said they were not making
progress.
   ``I can't be here bubbling with optimism about where they (the
talks) are going,'' said Lorenzo, who also is chairman of Eastern's
parent Texas Air Corp.
   Lorenzo also dismissed the plan by Ritchie and the unions to buy
Eastern as a ``public relations attempt.''
   Ritchie said Tuesday he is close to securing a ``highly
confident'' letter from his financial adviser, Shearson Lehman
Hutton Inc. In the letter, Shearson says it would agree to raise
$280 million in debt financing for the Eastern bid, Ritchie told The
Wall Street Journal.
   Ritchie, the principal owner and president of Chicago Research &amp;
Trading Group, also said he has been talking with the AFL-CIO about
an additional $200 million for an employee stock ownership plan.
   ``Mr. Ritchie's proposal always has appeared to be insubstantial
and irrelevant,'' Lorenzo said.
   Lorenzo also announced that Houston-based Texas Air planned a
$2.8 billion purchase of new-generation Boeing 737-300 aircraft.
   The plan calls for 50 firm purchases and 50 options. Lorenzo said
40 of the jets are earmarked for Eastern and 60 for its sister
carrier, Continental Airlines. In addition, Continental has agreed
to buy 13 Airbus A300 jets and spare parts from Eastern for $303.5
million.
</TEXT>
