<FIRST>r f AM-Nissan-UAW     07-19 0321</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nissan-UAW,0335</SECOND>
<HEAD>Union Vote Undercurrent at Celebration of 1-Millionth Nissan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CONNIE CASS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SMYRNA, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president of Nissan's U.S. auto plant
drove the 1-millionth vehicle off the assembly line Wednesday in a
ceremony touting company unity, while a vote on union organization
loomed one week away.
   ``Nissan's growth has been built on teamwork,'' president Jerry
Benefield told workers and dealers who applauded as the white pickup
truck rolled off the line in the cavernous plant.
   Benefield made no direct references to the vote during the
ceremony.
   Afterward, he said he was limiting his comment on the issue to
leave it ``between the union and our employees.'' Benefield declined
to predict a victory over the United Auto Workers.
   ``I think our employees will speak for themselves,'' he said.
``We'll know next week how they feel.''
   About 2,400 hourly workers are to vote Wednesday and Thursday on
UAW representation at the eight-year-old Nissan Motor Manufacturing
USA plant, a subsidiary of the Japanese automaker.
   The factory, about 30 miles southeast of Nashville, is one of
three nonunion U.S. plants owned by Japanese automakers.
   It has been a target of the UAW, which is concentrating on worker
injuries and assembly line speeds as major campaign issues.
   Initially the plant only built light pickup trucks. But Sentra
passenger cars were added in March 1985.
   The milestone truck, given away through a drawing conducted by
Nissan dealers, resembled the first truck off the line in 1983 _ a
white pickup called Job 1.
   The company is preparing to add a third vehicle line in 1992,
bringing its total production capacity to 440,000 vehicles per year
and making it the highest volume facility under one roof in the
United States, according to Nissan.
   The non-union environment of Tennessee, a right-to-work state,
helped attract the highly sought plant, and Nissan officials
maintain the lack of a union helps production and employment expand.
</TEXT>
