<FIRST>r f AM-BeverlyEnterprises     07-19 0370</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Beverly Enterprises,0381</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nursing Home Company Announces 2nd Qtr Loss; Big Investor Sells Stake</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Beverly Enterprises Inc., the nation's largest
operator of nursing homes, announced a $98 million second-quarter
loss Wednesday because of expenses associated with a restructuring,
inciting a big selloff in its stock.
   The company, which derives much of its income from Medicare
payments and has been struggling under a debt load of nearly $1
billion, said it was recording a $120 million pretax writeoff to
account for losses related to the sale or planned sale of 370
nursing homes with more than 38,000 beds.
   The second-quarter loss on revenue of $524 million compared with
earnings of $111,000 on revenue of $524 million in the year-earlier
quarter. Earnings per-share were negligible, because the company has
54 million shares outstanding.
   ``This is the critical step on the road back to consistent
profitability for Beverly,'' David Banks, who became chief executive
officer in May, told securities analysts in New York where the
earnings report was disclosed.
   But investors reacted negatively and the stock fell 87{ cents to
$8.25 in composite New York Stock Exchange volume of 5.24 million
shares.
   More than half the volume came from a single sale of 3.52 million
shares controlled by David H. Murdock, chairman of Castle &amp; Cook, a
Los Angeles-based food products concern.
   Murdock, who purchased the stock last year as an investment, said
in a statement released by his office that entities he controls sold
the entire stake at $8.62{ a share. He declined to specify his
reasons for selling the stake. Beverly spokesman Bill Ihle also
declined to comment.
   For the first six months of 1989, Beverly lost $107 million on
revenue of $1.03 billion, vs. a loss of $841,000 on revenue of $998
million for the first six months of 1988.
   Beverly, based in Pasadena, Calif., began a restructuring program
early last year to sell unprofitable facilities. Once all sales
announced Wednesday are completed, Beverly said, its beds will total
68,445, vs. 115,357 when the restructuring began. It will remain the
biggest U.S. nursing home operator.
   The company runs facilities in 38 states and the District of
Columbia with a workforce of more than 100,000 employees.
</TEXT>
