<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-89 2112EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-McDonnellDouglas     07-19 0391</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-McDonnell Douglas,0405</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reports Loss of $48 Million For Second Quarter</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By R.B. FALLSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   McDonnell Douglas Corp. said Wednesday it lost
$48 million in the second quarter, citing the continuing effects of
a major reorganization of its transport aircraft business segment.
   The loss for the defense contractor caught stock analysts by
surprise and sent the company's stock on the New York Stock Exchange
into a tailspin.
   McDonnell Douglas stock fell $5 a share to $72.
   The second-quarter loss contrasted with a profit of $71 million,
or $1.83 a share, in the three months ended June 30, 1988.
   Second-quarter sales fell 3.6 percent to $3.476 billion from
$3.605 billion last year.
   The loss comes on the heels of a poor first quarter when the
company reported a $169 million profit only because of a $179
million one-time tax credit.
   For the first six months, McDonnell Douglass said it earned $121
million, or $3.18 a share, compared with $122 milion, or $3.16 a
share, a year earlier. Six-month revenue fell to $6.82 billion from
$6.92 billion.
   ``Clearly, two bad quarters in a row with such large losses seem
to say McDonnell Douglas is in real difficulty,'' said Phillip
Brannon, an analyst with Merrill Lynch Research U.S. in New York.
   Brannon said he didn't expect the company's problems in the
transport segment, which accounts for nearly 30 percent of the
company's revenues, would have been so prolonged.
   ``This is definitely far worse than I think anyone anticipated,''
said Paul Nisbet, an analyst at Prudential-Bache in New York.
   In the transport segment, parts shortages and the training of
thousands of new employees have increased costs and forced the
reorganization, which began in February and affects 5,000 employees.
   McDonnell Douglas said improved performance in the combat
aircraft and information systems segments was overshadowed by a
second-quarter operating loss of $158 million in the transport
aircraft segment, which had revenues of $952 million. That compares
with operating earnings of $10 million on revenues of $1.1 billion
in the same quarter last year.
   The missiles, space and electronics systems segment had earnings
of $10 million in the quarter, down from $37 million in the same
period last year due to reduced earnings in the Delta II launch
vehicle program and a write-off reflecting higher-than-expected
costs in a laser communications program.
</TEXT>
