<DOCNO> AP890719-0300 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-89 1913EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Continental-Boeing     07-19 0467</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Continental-Boeing,0479</SECOND>
<HEAD>Continental to Buy Boeing Jets in $2.8 Billion Deal</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Northwest, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto HT3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF AWALT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Continental Airlines said Wednesday it is ordering
up to 100 new Boeing jets in a $2.8 billion deal that is the largest
ever for Texas Air Corp., the parent of both Continental and
strikebound Eastern Airlines.
   Forty of the new jets are earmarked for Eastern, now in the midst
of bankruptcy reorganization and a lingering strike. All the
purchases by Eastern first must be approved by a federal bankruptcy
court.
   Houston-based Texas Air also announced a complicated mix of
transactions in which Continental soon would purchase 11 widebody
Airbus A300 jets and spare parts from Eastern for $303.5 million.
Continental also would lease two McDonnell Douglas DC-10s from
Eastern and lease 34 jets back to its sister carrier.
   ``I think this is an important step in Continental's return to
profitability and confidence in the future of the airline,'' D.
Joseph Corr, Continental's chairman and chief executive officer,
told a news conference.
   ``What we're really doing is not only restructuring our fleet,
but we're also at the same time providing for our fleet way out into
the future,'' Corr said. ``Overall, we're looking at more seats to
more destinations than prior to these changes.''
   Under the deal, Houston-based Continental agreed to buy as many
as 60 of Boeing Co.'s narrow-body 737-300s, with deliveries of 30
aircraft planned for 1992 to 1994 and with an option to purchase
another 30 of the jets in 1995 and 1996.
   Total cost of the Continental purchase would be about $1.7
billion, Corr said, adding that about three-quarters of the new
fleet would replace aging aircraft.
   Corr declined to discuss financing for the purchase. Continental
posted a first-quarter loss of $16.5 million, narrowed from an $80.6
million loss in the same quarter of 1988.
   Continental, a non-union carrier which emerged from bankruptcy
reorganization in September 1986, and Miami-based Eastern were among
only three major U.S. airlines that did not have new planes on order
prior to the Boeing deal announced Wednesday. Pan Am Corp. is the
third carrier.
   Corr said the federal bankruptcy judge overseeing Eastern's
reorganization, Burton R. Lifland, probably will have the final say
over the airline's finances. But he said Continental's negotiations
on an order for Eastern planes had nothing to do with its sister
carrier's financial status.
   The agreement with Boeing allows Continental to substitute a
portion of its order for Boeing's 737-400s or 737-500s, which have
different seat capacities, allowing for greater flexibility as the
airline's needs change in the coming years, Corr said.
   He insisted that the prices were fair market value, denying any
suggestion that the arrangement was part of a shift in assets at the
expense of crippled Eastern.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
