<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-89 2316EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Allied-Signal     07-19 0181</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Allied-Signal,0190</SECOND>
<HEAD>Allied-Signal Reports Second-Quarter Profit of $143 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MORRIS TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Allied-Signal Inc.'s profit
increased 12 percent during the second quarter, the high technology
and automotive products company reported Wednesday.
   Earnings for the quarter were $166 million, or $1.11 a share,
compared with $128 million, or 85 cents a share, during the same
period in 1988.
   Included in the 1989 second-quarter figure is a one-time gain of
$23 million, or 16 cents a share, Allied-Signal received from an
insurance settlement awarded to Union Texas Petroleum Holdings Inc.
Allied-Signal has a 40 percent equity interest in Union Texas.
   Sales during the second quarter totaled $3.1 billion, up from $3
billion in the 1988 perioed, Allied said.
   Chairman and Chief Executive Edward L. Hennessy Jr. said the
company's strong performance was aided by the improved showing of
the company's operating units, particularly its aerospace sector.
   ``Earnings are expected to remain strong through the second half
of 1989 as we continue to concentrate on improving our operating
performance,'' Hennessy said.
   Allied-Signal's other business sectors are automotive products
and engineered materials.
</TEXT>
