<FIRST>r f BC-Eastern-Atlanta     07-19 0149</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Eastern-Atlanta,0156</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lorenzo Says Eastern Not Moving To Atlanta</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Frank Lorenzo, chairman of Eastern Airlines parent
Texas Air Corp., says the Miami-based airline is staying put,
despite speculation that he was considering moving its headquarters
to Atlanta.
   Atlanta is Eastern's largest hub, and a chief rival, Delta Air
Lines, is based here.
   Lorenzo said previously he would not rule out a move, but he told
a news conference Wednesday there is virtually no chance Eastern
would be coming to Atlanta.
   ``Eastern has an attractive physical setup in Miami. Miami has
been an important part of Eastern for many years. Many of the
families of headquarters' employees are located in Miami,'' he said.
   The airline is trying to rebuild amid a 4-month-old strike by
Machinists union members, pilots and flight attendants, and
increasing the number of flights at Atlanta has been the centerpiece
of that effort.
</TEXT>
