<DOCNO> AP890719-0306 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-89 2359EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-PrintingScam     07-19 0480</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Printing Scam,0497</SECOND>
<HEAD>Feds Stop Allegedly Fraudulent Sales By Maine Company</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIRK BEVERIDGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge has halted sales by a Maine
company that made up to $30 million over the past five years by
allegedly bilking thousands of investors nationwide and in Canada, a
Federal Trade Commission attorney said Wednesday.
   Case Equipment Co. of Turner is accused in an FTC lawsuit of
advertising a ``sublicolor'' printing system that the company said
could be used to print high-quality color pictures on T-shirts and
other consumer items. In reality, the investors were getting nothing
more than an outdated mimeograph machine, FTC attorney Sara
Greenberg said.
   Last week, U.S. District Judge Gene Carter issued a temporary
restraining order to stop the sale of the press through next
Wednesday. The FTC will ask Friday for an injunction that would stop
the sales until the matter is resolved in court, Ms. Greenberg said
from her office in Boston.
   Separately, a group of customers who say they were cheated have
filed a lawsuit against Case Equipment in U.S. District Court.
   Potential investors were lured by national magazine
advertisements, flown into Portland and picked up at the airport by
limousines that took them to Case Equipment's showroom in Turner,
Ms. Greenberg said.
   There the investors were shown impressive samples of printing and
given a sales pitch that said making money with the ``sublicolor''
system would be easy, and that Case Equipment had service centers
around the country and long lists of potential customers, Ms.
Greenberg said.
   ``It's a wine 'em and dine 'em sort of operation, and the people
are impressed,'' Ms. Greenberg said. ``Even people who had some
knowledge of the printing industry were taken in.''
   A Case Equipment brochure entered into the court record claims
that investors could have the potential of making ``$93,000 a month
or $1,116,000 a year.''
   Ms. Greenberg alleged that the scam cheated ``somewhere between
2,000 and 4,000 people, multiplied by a minimum of $10,000 each. We
estimated up to $30 million in court papers.''
   Case Equipment had been operating in Turner since 1984, shortly
after its owner, Anthony J. Casella, also known as A.J. Casella and
A.J. Case, abandoned a similar operation in Massachusetts when that
state's attorney general's office began investigating complaints,
Ms. Greenberg said.
   Casella was not available for comment at Case Equipment's office
on Wednesday afternoon, according to an employee who asked a
reporter whether the company's legal troubles were so serious that
he should leave his job.
   ``I'm scared,'' the employee said. ``I'm just wondering what's
going to happen.''
   Casella did not return a telephone message left by The Associated
Press.
   Ms. Greenberg said that the FTC is seeking to stop Casella's
company from misrepresenting its products, and it wants restitution
for all the investors.
   The lawsuit filed by Case Equipment customers seeks compensatory
and punitive damages.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
